text: bready and somewhat sweet aroma along with some mild citrus hops . very nice and certainly refreshing .  poured with a huge e finger head that settled down with an excellent pillowy top and a tan color , body was a dark dark brown but not quite black .  on the palate , this one is fairly light bodied with flavors of tart cherries , prunes , raisins and lightly roasted malt .

because it is great stuff . i like this boulevard pilsner . so this is pilsner .  superior lacing & head retention s : biscuitty malt & tangerine rind t : grapefruit , peppery hops , biscuitty malt & dryness up front .  m - a medium mouthfeel and rather smooth like caramel .

smell in the glass does n't amount to much when chilled , only a faint roasty malt . when swirling the dregs in the bottle , there was a plummy smell , like a baltic porter . this is a perfect session stout if you are so inclined .  '' pour was an amazing , thick used-motor oil black ( only a beer geek could find that description appetizing ) .  mouthfeel : thin and watery , but the carbonation is very crisp .

the smell does not leave me expecting much t- slightly fruity and still pretty grainy . m- smooth , little to no bitterness , watery mouthfeel .  a bit of an orange copper color , little haze , with a fantastic looking head .  thinner body .

s : smells like a standard ipa , nothing special t : not a fan of ipa 's , but this one tastes decent .  a hard pour produced a 3 finger head . excellent retention . color is a dark ruby brown . impressive head retention .  m : has medium to full body with very little carbonation to make my mouth tingle .

aroma is very faint , but i 'm in a typical college bar so i would be surprised if i could smell anything beyond the stale beer , ashtray and urinal cake . anyhoo , what i could detect was some sweet malt , faint fruity esters , and some flowery noble hops .  a - beautiful clear gold color with thick lasting foam . lots of lace . just beautiful .  the roast flavors give way to a hop bitterness in the finish with virtually no malt backbone in between . hints of licorice and coffee give this nice complexity for a lager . m- a little fuller than your typical schwarzbier . d- it drinks like a big beer , much more so than it 's 4.9 % abv would lend you to expect . overall : this is a very flavorful schwarzbier . my personal criticisms are that i would like it to have a little more malt in the middle while toning down the roast malts just a little . still , not a bad beer by any means .

split with the wife ... really excited about this one . will call it nice..wasnt expecting the `` lees '' . the nose was very faint..slight grainy malts , possible metallic note with spicy hops . spicy hops leaving a strong bitter bite on the swallow . really appreciating this beer .  the beer poured into the chalice crystal clear ruby red with a white frothy head which rose and retreated slowly to lace the chalice from top to bottom .  m - coarse throughout but not as sticky as i would like from an imperial ipa .

aroma is minimal and somewhat generic .  nice head and great retention .  m -- maybe i should n't have drank this after sipping on a j.w . its not quite what i would call `` watery , '' but it could use a little more body . carbonation levels are fine .

the only part that falls short is the nose . it 's not too strong at all , although it 's a nice blend of leafy and citrus hops and a bit of malt behind it .  looks really nice .  only criticism : powerful aggressive carbonation , would it ease if i left it a while - just too fresh ?

heavily understated nose , with just a hint of caramelly grapefruit pith and a chemical smell bordering on sulfuric .  a truly great looking beer .  you could certainly taste the chocolate , but it did n't fill the mouth with the heavy , rich bitter chocolate of some other beers in this same vein . i enjoyed drinking this beer ; it went down easily , but if given the choice , i would take the brooklyn chocolate stout , which is more like comfort food in the fall when it 's getting cold and the leaves are dying . this is supposed to be a beer you can snuggle with next to the fireplace while watching monday night football .

s - if you took most other beers drank half of it filled it back up with water and then evaluated it this is what it would smell like .  this is easily one of the best heads i 've seen in quite a while . one of the impressive things , was that there was hardly a hint of alcohol in the smell . the melons were a bit more upfront and pungent , with the spices and oakiness not far behind . i 'm not a big fan of melons , but this beer somehow changed my view on them .  hellooo hops ! this is a nice beer that hits you with hops right off the bat . nice hops with a touch of malt , and a lingering hop influenced aftertaste . i ca n't help but pick the slightest metallic twinge in the flavor and aftertaste , not sure where that could be coming from . not a bad strong ale at all , definitely worth revisiting but probably not distinguishable enough to stand in the upper echelon of style .

s-reminds me of a coffee flavored candy of my childhood -- a little too sweet smelling for my taste in a beer t-1st is sweet coffee- finishes with a nice bitterness , good carbonation if drunk with large head -- less so later -- but even after head is gone good for a stout d- would only want one of these per session between richness , coffee flavor and abv .  this beer pours black as night with a creamy amber foam . nice carbonation .  the mouthfeel is light also and thin .
s - dark fruits , some light chocolate , coffee ... not a lot of smoke .  a beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel is very acidic , carbonated .

appearance : beautiful crystal clear pale golden beer that pours a very thick & sticky white foam head . smell : soft grain , metallic and floral hop aromas .  the color is black with just a hint of brown when held up to a light . the tan head looks quite creamy and appealing , and it leaves plenty of lacing on the side of my glass . this beer could not look more attractive .  sour dishwater . i do n't think this beer can be rated because it is marginally spoiled . the bacterial taste is taking over whatever else it might have once tasted like . i think bayhawk has a problem with some of their bottled ales , and they seem to be happy to leave them on the shelves for the unwary to buy . i 'm going to look at my usual san diego retailers to see where i paid $ 3.99 for this . this is the second of their beers i have tried and it too will water the garden .

smell : not a whole lot going on here . faint chocolate and nuts with a little caramel . smells clean i suppose taste : it 's really sad they 're discontinuing this .  fantastic presentation . very light and frothy head over orange-yellow .  still , it seems a little light in body and the carbonation is low . without a doubt another quality beer by dogfish head , but i have a feeling that the pricetag of a 750 ml bottle would scare me from its purchase .

some fresh bread and sweet dark fruit , but it is very faint .  dark gold/bronze with a full pillowy beige head and very active carbonation .  my new pbr.ha . joke , but .. ill change the details later . it 's from a can , but.. please , please pour it into a glass . it is great . it is economical . enjoy responsibly . ... ... great beer . i really want to talk abotu it , .. but i dont have the time right now.. please let me just post my ratings . yes .

s : not really much smell to this one . you can catch a hint of the the nut flavor but you have to really take a deep smell . browns do not really have a strong smell to them though ... t : great taste . the nuttiness is just right to compliment the caramel and spices .  on cask at aobf a fluffy tan head rises over oily black , black , black .  the body seemed a bit light , and maybe a bit more weight would have made it more satisfying , but that 's a minor quibble .

pale malt and light floral aromas . crisp pale malt with light caramel and floral hops all in subtle balance with a light grassy bittersweet finish . at first i was not entirely impressed as it seemed to be just another amber style beer . however , the subtle qualities of this beer are so nicely in balance it creates one heckuva drinkable beer .  a - poured pitch black with medium head that slowly dissipated leaving average amount of lacing around the glass .  m - thin on the mouth , ok carbonation .

the aroma was citrusy , bready and with mild hops . overall though the aroma was n't too strong though .  the appearance was stunning : a rich dark red color , almost syrupy , and a large but quickly fading head . it looked incredible in a large wine glass .  m- near dead flat . it seems to be a bit on the thin side as well . d- despite the feel this beer still drinks deadly smooth .

s- slightly sweet . sort of buttery . cisco made sure their flagship ( this is their flaghship , right ? ) is one to talk about !  a : pours a hazy bright yellow , looking like a hay field . provides a nice 2 finger foam head with superb retention . there is a thick layer of lacing as well .  think prunes and raisins , but more complex and infinitely boozier . i ca n't believe that this beer is appearing thin on the palate and i think that it has to be with the insanely high abv . even though it 's clean , it 's still very sweet . i am loving the taste but i am certainly not digging the mouthfeel , that is into the moderate strength liqueur territory . a brewing achievement but not beer like ; delicious nonetheless .

s : not much there . metallic and chemical that detracts a bit . t : again , sweet malt with more chocolate than in the nose . i really like the taste of this .  one of my favorite sam adams offerings ... deliciously red with a huge foamy head making this an extremely attractive brew ... malt dominant aroma.. strong caramel notes and maybe even some toffee.. extremely smooth and sweet malts dominate the palate .  mouthfeel is oily and slick , and a little fizzy .

this was a drain pour - i think they got the maple and bacon flavorings somewhat correct although far too overpowering . however , the base beer is underwhelming - it does n't hold up or add anything to those flavors . this beer lacks body and complexity so about half way through a glass i was already bored and looking how to dispose of it .  2009 vintage pours a dark beautiful amber color with a perfect amount of head and some patchy lacing .  low , easy-going carbonation .

it sounded like the head was full of a certain snappy , crackly and poppy cereal . smell : surprisingly little smell for a beer of this style .  massive chunky head that has amazing retention with a bleached bone white color , and a clean and clear golden body with jets of carbination bubbles constantly rushing to the surface .  m - average carbonation .

s : shy on the nose . the scents are clean , though , and inviting .  the dubbel poured into my goblet with a dense head of natural carbonation provided by the bottle conditioning . the thick tan foam lingers minutes after the pour .  m : a little out of style ... pretty light bodied with good carbonation .

there was nothing to smell but maybe some citrus-like hops & water . tasted like watered down hops with a little straw left to sit in the brew kettle .  a - very dark and long lasting tight head . m - for how dark it is and the solid foam i was expecting a much heavier brew .  this beer really needs to sit a while before the mouthfeel is anywhere near decent . when its freshly poured and a bit too cool , it 's thin and prickly , but just letting it sit a while and come closer to room temp. , it becomes a bit fuller and mellows out a bit . really drinkable ris that has tons of flavor and a decent mouthfeel , once it warms up .

the smell left something to be desired as no flavors really stood out to me except for some alcohol . the taste though was very pleasant with coffee and chocolate extremely present all through out my sip of beer . very refreshing beer for a stout and not at all overwhelming .  poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 1/2 '' off-white head over the effervescent clear golden brew . head sno-cones above the rim over time , finally calming down to leave chunky bits of lacing .  it kind of explodes in the mouth and the carbonation is a bit on the sharp side .

smell is some bready malt and a bit of spice . very drinkable .  out of a bottle this beer was a chestnut brown color with a huge three finger head . the khaki foam died back slowly , displayed good retention and excellent lacing .  high carbonation is the only downfall i can find in this beer .

it has a small spice smell with a bit of sweet malts in there not impressed with smell , other than that the taste is quite refreshing the mouthfeel was a little lighter that i had hoped but overall a good winter ale .  pours pitch black with not even a hint of light coming through . has a large billowing dark cocoa colored head that takes forever to go down - nice lacing on the glass .  light body and a bit watery , but the munich possesses a david-like flavor that surprises those who order it expecting something more saccharine .

mild aroma of caramel and grapefruit . quite pleasantly surprised by this one -- seems much more like a double ipa than a strong ale , though .  displays awesome retention , forms a mesa in the middle of the glass and shows off an impressive formation of 3d lace . an awesome appearance and nice aroma save this one from finding the 'c ' range .  slick mouth feel , very drinkable .

hazy . s : little bit of caramel & pine . for some reason i 'm not getting much here . t : heavy on the pine , then some wood & grapefruit flavors . this beer is really damn bitter . another good west coast ipa ... does n't really distinguish itself from the rest , but worth the $ 11 a six pack .  great presentation with an amber pour with a thick and long lasting tan head .  the mouthfeel , as with the question , keeps this from being a world class brew . the aroma and flavor are sublime but the carbonation detracts from the beer . i 'm looking forward to trying this with proper carbonation and we 'd be talking about an unbelievable beer .

cherries and sourness dominate the aroma . a little dirt .  gorgeous dark brown pour settling inky black in the glass with a mighty thick dark tan foam of mashed up graham cracker-like quality . the lacing is more like shelving as it grabs on to the glass with thickly set curtains of foamy soup .  m ) this beer is suprisingly thing considering the nature of the style . it does , however , have a very nice wet sticky and lingering feel .

smells nondescript , but that does n't mean much .  pours a wonderfully deep mahogany with a two finger tan head that leaves impeccable sheets of lacing to the very end .  small amounts of a watery feel are noticed towards the back , overall has a decently appealing mouthfeel .

it had a mild malt aroma .  reviewed 4/7/2009 ( bottle bb 03jul09 ) : pours a very clear , orange-yellow colored body . big creamy white head , very lasting .  sweet maple syrup aroma with herbal hops and some yeast . the malts have a very sweet taste and also there is a toasted bread taste that really develops in the aftertaste . very good ale !

s - i 'm picking up some slight caramel malts and a bit of spiciness . not alot of aroma going on here t - but then it hits you ... big malty taste , nice sweetness with molasses , some coffee and brown sugar . the aroma leaves no hint of whats to come .  seriously - after the pour , there were three or more inches of solid head , never dying completely . this is stout-like head - thick and creamy . underneath lies a beautifully orange-gold beer , with carbonation bubbles streaming from the bottom of the glass .  mouthfeel - light for a winter seasonal brew , but not bad .

some malts on the nose , with perhaps just a tinge of a slight metallic scent , but not too terribly heavy . wonderful taste , however , nicely toasted , without tasting burnt , and with a hint of grain .  ) topped by a majestic light brown head that shows truly noteworthy retention and leaves tons of sticky brown lace - this is exactly what i want an imperial stout to look like : exactly .  m - disappointing , frankly .
s : fresh mowed grass .  thick black body , with a tan-coloured nitro head . a wonderful appearance , but the aroma seemed a bit muted .  mouthfeel : smooth with a relatively full body .

curious back story drew me in . split a bottle during an afternoon 's round robin . looked like a perky rose wine or a pink champagne with 7-up advertisement effervescence . initial taste was unanimously honey which mellowed w/each sip . the sake influence almost slipped in unnoticed , but was worth the wait , like an old friend arriving at a party full of strangers .  sits an opaque tawny sun color with thick head that simmers to a thin layer . the varied size in bubbles left a nice belgian lace pattern on the glass .  mouthfeel is good , but not great , almost leaves a little alcohol flavor at the end and a little carbonated .

nothing much on the aroma aside from some corny sweetness and metal ( admittedly i 'd say not from the can ... just that metallic crap lager taste ) light grainy , corny sweetness . slightly crisp , light , but has a heavier , creamy feel which is nice , but for the style , a crisper bite would have been more refreshing .  great lacing and head retention .  i found this beer to be one of the easiest-drinking beers i 've ever had . now , my review is flawed because i do n't believe i have any other saison/farmhouse ales to compare it to - this is my first . but from the description of the style , i expected something a bit more complex in flavor , and this was not complex at all . low abv combined with a mellow flavor equals very easy drinkability . for an every day summer beer , i 'd choose this hands down over the bmc beers ; unfortunately this runs $ 32 a case , so it could be come an expensive habit .

good beer . ( remind me to edit my review of michelob amberbock .  beautiful ruby red color .  mouthfeel : light bodied with moderate carbonation , slightly drying leaving that coffee dryness on the palate .

perhaps my fondness for this old friend clouds my judgement and raises the ranking but i do love to get nostalgic and revisit this stout . as usual , there was not much smell associated with the initial pour . i know there are better stouts out there and i am told what we get in the states is a pale comparison to what you would find in ireland but this will always remain a favorite .  22oz bottle into a duvel tulip pours a deep almost opaque black with a nice frothy khaki head that lasts and leaves nice lacing on the glass .  matching , but mild , after-taste m-medium creamy carbonation . somewhat watery finish . the carbonation really bothered me with this one also .

s : malt . that was about it . a small nutty scent , and alcohol was there but otherwise , malt . very nice .  it pours a stunning clear amber color with a tightly bubbled white head .  mouthfeel is on the thin sider , and a bit oily , but there 's enough carbonation to keep it pleasant .

light chocolate and butterscotch , w/ mild roasted barley and nuttiness . not as delectable in aroma compared to other imperials . the rich malt character is n't represented in aroma . it lacks the complete package of richness , but is highly enjoyable nonetheless .  pours a beautiful dark blue with a one-finger head into my glass .  pale straw with a fizzy head . no retention however and lacing is nowhere to be found . smells like the business end of a skunk . i tried several times to find anything else , but seemed to fail gracefully . taste is grassy and grainy . strange bitterness that did n't really seem like hops . yuck ! i was looking for cans to try and avoid the skunk aroma , but only found the evil green bottles . i will try this again someday when i work up the courage ... but it wo n't be from a bottle .

aroma- very light hop aroma but has a bit of grassy/malty aroma blended together . starts with an awesome pour but then the aroma is too light and off-balanced .  dies slowly and leaves lots of webby lace . recedes in a rocky fashion . leaves a solid froth dome that extends well over the glass ! the liquid is brown and clear .  m : creamy , light , and watery on the palate .

aroma is balance malt and hop and very tight . the flavor shines on this one , especially for a lager .  the appearance is flawless . the contrast of the thick tan head and deep black body is visually appealing .  mouthfeel medium -light mouthfeel with prickly carbonation . a bit too carbonated for my taste in a mild , but not too far off .

smell : smells good , aromas of light fruits like pear and apple .  reviewed 8/20/2007 ( bottle ) : pours a huge foamy head , good lacing .  thin even for this style , i 'd like to see just a little more intensity in the backbone . mouthfeel : as you 'd imagine as you watch it pour , this is very much light-bodied . good carbonation and a clean finish .

smells of rich roasted coffee , toasted grains , bitter chocolate , caramel , licorice . it also has sweet cream/milk notes to it , kind of like condensed milk .  quite a beauty in the glass . clear , gold and with a thick , rocky head that leaves a ton of lacing in its wake .  body is medium with a decent amount of carbonation .

this goes very well with spicy food . it does have a bit of the can taste in it , but oddly enough , it compliments it . the best of the sapporo beers .  it poured with a finger 's worth of lovely ecru head that experienced good retention . the color was a deep honey-gold with ne-quality clarity .  m : mouthfeel is where this loses points . very thin but good carbonation .

easy light drink , bit much on water , particularly with lower alcohol . a bit of bite -molasses and hoppy . liked : only mildly roasty , only bit of the coffee , and hint of chocolates and nutty . very good stout .  scored this at goebels in wichita pours copper/auburn with 2 fingers of tan head . superior head retention & insane lacing s : faint breadyness t : caramel , breadyness , earthy & herbal hops , dryness up front , plus just a touch of woody hops well .  light to medium carbonation , with a creamy mouthfeel on the tongue and in the mouth which leans towards crisp and almost watery in the overall feel to it .

good taste and average smell but nothing real distinctive .  pours a cloudy golden color with a massive head that nearly spills over the top of my giant snifter . foam recedes ridiculously slow leaving nice lacing and creating big rocky tops .  the beer is a little above average in drinkability , but the mouthfeel left much to be desired .

a - orangeish tan with almost two inches of head s - mild smell , not offensive but not appetizing either t - a bit sour and very bitter m - sharp on the tongue , you can tell there 's a lot of alcohol in this beer .  very nice looking beer .  it looks very inviting , dark brownish-reddish body , semi hazy and is topped off with a semi thick tan head that 's very bubbly and sticks around for a bit ; it has some strong lacing qualities . it has a medium to light mouth feel , clean and has mild carbonation . faint hops are present some roasted oats and grains , its sweet overall and no alcohol flavors , not even i the aftertaste .

the smell was surprising . very deep with , i dare to say , a meatiness to it . my kids called it a stink .  deep brown with lots of carbonation , huge tan head and it looked really good !  mouthfeel is a bit on the watery side , but not too bad .

i picked up a 6pk of pint cans at wal-mart for memories . s - no obvious smell here . hence my two since it 's mostly corn and water . t - very light and refreshing . d - very drinkable .  a creamy , marshmallowy , eggshell white head foams up about 1 cm and rests effortlessly on the surface . very nice appearance !  this 'beer ' is weak . this 'beer ' is flavourless . no wait , i can taste some corn syrup , and what 's that ... pickle juice ? honestly , i think i taste hints of pickle juice !

has a distinctly malty smell to it . dark amber in color . full flavored , but at the same time lighter than other ales in the category . although lighter and thinner than the scotch ale i was expecting , this ale has turned out to be something i really enjoy .  a : i once heard that the darkest place on earth is not even 100 % black . this is really black . ummmm ... kind of small head and , during it 's short life , i could tell it was creamy and light brown . none-the-less a full , creamy body , sticky ( you do n't want to spill this beer on yourself ) & warm ( pretty well hidden actually ) .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , slightly syrupy , and carbonation is low which produces a somewhat still feel .

aroma is sweet but weak . beer is thick in the mouth but i really like it .  a : extremely hazy orangish-yellow with a fluffy white head . it really is an attractive looking beer .  mf- lower carbonation than i was expecting right out of the gate . mouthfeel was the only slight flaw .

looks really good in the glass - just what i want from a brown ale . the smell is just okay - there 's some nuttiness there , but it 's not overpowering ( which i prefer ) .  a : poured a half finger white copper head that settled to a thin cap . lacing and glass presence is great lasting 45 min into the pour .  i gave the mouthfeel a lower score due to the extremely bitter after-taste and the thin-ness of the body .

not picking up a huge aroma but i am getting some , faint roasted malt and hint of vanilla and toffee . i 've had this many times before and i 'm glad it 's readily available in case i wanted a darker beer that is n't so brutal with a lower abv and subtleness to it .  a : deep clear red with a fantastic reddish-white head . great looking beer .  a light to medium body , with prickly , active carbonation . the carbonation was just a tad bit higher then i would have liked , but was still enjoyable .

s : sweet malt and faint hops , citrus , earthy . m : light to medium body with nice , lively carbonation . t : sweet barley malt followed by mild , grassy saaz hops .  a perfect amber color with tints of orange and yellow when held to a light . overall an excellent beer .  bought at whole foods , pasadena , ca-arroyo parkway . the taste is hoppy with a nice back end . can feel the abv in this pour . nice . i would drink this again .

the nose on this is so pungent ! for all the fantastic flavors it had , it could have been a little too sweet , but some nice flower and rind notes return from the nose . great ipa .  poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass a : a really beautiful beer with dark brown hue and thick , two finger tan head with lots of lacing .  got some from my daughter in texas as a christmas gift - it drinks well without filling you up . i poured it into a pilsner glass for a head of an inch or so . as a porter and stout drinker , i was surprised at the lightness of it given the color , but then , it 's a lager . i 'd like this on on a warm summer day .

n : i 'm not getting a big nose here . it really is n't prominent , i 'm surprised .  enormous two finger , very frothy , beige head . heavy , layered lacing .  the mouth is quite prickly and fairly heavy , even cloying a bit .

s : some grainyness & fruittyness t : huge breadyness & honey malt , plus some herbal hops up front . finishes cakey with loads of hop snap ( herbal & floral ) & a hint of boozeyness mf : chewy with low carbonation & perfect balance drinks great for the abv .  2005 edition . looks really great ; dark amber pour with a big soft pillowy head that gradually dissipates leaving insane amounts of foam .  the mouthfeel is a bit watery , but more substantial than most light beers .

sadly , i did n't take any notes so i have to rely on my feeble memory ! after having one of my favorite local beers , millstream schild brau ( amber ale ) , i decided i wanted something with some hoppy kick to it and saw the snpa on tap . i have no idea why people would drink something like bud ( which laughably touts its high quality hops in their commercials ) when stuff like this is available nationally . this will definitely be my `` go to '' beer when i want something hoppy , though usually i like something a little mellower in this area .  pours a perfect amber with a huge full light tan headskie that just wo n't quit .  and a bit thin d-easy and enjoyable , drinks almost like a session ale .

aroma is surprisingly tame for the style - vague hops run a spectrum of smells , none being particularly strong : warm fruits , piney , spicy , and aspirin . enjoyable , but not a favorite aroma and flavor profile of mine .  pours with a big and frothy head that threates to leave the glass and envelope the room ... beautiful mocha color . less than average lacing , but the head stays around to the end in a diminidhed form . the goodies beneath are a unique and cloudy reddish-brown hue that is murky and inviting .  slightly creamy body , though it falls flat at the front of the palate . it could use ( i ca n't believe i 'm saying this ) a bit more carbonation . or more body .

not much going for it in the smell area . slight malts , tiny willamette scent . eh . the taste is interesting .  pours an absolutely nice deep red colour , with an enormous brwonish head that seems to last forever .  taste and mouthfeel : medium bodied , mid level carbonation .

very nice hazy honey orange color with a small head that quickly fades.. aroma of faint piney/citrusy hops with an underlying maltiness.. wow ! what it lacks in aroma is definitely made up for in taste .  pours a brilliant hazy amber with lots of eggshell colored head .  consequently , the body was found to be light , yet the beer was flavorful , with a nice , almost malty , finish . the mouthfeel was similar to what one would find in most of the american large brew beers .

let us taste it . first , we discover the chocolate at first sip ; then , our palate is greeted by a warm blanket of malt that denotes a rather smooth , yet biscuit-like , mouthfeel . this one , if ordered on draught , must be allowed to sit if you wish to truly experience it - the way it was meant to be .  huge tan head with really tight bubbles . head lingers for the entire glass leaving lacing behind . brilliantly clear .  mouthfeel - medium bodied , very softly carbonated , gets a bit watery as it warms , which is a disappointment . lighter body than expected ( and preferred ) as a result .

thanks to bobsy for this one . smell : having trouble coaxing out an aroma but i do get a mix of yeast and lemon .  appearance : this is probably the most gorgeous pale beer i 've seen up to this point . retention is ridiculous , and lacing is incredible . superb .  the taste was strong sour vinegar with some cherry and alcohol flavors . this one upset my stomach and i think this 2005 vintage was past its prime . god only knows what it was like fresh . this beer was not good and i happen to like sour beers .

nice head , darker than guinness -- i 'd call it light brown instead of tan . the beer is really dark , somewhere between typical porter and typical stout . a bit of a coffee scent ; hints of chocolate . not what i expected . as it is , not bad , but nothing too special . tastes amazing . it 's lightly carbonated , which perfectly accents its flavor . it 's too heavy to really drink a lot of , but it would be great with a steak dinner ( or , i think , mexican food , as odd as that sounds -- think mole saucel ) .  as with all of the beers at the sn brewery , the carbonation is constant and active ; however the column of bubbles is not quite as dense . a big , fluffy , white , foamy head sits on top - looks just like a bubble bath . great head retention and tons of clumpy , foamy lace all the way down .  m : sticky , slight aftertaste .

gives a good two fingers bubbly white head with decent retention and lacing s - a bit of coriander and orange zest/citrus in the nose . feels a bit light in the nose , so i 'm thinking this will be easy drinking t & m - soft mouthfeel , a bit `` fluffy '' .  when poured into a glass the upward cascade of bubbles is a wonder to behold . the contrast of the black color of the beer and the ivory foam head scores highly with me .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with some carbonation on the tongue .

no head or lacing ( 2 ) s : hmm , this is ... interesting ? smells of burnt toast , prunes and a bourbony vanilla ( 3 ) t : oh dear , that 's abrasive .  a personal favorite in terms of appearance . black , usually does n't let light through . nice , thick , somewhat tan head sitting on top and leaving remnants on the glass throughout the drink .  this is an above-average premium bitter that , with a little more body and a less watery mouth feel , might have been a masterpiece .

there is a strongish malt smell with a hint of expresso .  damn fine looking beer- translucent brown with rusty orange highlights and a kick-ass tan head .  the worst part is , right out of the bottle , it 's prickly and way too fizzy , though it has adequate body . while it 's not spectacular , this is a moderately refreshing , sessionable choice that rivals hoegaarden if i want a low-priced wit .

s : as my friend suggested ... it gave of `` foamy '' smell ( sounds weird , i know ) . very mild and nothing really came through in the aroma . t : very smokey and roasty flavor that mixed quite well with the malt character .  just a beautiful sight to pour , very rich and thick , dark thin cream head . smelss and tastes of the following -- coffee , vanilla , chocolate , molasses .  12oz bottle poured into a shaped pint glass . after the initial pour , hopback amber looked exactly as a beer should . the smell and taste were very good , with a crisp grapefruity essence . hopback amber is refreshing and clean , with a solid , but short-lived hops presence that is as fleeting on the tongue as its good looks were in the glass . hopback amber could be a go-to hot weather , or post-workout , beer for hop heads . it was easy to drink and had me imagining i was sitting at a tavern 's outside deck on a lazy , sunny july day .

faint citrusy hop smell with a hint of toffee malts .  thanks to kurtissellen and everetends for throwing this beer into a trade , this beer is about 8 months old a : wow , fantastic , this is what a big stout is supposed to look like inky black with a dark stained mocha wood foamy head that is rich and creamy .  m : really carbonated , even a bit much . thin body otherwise , however -- just a bit more oomph here and this would be epic .

the nose leaves a bit to be desired . either way it is n't as fragrant as i would like . quite excellent and a much better than the nose would leave you to believe .  pours a clear amber with orange hues in the light ; blood red in poor light . lazy bubbles rise up to two fingers of light khaki head that last awhile before falling . there is all kinds of lacing sticking to my glass .  mouthfeel : on the light side of medium with a crisp finish . it is a touch too thin imho . with the malt being so delicous , i want a bit more body to compliment it .

not much aroma . taste is different for a winter warmer and a nice change of pace .  georgeous dark amber brown with an amazingly thick and creamy bubblebath of khaki head sitting on top .  body was a smidgen thin , but it held the 8 % back quite well , i knew it was more that 5 % , but thats what i perceived from this great brew .

aroma is surprisingly subdued . little bit of herbal aroma , slight bit of alcohol .  a : 1 and quarter creamy , fluffy white head with fantastic , thick lacing clinging to the sides of the glass . brew itself was a cloudy goldenrod color .  i 'm 90 % sure this is the same beer as their `` gretchen 's gold '' , which is really what i 'll be reviewing . the bottled version leaves much to be desired vs. on draught . i 've not tasted such a difference between tap and bottle in any other beer . extremely refreshing and drinkable , pleasant sweet malt w/ barely discernable hops for structure . scant head . overall a great beer in its style , with no real flaws . if you can get it on tap , it 's well worth it .

smell is a bit sweet , a hint of bavarian-style sweetness , banana and cloves , but just enough bitterness to balance it . a very distinct smell . taste is deceptive .  hazy apple cider coulourd liquid tumbles from the bottle and stirs up a huge white head which immediately threatens to spill over the lip of the glass . as the head slowly recedes it leaves huge chunks of lace that defy gravity , while a huge circular island takes up residence and refuses to die .  the mouthfeel is a little lighter and more carbonated then i am looking for in the imperial stout category .

this in my opinion is one of the finest hefe weizen ive come across , im not exactly spoiled for choice either where i live though ... . this beer pours a coppery brown colour with a thick head , if poured right has a nice lace too it ... s. not much in the way of an aroma , slight clove and vanilla ... . m. it is nicely carbonated and feels nice and smooth in the mouth , refreshes the mightiest of ( beer ) thirsts in my opinion d. it is a nice drinkable beer , not something that fills you up after 2-3 bottles but it certainly does the trick ... a must i think for any hefe lovers  tried leffe blonde for the first time and it poured as a lovely golden color with an amazing head . probably the best appearing beer that i 've ever had , especially when it was n't even poured into its signature chalice .  a little watery at the end .

it has a slight alcohol ting and smokey coffee/mocha scent . this beer has a nice full body with full viscous mouthfeel and an almost molasses and toffee beginning , moving to a coffee and chocolate taste , then finishing strong with a warming smokey aftertaste . there is a nice blend of maltiness and bitterness . it is very smooth and has the nice imperial stout taste nicely balanced with maltiness and bitterness .  poured this classic from a bottle , dark brown with thick creamy off white head .  mouthfeel was average -- no bad bite , but not much body either .

the smell of the beer was mostly of the alcohol . the color was just like i like em , pitch black .  poured this into my pint glass it has a murky orange color with a freaking huge slightly off white 5inch head . lacing is scattered all over the sides of my glass , man oh man this beer looks fantastic .  m - the pumpkin gives this beer a slick mouthfeel , and it could use a bit more carbonation , too .

nose is really different - chocolate , caramel , and the hops lend a lot of juicy citrus notes ( orange in particular ) , bordering on juicy fruit . black coffee comes on strong as the nose settles down some , though still what i would consider to be a rich , sweet nose . very nice . taste turns the sweetness from the nose on it 's head - right from the start , the hops take charge in this one . finish is bitter , a bit acrid , roastiness edges over to char , and once the dark chocolate in the beginning of the finish fades , becomes a bit unpleasantly one sided . still a really nice experience , but could use a bit less bitterness towards the finish .  i doubt a hefeweizen can be more appealing : pours a hazy golden orange with a massive off-white head that retains impressively ... the paradigm of a hefe .  light body , fizzy carbonation , as expected . basic adjuncts , some sweetness and a light touch of skunk .

a very slight amount of ginger in the nose , but not much at all .  a : a beautiful beer with golden very clear hue topped by massive 3-4 finger white head with pyramid of bubbles -- large at the bottom , small at the top -- with a whipped cream , frothy top with good retention and spots of lace .  the only place that is lacking is the body is a little watery .

aroma is caramel and some toffee mixing with a little bit of grassy and earthy hop qualities , i do get a little band-aid phenol buried in the nose , maybe opened this one just in time to save it .  the huge head has all sizes of bubbles and demonstrates impressive retention and lacing .  a bit fizzy , thinner mouthfeel -but this contributes to the drinkability of the beer .

s : fruity and floral aroma . t : orange flavor initially with some wheat and coriander spices present .  excellent retention and sheets of lace that coat the insides of the glass .  m- medium body , definitely unfiltered .

s : a clean aroma of orange peel and wheat . the smell is n't super strong .  this maerzen came out to be with a decent two finger thick , light tan head . the body is a picturesque dark golden amber color , and very well filtered .  mouthfeel : a ton of carbonation gave this beer a very fuzzy feel to it .

smelled really sweet . brown sugar , caramel , raisins , and a fairly stong alcohol aroma too .  poured a gorgeous 2 '' violet pink head .  oooh not so happy with this so very unfortunately . diaceytl ( sic ? ) characeristics brusquley intrude . me no likey . i 'm certain that there are other good qualities to this brew , but for me the butterscotch stuff supecedes . good bye .

pouring into a glass , it pours a nice black color , and if you like black this is for you , smell well it smell like beer , taste like nice dark larger that you want to drink again .  settles like a nitro with a good finger of head , foamy lacing and great retention .  there is a slight floral hop scent to go along with the malt aroma that you would expect from a beer this dark . this is a flavorful lager . it 's malty without being sweet and there is just enough hoppyness to leave a bite on the tongue .

fairly nice . t- good flavors of pumpkin with caramel malts dominating most of the flavor .  a - jet black . this is as black a beer as i have seen .  overall feel is good enough , but was a bit thin .

aroma is understated , but it 's all about the flavor .  the bottled version pours dark brown , almost black , revealing deep crimson highlights when held to the light . an awesomely creamy tight head the color of chocolate milk shows no signs of stopping even at the bottom of my glass .  body is thinner than expected on the palate , and the uppity carbonation level does n't help .

s- very flowery/powdery , little bit of dryness , hoppy , interesting mix of a kolsch and a lager . t- earthy , less flowery than the nose , not sure exactly how to word it , but it tastes very fresh , delicate hop bitterness hits the back of the mouth , lemon rind , delicate overall but definately drinkable for the fall , it 's a nice change of pace from oktoberfest beers .  a : this beer looks heavy . it pours slowly , and looks very viscous .  mouthfeel is thin and becomes slightly tannic at the finish .

smell is faint , even right after pouring . nothing really leaps out at me - not bad , but nothing really good either . towards the end of the glass as the beer has warmed up some of the hops is a little more present , but again , it is faint .  pours a super black thats tick and oily .  m- medium body , slightly carbonated , has a bit of creaminess to it .
sadly enough not much else going on .  pours pitch black with a strikingly dark , lush head that , for the style at least , hangs around for a long time .  mouthfeel : just barely medium-bodied .

the nose is very yeasty , fairly sweet malts , cocoa .  poured into a weizen a : dark black very little head ... looks amazing i love the way a good solid dark beer looks s : roasted malts hint of dark choclate t : coffee , roasted malt toffe with a kick of hps m : medium body d : the pint went quickly but i personally would only stick to one a session .  surprisingly light in the mouth , and very drinkable , but as i have been rereading some of my reviews lately , i think everything is drinkable , it seems that i would almost always take another .

nothing too exciting . t - delicious lightly toasted malt .  pours cloudy peach with wavy patterns of residual yeast and a billowy , lasting two finger head .  m : fairly light , slick body with a low amount of spiky carbonation . mediocre .

i was hoping the color would be darker but it looks more like a ipa , light yellow like a apwa . taste is spicey with a faint taste of hops , it is not really bitter . the 7.2 is masked very nice i and i could drink 2-3 easy . i read reviews before driking and i exspected this beer to suck but i was suprised at how well they melded the two styles .  exceptional looking beer .  m : medium body and carbonation . it is a little sticky . some sharpness on my tongue as i swallow .
s-nothing overwhelming , a bit of light roasted malt and a hint of licorice .  pours nearly opaqe brown with a huge cascading tan head .  mouthfeel : it was a very light beer .

smell is a standard stout aroma , rather bland , the weakest point of this beer , taste is much more like a hoppy porter than any brown ale i 've ever had , but this is a very good thing , toasty malts with a very pronounced bitter hop presence .  this is one beautiful looking beer . it is a slow pour , due to the vast amounts of light tan head that is created .  the body is light and the carbonation is very high .

s : sweet malt , real light hops . t : great noble hop flavour , grass , hay , soft bready malt .  pours a light golden crystal clear yellow with a massive white head that lasts , lasts , lasts , and lasts leaving a sticky thick lacing all over the glass as you drink .  m : medium-little body , ok carbonation .

smell is malt , light smoke , hint of citrus & spice .  appearance : a slightly hazy , deep reddish-orange body capped by three fingers of off-white head that fades slowly and leaves brilliant lacing .  m : medium but complex body with minimal carbonation .

ample white , creamy cover has a good amount of stickiness and lace , nice . aroma - juicy pineapple , grapefruit , and a resiny pine as well . taste - fair biscuity malt base , followed immediately by a stiff resiny smack of hops .  on tap in a guinness pint glass a-pours a very deep brown almost completely opaque with a nice creamy head that stay with the beer through out almost looks like sand rising to the top of the glass in a perfect ring.this is most definatly one of the worlds best looking beers .  the nose is malty and flowery ( like clover honey ) , but also a bit resinous as well . the flavor is not as sweet as the nose might lead you to think- dry malt and an odd spicyness- like some kind of combination of cinnamon , wood , and earth . this ancient traditional beer is another of those brews with a history - it 's been brewed in scotland for 4000 years . you wo n't think of beer as just a common drink after exposing yourself to this . well worth the experience , it is as complex as any wine you might try .

smell is a bit sub-par , not too strong , pilsner malt comes through , but it a bit unpleasant . i 'm sorry for the blasphemy , but i was reminded of pliny the elder when drinking this one -- hoppy with little malt backbone . maybe not worth the $ 3.49 , but definitely worth a try if you can get it cheap .  one of the coolest looking labels that i 've ever seen . it is blacker than charcoal and forms a great mocha colored head .  this beer is exceptionally thin in the mouth however .

not really breathtaking , but worth a whiff . t - delicious !  poured this into a tulip . looks just as i would hope . the beer pours dark and oily . great retention on this and it settles down to a nice layer of foam with sticky lace throughout the drink . like i said , this one just looks perfect to me .  m : a bit thin , but still decent .

the aroma is not overpowering but definitely has hints of the coffee implied by the name ... very espresso-y . that 's not really a word i guess huh ? the taste is great , very smooth ... .the coffee does n't come to the fore immediately which is pretty cool . the hop notes are pleasant and not sharp ... they accentuate the coffee bitterness which is the way it should be for this style .  11.2oz foamy pillowy head flows up the glass . clumpy head slowly slides down , leaving a rather decent trail behind .  mouthfeel -- medium-light in body with prickly carbonation . slightly gentler carbonation would have been preferable , but a twirl or two dozen remedies the issue .
the nose was a mixture of sweet malts , molasses and toffee . also acceptable .  nice tan head with amazing retention .  a little thin in the body for my taste , and a bit low in carbonation .

s-the smell of this beer is amazing ! having had perseguidor 3 , i would say this is the only trait that is better in 4 . insanely complex nose , smells of wood , funk , dried fruit , chestnuts and roasted malt . truely exceptional . there is virtually no stout flavor , i tastes similar to an old bruin , but thiner and less acidic , a sipper to be sure do to the tartness , but very tasty . d-another great offering in this series , captain ron is a master at blending his styles .  pours a brown black color and is topped by a prodigious light brown head . it is extremely clear and a deep garnet color when held up to the light , a visually perfect beer .  mouthfeel and carbonation are both slightly low .

nose is a bit subdued . musty hops - orange rind , oak , floral notes .  exceptional retention .  tart up front , with ample carbonation clinging to bitter noble hops . mouthfeel is medium bodied with a lingering puckering finish . a decent overall tripel here .

once in the glass from the tap , a beautiful color fils your mind , a perfect not quite brown , honey amber tone with hints of gold . not quite an average ale , but not quite a lager , reminds me of red oak for those of you who have had that pleasure .  pours a huge tan head , with nice retention throughout and good lacing . very dark brown in color with lots of carbonation smells of roast copper malt and some sweet toffee .  medium-bodied rather than thick .

a very light , blonde kolsch that is rather dry with mineralish notes hidden among toasted malt and slightly spicy hops . not much an aroma . a very drinkable beer , with a subtle complexity .  this is a fantastic looking beer .  mouthfeel was of mouthful of hand-picked lickers .

nice creamy head s : slight smokey smell . maybe some chocolate , but i was n't getting much else above the smoke t : smoke taste is subtle at first , strong in the end . for those who are afraid of thick/rich stouts or porters , start with this beauty !  a- black with a real nice thick 2 finger tan head .  the mouthfeel was much lighter than expected with a slight buttery feel .

smell : not extremely aromatic , but a subtle smell of pine scented hops . taste : light hops , crisp faint apple and floral up front that transforms to grapefruit in the back . it really tastes like a hoppy pale ale , but packs a decent 6.4 % that you would n't guess- nor would you peg it for a ipa . as an everyday beer i rate it as an a- , but i can see how some people are turned off on its mildness for an ipa .  from the first pour , i was quite excited since it looked like something i would love .  mouthfeel is pretty standard , with some syrupy texture from the malts .

s - overall , a restrained nose . light amounts of 2-row and some english noble hops .  a slightly hazy gold with a large off-white head that left huge sheets of lace .  man talk about pleasantly surprised ... after the last two i wasnt expecting much from this random brew ... glad i picked the best for last ... pour couldnt get much better with a great levitating head and awesome lacing ... nice floral hop aroma , slight alcohol tone not obnoxious at all ... taste is almost all nutty malt , somewhat dry ... alcohol is amazingly well hidden ... one of the easiest drinking malt liquors ive ever had ... too bad the turks got it right before we did ... keep in mind that this four is rated in accordance to other euro strong lagers/malt liquors ... cheers !

color was nice though , a robust golden-copper blend with glowing maize when held to the light . smell is ok ... there is a definite fruit and hop presence , probably a slight waft of estery alcohol , too .  pours pitch black . huge brown head .  medium body . i found the carbonation to be a bit low and felt the beer would have definitely benefited from more carbonation .

really a very nice beer . surprisngly it did n't have a strong smell , it seemed to be keeping it all in the beer , it tasted of toffee , surprisingly smooth given it 's about 9 % alcohol .  this beer is very nice looking . poured into a lindemans glass , this beer is very red and is topped with a short pink head that leaves sheets of lacing on the glass .  i am truely amazed to find a lighter version of yuengling 's premium . with a little bit less malt . the smell is spring fresh with no skunk to ruin your day . and blindfolded i dont think you could tell the difference in the taste from the premium . { i am becoming quite a fan of yuengling as one might tell ]

s : earth , sweet cotton candy smell .  carbonation looks solid throughout . lacing is fantastic and spiderwebs down the glass .  budweiser is supposidly the most popular beer in america , and it makes me curious as to why . budweiser is standard fodder as far as beers go . its a light golden yellow beer with nothing very remarkable about it . this beer is unimaginative and bland . this beer is no king .

the smell was essentially absent , but what i could sense was sweet .  a - poured out a deep copper hue with a tan , bubbly/soapy , 4-finger head that left sticky rings of lace .  living in georgia , i always heard about it . moving to new york i finally get to try it out . it was so strange that i tried it two nights in a row . it 's like someone dumped turpentine into my brownies . smells great , looks good . tastes bad . big disappointment again from dogfish .

poured a deep copper/orange with a fair bit of fog and a fluffy , thick white head.the smell was average at best and not too much interesting poking out .  cask conditioned ale of the week at the gaslight brewery the look is awesome . looks incredibly creamy and delicious looking .  smooth but lifeless .

s : simply fantastic . i think i literally spent more time smelling this beer than i did drinking it . great stuff .  flash forward to tonight : i really want a beer and no one to drink with - let 's crack the mean manalishi and see what happens ... looks absolutely amazing - everything you 'd want out of a strong midwest iipa : nice dark amber , almost red color . excellent rolling foam off-white head . leaves intermittent thick and sticky lace .  sierra nevada . and newcastle . and needed a change i 'm drinking rogue dead guy for the first time as i type this . for a strong beer .

s : aroma is not forefront to this brew , but it smells like good fermented barley should .  tried this on a whim ... made with raisins and beet sugars , i was hoping for an interesting experiment , but ended up finding one of my favorite recent discoveries , and the best so far by the amazing brewers at dogfish head . the color alone is an experience . i would paint my apartment with that rich , warm , brown-red color .  m - my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin . i may be just really enjoying everything else about this beer which makes we want to forgive it for being thin .

the aroma was not very apparant to this beer , just a slight notion of malt and grain . quite smooth and medium bodied . an excellent draft beer .  cloudy goldenrod with great creamy pure white head and lacing .  light and effervescent , with a hint of caramel malty sweetness . i bought a six pack of this , and after drinking the first beer , immediately grabbed another six . definitely the best 5.99 beer in the store . do n't pick this up if you 're looking for a complex thought-provoking brew . but if you want a session beer that 's a good alternative to macro-swill and are n't into over-hopped domestics like sam adams and goose island , this is a great seasonal . similar to a leinenkugel brew . a friend said that this was what you 'd get if newcastle brewed an amber . drink straight from the bottle - not really enough nuance to bother with a glass .

gorgeous pale ale . muted bready aromas -- cracker and crystal malts , and a touch of caramel , though not overly aromatic and certainly the least hoppy alpine beer i 've smelled to date . clean , simple flavors : bread , a touch of caramel , some citrus hops , though overall very simple and classic . a highly drinkable pale ale , though it disappoints , only because of alpine 's otherwise world-class lineup .  the apperance is exceptional , gold honey in color , the usual amber color . the head was a gorgeous cream color that lasted the whole way through .  m : smooth , full-bodied , but the lack of carbonation makes it a bit watery , the booze can stand out at times . d : this is certainly a tasty beer , but it is very expensive , and at the end of the day i prefer regular old viscosity more , especially with it 's nicer carbonation , body , and the fact that it is considerably cheaper .

holding this beer up to the light it looks amazing , it does n't have as much smell as some beers , but i might just have a stuffy nose !  the appearance is f*cking gorgeous . this is what a stout should look like . pitch black and pours like motor oil . a nice three finger chocolate marshmallow head upon a somewhat forceful pour .  the mouth is spritzy and bubbly . thank goodness for that . if this was mellow and flat , i would purge . flavor is of watered-down tomato soup , celery , and the faintest of grains .

there is a strong citrus grapefruit scent and a deep orange amber color upon pouring , a nice foam head lingers and sticks to the sides of the glass .  d- looks amazing and sure gets you effed up , but i was disappointed with the kaiser after being enlightened by the maharaja .  m - body is a little thin and watery , but silky smooth from the oats d - this is a really good ris - i have been wanting to try it for a while now .
the smell is faint with a slight whiff of honey . very little to no hop presence detected .  keeps a solid skim always present as well as a big fluffy collaring .  m : light body .

s- sweet brown sugar , caramel , hints of belgian yeast and raisin . not a complex belgian . only unibroue and a true belgian can pull of this style it seems .  st-ambroise oatmeal stout from mcauslan brewing pours dark in my glass with a 1 finger light brown head .  m- not its most impressive trait , actually evokes a macro in its carbonation level and texture .
smell- earthy and spicey noble hops . quite hard to get much on the nose out of this beer .  outstanding looking beer .  mouthfeel is unfortunately overly carbonated , it leaves it very bloating .

s : a little hop aroma , a little citrus and some malt ... nothing firm to nail down . t : very well balanced ... you get a nice hit of hops but not to much then a nice caramel like malt ending with a slight bitterness ... . d : very drinkable , tastes great , abv is pretty good and not too filling ... i 'm not the biggest pale ale fan , but this one kind of won me over ... .  moderately thick and quite sticky light tan head has excellent retention and leaves plenty of lacing on the glass all the way down .  m- medium body , slightly watery d- very drinkable . watery , but enjoyable .

very attractive an aroma that reminds me of cooked cabbage and melted cheese comes through on first whiff .  a - a big thick three finger head of densely packed tiny bubbles distributes a huge amount of creamy lace on the glass , and shows outstanding retention . the lace on the glass looks like icy frost on a window in the wintertime . this looks outstanding , and gets a rare five for appearance in my book .  a very thin malt sweetness with a hint of bitterness in the finish . the mouthfeel is unremarkable in any way . it actually has more mouthfeel than flavor .

appearance- comes in a green bottle with the beck 's name printed on it smell- it smells like eggs in the beginning , but it really wo n't bother anyone taste- it has a tad bit of a sugary taste , but it 's a great taste . it 's not watery at all mouthfeel- it 's great drinkability- it 's a great beer that i purchase a lot . next to imperial it 's my top beer .  the pour is excellent . coffee black with a tan head which seems to slowly rise well after the pour .  mouthfeel is kind of thin , and a little watery .

s - subtle nose . citrus and floral notes .  a - when poured properly , guinness draught is stunningly beautiful . cascading flows ride through the dark brown brew rising up the the thick , creamy head .  mouthfeel is carbonated enough , although not a lot .

aroma - roasted malts with a doughy edge . has a slightly full feel to it , but fades a little too much after set up . taste - nice evenly malt flavor , dark and delicious , not burnt or even toasted much .  golden in hue w/ a slight haze , topped by a formidabily thick , creamy , rocky persistant head that leaves lace . it 's reminescent of a belgian strong golden in appearance .  m- smooth , medium-high carbonation , clean , with a hint of dryness in the finish . d- of course . it 's cheap , available everywhere , and quite good .

s - lightly scented - just a bit of yeast spice and light malt notes . the wild yeast notes come through ever so slightly .  exceptional poured revealed a giant thick and chunky beige head.almost looked like a rootbeer float.long strands of sticky lace circled my glass.the aroma was great with smells of cinnamon , nutmeg , and hops.a medium body ale with a dark almost black red color.the finish was long and bitter that lasted in the back of your throat.the finish had an almost chemical or medicine-like taste.very malty and somewhat thick.the aroma seemed to offer more than the actual taste.a very smooth mouthfeel that seemed to lack in carbonation upon swallowing.an overall good beer.i would buy this again because i think the taste will grow on me later .  feels a bit watered-down in the mouth , but flavor is there and we 're not talking corona . a little fizzy .

scent is a bit floral , a bit bitter and ever so slightly nutty .  pours a beautiful crystal clear gold with hints of amber and amazing active bubbles . nice bright white 1 finger head . this is what a pilsener should look like , a beauty . this beer glistens .  i hate to give a beer ( especially a trappist ) a bad review but this beer was not very good at all . i had a few sips and then poured the rest of the 750 down the drain . i may have gotten a bad batch but i found this beer to be quite bitter and sour and not what i would expect from a tripel .

a bit of nuttyness comes through and finishes with a bit of dark coffee .  this has surprising carbonation for such a big beer . creamy head has great staying power . i 'm really impressed that the beer can be so mellow and so strong .  mouthfeel : full-bodied , low carbonation . there 's an odd chalkiness .

this is a great stout . there is coffee , malt , brown sugar , chocolate . its just not the overpowering nose present i was expecting . the taste is good , not great with much of the smell being tasted in direct proportioned amounts . the beer looked great when i poured it but my first hint that this was n't going to live up to the hype was in the nose . still thouroughly enjoyable .  the color is a deep , deep leather brown . floating contently above it was a beautiful cap of mocha-colored foam . definitely an inviting site .  i usually really enjoy drinking founder 's brews . it is missing much of the character that founder 's usually has from its selection of hops and malts . i could n't finish this , as it reminded me of raspberry pucker . somewhere someone probably really likes this brew , but it was way too sweet for me . sorry founder 's , but this seems like you tried too hard and failed . i 'll still have other founder 's brews because of there fairly good track record with me .

the smell is a magnificent , floral , citrusy hop aroma with a hint of pine . phenomenal . hop flavor is much more woody than anything else . overall it 's strong and `` extreeeme ! a bit disappointing in its extremity .  much darker too . gorgeous beer . big craters make it look like the dark side of the moon .  carbonation is just a bit higher than i like ... .and the liquid is a bit think to be really pleasing . a bit more body would be a good thing .

pours golden with a little haze , 1.5 finger of head , leaves beautiful lacing . smell , a little hops , kinda watery some yeast , ca n't make out anything specific taste : piney hops with some bite , pretty much just hops , finishes with alcohol notes that remind me of rum , warms a little body is medium , carbonation is pretty high , very crisp . leaves a little oily finish .  the color is as promised - not just copper , but the most refined , polished expression of crystalline copper purity you 've ever seen in an ale . the head is feathery and shows graceful retention and lace .  aroma of allspice , nutmeg , figs , apples , leathery yeast , and pepper . flavor of dark fruits including plums and cassis . slightly sour . palate lacks expected richness . good but not great like the previews ( appearance and aroma ) lead you to believe .

hints of toffee and pecans shrink behind a moderately roasted but otherwise unremarkable nose . everything is on display here ; light nuttiness is followed by a sometimes chocolaty , sometimes fruity body with no shortage of roasted quality . the finish is delightful , owing bitterness to both roasted malt and elegant hops ( cascade must be bittering because this is tettnang all the way ) .  a - nice and black , medium brown foamy head that does n't fade much and lastes throughout the session . the head also laces the glass evenly . i 'm impressed .  a little bit overcarbed but otherwise smooth .

nose is weak , no doubt there .  the beer poured deep golden and slightly hazy , topped by a dense , off-white head . excellent lacing remained on the glass .  the finish is fairly dry and woody , but the body is a little flaccid without much supporting carbonation .

i was in a bar , so my already weak nose ca n't give a review of this .  beautiful beer bottle brown . it 's full , like a silk pillow .  tumbler pours a perfect dark brown smellign of roasted malt and nutty goodness . first sip is a mix of hops and chocolate , caramel deliciousness . nice malt backbone and easy going down . nice drinkable brown ale for session drinking . certainly worth your money and time to enjoy .

smells like caramel malts with a hint of hops .  bottle : poured a dark brown color ale in my trappist glass with a good inch of off-white foamy head with excellent retention .  m- a little on the watery side , a little carb still hangs around .

does n't tantelize me with its aroma tatste was very nice though , big malts throughout with hints of caramel and cherries and a slight warmth from the alcohol .  500 ml bottle poured into a white wine glass fridge temp lot 07/19/11 appearance : pours a golden orange color with quite a vigorous head which is white . great retention , soapy entrails , tons of lacing . very nice .  a bit light bodied with ample carbonation .

s : sweet roasted malts ; burnt toffee , slightly smokey aroma .  pours a hazy orange color with a beautiful amount of thick head . head retention is very good , with above average lacing left on the glass .  m : thick , creamy , almost sticky . a bit too heavy for me .

hats off to my beer brother james for giving me this bottle as part of a birthday present package . the subtelty of the finish is the best part ... no bitter beer face  combined w/ the copious , lively bubbling and clear , light amber hue , this beer is vibrant and visually appealing .  aroma is all grassy and sour , smells very much like a german helles lager . the rest of the way this is a great balance of malt and hops . otherwise the beer is spot on and is fine summer drinking experience . this is a beer that is obviously well made and a pleasure to drink . the only catch is that the price of a 6 pack of great lakes is not really much different than most german lagers such as spaten , warsteiner , etc . so i 'm thinking the major reason to buy this over those would be the freshness of the beer . if the price difference were two bucks a sixer less i would make this beer one of my default lagers for sure .

the aroma ... . light sweetness ... light malt . not much on the aroma ... the taste ... quite good .  it looks great . pilsener colour with a fat creamy top .  if this beer has anything going for it , it 's a decent body which lends itself to an okay drinkability rating .

s-very good . the smell of toasted grains hits you right off . traces of caramel , chocolate malts , as well as some grassy hops . t-not what it smelled like . very disappointing .  bottled on 12/15/11 this beer is dark , darkest head i have seen .  seems nicely carbonated , but a little thin .

s- lime , some sort of ... hmm , it smells like ginger ale a bit .  lacing is superb but head retention is merely `` well above average . '' color is an opaque blackness that turns a reddish brown only when held up to the brightest lights at the thinnest portion of your glass .  m-for a beer and a stout this is a very odd mouth feel . it is super creamy and leaves a mess on your tongue .
the smell is pretty simple , grainy malts and not too much else .  a amazing . viscous , onyx with a tan-garnet head , very sticky .  mouthfeel - refreshing but a little sour-ish on the tongue .

pours reddish light brown , appearance is closest to a belgian dubbel in my opinion , which may be a consistent characteristic . nose is strong on the bourbon which is a definite plus in my book - so often these bourbon aged beers dont carry as much of the characteristic .  poured an opaque dark baker 's chocolate brown with a slow rising tan head that fills the glass and stays up forever yeilding a thick wall of lace , just beautiful . and that 's just after the pour , i hav n't even smelled it yet !  of course . a little high in the effervescence .

smell is ok . the sweet caramel malts cover up a lot in the nose . i pick up the slightest bit of hops and orange peel when i really get a good swirl .  pours a super clear magnifying fiery orange/red . a modest off white to tan head is bubbly from the the profile and creamy up top .  very thin body and i could easily put away six of these . i feel it is a little thin overall and that would be something i would like to see changed .

s -malt and earthy english hops . f - excellently balanced . sweet malt is upfront and there is a buttery diacetyl nuance .  this brew pours with a beautiful deep amber body topped by a thick off-white head with a good amount of lacing .  low carbonation .

smells of dry dirty yeast , sweet corn and plumb skins .  appearance : the beer poured a nice 3 finger chocolate colored head . also , beer is pitch black with no clarity and no signs of carbonation . the head of beer has not come down yet and will have to say the retention is fantastic and lacing on the glass .  just a bit too light bodied , i would have prefered it thicker , otherwise a good session beer .

not much aroma initially.nice 2 finger foamy head . feels like at porter wiuth the exception of nice spiciness to it .  poured from a bottle into a dogfish snifter a- pours a perfectly transparent shade of yellow/orange with a big two finger white head that 's very puffy . looks perfect s- citrus hops with a big of a bite to them ... .lovely t- getting a lot of citrus , but it almost tastes like dishwater ... no real bite to the hops at all .  i saw this on the top of a shelf in the back of a local beer store and it was not priced but i decided to buy it and give it a try seeing who i never hear of it , i think i bought it for a quarter . i was very suprised when i poured it out , it was a nice pale ale and it was full of hops aroma and flavor . when i drank it i just sat back and sipped it tring to enjoy every drop . well done .

overall presentation was spot on s : grains , feeble stale coffee , touch of chocolate sweets m : mostly barely and light malts . creamy and super slick d : yes , very drinkable and inviting  a : pours a beautiful , slightly opaque , medium golden . enormous light yellow head that show fantastic retention .  poured into my maudite snifter and produces a caramel color with a finger and a half of off-white foam . light carbonation . banana , pear and floral aromas . a rather tart , spicy taste with some alcohol taste present . while this is highly drinkable , the experience is more enjoyable as it warms .

aroma is a slight improvement , with some great berry and cream characters backed by a heavy perfume of booze .  bottle purchased at julio 's liquors , westboro , ma poured a somewhat hazy , light straw with a huge , five-finger bubbly head . the resulting chunks of froth eventually faded to a dollop of foam in the middle of the glass , which lasted for most of the drink . tons of bubbly , sticking lacing throughout .  mouthfeel was deceptively thin because of the high carbonation , but was n't that bad if given a chance .

not a very strong smell emminating , but heavy on the malts and chocolates with some sense of coffee . definately a roasty scent .  the pour begins with an ever-expanding head that forms quickly and sorta takes over . very mousse-like and very sturdy in formaiton and retention . the color is the standard copper-golden and with typical dry-hopped haze . an outstanding look .  mouthfeel has a medium body with a spritzy carbonation that is much too high .

nose is awesome in my book . big toasted nuttyness with chocolate and a hint of deeper roast . very well balanced and very enticing . flavor is very good as well .  a : pours a brilliant , hazy gold . one of the creamiest 2-finger eggshell heads i 've ever seen , with excellent retention .  this felt very light on the palate , but given it is a pale ale it does what it is supposed too . again the sense of freshness was brought through to the taste .

smell is the weakest point here , mostly smells like metallic yeast .  great looking pour : 3f worth of white head over a deep golden body , with plenty of carbonation flowing up . really nice lacing , too .  mouthfeel is ok , but a bit to thin for what i expect from a stout .
a light scent - similar to blue moon .  this pours a nice rosewood color with a good pillow head on the top that is well retained with beautiful lacing down the glass .  mouthfeel : a touch thin .

malty and sweet but rather mild . a hint of dry yeastiness and just a bit of light fruit , mostly uneventful but still appetizing . not too terribly flavorful but pleasant . certainly a nice session beer . very nice overall , decently balanced and a good accompaniment to food .  looks delicious . very good looking beer .  it felt a little too thin , with less carbonation than i would have liked .

s - some banana esters and wheat twang but very little here . t - subdued banana esters followed by the soft caramel taste of pilsen malt , finishes with some wheat twang .  a : pours a somewhat cloudy pale pink with a beautiful pinkish-white head that never goes away and leaves one the nicest , stickiest laces i 've ever seen . gorgeous .  mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side for the style .

s - sweet plums and malt . t - robust hops flavor throughout .  this is a great looking beer ... .as black as you can get .  5.5 % abv . fizzy off-white head . ) & ginger..macro-ish metallic attributes as well . plenty of sweet honey right off the bat..the combination of that and the tangy overuse of lemon peel made me feel like i was eating a pack of skittles . a ton of ginger thrown in for good measure.. wow , is my palate confused on whether or not this is a beer . certainly a bold taste from an interesting beer , but the flavors honestly do not blend together well at all . it 's hard to believe our forefathers would drink this stuff.. i hope they had better taste , because yeah , this one did n't work for me at all .

appearance : this is definitely not a pitch black stout . smell : not much . taste : awesome . the first thing that jumps out at me is the roasted flavor , then coffee , then creaminess . this is definitely a relative of left hand 's milk stout , but jacked up on imperial steroids .  a : it poured a thick , black with a massive dark chocolate three finger sticky head .  t & m : slightly alcoholic bite at first . very fizzy taste of citrus with a somewhat sour lemony wheat taste . d : very fizzy so will fill ( bloat ) you quickly . exemplary of the style .

the smell is big and hoppy ; piney and sappy with hints of malt sweetness . the first taste is medicinal in a high alcohol way .  it was a clear dark honey color with lots of carb streams and great lacing . it had a massive white head that took forever to whittle down to a constant 1/4 '' foam .  m - light and fizzy .

all these flavors and more really hit your nose as well . wow .  i poured this into a palm tulip and belgo made a good two finger thick head , and the body is nicely filtered and is copper in color . head retention is outstanding .  the moutfeel is medium , thicker than a lager , but about average for this style .

smell was almost non-existent .  poured a very unusual and quite beautiful shade of ruby or perhaps garnet , quite striking visually which i was not really expecting .  it doesnt stand up to much like the bigger stouts im used to and has a bit of a watery feel to it .

being a long time fan of belhaven beer , i eagerly awaited the opporunity to try this one . ) the nose , while somewhat average , is subtle in that there is some notes of pear . the palate detects some lemon hint backed by a pliant hoppiness that makes for a smooth body . this is not the greatest ipa out there , but it is belhaven , a brewery that has always gotten my respect .  poured from bottle into tulip a- beautuful thick off white head . stout like . head lasts and leaves perfect rings of lace . body is pretty dark .  lacing is minimal and carbonation is low . sweet toasted malts are the dominant flavor followed by a slight dry hop finish . an all around good easy drinking session beer that almost anyone could enjoy . a solid choice for any occasion .

smell : mild caramel is all that is picked up .  bottle into a tulip glass . the color is a dark and opaque black with some light brown foam and so nice lacing .  body is a bit thin , but overall it has good drinkability .

the aroma is almost neutral , and the taste is very mild , with some extremely slight hop spiciness .  appearance wis is is a fairly typical black brew with a very nice brown head leaving a good lace . the high gravity of the stout adds to the aroma with a whiff of alcohol .  medium mouthfeel .

smelled of brown sugar and ginger like scent , plenty of spice , and some sweet malt presence in the back .  the retention of the delicate cap was terrific and the lacing prodigious . it looked great , felt great and smelled good but the taste just was n't what i wanted .  i would recommend this beer both as a meal beer and a drinking man 's beer , versatile and a solid wheat ... not too fruity , but not to plain ... too carbonated , but i imagine a great american/bavarian weisse on tap .
