the smell is light for a siason . a still noticeable smell with a note of candi sweetness and lighter belgium malts . a light phenol aroma is also there but subtle . the taste is smooth .  dark red-brown/mohagony body topped by a thick off-white lasting head with a good amount of lace left on the glass .  m- carbonation is high , and initial mouthfeel is good , but somewhat thin .

clear amber colored light bodied , starts malty/hoppy , finishes hoppy . nose is indistinguishable no floral hops , no malt nada .  i got a chance to try this at cobblestone 's last night -served chilled in a pils glass . the beer is downright beautiful , dare i say elegant looking in the glass ? the pale is brilliant golden with amber hues and has great clarity with thick sturdy cap of snow white . the lace clings in rings and bead is fine , good retention all around .  m : it was watery with lots of carbonation .

smell was very light , minor hop odor lingering , not to much else .  liked it last year ; let 's see how this stacks up pours caramel with 2.5 fingers of rocky off-white colored head . stellar head retention & lacing s : subdued hop nose up front .  this beer is very balanced m : little bit of body but still water and plenty of carbination but it complements this beer extremely well d : give me a twelve pack of these and i would be glad to finish them any time .

s- roasted malts , peppercorn ? and caramel , a bit of hop spice and baking chocolate .  a : pours a clear straw yellow , nice 3 finger bone white head settles to a small cap , lacing everywhere and sticks to the glass like almost no other beer i have drank , save for duvel .  m - medium body . a touch watery at times .

aroma is very mild with slight grainy notes and a hint of hops .  it makes a great first impression , with a hazy yet brilliant orange color being topped by a thick , creamy , off-white head that leaves great lacing as i emptied the glass .  carbonation is a bit higher than i would have preferred . overall impression : other than the prickly carbonation , this was a great beer - nice balance of flavors , highly drinkable , should go well with food

s : some chocolate and coffee notes.. not getting a huge scent off this one ... t : sweet chocolate . d : i could do a six pack of this.. a pretty decent imperial stout , for a pretty fair price .  a - this brew is a black as i 've ever seen any beer . it is the perfect black . this has the looks by which all other stouts should be measured . ~ this is a stellar example of what a stout should be .  the carbonation felt on the high side to me .

pours a dark mahogany , sort of like a lighter brown ale . no discernible aromas from the beer upon the initial pour . very refreshing and smooth for an american style barley wine . at 8.5 % , probably a beer i would only have one-i enjoyed this at the end of the meal after having two two hearted ales . a nice meal , a great finish !  this beer is a great looking o'fest beer .  mouthfeel great carbonation . perhaps a little thin , but not a detraction . a bit sticky on the aftertaste .

s : citric and a little cindery t : this is a different taste ; there is fruitiness and some spiciness .  poured a delcicious deep amber that was absolutely clear . the carbonation was perfect ; a two finger head persisted for several minutes before leaving a thin lace .  not exactly a esb by definition but a good beer by my standards . a dark beer in color , with a fruity hint on the nose , of apple and a strawberry sort of smell . the taste is smooth fruity and a bit hoppy all at once . my only complaint was a bit of a bitter after taste , but hey it is a esb

smell is malty , with a hint of cabbage , straw .  poured into a tulip glass . the appearance of ommegang in a tulip glass is one to behold .  carbonation was ok , but with the heavier than expected mouthfeel , i think the hops were lost on the palate more than others textures .

i was underwhelmed on first try of this brew . i find that a heavy , yeasty aroma masks most the fruit and malt notes .  very high carbonation . about 2 '' of tan head forms that has phenomenal retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is rather full but not heavy , and it is certainly not full-bodied but moderate .

s- mild aroma of some sweet apple .  half dark brown liquid half egg cream like foam . staying power is somewhat exceptional .  to me smelled like wheat/grain , nuts . t : taste just like you would expect , after smelling . d : pretty good beer , surpassed my expectations . could drink this one all night and be satisfied !

s - this is all about anise . some cocoa tries to pop through . t - anise , root beer , cocoa and cough syrup , the latter i did n't care much for at all . small bitter in finish , but kinda cloying . d - was happy to try .  this is the first time i had a foreign hefeweizen and i am very impressed . i love it .  m : the only real cavet of the brew is the feel . but it 's generally a bit thin .

big and fruity smell that reminds me of raisins .  the appearance is positively phenomenal . a deep ruby body fills my gulden draak tulip , capped with four inches of absolutely perfect head .  rich deep amber red / clear / mild carbonation / mild head sweet sugar almost like a cake / fruity and roasted sweet and tart / significant bitterness / powdery malt / rich roasted / fruity floral hop impact too / interesting sushi flavor must be spices and proteins or maybe it just smells like horseradish / rich caramel sweetness / finishes tart mildly spicy carbonation / medium body beautiful color . would go nicely with sushi . high enjoyable brew .

it smelled very rank and tasted even worse . very unpleasant .  poured black with a nice tan head that didnt last long .  about half-way down the glass , the mouthfeel seem smoother and slicker as well .

smell- creamy , milky , mocha aroma . the best smelling milk stout i have ever come across . as it says on the bottle `` utterly amazing ! '' .  this was poured at 60 deg into a large belgian glass from a capped belgian style bottle . thick frothy dark brown head sits atop a velvety black abyss .  these two attributes remind me of a sparkling cider , but nowhere near as sweet . ends with playful yeast rawness and spiciness a little too fuzzy in the mouth , but like most hefe 's i could hardly keep it from my lips

since this beer moved out of latrobe , it left the slightly bad taste back the old rolling rock 's used to have back in western pa . the new beer is the most refreshing and lightest beer out there . as others mentioned , its great to quench thirst with food or to pound several in the summer heat .  can poured dark brown-black , lots of creamy bubbles in the body that slowly rise to the top to create a creamy thick meringue head on top of the dark beer . nice odor of chocolate and coffee not too heavy taste with a nice lingering coffee feel basic stout that i think sets the above average drink .  smell : piney hops and malts are slightly toasty , tickles the nose readily easily . taste : hop sensation is immediate , blending with the mild toasty-earthy malt taste , progressing to a light , tangy-hop bitterness in the finish , surprisingly balanced . drinkability : darker than a typical ipa , the character of the malts successfully complements the well-hopped taste , very drinkable .

very long lasting had nose is small . hops present but fairly undefined . a little rich for the style .  it pours a really pretty reddish brown with a nice off white head that just lasts and lasts . very pretty , lol .  the one area this beer disappoints is in mouthfeel , where it falls into a watery trap .

the smell is simple : floral , citrus and grains .  this guy poured a deep amber/red , with an awesome amount of creamy foamy head that retained very well and left tons on the sides of the glass .  m - my only knock against the beer is that it has a thinner than expected mouthfeel .

the smell was of malt with a slite hint of hops . overall this one was excellent .  nice lacing . looks very thick .  it tastes like a quadrupel ... .vinous , lots of sticky caramel malts , somewhat flat mouthfeel ( which i 'm never all that fond of ... i wish quads could be more prickly somehow ) ... but again , the addition of the slightly sour cherry keeps this from being a garden-variety quad .

the aroma is mainly of hops with a little bit of caramel malt . there was a little bit of a chemical like aroma too . i thinking maybe i have a bad bottle .  bottle , a : pours a cloudy sun yellow , with a perfect cap of white foam , great retention , with extensive lacing .  mouthfeel was a little bit thin , thus it did n't pair well with the taste .

taste had a malty , sour fruit finish to it . not a bad lil brew , but ive had better dubbels . still a very good performing brew .  hoppy , approachable , and ( like most southern tier beers ) a highly attractive appearance . most southern tier beers have a clear body and brilliant color , and this beer is no exception .  mouthfeel ; loose and smooth , with weak carbonation , certainly not flat though , nothing special just quality .

taste is really , really solid but the aroma was rather bizarre with a strange `` coffee-gone-bad '' funk to it or something .  pours with a dark brown to black body topped by a thick creamy tan head with good lacing .  shortfalls are slightly thin , flattens out fast , washing out the complexity , and slight sour aftertaste -- which is fleeting . but perfect balance is why i give this super-smooth coffee-style beer a high rating .
the aroma is very light , small amounts of hops but that 's pretty much it .  black in hue with a tan head .  quite a strong tongue-tingling carbonation , a bit too much for my taste .

aromas of yeast , malt , grains , and hops .  gorgeous clear and deep mahogany oak pour , topped by a massive ivory head . really liked the sediment goodies at the end of the bottle .  this was probably just average on the mouthfeel , imo - whether you consider this a wild ale or bsda .

a -- clear dark brown with a nice thick tan head ... very nice . s -- most disappointing thing about this beer . a mild malty smell but not much else . t -- what it lacks in smell it makes up in taste . d -- a delightful beer , a session beer for sure .  bottle : poured a hazy deep yellow color ale with a super large foamy head with perfect retention and great lacing reminiscent of belgian ale .  carbonation is a bit on the high side , body is light to medium , mouthfeel is a bit syrupy .

i ca n't say that i was thinking to myself , `` man this thing is going to be awesome '' aroma is skunky and just plain awful .  coal black body with a rich , milk chocolate brown head that stacks up like abandoned cars in a snowstorm . the head clings to the side of the glass as i drink , and it leaves fluffy chunky rings .  found the body to be a little watery and well carbonated .

the smell is a little sour and tart . some cloying sweetness and a lot of alcohol .  a : bright golden with large foamy white head with great retention and lace grabbing glass the enitre way down .  mouthfeel : the weight and carbonation do well , nothing bad to say about it , nothing extraordinary .

light toasty malt is about all i get from the aroma . maybe it 's just a style of beer i do n't appreciate , but i 'm not impressed yet . lightly toasted grains with subtle hop bitterness . fairly clean flavor over all with a bright crisp bitterness . a nice sweetness and subtle fruitiness . what impresses me most is the clean freshness to this beer . it 's a very solid oktoberfest beer with a nice toasted malt profile and slight hop character , but unfortunately i 'm not a huge fan of most lagers .  pours a ruby color with a 1 finger fluffy pink head . good amount of carbonation rising . just beautiful to look at .  the body is medium , smooth but a little weak - medium carbonation adds a touch .
s : not much aroma . faint dry , woodsy smell if anything at all .  hazy dark yellow colour . there is a huge off-white head which lasts and lasts .  m : a bit dry . average carbonation .

appearance is light straw with a decent sized head that retains solid lacing throughout . little to no hop aroma in this one ; sweet malts only . typical for the style .  short , sustainable head with a creamy looking dollop of foam clinging to the glass . extremely enticing .  i was debating if i should review this beer at all since after reading everyones reviews it seems to be well liked . however i continue with my opinion to state perhaps that in my area of distribution ( ri ) this would be what to expect . it tastes , smells , and almost lookes like the marzen . the yeast bite is overpoewering and no true flavors come through . there is a bit more caramel and no roasted and the beer isnt even dark . its orange in color and tangu in taste . i was hoping i had a mislabeled marzen , but thats not he case . the yeasty soapy/buttery flavor is dominate . hopefully this is a bad batch , not a bad beer , and i will try to revisit it later .

coffee grounds and some light cocoa aromas .  first off , this brew is a picture perfect pour for a german pilsner . ultra clear and golden body , with a brilliant white head . retention lasts for a few minutes and diminishes into clumpy lacing .  taste : sweet and funky but so refreshing . mouthfeel : lingering taste .

nice , if subdued .  pitch , midnight black colour with a creamy , foamy , long lasting tan head . great lacing . pretty much as good as a stout looks .  somewhat thin on the mouth , dale 's pale tastes like citrus hops , only a hint of malt . it 's crisp and clean , quite hoppy . a great example of the style , and very refreshing .

the head is a fine texture but does n't stick to the glass much s- aroma is a lighter grainy smell with a little bit of corn .  pours a beautiful cherry-brown hue with a significant cap of creamy , active foam.. gorgeous .  it is a bit thin and has a low abv , but this makes the beer a great summer refresher , when you do n't want a heavy beer .

smell : very slight smell to this beer . taste and mouthfeel : a very nice and balance malt taste to it .  i 've never had this on tap , and as such , feel that canned beer always has a metallic flavor the appearance is excellent with a nice cascade effect as it 's poured with an attractive clear copper color . good head retention as well .  medium and a little grainy with prickly carbonation .

smells of alcohol , some malt and an unpleasant ground corn . on a side note , this beer is best consumed out of the bottle ( and with some chips and salsa of course ) because of the aroma ( smells like a cheap macro to me ) is not appealing .  a- the settles out to a nice two fingers of off white frothy head that holds wonderfully and leaves some spots of lace at first then an epic landslide of think foam grabs hold and slowly cascades down the glass .  only bummer part , was a bit too thin and carbonated .

smell : some very mild bread and grassy tones are hard to pull out of the glass , but pleasant . taste : mild bready maltiness with some apples , sweet green grapes , and some soft grass in the background .  this brew poured an opaque black colored body with a dark brown head that was mostly lasting .  there 's a thin hop-tea mouthfeel that is not bold enough for the style , and the hop-tea quality of the bittering is also less than stellar .

smell is pretty average to be honest . not a lot of hop character , just a mild malt flavor and some typical lager sourness .  really fantastic retention from the one-winger white head .  ok , born and raised in st.louis.. i may be a bit biased . but last summer , i had my heart stole by this beer . i didnt want it to happen.. it just sorta did . its bright a little rich , and nice bitter finish . citrus and maybe honey , i think in these hot humid summers , it cant get any better than a nice summer kolsh at about 35 degrees . ahhhh

i was impressed with the rich amber colour , but the smell was very plain . could n't really get a whiff of anything off this beer . the mouthfeel is gorgeous , very creamy and goes down an absolute treat . overall very nice , i 'd drink it again . its there in the smell as well , however faint .  2010 vintage poured into a nonic . pours a deep , viscous black with a thick dark khaki head .  similar to points cascade pale ale where the hop just shines right through and you taste the hops in every swig . the abv has to be pretty low cuz it was a little watery tasting . but overall a great refreshing , thirst quenching summer brew . i 'm guessing the batch was limited , cuz i heard horizon hops are in real short supply .

bone white head ontop of a watered-down coffee pour . aroma of coffee , toasted , buttery bread and grilled cheese . ( i know , fuckin weird , but i ca n't deny it . ) light cocoa powder , nutella smeared toast , and ovaltine powder .  appearance : thick white/tan chunky head with excellent retention and nice lacing . a better looking red ale you 'll be hard pressed to find .  alcohol and bolder flavor peak at about 60 degrees m & d : pretty thin on the mouth and not as carbonated as you 'd expect based on the intense head .

pretty light amber color that was fairly clear ( also surprising ) that turns more of light straw when held to the light . there was a really nice white head from the pour that lasted for quite a while and left some white specks down the glass . citrusy , piney and some sourness also . t : very , very drinkable for a dipa . crazy how drinkable and smooth this is . not quite at the top of my list my really good .  this brew produces big bright white and rocky head . the body is hazy with a white/gold colored body .  mouthfeel : a little thin , but not bad .

first thing i get is faint herbal hops in the nose . lightly metallic . rich , far more rich that the nose suggested .  it pours a nice ruby brown color with an amazingly thick foamy , slightly creamy off white head . amazing retention we 're talking about with this beer .  also a bit of a watery feel .

while not offensive , the smell is timid sweet and slightly fruity like a peach cotton candy ... not at all what you might expect .  pours tar black with a thick dark tan head with abundant lacing . one of the most impressive beers i have ever layed eyes on .  m-to me its a little thin to carry around this level of hops .

s- there is a rich perfumed caramel malt flows even during the pour with a cream note and a dark malt hint adds depth to this rich aroma . t- the dry toasted malt has a faint caramel note with a soft bitter hint in the finish with a slight sweetness . d- this amazing aroma is wonderful but the taste just does n't follow through with the same richness and depth .  a- beautiful looking beer in my opinion , light yellow color , hazy with a foamy , long lasting head .  m - sticky for a bock with low levels of carbonation .

this pale poured a deep gold color with a good finger size head . unfortunately , i could n't pin down a definite aroma . it was sweet , but that 's all i could determine . perhaps my nose had an off night . the perfect timing of taste continues as the beer has a solid hoppy finish . it leaves you wanting another taste , while retaining a the hoppiness a pale lover would enjoy .  a : pour is a hazy light orange , almost like a creamsicle . 3 inches of frothy head sinks slowly back into the beer .  it has good body , but a decent amount of carbonation . mouthfeel is still good , just not great .
s : weak . could n't smell any hops .  this beer is one of the most beautiful beer i have ever seen in a glass .  a bit thin in the mouthfeel but nothing off-putting .

the smell is heavy on the chocolate malt . very little else is noticeable .  half a pour leaves a towering 4 finger pillow in my snifter . the beer is jet black , and lacing is excellent when the head finally dies down .  the mouthfeel is ... well ... ok ... a little bit of an after taste and the alcohol is apparent ... the beer is absolutely worth a try ...

this is a good looking pale ale that has just the slightest orange/reddish hue . the aroma is pretty light of grains , hops and just a touch metallic .  a - vibrant , pale golden yellow with a massive , pillowy , tightly-packed cream colored head that rises high and just sits .  it does feel a little thin in your mouth , but it smells exactly what it 's name says : a cocoa porter . the beer tastes like chocolate milk made with nesquick or ovalteen or anything other chocolate powder brand with a mild , beer after-taste .
smell : i detected some berries and citrus , good hops , some grain , and a light malt .  great head retention .  m : carbonation comes on unexpectedly crisp , but it drinks smoothly .

ok lacing aroma of malts , caramelly . slight bit of hops , english herbal in nature .  looks incredible . the smell was a bit disappointing .  mouthfeel : a bit loose , i expected it to be a bit thicker . carbonation is spot on though .

i drank this out of a 12oz stein glass ... pour is a darker than amber/lighter than copper hue with an off cream colored head that settles ... .nose is unremarkable ... slightly perfumed with a touch of floral hop aroma but nothing of particular note .  wow , one of the best looking beers i have ever had . pours a clear dark copper hue with an extremely generous light khaki colored head .  mouthfeel was disappointingly thin and watery with a medium amount of carbonation .

not much for smell here . a bit sour and malty . the flavor is awesome with big hops and a subtly paired malt .  pours black and appears to be clear if one could see through it , a big tan/light brown head rests without much thought to receding above this moderately carbonated ale .  m : slightly watery , but forgivable considering its low alcohol content .

rye crystal and malted oats gives it the colour and aroma , challenger and goldings give it the bitterness .  a : poured a sexy orangle color with good carbonation and a nice fluffy white cap s : bread , caramel , citrus and pine t : starts off with sharp booze , pine , orange peel , other citrus and sharp bite m : medium body , tasty , booze is stinging and pungent but not to bad , lots of flavor here o : this ia big , bold in your face hoptacular iipa .  bottle thanks to scoobydank referral ! blackberry is heavy on the nose . very nice . blackberry hard on the front , then a nice porter , then blackberry hard on the finish . i recommend this one , try it , for the price , you cant go wrong . honestly nothing more i can say about it . worth it , but not amazing .

s : mild brown sugar suggests sweetness to come , but is otherwise fairly featureless .  pours an opaque brown with an off-white head . almost 0 light was shining through the liquid which was pretty cool .  weakest aspect of this beer is the body , which is a bit on the thin side , with light carbonation .

s : this one 's yeasty with a hint of alcohol in there which masked other things for me . t : caramelized malts and plum seem to dominate as well as a smokey taste .  poured a beautiful color , phenomenally shiny , that shifted slowly from gold edges to deep but lustrous amber in the middle . had a thin and simple soft head , sat very well , with thick and slow lace that leaft a stain of sloppy but wide horizontal strings and splotches . a good looking glass of beer , no doubt . smelled of soft pumpkin , moderate toffee malts , with notes of sweet cinnamon and hearty nutmeg poking up , as well as small hints of cinnamon .  m - even , with a slight bitter aftertaste .

i love kolsch . s & # 8211 ; clean sweet german malt , and light esters . t & # 8211 ; this brew has the distinct german taste , presented in a big , rich , full manner and avoiding the sweatiness .  pours black with the prettiest dark tan head that slowly subsides .  mouthfeel was n't terrible , with the nice carbonation going on it actually kinda danced on the tongue .
smell - caramel pasty with a extremely slight hint of hops .  it is as black as anything i 've ever seen and pours with two fat fingers of rootbeer float-colored head .  m - very light for a stout .

the hops are a bit dull but the fruit aromas make up for it a little bit , still a letdown tho .  pours a hazy dark orange with a huge tightly compacted head that dissipated into huge bubbles on the side of my tulip glass with a tight mesa in the middle .  mouthfeel has definitely lost some over the years unfortunately , its almost still and lacks life .

smells fresh but that is about all i can gather ( my nose is not very good ) .  this beer has a sexy apperance , but is lacking in mouthfeel and taste . it has a wonderful head and is a very nice dark ruby , but something was missing when i tasted it .  it 's a bit thin in the mouth .

s- musty citrus , some pale malts and some spice from the yeast , no funk or lactic notes . this beer really reminds me of the stone , victory , dfh collaboration last year , only alot better .  pours a deep dark brown with thick creamy dark khaki head that leaves lots of lacing !  medium mouth feel , with decent drinkablity

s : a little lacking . t : the fruit hits you first . very nice . very nice .  lacing is tremendous . the head on this beer is magnificent , probably from the pour , but holds well regardless . beer is dark , dark brown with a light brown head .  medium-light body with moderately-high carbonation . good but a bit astringent and tannic .

s : sent of pine and flowery hops . no citrus smell at all . the pine smell dominates . t : big pine and floral taste , limited malt flavor , all hop presence .  it 's a beautiful rusty brown copper , with a nice foamy off-white head , and exceptional lacing . looks delicious .  the carbonation is medium strong ; the few medium sized bubbles are fresh . the liquid is semi-smooth . a lager with lots of off flavours .

smell : this is where it missed for me . glad i did n't judge this brew soley on the basis of smell . taste : here we go ... .sweetness , dried fruits , vanilla , espresso . all the cool things you would expect from an imperial stout .  the pour is pitch-black in color ; head is immoderate in size , light chocolate in color , and the lace thick clinging sheets that last till the bottom of the glass .  a nice malty finish mouthfeel is a crisp and clean , quite a bit of carbonation , somewhat dry and sticky aftertaste . a bit more body would have made it excellent for it was a bit light a very drinkable beer .

flavor was heavy on the lemon-citric side with floral elements as well , though there was surprisingly little aroma . a good quaffer .  a : very dark pour with carbonation bubbles that fall down and end up creating a long lasting dark tan , wet sand , brown head .  mouthfeel : carbonation is average . body is unfortunately a little thin , contrary to what your taste buds are telling you .

nothing remarkable .  appearance - high marks in every way ! from the midnight black color to the coco powder brown head . leaves a superb patchwork of lacing just to push the envelope a little bit more .  m- light body and good carbonation , nothing stellar here .

a - pour a deep amber/brown , smallish tan head with retention around the edges , not much lacing , very cloudy s - i did n't care much for the aroma of this one , a bit of funkiness , some wet dog , a little oak as it warmed t - malty sweetness up front , intense citrusy hops in the body that evolve into a nice smooth oakiness , some vanilla , slight sourness on the finish surprisingly , not much alcohol noticeable m - moderate carbonation , medium-bodied , somewhat dry finish , some warming d - fairly drinkable , but this is a big beer , alcohol not that noticeable in the taste though the warming is evident , does n't wear out the palate too much great aged/oaked version of fred by hotd . i was just let down by the aroma . well worth seeking out .  pours out to a sparkingly clear bright yellow , forming a rocky spongy head with excellent retention and wonderful lacing .  m : moderate body , mild carbonation .

smell : not alot just some musk and honey . it 's got a spritz to the carbonation with a sweetness and earthy blend with citrus thats really very pleasing . alcohol is well masked and this stuff will rock your world ! they are very drinkable !  this one poured a beautiful dark reddish brown with a creamy tan head .  i poured this guinness into my tumbler at 45 degrees . the beer was very black and bore out a big tan head . the beer smells like a guinness as it should . the taste was big molasses but the brew had a bit of a dry finish . i like the beer and will buy again .

s : nose is somewhat muted . hints of sweetness are present - caramel malts and raisin , and a nice chili chipotle note .  pours blacker than a saharan night during an eclipse . head is a thick , dense , and tan .  s. rich brown sugar , molasses and smoke t. quite complex with molasses , roasted malt , smoke , brown sugar , cinnamon and clove in the front with a touch of hops in the back m. surprisingly clean , with lingering malt behind medium carbonation d. very drinkable for anyone who likes malt i first tried this beer at a local liquor store 's beer tasting . this is a great example of a fall seasonal for the relaxed craft drinker .

roasty malt aroma but not much else .  excellent caramel color but not a very pronounced rye smell .  the beer poured into the glass to reveal a nice copper color . the aroma was slightly bready with a mild hop character . the taste was mildly malty at first then gave way to a nice hoppy dryness in the finish . the is a nice quaffable beer .

smell : unexceptional taste : like really , really delicious candy . i found this a delightful accompaniment to an ethiopian meal and a wonderful surprise to boot .  a rather pretty presentation .  quite an enjoyable beer but in my opinion not as good as rogues other beers . i wish that the mocha flavor was more prominent like kona brewerys pipeline porter . the subtle tones of mocha make this an appealing porter . i 'd recommend this to any porter lover .

smell : sweet , coffee smell , kind of disappointingly one dimenional , but i 'm a hop head i ask a lot .  not a huge imperial stout fan , but i enjoy one now and then . this beer is night black , and no light through it . solid  lightly bodied with a lean , but passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

after reading these reviews , i must have gotten a `` skunked '' one . this was the worst ipa ive ever tasted .  very eligant head , thin , but lasting .  very nice hoppy taste , crisp and clean with a nice malt balance and a great bitter aftertaste . goes down fine , perhaps a bit rough from overcarbonation , but a very well down ipa .

extremely dark brown color and approaching black . there is a sweet and smooth malt attack . faint traces of coffee are present in the finish . it is pretty sweet and malty compared to what i normally prefer , but i really enjoyed this .  a : exceptional . very nice brilliant copper with a good foamy head .  mouthfeel : medium bodied and a bit undercarbonated imho .

very nice aroma on this one .  appearance ; clear , deep amber , light tan head , excellent rention and beautiful lacing . about as perfect as it can be .  brief bitter finish and mouthfeel was a little watery for the style .

licorice , flower pollen , must , stale attic smell . very odd , and not what i would call desirable .  the exceptional head is just about 3 fingers thick , and a rich chocolate cream color . on the way down , this brew leaves a considerable amount of lace for it 's abv . truly the best stout i 've ever seen poured ( along with a yeti ... tied for first ) .  m : a little too much carbonation on this one .

s-sweet malt and sulphur , with a light orange and banana scent t-wheat , just like a proper hefeweisen .  appearance : its body is black as night and opaque with a typical nitro head on top . it has very good retention and makes cool lacing on the glass as i drink .  i wonder how this brew would taste on my pancakes , or maybe waffles ? thick and syrupy body , which was expected because its made with maple syrupmaple aromas on the nose , along with molasses , raisins , caramel and of course alcohol . exactly the same can be tasted on the palate , but everything is just taken to the extreme and it not enjoyable at all . i split this with my pop on father 's day , and he agreed that it also , is just to extreme , i could n't imagine drinking the whole bottle myself ...

more important a steady hand produced a clear honey golden brew . nose seems like a `` belgian '' lite ... a little flat smelling . thankfully the flavor is miles ahead of the aroma . belgian pale malts are heavy with a touch of candy sugar and spicy notes . maybe only the 3rd time i 've had this brew ... i always look over it , because my brew stores typically only carry the 750 's and i try and get smaller bottles because my add tells me i must try something else ... good choice even though the nose is definately lacking .  but the beer also looks great in the glass with a deeply hued brown and a vanilla cream colored head that is thick and persistent while in the glass .  feels like champagne .

the neglected little brother of negro modelo , modelo especial , is an exceptional crisp clean summer beer .  ( a ) - pours a clear amber color that produces a large 2+ finger off-white head that has superb retention ; thick fluffy stuff that is sticking to all the sides of the glass .  taste : this is a fairly thin-bodied brew , and the carbonation seems a little much . it has a nice malty taste in the middle , but it 's dominated by strong , orange-tasting hops . this is certainly a hoppy beer , but the hops are n't that intense or asskicking .

s : smells malty with a hint of fruity sweetness and a little bit of that adjunct bitterness . not exactly the greatest . t/m : the taste is great , though : heavy amounts of belgian dark fruits and a bitter finish , better than the aroma lets on . its very good and a lot fuller flavored than youd think .  a very attractive beer : clear , clean ruby-amber with a strong frothy head and tons of lacing .  the aroma has a touch of stale coffee that then moves to a better defined roasted malt in lager form . the dark malts are great , minus ther adjunt must to it . i ca n't really explain why , but this is one of my , `` right after a hard day of work while you wait for dinner to cook beer . '' easy on the palate and tastes good from the bottle and the glass .

the smell is faint and fruity . there are some pine notes and sour citrus aromas . the taste is good .  poured into a snifter at cellar tempature a- dark black with a carmel brown head that lingered for most of th tasting . nice legs on the glass .  somewhat thin and watery mouthfeel .

smell : the aroma was somewhat soft and weak , as only a hint of caramel and floral hops were detectable . drinkability : i found this to be extremely flavorful , its a shame the nose was so weak . nice brew .  bottled on : 2011/09/09 pours a nice clear medium-light bronze hue , tons of white foamy head - lasts forever .  this is not a beer for holding onto and chatting this is a beer for downing quick . when it heats up , the taste gets worse . there are alot better australian beers than this .

what makes this beer stand out , both positively and negatively , is the chocolate taste . the highly malty taste complements the very potent chocolate taste . in brief , this tastes like a milkshake . if you want a light cocoa taste in your beer , this is not for you .  a gigantic frothy head that left plenty of lacing . nice looking beer , average stout appearance .  the mouthfeel is a decent medium , a little too much carbonation results in a thinner feel than i would like .

a rather dark lager , and has a look of being `` heavy bodied . '' smell : not a lot to pick up off the aroma ... a very slight smokiness when agitated , but giving away very little . clean lager ... taste : smooth , clean brew with lingering smoky aftertaste and only a hint of smokiness during . truly delicious , un-challenging version of a smoked lager and very enjoyable , fresh beer .  i poured a 12 ounce capped bottle into a tulip . a : it poured a dark thick black with a dark rich chocolate head that was massive , sticky and lingering . as the head slowly fell it left a bold lacing around the glass .  fairly light body and a slightly watery mouthfeel .

another clear bottle import ruined by skunky smell . another $ 3.50 down the drain .  the beer poured black with an incredibly creamy light brown head .  mouthfeel was fine . a little thin - i think that a big , thick mouthfeel would accentuate the pumpkin pie-like characteristic that i think they 're going for .

this was a very good ipa , but the aroma was n't overly impressive .  appearance : pours a clear orange color with a 3 '' fluffy merangue-like head .  perhaps just a bit light in the mouthfeel as far as the style goes .

smells really nice and roasty- similar to their indian brown ale which surprised me that it would have such a darker beer character .  appearance- pours a 1 finger head that has awesome retention . head stays the entire time and remains a dark off-white color . the beer has a deep brown color with no visible clarity . ties many other brews in the best appearance contest !  starts creamy , but finishes surprisingly thin , which is more noticeable as the beer warms .

the beer is a super clear straw with about a finger and half of white head . the aroma us super light , hardly gives off anything at all .  amazing retention and lacing on top a deep amber body .  a bit prickly in the mouthfeel , but a nice tripel .

off the bat , i was surprised by the flavor of this brew . a nice ginger kick with nice malt flavor and a decent hop finish . definitely a nice winter brew . i was pleasantly surprised .  kozel master tmavy 18 .4l draft served in stem ware in pilsen a - near black and opaque with reddish mahogany at edges/ generous creamy tan head that leaves patchy lacing . remnants of head lasted until the end during an entire meal .  m - the feel is sharp initially with a chalky and sublime salty finish on the palate .

malty aroma has hoppy and fruity hints , and is not strong but still has appeal .  definitely the best looking of the three with a nice yellow/orangey color , cloudy with tasty yeasties .  light body , wish it were bigger and more creamy .

aroma is grainy and slightly lemony . taste is spicy & herbal , hint of flowers .  a - wow a pitch black liquid and with an aggressive pour i saw at least an inch of coco head .  m-moderate carbonation , medium-bodied beer , with a noticeable hoppy dryness .

it is pretty pale , but much more vibrant than a macro adjunct lager . s : grainy and sweet . other than that i am not picking much up , but the beer is pretty chilled.a t : hop bitterness is most certainly throughout the entire sip , and at its strongest on the back of palate and aftertaste .  a : it 's a dark amber or bronze color that is brilliantly clear . the head is a foamy eggshell white that stands about a finger and a half . a whole lot of lacing !  m : a little spritzy and thin for my taste .

very mild roasted malt scent , not much is jumpking out at you .  medium amber with a big , tight head that does n't seem to recede at all throughout . tons of lacing . tiny , tiny bubbles rising all the while . man this looks inviting .  very light and summer-appropriate . could drink several . definitely a solid brew .

the only problem is the hops are a little muted for the style . the flavor overall is excellent though and very drinkable - had three of them with no regrets .  pours honey colored with 3 fingers of rocky egg shell white head . insane lacing & head retention s : biscuitty malt & leafy hops t : biscuitty malt , leafy & minty hops up front , plus slight medicinal juniper twang .  saison du buff appearance- very hazy golden , lively white head that dissipates quickly.4 smell- hops - green buds to the max 5 taste- wow . delicious . sweet and citrusy but with huge hop and wheat finish.complex balanced . spicy nutmeg 5 mouf- easy 3 drinkable - oh so drinkability 4

the aroma is comprised of toffeeish dark lovibond caramel malt with a roasted edge along with fruity sweet , ripe cassis like esters . unfortunately a metallic smattering adds a slight astringent note . the aroma is the only detraction from excellence . overall well above the norm for the ubiquitous and too often insipid `` red ale .  a : pretty head turns into lucious lacing . pearly , continuous carbonation is unusually beautiful .  carbonation is a little too pronounced .

the small is a bit light , and malty . the taste is strong very malty , no other flavors are present , this beer is just for those who want beer and nothing else . overall this is an excelent beer , one of a kind .  lot and lots of foam reminiscent of a soda more than a beer , but once gone , left great lacing . it feels a bit thin for a stout but you would never know it was eight percent .  the mouthfeel is a little crisp but does smooth out .

sweet malts ... .candylike in the nose . ever present hops taking a vacation .  pretty clear golden color with a humongous white head . tons of stick here , crazy frothy , and overall just beautiful .  m - thin body , or at least thinner than expected . low carbonation .

s : not much - some wood is definitely present , some caramel , a hint of vanilla . t : the oak is one of the leading flavors , imparting it 's wonderful taste upon this beer . d : this is a pretty good strong ale - if i could get it up here , i would likely buy it from time to time . definitely worth a try though .  pours a deep orange- got ta love marzen- slash bronze hue with a fluffy white head .  smells very nutty with mild chocolate roast . the beer fairly sweet tasting with the nuttiness coming through . cabonation is a bit higher than i would like , but other than that it is a very good brown ale .

s : kind of weak with faint coffee grounds odor with sweet raisins and vanilla . t : pleasant and grabbing coffee presence immediate with a ton of chocolaty sweetness to boot .  had this out of a can poured into a pint glass ... a : nice dark amber and red color with a wicked head . just huge and rocky as hell , great lacing .  the mouthfeel is not a complex one and is rather unbalanced and nondescript .

the smell is of dark malts although slightly sour and dusty . the taste follows the smell , malty with just a bit of sourness , then the bitter finish .  a : a beauty ! hazy copper with a creamy head with tons of retention and lace .  typical mouthfeel for a lager i guess , although i do n't know a lot about what this style should be like .

aroma is nominal , fresh and slightly coffee/alcohol . a very enjoyable imperial stout , not the most complex i 've ever had , but really nice . strong though .  it pours from 12oz bottle a clear amber with a solid 2 finger head of foam . i 'm near the end of my session and the head retention is excellent !  m- much too thin for the style and something this big .

at first , aroma is sharp and pine-y . hoppy for a pils , for sure .  appearance : golden amber that looks great beneath the fluffy off-white head that lasts . decent lacing . my favorite appearance for an apa .  mouthfeel was a bit thin , pretty amazing for a beer of this gravity , making this dangerously drinkable .

the smell is a very light hint of chocolate .  bottle enjoy before month notched-sep served in a pint glass like the other beers in the latitude 48 deconstructed ipa series , this one poured a glowing , orangey-amber color with a near three-finger tall head of khaki colored froth . outstanding retention .  somewhat thin in it 's mouthfeel although a good creaminess creeps up toward the end .

golden in color , straw-like with a thick white beautiful head that laces the aroma is very lite malty with some earthy hops but hard to get .  after poured into a glass it 's great looking . extremely dark , white foam .  a - poured a black color with a tan head that leaves lacing behind s - is of roasted malt vanilla and some smoke t - follows the nose for the most part the oak gives nice hints of vanilla and the smoked malt seems more present than the regular bottled version which is n't bad to me m - this beer has a thin body with medium carbonation to it d - this oaked version was a very good beer but i 'm still disappointed with the body definitely worth grabbing a pint of if you ever hear about it being tapped

not much smell there , which is a huge letdown compared to everything else about this beer . faint slightly smoky smell with hints of chocolate . no real pepper smell , but you can actually feel a slight burn in your nose . t - chocolate , roasted malt , slight smoky flavor , and chipotle pepper in the background .  forming a very foamy 2 inch off white head . very constant carbonation rise . the head takes several minutes to settle , leaving mounds of clumpy foam and plenty of very thick curtains of sticky lace .  carbonation scrubs the tongue with perky bubbles ( almost too much , but not quite ) and has a medium-light body .

as for scents , i can find much more than diacetyl and bare notices of amber malt . not loud or jumping with bold aspects , but on-point for the style and well-rounded .  a - a clear golden color , pores a thick head and tons of sticky lace that just never quits s - piny and floral hops and spices , with the yeast providing the earthy aromas that give it that saison style t - light malts and spicy with dry hop notes towards the end .  medium carbonation and a slight astringency .

s - toasty malt with a citrus hop notes . t - good toasty malt taste .  it looks incredibly inviting , well done .  wow , i enjoyed the flavor of this beer , the hops are more present in the aroma than the taste , maybe showing up in the extremely dry mouthfeel though . not exactly full bodied , a little light compared to the dark lords we were drinking prior to this , but still it matches the flavors in an appealing way .

not a bad looking winter beer . s- some rye , caramely malt , kind of oaty . mild is a good word for it . t- the smell does not really set you up for how this tastes . very appealing . but this is a really nice winter beer .  sierra nevada 30th pours a inky , impenetrable black with a deep brown head .  mouthfeel is a letdown - it may just be this bottle but the carbonation is too weak . only have one of these 750ml bottles as it 's imported and a special occasion but i 'd be keen to have another one , if only to compare the carbonation .
s - fruits , malt , mild not pungent smell .  the beer is a super dark red or amber . it looks delicious on appearance .  m - high carbonation , but a little watery .

this is a beer snob 's beer . nice brown color w/ hints of orange , this is a great example of a flemish sour ale . it starts out quite sour , but finishes slightly sweet .  watching this beer settle is part of it 's mistique - its a lava lamp for beer geeks ... once settled , a perfect 1-finger head of slightly off-white cream meets a pitch black beer . the commercial ( widget bottle , nitro-can ) are pale shadows compared .  m : the body is medium with a low carbonation and a tooth rotting sweetness . so unbearably sweet and sugary without any sort of balance .

s : a bit weak here , not much of a smell..bitter , a bit of citrus . t : awesome ! i 'm a huge non-chill filtered scotch fan , the more bite on the tongue the better .  a - pitch black . huge , solid brown foam with fantastic lace .  mf is a bit lacking , thin , though creamy .

aroma is a little flat but pleasant . flavor is exceptional , very subtle and complex on the palate full body excellent complement to the flavor .  poured a motor oil brownish black with a light brown head of frothy , creamy foam . good head retention and a fair amount of laced sticking .  the mouthfeel was slightly thinner than expected .

s : malt and honey . t : smooth honey and malt sweetness with faint hop bitterness .  dark brown body , very clear with a one finger tight head that lasts the whole beer and leaves huge amounts of lacing .  m : mouthfeel was a little thin for the style .

very average smelling . malt for the most part and pretty boozy . t : bitter and heavy .  a - a thick , frothy and solid head with great stamina . the body is a deep yet translucent orange .  like other ommegang brews , too carbonated , which detracts from what would be a nice heavy feel . nice balance makes for very good drinkability ; biggest knock from me is the excessively fizzy feel .

the aromas are earthy and sweet hops , although not extremely aromatic .  pours dark gold with a copper hue and a massive plumage of dense bone foam . the four inch pillow of froth took forever to settle and a thick cap remained for the duration with some of the most substantial lacing i 've ever seen .  mouthfeel is okay , but needs to be either thicker or creamier to work with the taste -- as is , it 's just a tad watery .

the aroma was comprised of sweet malt , bitter hop , and subtle citrus .  looks like heaven in a glass , slightly hazed golden hue , massive amount of carbonation action ( more fun than watching sea monkeys ) , and a massive chunky white head that stayed all of the way and left some serious lacing .  mouthfeel : has a fair body , but nothing out of the ordinary .
smell is a bit bland , but this beer makes up for it with flavor and drinkability .  i must say that the bottle is very cool looking !  m : pretty thin and not too lively .

while mentioned repeatedly as a saison , it has a much maltier character then your typical farmhouse ale . in the same vein at first look it appears to be a brown ale with a thin white head .  appearance : excellent in all respects , color , carbonation , head , lacing . great looking stuff .  it lingers really well on the tongue , very good aftertaste . the mouthfeel is meh , as it 's a little thin .

almost non-existent aroma . flavor is bitter . sorta reminds me of a pacific nw pale ale meeting a stout .  a huge head starts off this brew , nice and tan . sexy lacing , makes you want to lick it off the glass .  well , it looks like a good brown ale and smells like a good raspberry brown ale . the taste of this nice looking raspberry brown was that of nutty , roasted malts ( good ) and burnt raspberries ( bad ) . the charred flavor that came through in this sampling was overwhelmingly horrible . i like the other harbor city brews , so i 'm willing to try this again in case i had a very bad batch .

sweet light malt aroma with some subtle spice and light floral hops . clean , crisp and extremely smooth creamy body .  bottle poured into a tulip glass . some evidence of lacing . gorgeous . aroma-up front i get an aroma of fresh cut apples that is a little bit acetaldehyde-like , mixed with some light perfumy alcohols .  mouthfeel is slightly thin , with lower carbonation , not bad .

appearance- dark black with a bit of carbonation and a moderate tan head , smell- slightly roasted malts and slight hop smell not a very overpowering smell at all taste- i really like the taste of this beer , its a mix of slight roasted malts and chocolate and espresso tones mixed with crispness and slight hop bitterness of a lager , its a great combination and each sip is very enjoyable , a unique combo mouthfeel- light crisp and refreshing with good carbonation , just very smooth drinking drinkablitly- i find this drink from the can to be just so incredible in drinkability , its so refreshing and so enjoyable , its something i often now seek out for a unique and refreshing beer , and it has to be stated that it such a value !  a-deep brown with some reddishness . big tan head on this one . quite the lovely looking beer .  wow ! what a pleasant surprise ! i tried this beer on-tap at a new restaurant near my apartment called `` kushi . '' i was in the mood for a light , white ale - and this beer definitely delivered . it was crisp and refreshing . taste was tart and light , a little sour , but well balanced . i 'd have this beer again , and again , and again..

smell was sweet with slight coffee hints .  this brew looks very enticing . there is a massive amount of milk chocolate looking head , with great retention .  got this in the secret santa 2008 - from dmeadows , thanks again ! a bit of a funky musty aroma mixed with the spicy nutmeg , quaff is a boatload of allspice , nutmeg , fig , plum and an underlying hint of alcohol booze - even after 2 years in the cellar . and the elderberries add quite a different take on the solid offering . sweet initial start , boozy and hoppy finish . a true winter sipper , tasty and enjoyable with the football game .

i have a cold so the smell was way less than expected but probably mostly due to the cold . taste is very good . overall a great beer .  single from a mixed six poured into a pint glass a : aggressive pour yields 1.5 fingers of dense brown head with good retention . perfect .  after several sips i finished the taster and got a bottle of water to cleanse the palate . the body was average for a wit , but the hops made this sloppy mess nearly undrinkable .
s : wheat and faint peach smell .  this looked exceptionally wonderful .  m : the body is medium and the carbonation is low to medium i suppose .

trademark flossmoor hops aroma is definitely there , but is a bit one-dimensional . faintly floral , this one is mildly bitter , with a definite bite of fresh , sharp rye .  impressive head is like a cloud . beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel : medium carbonation .

smell is bready with a hint of spice . not a ton going on here .  hinninger kaiser pils looks beautiful , and almost unmatched when poured into a regular stein . there are vast amounts of bright white and soft pillowy head , and the body is gold and crystal clear .  deep red-brown color with amazing billowy off-white head : thick and lasting with good lacing s : hoppy and malty balance with yeasty notes and spices t : orange and nutmeg maltiness with a hoppy bitter finish m : a little thin , but this is towards the end of its season by now .

smells of roasted malts and alcohol . i am not a big fan of the style but this brew is pretty good .  brilliant golden hue , and absolutely crystal clear indicating ample lagering . thin , but dense head leaves loose lace .  body a bit light and bubbly .

drank right out of the red , gold and white 16 oz can . s : maybe some burnt corn , metal , typical cheap amercan adjunct canned lager smell . t : taste was surprizingly refreshing and um , good ! . much better than any bmc product in my opinion .  looks quite beautiful .  the mouthfeel is clean and crisp , with less body than i 'd hoped for .

smells of roasted malt and chocolate .  a - pours black brown , large frothy tan head , sticky lacing , large cap . this one was very frothy , sticky , and dark . the brett adds another dimension onto an already stellar quad .  mouthfeel is medium to full-bodied .

s : smells like most unibroue 's yeast but with a slight touch of fruityness . t : nose is fizzy like a wine cooler and full of fruit character followed by a body that is distinctly malt .  the appearance is one intangible , with a thick , clumpy froth leaving gorgeous lacing down the glass . brilliant orange .  medium finish . a bit too bubbly at first , but a smooth finish .

22oz bomber a-nice amber body with a thin head of lace . a little darker than expected but color was very pleasing . seemed like i was picking up more from the bittering and flavor hops than any aroma hops . the hops are supremely evident , as well as the rye , but nothing is cloying .  appears a pitch black hue absolutely no light shines through when held up to the light , although it does form a large tan moccha frothing head rising at least an inch above my gulden draak chalice .  m - well balanced , but thin and slightly sweet . was hoping for a medium to full-bodied saison .

aroma was of hops and malt not much going on in the aroma department .  poured a hazy orange amber colour with a thick head that had very good retention . this was a beautiful beer with tons of visual character .  o-a nice stout that would benefit greatly from a more viscous and luxurious mouthfeel . with the harsh carbonation it seems more like a coffee soda pop .

smell : a little grassy hop , a little citrus hop . there 's some doughy malt in there too . the aroma is a little on the weak side . i usually like my dipas to be potent in the nose and this lets me down . its not intensely bold as some dipas but its still pretty good . feel : not intensely bitter , fairly crisp and refreshing , the alcohol is hidden very well . drinks like an american pale ale with 5 % alcohol by volume , not a 9 % dipa . its not exceptional but its very solid .  poured an extremely murky cider color with a great , 2-fingered head of frothy , beige foam that loved to just hang out and leave terrific lacing behind on the glassware . beautiful looking beer ... like an apple cider with a frothy head on top .  m : too thin and unsustained to be great .

s- really not picking up much here besides grain and maybe some malt , my buddy confirms this so i 'm not crazy here .  excellent lacing this beer is great to look at .  i 'm almost halfway through the pint and still impressed with the carbonation . i 'm also surprised at the body ; it seems a bit thin and makes the beer rather perilously drinkable at nearly 7 percent alcohol . this long , bitter and dry finish is perhaps the most enjoyable quality of this beer , that and i suppose it 's dangerous drinkability .

the nose is a bit weak , and almost reminds me of a milk stout . fortunately , the smell did n't begin to do edmund fitz justice .  pours a bright , clear golden with tons and tons of bubbles streaming to the top feeding an enormous fluffy white head that shows crazy retention and lacing . gorgeous beer .  well , what can i say . this is definantly the most unique beer i have ever tried . this beer would make a wonderful cooking beer but for drinking it is possibly one of the worst i have ever tasted . the smell and flavour are just not something i want to drink . very hickory smoked ham . used to flavour a chili it would be wonderful , but like i said , as a drink the nastiest thing in the world . literally like drinking smoked ham .

the smell left much to be desired and then got awful .  a - it 's damn hot and muggy here right now , and the bright golden body and thick , fluffy white head 'atop this beer looks really damn good .  mouthfeel is a bit sticky and the flavors stick around for a bit after swallowing .

smell is lacking and is the worst attribute of this beer .  pours an absolutely gorgeous orange hue that is impeccably clear and just a tad bit of pale head and some effervescence .  smooth and sweet , this is pretty nice . carbonation is a bit low , even for my liking .

the smell was still lacking , but this may have been due to the temperature it was served at . it was delicious .  this beer delivers a ton of frothy white cranium that sticks up well above the glass , and has a golden clear body .  m- this beer is very carbonated and somewhat thin , very refreshing .

s ~ a good dose of coco , chocolate syrup , hint of vanilla in there ... t ~ bitter chocolate ... .dry on the back ... lingering flavors of coco that stay behind well after the sip is gone m ~ lighter to medium bodied bock ... i like my chocolate beers thick and rich - s. tier chokolat ... this was a random bottle i picked up.. o ~ not bad ... i remember the hype behind the beer a year or two ago when it was in the bigger bottles for $ 15 per..glad i did n't buy one then and held out for the $ 1 something 12 ozer ... worth a try..but nothing super special..  nitro tap at the palmdale location look : almost black and totally opaque with a brown ring on the bottom of the glass with a 1/2 inch tan head and exceptional retention and some spotty lacing smell : coffee notes upfront with hints of chocolate but the nose is fairly muted taste : roasted malts with hints of ash coffee and chocolate .  m : medium , but thicker than expected , this is one of my first lambics , but it really steps up to the plate and is a home run .

nose was slightly sweet , tending more towards malty , unusual for the style .  12oz bottle into a goblet a : pours pitch black with almost two fingers of light brown head . carbonation is very thick and seems to stick around forever . beautiful .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied and slightly syrupy . minimal carbonation .

s - caramel , molasses and brown sugar but all are relatively subtle . t - the flavors are extremely potent and robust while maintating a very fluid transistion from one to another .  nearly perfect for a stout , leaving even a nice bit of lacing on the top of the head as it begins to dissipate .  its a huge beer , but the mouthfeel isnt as thick as i would like or expect . good levels of carbonation , and they did a great job of hiding the alcohol .

smells faintly of caramelized malts and honey with some bready yeasts- pretty light and simple . tastes similar to the nose , only more intense . highly drinkable , easy and refreshing .  it pours a beautiful deep gold/orange , crystal clear .  m : sticky and fairly thick , dry , slightly dry , prickly carbonation , hint of warm alcohol , just a little too syrupy for my taste .

it also has a nice earthiness to it . the smell is however a little subdued .  pours a beautiful red-pink with some fizzy head that lasts for about a second and recededs to a glass that looks more like wine than anything , carbonation rising on the sides of the glass looks great .  mouthfeel : medium body , ok carbonation . pretty average .

subtle aroma , but followed with an eye-openingly brilliant taste .  really quite impressive . the liquid is cloudy with a yellow-gold color .  feels a bit thin , low-medium body and medium carbonation .

s- caramel and malt . there was not a strong alcohol smell . nothing extraordinary . nothing too strong here .  very nice looking beer .  102 ibu ... tastes sweet , like honey and ginger ale with a touch of malt . little too syrupy to be super refreshing but still awesome .

salty briny nose , most likely through the power of suggestion .  reviewed 7/12/2007 ( 550ml bottle ) : pours a dark park brown/black colored body , with a tannish colored head , huge and lasting .  t & m : this is a well rounded stout . nicely carbonated , well balanced with a nice roasted bitterness ( but not offensively so ) and sweetness from the malted oats . feels a little on the `` watery '' side for a stout though .

the aroma is a bit weak , with notes of raisin and other dark fruit plus mild alcohol .  appearance : black in color with a one inch creamy head , opaque -- even when poured from a nitro can , beers do not look much better than guinness smell : roasted malt and tobacco taste : dry roasted malt , tobacco , and some creamy sweetness mouthfeel : dry , light bodied , moderate carbonation , sweet and roasty drinkability : a classic and one of the best looking beers i have seen .  mouthfeel - the only downside imo is that it has a dry finish and leaves the pallet thirsty .

s - sweet , bready malt , dried fruits - golden raisins , apricots . some metallic aroma apparent .  plumes of billowing bubbles bloom in this crystal clear honey colored brew . head is a large , off-white and meringue-like head that shimmers and sparkles and glimmers while being fed by the frantic carbonation below . looks great and smells and tastes pretty good .  m/d : medium bodied , but seemed a little thin and very easy to drink .

the nose is pretty subdued .  this beer poured wonderfully , gave great head , and had the most beautiful dark appearance .  m : the mouthfeel is okay but feels a little thin , especially for a dipa .

aroma is arid and floral . actually a bit faint . just could stand a big more aroma .  purchased a single can from martignetti's appearance = great thick , milky creamy head that goes down to about 1/4 '' and stays . deep , clear amber . very beautiful . it looks beautiful and i can see why some might like the taste .  it feels pretty average for this style .

well , it 's winter and i have a cold . smell was hard to detect . tastes good .  pours a very attractive cherry red color , and smells of fruit , candy , and slight spicy alcohol taste is amazingly complex with a full , smooth , creamy mouthfeel .  light-medium bodied , needs to be fuller .

not a whole lot of smells goin on here . t : smooth cream ale with a crisp clean finish .  bottle : poured a light yellow ale with some white haze and a large pure white foamy head with good retention and good lacing .  however , the body is a little thin , with a slighlty soapy feel .

above average head retention & lacing ... s : biscuitty malt , a bit of lemon , does n't really assert itself t : lemons , grapefruit , pine & biscuitty malt up front , the malts take a back seat quickly .  first , the pour is one of the best with the cascading nitro effect . the head is a beautiful finger high creamy off-white and the lacing is great also .  mouthfeel is not quite as full as it could be , but still does a good job delivering and distributing flavor around the mouth .

s - very light amount of spices . not much there .  apperance- quite opaque in color , unable to see through the glass , beautiful creamy head that makes this beer look like a milkshake . like usual there is at least a quarter inch of white creamy head at all times .  mouthfeel is about medium in weight , but the carbonation is dull .

smells like a good belgian pale ale , but the aroma is a bit weak .  a duvel poured properly into a large goblet looks absolutely amazing - clean , bright goldenrod color swirled with smokey looking yeast , with a thick white layer of foam made up of large champagne size bubbles and fine spongy head .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with sharp carbonation .

not much in terms of aroma , and i do n't think it 's just my choice of glassware . maybe some biscuity malt and hop leaf ? tastes delicious , though . i think part of why i like it better now is that i 've come to appreciate tasteful use of diacetyl -- the buttery sweetness is complemented by light hop spiciness and even lighter citrus notes . finishes somewhat dry but could be crisper for the style and my tastes .  quick review : pours a clear and bright amber with some orange hues and 2 fingers of fluffy off-white head with great retention . leaves lots of lacing .  as a williamsburg native , and dark beer fan , i was severly disappointed with this porter . it could have been that the six pack was skunky , i guess . nonetheless , a big disappointment . if one could imagine a porter that is too sweet , this would fit into that category . baltika is also a sweeter porter , but only has a hint . this beer is blatantly sweet .

3.5 s mostly citrus and florals , but also grains & yeast , reminds me of saison more than ipa 3.5 t hmmm lemony floral and herbal bitterness , does not flow well and is a work in progress 2 m loads of carbonation is very excessive , light body , ill drain pour what is left in my glass 1 o drinkability is not good , difficult for me to believe that this would sell well in spain or the us , ill not buy this again nor would i recommend it 2  this beer pours a seemingly familiar deep , practically opaque dark brown oily hue , with a ton of foamy , rocky head , which settles in the glass at the three finger mark , slowly receding to reveal a nice dense curtain of lace around the glass .  the flavor is lightly sweet thought , with some wheat towards the beginning , going to some hops , and a light sweet finish . for me , a pretty good summer session brew .

streaky lacing after every sip s- very under whelming aroma . im picking up sweet fruit smells but they are muted .  what a beauty . the head is rich and downright pillowy .  mf- a bit thin . leaves a good feeling in the mouth after you are finished . carbonation a bit high .

s-not much to speak of , a little malty . t-pretty darned good . rich malt followed by a nice soapy hop bitterness . very well balanced in the malt to hop ratio .  this brew pours a medium head of fine creamy light brown bubbles that leaves a fair lacing and a dark opaque black brown body .  there is a lack of head or carbonation , the body is very cloudy with a chunky suspension . the flavor is also adversely affected , the malt tastes raw and grainy , and it masks whatever this beer is supposed to taste like . i will be pouring this bottle out , i am hoping that this is an exception , not the rule from this beer .

s - slight whiff of coffee , roasted malts , and a touch of chocolate t - surprised at how tasty this is given the fact the smell was ok , it has great sweetness mixed with roasted malts , great hoppiness in the middle , very well balanced .  a : exceptional , should be the example of perfect lacing ! it pours a golden hue topped with a frothy white head that leaves you feeling the beer wants you to drink it .  m - medium to light body .

smell : oh wow . just ... wow .  pours beautiful , medium-large head with huge retention .  very dark with maybe a hint of red if you hold it up to the light . a little flat so the mouthfeel is not as good .

nose is phenomenal , it 's very fruity and floral , dank and spicy . not sure how he does it with these ipas , but they all smell amazing . wow , this is so creamy and juicy and dank .  poured a gorgeous oranged amber color with a bubbly off-white head , good slow lace , and a little staining on the glass .  on the downside the mouthfeel was much fizzier than one would expect ... very thin , too .

smell : i think it is fair to say that this beer lacks in the smell department . i caught a little malt but that is about all . taste : an agreeable taste/flavor which is fairly mild .  a : clear pale amber body under a breathtaking 3-finger head that towers confidently above the rim of the glass . big , creamy , and white , this might be the best looking head i 've ever seen in a pint glass . amazing .  the mouthfeel is nothing exceptional but it is also not bad . it is a bit fizzy but this does n't offset the flavors .

weak pine and citrus aroma . not much going on here for a fresh hop beer . pretty nice , except the aroma seemed to be lacking .  appearance : this beer looks incredibly promising when it is poured .  the mouthfeel is just average .

pale straw body with an overall subdued aroma consisting of muddled potpourri , perfume .  a : pours a massive head that laces nicely . clear brown color , very bubbly . sounded like pouring champagne .  the body is a little thin for my likes .

dark mahogany brown in the glass , not quite black ; on the light side for the world 's strongest stout . swirling reveals thick , syrupy legs not unlike a spirit or liqueur . it smells intensely of alcohol , peat , oak , faint roast - a hell of a lot like scotch . it 's simple and unimpressive .  a-black with a creamy dark tan head . has a perfect lacing that coats the glass .  m - maybe a little on the thin side for me -- the carbonation is higher than i 'm used to .

nose - didnt get a good smell because of the atmosphere - fried bar food ruins beer aroma .  appearance : pitch black body with a tall , dense , pile of brown foam on top . great lacing . perfect !  the disappointing : wow , what a highly carbonated brew , almost champaign in the fizziness .

essentially it comes off as a baby mcewans scotch ale , but it has its own personality . midway is the classic hard and cruchy ale water . it finishes ( waaay back in the throat ) with a hop-like pop , but i think it is the roasted malt doing the dirty work on this one .  pours caramel with 3+ fingers of fluffed up khaki colored head . insane lacing & head retention s : plummy , some herbal hops , a touch of booze t : rich dark fruit herbal & woody hoppyness , plus much dryness & some boozey pine needles up front .  ( 4 ) m : thin with hi carb ( a little too hi ) and a dry finish . would like a little more body or a little less carb to make this a little more palatable .

nose is full of banana and coriander , though `` full '' may be an overstatement as the aroma is not particularly strong . the way i would put the taste ... peaceful banana . i 'm really enjoying this in mid-september as i 'm transitioning from summer ales to festbiers .  mine is just plain beautiful . huge billowy white head off the pour .  m - uberchewy , sweet . med-light carbonation .

not too much going on aroma wise . taste : wonderful chocolate toasty flavors abound .  this brew pours a bright , crystal-clear gold , with lots of beads of carbonation and three inches of beautiful head . there is a bit of haze at the end of the pour , and a huge amount of lacing on the glass .  body is full with smooth carbonation , but a bit on the low side .
there is a slight , light malty smell with jsut a touch of hop aroma .  this beer is just beautiful when poured into a glass . two finger light brown head that is very creamy .  m : nothing special .

s- strong citrus , grapefruit and lemon . pine and floral notes also come through . this is an amazingly hoppy beer with just enough sweet malt to give it a nice depth and complexity .  bottle : poured a deep burgundy color ale with a super huge off-white foamy head with perfect retention .  overall quite mouthfilling , cakey , dangerously smooth and rounded . the beer takes a bit of a down turn towards the end as the flavors fizzle a bit and the beer seems to thin out and go a bit watery . mouthfeel , while not ever being truly creamy , comes close with real soft and smooth carbonation .

mild grainy aroma , difficult to detect any hops .  the beer looks great , dark brown very bubbly brew with a tan creamy chunky head that sits nicely through out the expierence . nice lacing - very impressive looking beer .  the mouth is fairly thick ( for a lower abv lager , that is ) , and the carbonation is too high , unless poured a little hard .

the smell was ok , but the taste , oh man , what the hell .  11.2oz bottle a- pours a dark brown color with a huge light tan head that sticks around forever and leaves a lot of retention along the glass . this is a really pretty pouring beer .  m - thin and a little astringent , but it is very refreshing apart from that .

amazing . even though the hops are not afraid to show themselves in the flavor , this definitely works as an english barleywine , as the malts stay at the forefront . feels resiny and creamy in the mouth without being overly thick .  after a sip of beer , the sun came out from behind some clouds and a ray of light from a high , transom window knifed down and lit up my beer with an angelic glow . it was the best looking beer i 'd ever seen .  i am almost positive this is living under the assumed name of `` doc mason 's ryepa '' at solana beach . aroma is rye , caramel malt , and hops . nice hop bite up front with a smoother rye and caramel back . acidic and alcoholic finish .

s - not a lot of smell to this one , mostly some bready malt , hints of spice t - taste is fruity and bready with a touch of spice . good blend of everything here .  very pretty reddish brown .  m : on the lighter side .

smell - the scent is simple consisting mainly of malt but there is a hint of hops as well .  the prototypical stout color that i love , deep brown to ebony , the head impressive , the consistency creamy , the lace a latticework to coat the glass .  the mouthfeel is atypical for a saison . it 's a little heavier and not as carbonated as is typical of the style .

smells phenomenal . funk and very tart cherries . still , a nice beer and i 'd have to imagine it would be much better with any semblance of carbonation .  bottle : poured a murky brown color ale with a super huge foamy head with good retention .  i 'm sorry guys but another swing and a miss . beer aggressively foamed out the bottle immediately on opening , after sitting in the refigerator for two days , so no mistakes on my part there . the sourness overwhelms any good qualities which are there , lying underneath but truly irrelevent . cigar city is a great brewery with great potential but lets get it together guys . do not put these beers on the shelf when they are clearly sub-par . cheers everybody- it 's only beer . i expect great things from this brewery but let 's please enact some quality control .

aroma : hard to detect anything , other than some slight toasted grain . flavor/body : excellent blend of nutty malt and dry , lemongrass bitterness . an uncomplex , but oh-so-tasty brew , perfect for a session beer .  incredible lacing . just a beauty to behold . i could look at it all day .  mouthfeel : feels slightly carbonated and thicker than water on the tongue .

the aroma is huge , lots of chocolate , roasted grain , and raisins in this tan foam .  12oz bottle , freshness date 07/09 poured into pint glass : a : amazing . hazy , deep golden color .  medium thin body .

not much of an aroma , but what i could smell hinted lightly of a wine rather than a beer . it is a light bodied beer with a definite warmth about it .  poured from the bomber into a duvel tulip glass the beer was jet black in color and topped with three fingers of sticky head that retains very well .  the drink was citrusy at the front , with a floral spicy taste towards the middle with a subtle hop kick at the end . i found this beer to be very interesting and enjoyable . it would make a good stand alone , or a good session beer .

i do n't get too much aroma but it 's certainly a pleasant coffee presence . the flavor is wonderful . there'the typical fruity sweetness you come to expect from an alt .  the beer pours out a hazy reddish orange , and has a magnificent head that stays around for minutes and leaves lacing down the side of the glass.. has a very clean taste .  taste was somewhat bitter , and more of the hops , with alcohol becoming more evident in both the aroma and taste at mid-glass . finish was slightly bitter aftertaste , but mostly smooth and a bit dry .

i really love the packaging on this one , very unique . poured a crystal clear , straw/light orange color . i did n't get alot off the nose on this pour . light hops and malts , but nothing too distinguishible .  pours thick and black with a one finger heavy tan head on it .  m-not very carbonated , lighter body than expected but too light in between the medium .

it poured a dark brown but did n't have strong smell to me . i 'm not sure if i was just in the mood for a stout , but this surely hit the spot .  my overly aggressive pour not only caused a wee bit of spill-over , but also netted me two fingers ' worth of light-tan head with good retention . color was a solid copper ( no amber at all ) with ne-quality clarity . beautiful !  m : one of the few beers where carbonation is probably a bit too strong and covers up some of the wonderful and interesting flavors going on here .
s : not much aroma to speak of . quite a remarkable stout .  beautiful color s-more malts than hops .  m - medium to light bodied . it 's just thinner than i expected .
