as far as smell , i get the belgian yeast first and then some decent hop aroma .  exceptional appearance ... very dark brown with a pillowy head that clings in a beautiful lace .  i had this on tap at victory brewing a - a very pale golden with good clarity and small snowy head with small bead , little lacing collects s - the smell is yeasty , with subtle sweet malt and mild floral hops m - the feel is thin , but apropos to style w/ light malt texture sweet herbal hop feel and kind of watery finish t - the flavor is crisp , clean and sweet w/ floral hops not really adding any contrast in the way of bitterness .

s : coffee but that is about it t : roasted malt , finishing into coffee and chocolate .  poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass a : beautiful hazy yellow-copper with a towering , rocky two-to-three finger head and sheets of lace s : hallertauer hops smell great -- tangy and spicy .  mouthfeel : a little thin ; carbonation too .

nose : has a sour smell to it . a little white sugar sweetness comes though . for an 8 % , this is very good .  pours a clear deep reddish with brown edges and a pretty beige head with lots of tiny bubbles . a beauty !  if only the texture was less paper thin and more like cardboard .

i have been searching for a 'true ' american hefe , and i believe i have found it . smell just a tad weak , but the flavor more than makes up for it . very nice clove and ripe banana in the backround , and incredible drinkability .  a - dark , dark brown allowing a mere hint of light through at the base of the pint . the head is substantial at two plus inches and maintains some very nice lacing .  m : mouthfeel is thin , crisp , but a little watery .

smell- had a sweet almost candy like smell . subtle floral tones . taste- sweet brown suger , caramely taste .  dark brown with amber undertones topped with a medium thick to thick head that leaves lots of lace behind .  sampled at the paper city brewery on free beer night . i know that this beer was free so i should n't complain about it but there was something wrong with this beer . my guess is this was a bad keg otherwise they brewed it with their dirty gym socks . reflection : i know that this is a harsh review but unless you were there that night and tried it you ca n't understand the horror of this beer .

smell is sweetish malts , caramel and chocolate .  appearance was great especially the persistant head still clinging to the glass as i finished .  a beer haiku for you : '' norwegian beer ? yes ! a great ipa option , seek out and find one ! '' my first norwegian [ that 's what she said ] . nice citrus overtones , not too 'hoppish ' , and very drinkable . a rare find , but well worth the money to have another option .

floral notes were the most obvious odor , as was a touch of hops .  black as night . firm one inch classic looking nitro-head , that after quite awhile receded to a ring .  it had a medium to light body .

i was mildly surprised to see a stout on draft in the netherlands , but the bar came highly recommended . nonetheless , a very tasty stout , with nice dry tones and not much residual sugar .  while watching the foam recede to the point that i can quaff some beer , i admire the brilliantly clear , orangey gold liquid below it .  modest bitterness , warmth . some great foaminess but a bit too much . malty sweetness . this is high calorie beer , the good stuff .

s : grainy , yeasty , and decent . sweetish .  a- a brilliant copper color , this is a very nice looking beer .  a little grittiness in the texture . m - a little weird and overcarbonated for a porter . it would be better off less carbonated and as creamy as it appears .

smell is n't remarkable and nothing really sticks out . there 's better stouts but this is n't bad .  pour is opaque brown/black with a solid-sized tan head . never get an inkling this is a 13 percent abv beer ; it 's big but there 's nothing boozy about it . a very impressive and interesting brew ; definitely a walk from the normal ris .  for the most part this is quite smooth , although the carbonation is just a tad too harsh to fully appreciate some of the nuanced flavors .

smells of cinnamon , ginger , something nasty i ca n't put my finger on .  massive and dense biege rocky foam cloud that measures about 4 fingers tall and leaves incredible lacing rests on top of this deep dark dirty brown brew .  m - my only complaint about this beer , wish it would thicken up a bit . approriate carbonation .

love it . the aroma and taste are ( naturally ) severely muted here compared to the regular drafts i had previously . but for it 's style , i 'm happy to find only the slightest sweetness ( in either of the servings i 've had so far ) , whereas i 've come accustomed to tasting a more sour , sugary sweet character taken from the lactose . they 've crafted a fine ale indeed .  pours a deep , opaque black-brown with a fairly thick and fine-bubbled light tan head , quite appealing .  t-coffee up front followed by a grape raisin in the middle and a cocoa powder/unsweetened chocolate finish . m-kind of watery and a bit syrupy , not unpleasant but not great d-alcohol very well hidden , but warming and at 4.50 $ a bomber could be quite dangerous .

smell - definately an ipa simply based on the bitter hop aroma . just as the smell would suggest , the hoppy flavor so typical of ipa 's just is n't present .  very beautiful to look at . the color is just awesome !  light bodied with a crisp carbonation . this beer is pretty damn horrible .

fairly dull aroma of malt . weakest part of this beer .  appearance- wonderful semi-cloudy off orange , slightly golden colored pour . full one inch head on pour which form a ultra creamy milkshake-like head . actually , more like cool whip . leaves behind great trails and patches of lace .  roasted aroma with hints of dark ( bittersweet ) chocolate and coffee . could be fuller bodied , a little less on the tounge then expected . different flavors hint you on the first sip , roasted malt , coffee , dark chocolate , hop citrusness . finishes dry with some hop bitterness and a nice aftertaste . another quality brew from the boys and rogue !

the aroma is very faint , but is slightly sweet . in my opinion it is the pinnacle example of an esb . balance plays a huge part here and because its not over the top , its highly drinkable unlike some of the bigger american versions of the style .  bottle it has reddish brown color with a khaki colored head . this beer has some of the best lacing i 've seen . fifteen minutes after the beer is gone , lacing still lines the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side for a stout .

nose is primarily light citric hops .  huge inch or more very creamy white head . one of the best lacing jobs i have ever seen from an ipa .  m : a little bit smooth , medium body , medium carbonation , finishes a little bit sticky , like i said before , its more like juice than beer .

s-not so good . not much there ... . balanced carbo .  appearance - total black pour with a finger of smooth , rich , mocha foam .  i like the way this beer opens up although it ends up tasting a bit thin for the rest of the drink . m- smooth , sticky , but not thick at all .

upon pouring the beer , i am shocked that the aroma is quite muted . some of the distinct malt aromas from the mikkeller series but not a huge fresh hop nose . very fruity as expected .  outstanding frothy finger of head atop a beautiful , nearly opaque mahogany body .  m- medium mouthfeel with a bit of fizz .

no aroma to speak of . taste is excellent , caramel malt with the lightest touch of hops to balance .  beautiful rich , brown pour with a tawny white head .  m : lighter body than i would like in this style , kind of like zywiec porter light in this respect .

this beer pours a clear , pale yellow with a rapidly fading head . it 's aroma has hints of lemon , vanilla , resin , and yeast .  appearance- pours a standard two fimger head with an awesome thick foamy film retention throughout the whole beer . add to this a lovley deep amber and a constant stream of bubbling , and the best lacing i'v seen on any english pale ale .  m- a bit too carbonated for the style in my opinon .

not much smell ( unless you live on arsenal , it 's really hard to smell an ab beer . ) very good taste .  750ml bomber poured into a flute ; march 2011 bottling an extremely soft golden straw color with streams of tiny bubbles pushing north to a huge , meringue-like cap . excellent retention and loads of sticky lace . it looks awesome .  a bit of a thin mouthfeel , for a porter .

im not sure if was a contaminated batch or just poor handling but it was all foam and tasted terrible . the smell is faintly of sweet malt with a little freshness of hops . the color is a great dark amber and is suprisingly clear if poored right .  a-light ruby red color . very vibrant . maybe an orangish , pinkish , brownish . a swirl of the glass releases some carbonation and leaves some nice lacing that slowly settles into the glass .  this brew can feel a little thin , although it 's so tasty that it hardly bothered me .

smell is sweet malt and a slight floral hop note , seems like a watered down typical american oktoberfest .  11oz tulip/wine appearance : the color is a dark amber , the head a light tan with sticky lace formed on the glass as you drink .  was n't crazy about the mouthfeel of this beer though , as i felt it lacked significant carbonation and was a bit thin and lifeless .

smell - a strong sweet smell with only a little malt scent to it . smells a little young to me . very tasty i take back what i said about it being young , smells young yes but the flavor is just right for the style . drinkability - not a session beer but if you can get past the smell its pretty good . nice show for the style .  appearance - a dark orange and brown color with white floaties inside the glass . plenty of lacing left on the glass after the beer is finished . an ideal looking ipa .  body is a bit thin , probably due to the low alcohol .

smell : fruity and bready . slight hint of the malty depth of the taste , but too faint and indistinct . some roasted character to the flavor emerges with warmth , further balancing the great fruit and malt notes . rather hoppy for a doppelbock , but everything is superbly balanced , and bold enough to justify the high abv ( which is detectable only through the deep malty flavors ; not much alcohol burn here ) . juicy , like a good dipa ( which works great with the peachy hop flavor ) . overall : tastes more like a riff on a doppelbock than an actual doppelbock , but the flavors work great together and all the classic elements are present . very good .  moderate pour produced an eruption of white foam that mushroomed to a billowing white head which never completely receded , leaving a small archipelago shaped cap stubbornly floating on the beer . the beer is a beautiful purely yellow gold . visually this may be the best looking beer i 've ever seen and i can only imagine how jealous bmc beer marketers must look at this beer .  the belgian/wheat characteristics are present in the background but also help to make it such a smooth drinking brew m : average mouthfeel with a slight ammount of tongue tingle d : highly drinkable beer with very smooth characteristics but still beautiful tastes overall i absolutly love this beer and it is my mission to spread its wonder to all

s- slightly peppery , boozy , and very caramel-riffic . t- the caramel was borderline overpowering in the nose , but nowhere to be found in the taste ( a good thing ! ! ) . sweet , but in check , this is a tasty porter . has some similar flavors to a few old ales i 've had ... the 2007 old stock i recently had is ringing in my head as i drink this . very fruity for a porter , something different , and something welcome as well . another tasty treat from smuttynose ... which is quickly surpassing dfh as my favorite east coast brewery .  a- a deep , dark inky black liquid with barely any light coming through at the edges . the brown head is thin but very creamy and leaves some nice lacing .  this one strikes me as kind of flat . needs a tad more carbonation and i think it would be leaps better than it is . nice creamy smooth mouthfeel though .

smells ... like nothing just a hint of toasted malt ... .  this brown ale pours iwth a dark red-brown body topped by a medium thick , tan head with lots of lacing .  this has got a lot of hop bitterness to it , this reminds me a little of hopslam . i did n't really notice the `` hop backbone '' like everyone else has mentioned . like hopslam , this is best drank slowly due to the high abv .

not much of a scent on it , something like caramel ... i ca n't really put my finger on it . i expected fruits galore but i did n't find it . pretty sweet beer too , i like it but too strong for me right now .  fantastic sheets of lace coat the glass in one hell of an attractive manner .  the taste is thick and interesting . its just a tad lacking , leaving this beer to taste like eating hershey 's special dark chocolate powder . this beer coats the tongue well , but the taste is over-powering . i 'm really impressed with the idea here and think this is a good beer .

aroma is lacking a little , sweet , slight alcohol and hoppy , not much there . full bodied , smooth and highly drinkable considering the abv . the hops and malt are well balanced , one does n't overpower the other and this will certainly please a hophead but would also work well as an introduction to the style .  poured into a delerium tulip the body is a very clear golden color . if i poured this into a mug it would look like the ideal image of a beer .  alas , the mouthfeel is more watery than what one would come to expect from such a taste .

something along the lines of ginger ale or dish soap and an unidentifiable frutiness . fresh water and overall clean . not quite as roasty as the nose suggests , but roasty nonetheless . the nose is a little weird and does n't quite reflect the taste , but no big deal .  a : this beer pours a beautiful , clear , copper color with a one finger of offwhite creamy head that holds nicely .  mouthfeel : feels like every other kind of amber ale i 've had , not bad .

maybe due to age , but the aroma is very basic . quite complex . m : soft , creamy , with near perfect carbonation .  appearance - super pale straw body .  bourbon . fizzy enough to make this way too drinkable , and that does a wonderful job of injecting dryness into the sweet , caramelly notes of woody bourbon that are certainly present here . it would be nicer if this beer was a bit thicker and smoother , but i think that would open it up to extreme booziness .

it 's opaque and thick in apperance , but actaully quite drinkable . the smell is coffee and charcoal ... the taste is slightly acidic when it first hits the mouth , but it quickly smooths out to a rich coffee flavor .  very attractive presentation . this alsatian amber looks phenomenal in the glass . the body is a brilliant deep copper/amber with generous carbonation that gives rise to an rocky creamy white head . wow , looks more like some belgian ales i have sampled rather than a lager . a very beautiful beer .  the mouthfeel is thin with a watery texture , and lively carbonation .

i detect a slight citrus nose , not unpleasant at all .  a beautiful red color next to that head gives this beer an exceptional appearance , with a light malty\fruity smell .  i just think it 's amazing what ab will do to make a quick buck . hopefully this will quickly go into the grave along with new coke and chrystal pepsi .

the smell is a little sweet with a mild but present nobles hop aroma . a little bit fruity and mildly floral with a little grassy scent .  great lacing head retention s : dark fruit , vinous notes , slight tobacco hop signature , all tail off after a while t : follows the nose , serious fig action , herbal hoppyness that is bordering on astrigent , not a very good start so far ... smooths out a little as time goes by , hints of baker 's chocolate & coffee too .  carbonation is quite high , body is medium but filled with bubbles , mouthfeel is creamy but slick . very flavorful , but the carbonation ruins the mouthfeel for me .

the nose is suprisingly light for a big stout with hints of chocolate and dark malt . a pretty solid russian imperial with its only real weak spot in the nose .  it pours pitch black with an expansive light tan head that never goes away throughout the whole pint and leaves plenty of sticky lace .  feels a bit thin , where creamier and chewier would 've done the trick .

smell is a bit strong of oak wood and a mild amount of spice . not a whole lot else on the nose . very little oak comes to play , and what is there really amps up the flavor of the pumpkin .  appearance - a very appropriate pumpkiny-orange pour capped off by an incredibly full 3-finger , subtly orange tinted off-white head . cloudy appearance . very impressive .  mouthfeel is thick , but a little too fizzy .

this lacing continues down the sides of the glass as i empty this pint . nose is heavy on the roasted malts and toasted grains . creamy malts and roasted flavors mingle together nicely .  a - black as night with the smallest amber/ruby highlights and an enormous tan , dense , and lumpy head which seemed to refuse to go down .  m : very medium-light body and a slightly bitter but almost watery finish .
again , the smell was `` off '' but all was forgotten when tasting .  2004 bottle appearance- amazing head on this beer . the beer was a dark ruby color .  it was very astringent .

this brew pours up a murky reddish brown color with a nice off white head ... the nose is sweet malts and a nice funky aroma ... the taste is funky ( get down !  pours out with a cloudy yellow body and a huge white pillowy head of foam . the head breaks down slowly leaving a mountain of foam in the middle and covering the entire glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit lighter than expected but doesnt detract , and drinkability is excellent for the abv .

rich amber orange color , moderate rising carbonation . s : cinnamon candy , somewhat sweet , apricot syrup , sour grass t : sweet and sour . o : pretty terrible , undrinkable .  it pours with a massive head that has real staying power ! a lot of different flavours going on in this brew ... overall , a good buy but maybe it needs more ... funk perhaps , i do n't know but it needs something ... but i did enjoy it !  little helper is a good beer . defining it is a bit difficult , i would call it a hoppy but light ( er than normal ) red ale . very drinkable . nearly no head . good beer , but the malt flavor is not very interesting , and not pronounced considering the color . but i am a hop fan so that is just fine . all around great , hoppy , and drinkable red . wish rogue made less expensive beer !

overall , the smell is nice , but rather faint . the aroma leaves a little to be desired , but overall it 's got just a touch of everything - maltiness , hoppiness , spices , dryness , sweetness and carbonation .  $ 13.99 / 4 pack dan 's liquor plover , wisconsin appearance - a hazy pale orange to dark yellow in color . the bright white head tops the brew at up to 3 inches and is solid . as the head slowly tapers it leaves a great lacing along the inside of the glass .  the body on this one is a little too thin .

a ruby red colour , with a nice smell to it too .  very nice retention and great thick sticky lacing . excellent appearance .  ... big foamy head in to the glass that seems to break its neck to dissipate , but leaves a tiny ring ... is very refreshing and tangy but when it warms it can be a beast , serve cold ! ! .. better than most bmc products and probably somewhat better than miller chill ...

rich , medium amber color topped by a large , bubbly off-white head with lots of staying power and a good amount of thick lace left on the glass . smell was mild ... malt with a bit of hop spiciness . an excellent choice when everything else on the menu is a fizzy , yellow macro brew !  a : clear dark brown with red hues and lots of tiny little bubbles . two-finger , off-white , creamy head that lasted a while . very nice lacing .  mouthfeel is light bodied , light carbonation . smooth , but average .

subtle malt , a hint of earth and a touch of cream ... aroma almost reminds me of guinness .  this ale pours a beautiful chestnut brown with an off-white head that clings to the sides of the glass . looks grand in a scotch thistle glass .  there 's a really nice level of hopping in this one , that becomes apparent in the middle and finish . could do with having a bit more body , but its okay as it is .

the smell was not remarkable - average at best .  a- dark black looking , held up to the light a dark ruby tint appears and you can notice definite clarity from such lively carbonation . leaves an amazingly full lace . as it is consumed the head turns more cloudlike .  medium carbonation and thin mouthfeel makes this brew very drinkable .
s : a very weak grainy smell . not much going for it .  it is a beauty to look at - but enough with looking .  mouthfeel is moderate in weight , but this could really use some more carbonation .
s-mild smell of roasted barley with little else that i can detect .  pitch black colour , impressive brown head .  the mouthfeel is a tad thin , lack of malt .

n : alcohol right up front makes itself known , grassy background flavors with some yeast and some banana specs . no detection of hops . t : abundance of fruity sweetness and spices . d : extremely drinkable and i think it would be even moreso with some age on it .  superb creamy egg shell head . dark copper pour .  m : dry , bitter , light/medium bodied , crisp , too much bite from the alcohol .

dark fruit , specifically currant , dominates the smell . there is also a good dose of dark roasty malts and definitely creamy chocolate . its even nicer that it is both cheap and available .  black as nite . amazing layers of stacked , brown foam .  body is light and mouthfeel is fairly thin and bubbly , with a very clean finish .

s- i 'm not a fan of fruity beers at all , but this smells amazing ! it smells like strawberry shortcake , very strong ! subtle notes of wheat but this smells good !  dark copper to amber in color , with the most interesting head i have ever seen out of a bottle .  m- now this is a little off , the body is a little flabby , and even slightly watery .

three finger high foamy tan head with decent retention and some sporadic patchy lacing the aroma is full of peat and chocolate , malted milk ball a little bit of butter scotch , caramel some smoke , sweet and malty . the taste is pretty in line with the aroma one gets of the nose , no real surprise here .  a - a taller-than-normal pour reveals the beer to be a clear dark brown color but in the glass it 's as black as night . the head foams up right away to a dense tan froth with great retention and dense , thick lacing on the glass . d - huge waves of lace and foam til the last sip , this extra stout looks perfect , tastes good , and feels fine which really makes it one easy drinking extra stout .  m - smooth and medium/light body . a slightly dry aftertaste .

s : mild hoppy smell , but overall pretty nonexistent .  a- this beer poured a gorgous amberish orange color with a huge fluffy white cream colored head . the body is slightly hazy and there are some gigantic horizontal mountains of lacing from the head that cling to the glass .  it had a medium feel in my mouth with ok carbonation .

s : the nose was a very mild citrous aroma , discreet of a mild pale .  a : nearly faultless . rich mahogany color , incredibly puffy 1 '' head that lasts forever , nice lacing .  feels lighter than expected . reasonable carbonation . perhaps lacking in body but only slightly .

this stout pours a dark black with a light tan head ... not as frothy as most stouts i have had . the smells are definitely different as aside from the coffee and chocolate one can sense a bit of vanilla and banana .  the beer after its departure from the 12-ounce brown bottle resides in the glass an onyx color with a modest creamy chocolate colored head , the lace a thick coating to cover the glass .  smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing . the apple/apricot scent is strong but would be overpowering to the tongue , the muted apple notes balanced well . i would definitely order this again .

the nose consists of sweet pale malts , clover-y lager yeast , and just a touch of noble hops . if anything , the nose is just like a typical helles .  a massive white foamy head greets me like a beer commercial . great retention and a crazy amount of sticky lacing .  m - thinner than i 'd like , with very fine carbonation . the finish is very dry and short , which contributes to the impression .
the smell is very faint . sweet , malty , nutty , in taste and smell .  looks very very dark and pretty .  it was thin and gave a slight hoppiness that did n't last long in the mouth .

aroma - has a bready malty base with hints of spice and yeast . kind of short-lived , the scents are light but steady , even in a belgian glass . mouthfeel - sturdy feel , moderate carbonation , well done for the style .  a - pours a brilliant clear amber with an off-white moundy head that takes it 's time going down . provides beautiful sheets of lacing .  the feel is a little to light , almost watery .

s : inviting fresh aroma ; metallic and a grainy/wheat smell .  this beer pours a cloudy pale orange color . this beer looks a lot like a really good hefe , and i like that .  served on tap in the black angus restaurant at the stoudt 's brewery . body is a dark copper color . thick head with excellent lace . the scent is a bit fruity and has elements of apples and hops . a nice balance of sweet malts and bitter hops make up the flavor . alcohol peeks through , which is surprising as this is a relitively low abv ale .

s - not much aroma going on here , just a bland ale smell .  a= pours a nice deep amber color with a huge off white head . holds great retention and lacing .  medium to thin in the body . i thought the carbonation seemed a bit to high and lessened my enjoyment of this brew .

s - not overly aromatic , faint citrus with a little caramel malt and some alcohol is there , but does n't smack you in the face . m - a lighter mouthfeel than expected and very smooth for the style . o - a well-balanced , highly drinkable ipa that does not overwhelm with flavor complexity , but is still quite enjoyable .  bbd of 4/27/07 07 version pours copper/orange with 3 fingers of fluffy head . superoir lacing & very good head retention s : nothing up front , but then earthy hoppyness & whisper of fruit .  m : smooth & a little flat ( thanks to the nitro i 'm sure ) .

smell : this brew smells absolute amazing , with a smokey , wood-like smell that is intoxicating . one of my favorite so far . taste : lots of malty flavor , with the obvious peat overtones from scotch barrels . drinkability : not for the brew pounding type , this is definitely a heavy beer , thought very satisfying .  reviewed from notes taken on 4/4/2011 appearance : pours jet black with three fingers of thick tan head .  mouthfeel is rather light with less than medium carbonation .

s - malty with a sharp cocoa aroma . t - roasted malt of chocolate and coffee with a definite hop presence .  pours a gorgeous pitch black in my duvel tulip , with a thick creamy two plus fingers of espresso colored foam . truly a beautiful looking forward .  it 's union made , can you tell ? there 's little doubt that every canadian past the age of 16 has tried this beer on more than one occasion . when a little older but not wiser , if nothing else comes to mind when the waitress asks , you instinctively order `` just a blue '' . ice cold it 's refreshing , and that is this brew 's raison d'etre . every time . i 've begun the habit of adding a pinch of salt in the glass , which seems to cut the skunk and make this somewhat palatable .

aromas of pine , citrus and floral . the aromas on this one was all hops .  this beer poured black into my glass , not simply dark brown , but a light impervious black with a creamy coffee colored mousse of a head that floated above the abyss darkness below out of pure fear .  the mouthfeel on a doppelbock is a tricky thing -- too thick and you wo n't be able to drink your half-liter bottle , let alone your full liter mass .

aroma is clean , sweet , and cold . hops are subtle and faint . a decent nose , though a bit muted and weak .  367th review on ba bottle to tulip 750 ml cap & cork 086/477044 app- sunshine yellow with a gigantic three finger bell filling head . very good looking saison .  the ringwood yeast just tore this up and gave it a slab of butter on top ... m : crisp , but just tastes pretty bad ... d : a pretty bad beer , the ringwood yeast dominates this brew so much that i had to drain pour the rest , too bad .

massively drinkable and very enjoyable . could be misplaced as an english bitter and close the best of its kind in australia .  pours beautifully into my glass , a deep and dark black that continues to appear solid , even when held to a bright light . even the edges are just slightly lighter , say charcoal , rather than betray this beer to having any color . at that point , the head came down to a thick film , with the usual pacman `` moon crater '' divots in it .  smells of sweet malt , grains , hops , toasted bread and honey . very weak nose overall . tastes of roasted malt , grains , lemon , citrus hops , caramel , bread and yeast ... a toasty flavor that is not typical for an ipa and more like a lager than an ipa . it 's a bad ipa , not hoppy or like an ipa at all ... a drain pour , as it was tough to finish this beer . bordered on terrible .

smell : very weak smell .  poured into a new belgium snifter a - transparent blood red , half finger head , off white almost tan/brown and some serious lacing s - sweet .  appearance : pours a cloudy amber , moderately carbonated with offwhite foam , leaving moderate foamy lacing . smell : hops are floral and sweet , blending well with the strong raspberry undertones . taste : begins tart , with mellow floral hop taste , very light toasty malts which bring forth the hints of raspberry and honeycomb , finishes witha tangy bitterness that allows a slight yet lasting raspberry lingering . drinkability : very delicious small batch by mbc , its well brewed and the subtle notes of the raspberry are not forced , decent abv as well .

poured a clear light gold color with a huge white head . nose has smell of cloves and a slight wheat and funk . good beer overall would recommend to anyone who desires the style .  this stout pours with a jet black body topped by a thick brown head with a decent amount of lacing .  mouthfeel : feels soft and smooth at first , but the finish is harsh and drying in a way that really detracts from the overall beer .

lot 's of sweet caramel in the nose . little to no hops in the aroma .  head is tan in color and has great retention with a solid one finger above the brew . head is creamy in appearance and is looking like it will leave some stellar lacing ... hey what do you know it does !  mouthfeel- a tad thin for the style but still got a nice solid body .

smell is mainly of english hops , nothing overpowering . nice chocolaty taste , with a good coffee bitterness that make for a nice dry mouthfeel . nice job .  reviewed from notes a - poured into a standard pint glass a wonderous midnight black that had a one finger mocha head resulting in massive , massive side lacing .  m : pretty low carbonation , which is definitely not a problem for the style . the body 's a little thinner than i 'd prefer , though . a nice , smooth mouthfeel to the beer .

s : very little smell coming out of this one .  a : looks great , deep red , very vibrant , with a nice off-white head and great head retention . fantastic lacing .  the body has a little chalky hard-water feel to it -- like mineraly .
s- all i can smell is the roasted malt .  it 's got a beautiful brown body with a fantastic , super long lasting tan head .  medium to light bodied .

smell : fruity/floral hops with a noticeable bitterness . i 'm not a fan of smelling the bitterness beforehand .  pretty badass looking- near black with a huge blanket of uneven foamy tan head that slowly reduces into a thick skim . great retention with a crazy amount of sticky lace rings .  taste was similar , with a slight sourness . maybe it was n't so fresh , but i drank it within a couple days of buying it . did n't taste the alcohol really , but it was still pretty poor i thought , and not what i was hoping or thinking it 'd be .

not much carbonation as is expected with this hand pumped beer . the flavor is rich with cirus , orange , hops , mixed malts i suspect , cream , raisin sead and a sweet yeasty flavor . this is a good ipa and if i could get it everyday in a cask-conditioned state , i would drink it often .  very nice looking beer .  m : a bit too fizzy upon sipping , and i was looking for a bit more 'heft ' .

s -- less citric , more gently floral . definitely a subtler hop variety for a big style of beer . i got some deep rose and magnolia in there , along with the usual generic nectar type smells . t -- really interesting .  a : this is a great looking imperial stout : black in color with a nice mocha colored foam .  mouthfeel : i 've never been a big fan of the body of almost all american porters as they just seem thin , a tad watery , and big on carbonation , and this one does n't break that trend .

smell is weaker than expected , but fuity , with notes of wine ( for obvious reasons ) . great summer ale . very fruity , and definitely on the sweeter side . perfect carbonation , makes this a very drinkable beer .  pours an awesome deep black with a super sticky tan head and awesome lacing . looks good .  mouthfeel is moderately smooth and prickly but ends with a harsh , dry finish with a medium-light body . the finish is intensely dry with an initially harsh potent hop bitterness which smooths out somewhat and lingers on the palate for a long time . a very fine ipa in it 's own right , but not smooth enough or balanced enough to compete with stone ipa or centennial ipa .

smells of molasses and a sort of sweet oak .  a - the pitch black pour is topped by a dense tan head . fantastic retention and sticky lace rings cover the inside of the snifter .  mouth feel is a little thin at first with too much carbonation for an english style brown .

the aroma is light but gives a slight skunkiness that i foud surprising given the brown 12 ounce bottle . the flavor is quite good with a decent balance between the malt and hops . it has a somewhat watery body for feel but is eminently drinkable .  black oily pour with a medium dark brown head .  light bodied , with very light carbonation tingle on the roof of the mouth , and a slippery feel .

cold , it smells a little like weak french roast . warming up , i get coffee creamer & cocoa powder , bark , & surprisingly clean yeast ( where are the belgian phenols ? the alcohol detracts slightly , but overall , a really nice beer .  basically pitch black with a creamy tan head that just rests and barely settles during consumption . great lacing and just all around excellent to the eye .  taste was very pleasant and hard to describe as well . maybe fruity , maybe nutty , not hard to drink at all with a very slight bitter aftertaste . not a hint of the 7 % abv . given the chance i would share it again with someone because of how different it is . i would also like to get my hands on some of the other brews from hitachino nest .

sweet malt dominates the nose ( think digestive crackers ) .  has little carbonation and a small whitish head that dissipates into a milk mustache ... a beautiful auburn color that diffracts the light .  t- hop fruitiness up front , not particularly citrus from the big c hops but just fruity . aftertaste brings up the rear with a hop bitter whollop . m- average for this style , not great but definately not bad .

the standard yeasty belgian aroma is missing .  pours out to a thick opaque black , forming a nice whipped dark espresso crema head with amazing retention and one sticky sheet of lace .  slightly bitter but balnced for a stout , i like the chocolate/coffee malty-ness mf 3.0 - bitterness makes me pucker a bit , slows me down , it 's a sipping stout , slightly thin for a stout .

source/serving : bottle smell : raisins and chocolate , but quite mild actually . taste : quite bitter up front followed by a massive wave of malts . notes : a multidimensional beer that has so much going for it .  pours a slightly hazed copper colour with a massive , massive tan head that foams into a mountain above the rim of the glass and hangs around for a long long time and once dissolved leaves chunks of residue on the glass . awesome stuff .  m- thin to medium body- highly attenuated- with a coarse carbonation which delivers a slightly bloating feeling . could stand to have some softer carbonation .

s : creme brulee aroma comes through strong and hard , the name does n't lie .  it 's alive and frothy ! wonderful head , beautiful jet black color .  well attenuated , yet with a little viscocity to it . the carbonation is so soft it is almost impereceptible .

s : not particularly smelly . light notes of hops , caramel malt and faint mint . t : citrus hops dominate .  watching the cascading effect is truly one of the pleasures of a beer drinker .  maybe this was chilled too much but it seems to have a little too much bite , which might also be the carbonation .

s - not much scent , only a little burtness , aroma smelled by 3 people to make sure it was n't me . t - great , bitter bitter roasted malts , with a chocolate finish .  a-pours an orange/copper with a head that is four fingers thick . the head is extremely dense and it dissipates slowly leaving a thick lacing on the sides of the mug . there was lacing down the entire glass .  it was a little over carbonated for my likes but still had a great feel to it in my mouth .

h : 1/4 '' head a : beautiful dark amber s : light , hoppy t : wow , perfect balance of hops/yeast/carbonation m : rico suave d : i can drink this all night this is a great beer to relax to over dinner or in front of the idiot box .  appearance - a rich , cloudy red-brown with a two to three finger head of creme foam .  some candy-nougat sweet malt comes up for support but lacks some oomph , imo , which contributes to a slightly thin mouthfeel .

very pale yellow brown color , after the pour you see alot of big bubbled carbination . i catch mainly a citrus smell and flavor , but nothing really presents itself as overpowering .  ( a ) - pours almost pitch black with a large light brown head that slowly dissipated to a solid 1-finger . plenty of lacing present .  it was also too carbonated . d- if it was n't for the mouthfeel i would rate this a 5 for sure .

s : nose is somewhat muted - sweet caramel malts with minor smoked notes . t : taste is nice .  the beer in my shaped pint is black , with some brown around the edges . fluffy tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  m - it seems fairly still , but there is a sharpness that remains . the feel is unusual , but it works well enough .

smell is deceptively underwhelming ... lightly `` beery '' with a hint of rubbing alcohol ... but the taste is outstanding !  lacing is also fantastic , leaving artistic patterns on my glass .  m : a bit light and quite fizzy for the style .

malt dominates the aroma . slightly roasty , slightly toasty . very mild aroma . a very nice drinking porter .  appearance- beautiful beer ! gold , leaning almost into a cognac tone , the monstrous three to four finger crown billows and slowly begins to pop away . incredible , massive lacing .  a bit heavy on the carbonation .

smell : light smelling with malt being the dominate odor .  poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glass . crystal clear pale gold color with a 1 '' firm , fluffy white head .  even after the 4 day limit they say for the growler , this is a great beer . very light , both physically and taste wise . it is not something that will bog you down , but it is not like standard light beer style crap . it is very delicate , but potent enough to be something.flat or fresh , this is a very satisfying beer . watch out , becuase the can be gone without a notice - and everyone should drink responsibly ; - ) this is something you can use convince you macroswill freinds and their girlfriends to switch to quality .

the nose is faint and sugary with a wisp of spice . interestingly , i had it with a gingery dish and that slight cinnamon came out in a big way that was quite pleasing .  a : one of the most beautiful beers i have ever seen . it pours a murky creamy brown color . the head is monstrous . it is sooo large and fluffy kind of like whipped cream in appearance . this baby reminds me of a root beer float . the head absolutely refuses to die . it 's a very solid example of a dubbel .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with low to medium carbonation . smooth , easy to drink , but gets kind of muddy in the finish like some of the other nognes i 've had , which kind of makes my mouth feel dirty , but good winter beer nonetheless .
smell : muted malt with a surprising hop presence .  this fruit beer pours a beautiful deep , dark ruby red with a light pink cap .  m - carbonation is more muted than i thought .

pours black with nice head and lacing smells amazing . i get creme brulee with a bit of underlying funk . lovely rich and inviting . blowing me away .  a : slightly hazy orange light copper color with pillowing white head . great head retention especially considering the abv .  other than the slightly thin body , this is a superior porter .

crystal clear pale ( maybe a little too much on the pale side ) nutty amber body that pours with a great 3 finger off-white foamy head . s-lots of hop aroma almost overshadows the solid caramel malt backbone .  this has exceptional retention and lacing , especially for the style/abv .  m/d - a little thin , though probably appropriate for a session beer .

the fruity aroma was apparent , but not overly sweet smelling . appearance - 4.5/5.0 - beautiful rich brown color , light head , but color is awesome smell - 3.0/5.0 - fruity but not overly so , little malt , ok , but nothing special taste - 4.0/5.0 - rich malt flavor , sticks around a bit , licoricsh , little chocolate , full flavor takes a bit to kick in feel - 4.5/5.0 - smooth and velvety , some aftertaste but enjoyable drinkability - 4.0/5.0 - not regularly otherwise i 'd be an alcoholic , would definitely have again though  dark black body , dark milk chocolate head . extremely dark and perhaps the darkest of the yeti beers .  m_moutheel was actually ok except that it felt like sugar was coating teeth . other than that it was thick and full bodied .

pretty weak on the nose - slightly nutty , slightly yeasty aroma , with a good whack of sweaty armpits or wet leather . not great .  beautiful night black color with a nice tan head . about 1 pinky thick head with good retention . fades to a nice white ring . good lacing on the glass .  the sweet smell was picked up in the taste after swallowing the sip but only for a second and then the taste disappears . it is very light and easy to drink without being light in flavor .

s- very fresh pale cereal grains and fruity floral pineapple and fruit blossom aroma . i appreciate pilseners with ale complexities . t- very crisp and perfectly bittered and balanced .  pours a dark dark dark brown ( pretty much black ) with a crazy thick inch of dark brown foam/head which leaves a boat ton of sticky brown lacing .  m-a little thinner in the body than i expected , but does n't ruin it by any means .

there 's a bit of diacetyl in the nose , along with some grainy aromas and subdued earthy hops . the flavor follows the aroma , but without the diacetyl .  gorgeous pour ! deep , dark orangehoneysuckle gold with a giant white head .  i thought the mouthfeel may have been a tad dry and thin for all that malt , but that just adds to the drinkability , which is very good for the strength of this beer .

it has a very odd aroma . a very tangy smell is present with bits of raspberry . smells almost like vinegar..almost .  a - beautiful dark amber with tons of head - good 2 inches . retention is pretty good over the course , lacing sudsy but thick and a little web like .  m- mouthfeel is carbonated and a bit watery .
smells awesome . little spicey .  the beer a deep brown to black , the head gigantean in size , creamy in texture and a beauteous light chocolate in color .  mouthfeel - very beerlike .

the smell was strongly hoppy and a little bit of malt . there was also a slight citrusy aroma - i would like to have more citrus .  bottle courtesy of fonefan : poured a dirty beige yellow color ale with a huge foamy head with great retention and perfect lacing .  overall , a bit thin .

aroma is of raisins and alcohol . fantastic beer , and well worth the $ 12.50 this normally costs . i was lucky enough to find a bottle mis-marked at $ 4.99 !  impenetrable black with an ovaltene head .  the mouthfeel is slightly thin and foams up in the mouth a little ; the beer needs some sort of aeration .

it does n't give me much smell , but there is at least a hint of sweet fruit .  has outstanding appearance for a lager .  the chocolate is the predominate flavor here , but it only enhances the brew . slightly sweet with just the right level of dark roasted malt and hops to balance out the bitterness . good drinkability . great looking head after an agressive pour .

mmmm ... coffee , mmmmm ... . the lace is definitely forming in rings to my glass here , pretty good head retention for something with whole mexican coffee beans . i heard it 's really hard to pull off , the aroma here is primarily in your face eye opener of coffee beans , a whiff of chocolate tones , dark roasts , and a very light hop aroma is hidden in there . the aroma is the best thing this beer 's got going for it .  not even the same name , but anyway ... appearance : opaque , glorious deep orangey gold with big white head receding to leave heavy lacing .  4.5 m a bit on the thin side .

this brew is very hazy - a definite plus for me . not a strong smelling ipa . ( t ) moderate bitterness with grapefruit-like hops .  beautiful dark ruby colour , very good thick head .  it feels a bit thin and overly carbonated for a strong english ale .

smell is a bit distant but bring more of the belgian sweet & yeast than hops . i 'll warrant i was skeptical popping open an eight month old belgian ipa , but this is far & away the most complex belgian ipa i 've tasted to date .  pours a a clear gold with a constant upward stream of fine white bubbles and an extremely long lasting , frumpy , pure white head . the overall effect is of a beautiful looking beer that is interesting to taste but that i wish would stand still for a moment so that my palate could peg it down .  the mouth feel is average , the aroma is less than appealing and the taste is well insipid . lesson learned , do n't send the wife to the package store with less than specific instructions on which beer to purchase .

smell : malt sweetness is mild but pleasant . taste : nice malt profile with caramel , bits of chocolate , and a soft bitterness .  pours a surprisingly clear amber , with a fluffy , sticky , voluminous , lace-leaving head of slightly off-white .  a - deep clear brown with some dark amber highlights ; one finger tan head settled down to a nice frothy cap ; light lacing that seemed to slide down glass s - rich , dark coffee starts to come through then milk chocolate and caramel t - coffee is present throughout but it is understated and just part of the profile ; some malt and bread toward the end with a mildly sweet chocolate and caramel finish m - very lightly carbonated ; thin bodied ; no bite or drying finish d - while this one left a bit to be desired in the mouthfeel and taste department it is very drinkable overall - thin body and light carbonation make it go down easy with a nice light , coffee/candy bar flavor ; what 's not to like right ?

surprisingly subdued nose , but after a few deep sniffs , a clear aroma of liquid caramel / toffee arises . could use a bigger nose . certainly enjoyable .  appearance : beautiful yellow sunset over the western skies - 5 smell : minty pine with a touch of aspen covered hills - 5 taste : tastes of juniper molasses tea , if youve had it you know what i mean - 5 mouthfeel : have to be honest on this one - 2 drinkablitiy : if youre listening to willie and youve had a few ... 5  medium to full bodied imperial stout , a bit lighter than i expected .

the aroma does n't provide much hint that it is terribly different either , but what is discernible is pleasant . the flavor is n't hidden , though , with a crisp , musty noble hop character that is balanced by a dry grainy malt base . although the first impression is n't overly impressive , this is a terrific beer that i would gladly order again and again .  the beer pours a cloudy yellow with a rocky off white head that holds wonderfully and laces incredibly .  watery feel for a stout but with just enough body to get you through .

the nose is limited , offering just a bit of malt , but it 's clean and welcoming . it 's dextrinous in the mouth with a fine , moderate carbonation ( @ 2.4 volumes co2/ltr ) that leaves it quite smooth .  wow , good looking beer . pours with my favorite waterfall type head ... ( forms from the bottom ) 2 fingers of creamy tan head form and clearly let you know they are going to stay a while . lacing is everywhere .  m - a bit flat . mouthfeel is so far the best part of this beer .

smells mapley , a little too sweet . tastes mapley and nutty with a subtle , bitter finish -- really nice .  if nothing else , olde mecklenburg makes gorgeous beers . the head is ample , pale-cream , and tight . mecktoberfest is , over all , a solid sessionable , gorgeous beer , whose only fault is a hit of diacetyl .  mouthfeel is on the light side , but there is too much carbonation in this .

s - subdued citrus hop aroma , probably due to the age of the beer .  i have been very , very impressed with the consistent perfect pour this beer offers .  the only thing i do not like about this beer is that it is a little lacking in body - seems a bit thin .

s - very very mild malts . not a strong aroma at all . t - light malts and oats .  pours a really thick head , nothing frothy but thick and luscious . a golden amber red body , thick with nice color .  mouthfeel suffers from lack of carbonation , but flavors are all right up my alley .

best part about it is you can get it almost everywhere.bad part is few sellers can pour a decent pint . low abv makes drinking it like pushing a rock up a hill , just keeps getting harder and harder till your too tired to lift an arm . pass me a straw and some whiskey please .  appearance - looks great , black as night with a nice caramel tan head that hangs on the whole time .  mouthfeel is slightly thin .

i love a good stout - and this is a good stout . i am bias to dark beers , but this one is all around very enjoyable . notes of anything dark - chocolate , coffee , but again , nothing that stands out or over anything else , and working together in harmony . it finished really smooth , very very slight bitter , and sweet almost , and entirely satisfying .  best by ( i assume ) 12/1/11a poured into a tulip . very clear shiny brass color with a tall rush of white foam . excellent lace plasters the glass .  only complaint is it is a little thin but nothing that deters me from wanting more . the rich citrusy hops , leave you wanting another drink to quench your thirst they are so drying , it 's basically a no win situation . mid palate is lacking roundness but otherwise delicious . because of the immense amount of hops it would be hard to drink many of these .

wonderful lacing and good head retention . smell is of dark roasted malts with a light vanilla presence , not as much vanilla as i had hoped .  comes to the table with a wonderfully cascading creamy off-white head . huge sheets of lace , and an ever present nice cap round off a nice nitro appearance , which is only marred by the fact that the russet coloured body is off base for a porter .  mouthfeel is light-medium to medium , drinkability is really nice , i bought a six last week and again this week , i rarely do that .

not much smell but some roasted and syrupy notes . wow . when a wave of this brew comes crashing across my tongue my tastebuds scream and run in fright as if from a tsunami of hugely sweet , just on the edge of cloying , syrupy malt topped off with obvious alcohol and strongly bitter resinous hops intent on the destruction of every living thing in my mouth .  appearance : very dark brown , gigantic head that cascades almost like a guinness , tons of head retention while i drank , tons of lacing .  light carbonation . lacking in creaminess .

yup , st. patty 's day . the long cascade , the almondy , coffee taste and thick creamy head . the low abv makes it a great all day beer .  nose : deep fruit , clove like spice , dark malts especially some coffee/chocolate notes , and maybe a slight hint of oxidation appearance : black , viscous , with a lasting brown head flavor : chocolate/coffee from dark malts , a bit of candied cherries , some slight oxidation , but not much in the way of typical bourbon barrel flavor .  low carbonation .

the smell is faint . i detect an alcoholic , brandy-like smell . the taste is wonderfully complex , with a cherry brandy flavor , along with a smoky toasty chocolate malt presence , as well as a slight taste of vanilla .  pours dark black colour with a nice medium tan head . great head retention and lacing of the glass . awesome stuff .  it was watery and smooth with just a little carbonation and a strong malt aftertaste .

a huge light an head great retention and lacing ... the aroma is light and disappointing , not a ton going on . light soapy hops , chocolate , a hint of alcohol .  dark chocolate with a reddish tint , the head is big and mocha colored and leaves some wonderful lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but the carbonation is pleasant .

smell : i could n't really smell much . taste : definitely bitter , but in a good way .  bottled on 7-10-04 best before 7-10-09 a- pours a great looking , barely cloudy , luminescent liquid . it is a great golden color . this looks great in a duvel tulip .  the taste is light liquid sugar : a strong fruit and candy beginning that rolls across the tongue and leaves a sea-like ( read , salty ) aftertaste that crisply dries the back of the tongue and leaves the mouth wanting more . the overall feeling is medium bodied and the beer develops stronger hints of clove , dirt , and pepper throughout the pint . i ca n't wait to match it to a nice cheesy pasa or crostini !

not sure if i should review this beer based on expectations for an ipa or for the flavor alone . the taste starts with some nutty malts and finishes hoppy , with a slightly metallic taste somewhere in between . at 5.5 % abv i 'd consider this a session brew . as a side note : what is the difference between this and your standard run-of-the-mill brown ale ?  a - pours to a two finger tan head . body has a rich amber or reddish brown tint . cloudy with no visible particulate . beautiful lacing clings to the glass .  review to style as they say and for a mass produced macro swill this is my favorite for just chillin and enjoying some beer thats not gon na get me too wasted . the appearance on all of em ( macro swills ) is pretty nice gold straw with continued effervescence throughout and a good carbonation level . extremely drinkable and the flavor is a very mellow german or czech type hops . they arent making it strong but it still tastes like one of the beers i grew up with .

the massive , whipped egg-white head on this tarnished gold beer offers up an awesome bouquet of fresh lemon . lemongrass , herbal hops , sour yeastiness , white pepper , and just a touch of pine or maybe even juniper .  poured from the bottle into a stemmed tulip . a - nice orange amber body with a white fluffy head on top . lots of sticky lacing on the glass .  m-medium body and a little grainy and rough on the palate with an agressive carbonation the gives it a crisp finish with just a hint of driness .

smell : caramel malt and toffee and some hints of dark drapes and prunes . relatively mild . overall : very enjoyable strong ale . enjoyable and drinkable , one i 'll certainly visit again .  i had this beer poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a nice light brown color with some orange and yellow hues shining through . the head is about 2 finger and very fluffy , the lacing is top notch ... s : the smell is nothing above average .  felt a little weak in the mouth , not much texture .

a - pours up a slightly hazy gold , with a dense white head s - faint smell of malt with hop accents .  o'hara 's irish stout is an opaque black beer with a dense , light brown foam that has outstanding retention and lacing .  mouthfeel : highly carbonated for the style .

beer tasted while sitting at my campsite , poured into clear , hard plastic glass . the aroma i found to be weak , maybe the bottle was too cold ? the taste is way better than the aroma , a good solid malty doppelbock ( kinda redundant , i know !  this looks beautiful in my tulip glass .  there 's a slight bready quality to the mid mouth impact , but the flavor is balanced and lessens evenly as its swallowed . i do n't look for a lot of bite or chewy mouthfeel in vienna lagers , so i 'm pretty happy with firebrick .

s : wheaty with citris smells . primary a lemon smell for me .  moderate to light brown pour , turns opaque in the glass . huge head that holds well , has a touch of oil and stickiness to it .  mouthfeel : thin to reference the entire continuum of beers , but average for a pilsner .

smell - the most noticable aroma is a crisp and bitter hop presence . the malt character is moderate , and definitely in the background . overall this is an average pale ale , in my opinion .  pours a jet black , very opaque , big frothy khaki head , excellent lacing .  m : very normal carbonation .

the aroma surprised me to seem somewhat non-descript . the usual citrus was not pronounced in this tulip glassful . i did get some mild malt sweetness and a hint of the grapefruit , but i found it odd that the this would be less impressive on tap , and unfortunately the taste followed suit .  15.5 ibus og 1.016 12 oz bottle with a best by date of 02/20/2011 poured into a saison dupont glass on 12/16/2010 . appearance 5/5 brilliantly clear , deep ruby brown with a light pink colored fluffy and persistent head that left excellent lacing .  mouthfeel : heavy in the front with a dry almost astringent pucker at the end . tastes like it 's been decoction mashed . drinkability : a hybrid of belgian and czech styles , this one does n't really stand out in my opinion , however it is an easy drinker and a much better alternative to bmc .

errrr ... not sure what 's going on with the aroma here . is it my sniffer or does this smell like wet dog ? there is a very faint ginger smell getting through , like that of a lesser ginger ale soda . it reminds of a car-crash between the kind of hops/malt balance found in good barley wines and the fragrant spiciness of a pumpkin ale . there 's a medicinal quality to this too , but not in the negative way i would usually use that term to describe beer . fruit-like , candy-like , allkindsa-like , this is one intriguing concoction . a pleasure to sip and ponder , as each sip offers something a little different than the one before .  it pours a beautiful cloudy gold with a thick creamy head .  this harp was brewed in canada by moosehead . this is a very satisfying beer ; especially when all the over-hopped , over-malted , extreme productions . become too much ... which is the true beauty of this harp . it is straight forwardly flavorful without making great demands on the palate . lively with a clean finish . this is the first harp i have sampled in a few years , and is easily the most tasty i have ever encountered .

nose is mainly cool , soft pine notes , maybe a bit of sweet fruit in there also .  appearance - a few moments after uncapping , a plug of foam starts slowly creeping up the neck in the bottle . the beer has a purplish red cast , but needs a strong backlight to show it .  carbonation is strong ; lots of small short bubbles . nope : another dull beer with an organic excuse .

pours a dark ruby/amber colo with a nice big one finger light yellow head an lots of light white lacing . nose is very light on this sadly .  keeps a huge frothy lasting beige head . gorgeous beer .  a smoked lager from fort collins brewery . 1.0 liter bottle for $ 8.29 . i was somewhat skeptical about this beer especially because i thought there two other beers edgar and doktor were an abomination , but i opted for it and was it ever worth it ! a slight smokinness stimulates the nose as well as some alcohol , caramel and citrus hops . the palate was dominated with notes of butterschotch , smoked malts , cedar , citrus notes , light fruits and the flavor was very lingering on the palate . i did polish off a 1.0 so obviously this brew was pretty damn drinkable !

lagers get a bad reputation thanks to the macros , so i fear that this little beauty has n't gotten the attention it deserves . floral hops throuhgout , but none of that comes out on the nose . strong barley malt presence goign down , finishing up clean . damn refreshing , like any good lager .  this is a beautiful looking beer .  this is a pretty good belgian , but the spicy character takes away from the drinkability and the mouthfeel .

aroma is very lager-ish .  pours a nice honey golden color with voluminous , thick , white head . beautiful lacing/head . great retention into a little cap .  an astoundingly good dark beer for the price : 10 bucks for a 12-pack at wegmans in state college , pa . it brings some of the unique flavors found in yuengling porter to a slightly lighter beer , but make no mistake ; the stuff is not weak . it might not be the most delicious beer on the planet , but the combination of good flavor and low price are unbeatable for me as a beer-enthusiast college student ( not a drunkard ! ) everyone else has described the taste well enough . my review is mainly economic .

s. grassy bread with a hint of honey . t : sweet caramel malt dominates the palate .  pours with a very healthy light tan head ... .some molasses , burnt caramel aroma ... dark ruby red ... quite smoky on the first sip , which develops some delicious flavours ! ... alcohol is very well masked ... leaves some great lacing ... some will find it abit thin but i find it very drinkable and way to easy to drink , this sixer will be gone very quick !  the mouthfeel is medium and slightly watery with some sharp carbonation .

s : a faint smell of sweet malt , coffee and hot liquor .  perfect . seriously cloudy lace all the way down .  m_light bodied with a tight aggressive carbonation . d_i am actually pretty impressed by this .

smell - slight floral hop smell and sweet malt . do n't smell too much in this beer . taste - knocks you on your ass from the first sip .  finger and a half of white lacing ? insane lacing ? the lacing was some of the finest i have ever seen .  no real cascade , but a full , rich tan head with plenty of texture over a nearly black and opaque body . heavy lacing clings to the glass . delicious aroma of black bread . espresso and chocolate flavors . labels soak off easily and make an excellent decoration for plain garage walls .

s- this is not the best part of any cask beer , i am not sure why but you do n't get an aroma with cask ale . t- this is a solid pale ale , definitely a session ale and this beer is much better because it is served at the proper temperature , chilled , not ice cold .  appearance- midnight black with a large carmel color head .  that being said , it feels a bit too thin . qutie unfortunate .

s - surprisingly subdued but there are definite hints of dark fruits , especially figs . it smells tasty , but not like something extraordinary .  appearance this winter time special is dark , reddish-brown in color with a nice head that showed great retention and laced the hell out of my pint glass . i mean to tell you , even as i drank this down the head stayed and filmed the glass . this one was just gorgeous .  it drinks a little like carbonated white wine . the finish is somewhat dry . an interesting and refreshing brew .

s : roasted grains ... not much more . t : this is the best way to have your guinness . d : guinness on tap is always a good , safe choice and always beats out the bmc competition .  the pour is outstanding with brilliant white cranium and a golden rich looking and clear body . lots of carbonation is stimulating the head retention that lasts throughout the 1 liter serving .  the mouth is actually a little heavy and chalky for what should be , and mostly is , refreshing .

it is a nice , rusty amber color with a hint of spice in the smell . it tastes great-almost like a brown ale with a nutty after taste .  a - poured into a tulip a clear amber with a two finger head that sinks to a thick blanket and leaves huge creamy side lacing .  the mouthfeel is low carbonated almost syrupy , not what i expected .

aroma reminds me of hallertauer hops and it is blended with a dry toasty malt flavor and a weird ester i am not familiar with .  a : deep gold color . very good clarity . fades to the classic belgian lacing .  yes officer i have been drinking tonight as a matter a fact i have a fuck of a lot to drink tonight , i think 12 beers but i ca n't remember . yes i will take a breathalyzer and a blood test . yes my breath does smell like hops . no your machines are n't broken , i forgot to mention the beers i was drinking are 0.5 % alcohol by volume .

soft and mild in the nose , with timid notes of nougat , caramel , and peanuts , plus a faint berry-like fruitiness .  this poured the most amazing red with un-ending pinkish head .  the mouthfeel is kind of bland .

a : a pleasant straw to light amber color with a two finger foam . s : for me a beer should smell much as it tastes . this is not to say the smell is bad it is fine but does n't comvey to the drinker the full range of flavors that sre found in the beer .  the appearance is like black tar . amazing stuff . had a nice light brown , cream head that lasted quite long . quite an eye catching beer and perfect for a stout .  m- a very fine carbonation .

musty aroma . slightly funky , coffee , raisins and oak . a light tart crispness is actually nice but reveals a light brett infection in combination with the nose . medium-full body with moderately-high carbonation . good .  first of all , it was an amazing red with a pink head .  the palate is completely overwhelmed by a hugely complex beastly drink .

the small was like burnt oak . a little hint of a plastic-like smell . aahh , a nice flavor a little burnt oak taste , a little coffee taste , a bit of a chocolate flavor , a nice blend of tastes with a solid hop background . a fine example of a porter .  bottle : poured a clear golden color ale with a huge pure white foamy head with good retention and some good lacing .  very good beer but does lack with a thin somwhat over carbonated mouthfeel for a stout .

the aroma first struck me as very grainy , with a slightly sweet malty undertone . as it warmed , however , i read another review on here which described it as `` soapy , '' and from that point on , sure enough , soap was all i could smell . odd .  pours dark brown with ruby highlights . tan sea-foam head settles to a surprisingly thick film . lacings completely coat the glass , and absolutely refuse to slide down the glass . impressive .  mouthfeel is a little thin with very little carbonation .

try getting them to drink a belgium ; ) do n't get me wrong i like incredibly hoppy beer , but you know i 've forgotten how nice a well balanced ipa can be . smell was perhaps a little lacking . but a very pleasing beer .  appearance- golden honey , beautiful color in the pils glass . no unattractive , excessive bubbling . a nice head formed during the pour and lasted the duration of my drink . there was a significant amount of lacing on the sides of the glass .  the lack of flavor is the most important part , it 's more like a watery , sour drink with a bit of beer added . i guess that is malt , but it 's ... light . on the bright side , it 's refreshing at first and there is no really offensive `` off '' flavor 's , i 'm not picking up any metal and it 's rather clean .

slightly more hoppy than malty but a pretty tame nose altogether . the roasted chocolatey malts make their way forward about halfway through the glass .  pours a beautiful deep dark mahogony with dark cherry barely peeking out on the edge if held up to a light an awesome thick rock light brown head rushed to the top of the glass .  m : well at least it is n't as over carbonated as the macros .

the smell was muted in comparison just some banana , a slight whiff of lemon and faint husky grain . sweet start with banana , cotton candy that was cut nicely by wheat and grain flavour .  beer poured a clear golden orange with a generous 2 finger white head that is leaving a perfect lacing behind .  carbonation is medium to medium-heavy , and mouthfeel is slightly viscous , landing just north of water .

excellent lacing left behind . s - faint earthy hop aroma matched by sweet caramel malt . the aroma is on the sweet side . as it warms a light fruitiness comes through with light hints of grapefruit .  a deep rustic orange in color with a gigantic , sticky and awkwardly shaped head of foam .  m : a bit lighter in body that i would prefer .

smell : light floral malty aromas with a soapy character .  picked this up today at the cellar in olathe , ks ... appearance : pours a startling contrast of yellowish at the bottom moving towards a dark orange copper near the head . it quickly recedes , but there remains quite a film around the tops of the beer and sticky lacing all down the sides of the glass .  the body is better than medium and the mouthfeel could use a little bit more of a prick of carbonation to it .

it is not skunky and is holding up well . based on the previous review , i think the hop aroma is almost gone leaving a nice malt aroma .  poured a dark black color with an averaged sized brown head .  m - light body . pleasant carb .

and it smells fantastic ! a truly great smelling beer . t- wow .  pours from the bottle to a highly carbonated bright copper color with thick off-white head that lingers for the entire glass , and leaving excellent lacing .  overall : very light bodied for the style , but very drinkable .

smells of burnt malts almost like toast , with some slight chocolate undertones .  a : what can i say ... perfect ! ! ! white one-finger head with a dark gold color . carbonation was visible and the beer itself was somewhat transparent . filtered quite nicely ! ! !  lager quality with a lighter cleaner body and feel . my one `` complaint '' is the bite of the carbonation that holds a particularly sharp feel .

smell is not too strong . chocolate and coffee with some sweetness to it creamy sweet bitter roasted coffee .  appearance : gorgeous frosted lemon body with a luciously frothy 2 finger white crown . seriously sexy !  even when it 's a 12 pack for $ 6 this stuff is hard to swallow . i 've done it before , sure , but i probably wo n't do it again . always tastes and smells a little ... off ; perhaps skunked but i think it tastes and smells that way when fresh . maybe they 're using moldy ingredients . not even average . blah .

very little smell . taste : great mouthfilling taste ! upfront caramel malt with a hint of sweetness .  pretty much black , with nice darkish beige head , fluffy and dense with stunning lace . retains amazingly well . pretty damn close to looking perfect .  m - light mouthfeel overall .

a bit of bread in the aroma , but not very prominent aroma overall .  slowly darkens to nearly black , with a ruby tint . a milky off-white head of about 1/2 inch appears and leaves patchy spiderweb lacing . aromas released during the pour are strongest , then weaken after the head forms ; roasted barley and background english hops .  m : a little thin probably due to low carbonation .

the golden amber color is not far off from palm . i find the smell short . having to really search for an aroma .  huge , light brown , frothy head . color was cloudy amber .  body is a little thin for an oatmeal stout , but it still has the smoothness . carbonation feels a little too heavy for this style i think .

it smells good though ! this is honestly a complete 180 from the slightly disgusting appearance . t - tastes much like the aroma ... lots of fresh glazed doughnuts , gooey caramel , mildly fruity hops , drier grassy hops , and a touch of ethanol . this is pretty good stuff !  murphys draught style stout pourers a cole sack reddish black from a 16oz nitro can . head is off the scale ... massive ... lacing ... massive .  very clear and bubbly , one finger head that looked like the fizz produced when pouring a pepsi . smells hoppy , lively citrusy orange peel and carbonation galore . the hops mildly dominate the brew , just enough to mask any malty flavor . well worth it . would recommend this brew .

this is one the beer closest to a belgian from us of a that i 've ever encountered . big foamy frothy textured head and plenty of lace . clear dark rich amber with red highlights . not too sweet . great balance .  on to the beer : it looks just like a duvel . outstanding head retention and lacing .  mouthfeel was medium with a curious admixture of cereal adjuncts and a metallic tang on the tongue . this was brutal !

s : malts , metallic tones , faint tones of dried apricots .  16.9oz bottle into my excuse for a stein a : amber with a massive beige head that slowly recedes to a disk , leaving some sticky foam on the side of my glass . crystal clear and gorgeous carbonation s : bigger than some of the marzens i 've had recently with a solid malty sweetness , pronounced bready character .  m : medium body with moderate to low carb . dry finish .

simple but aromatic .  the beautiful , deep reddish amber body of this beer is topped by a thick off white head with a good amount of lacing .  mouthfeel was medium with a heat that would be completely incorrect for the style .

this one was very disappointing . this beer is not an ipa . i tasted little hops and an off flavor that made me think of grape kool-aid . another reviewer said something about plums .  almost perfect lacing , like somebody painted it on the glass .  again , this beer was a bit thin for my taste .

verry mild nose ; some light fruitiness present . overall : 3.9 appearance : 4.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | mouthfeel : 4 | drinkability : 4 732  poured into a snifter , revealing rich brown body and a very thick , very tall tan head .  m : medium mouthfeel , slightly thinner than what i was expecting , especially once the carbonation is gone .

a frothy billowing slightly off white head erupts from this brew . what little aroma is present is well balanced between yeast , malt , and hops . no single fragrance takes over . barely any fragrance is detectable .  bottle : poured a clear amber color ale with a bug white foamy head with great retention .  the mouthfeel is crisp and refreshing , although almost too light and dry .

quilmes is great ! i 've yet to try the other varieties , but i 'd like to try a pumpkin one if they made it .  a- excellent black color with a large lingering head- tinted grey- and some lacing .  a light body , but refreshing and enjoyable , i was intriqued by this one .

the smell is a bit underwhelming , fairly faint generic fruity hop aromas and caramel maltiness with a touch of earth . decent , but too faint to make much of an impression . i almost detect aluminum , which could be my imagination .  appearance : wow ... best head ever .  watery body runs to the back of the tongue .

s - some roasty coffee notes come through . alcohol is definitely apparent . nose is not as strong as i expected .  extrememly frothy and creamy . leaves large chunks and patches behind . a nice lightly clouded golden colored pour .  taste was grain almost wheat like , slightly floral hops , light in taste and mouthfeel , lightly toasted barley taste is very clean , hops where rather low . i really like this beer
nose of hops and malt but very subdued . no real tasting notes to smell .  very nice appearance .  mf- medium/light bodied with kind of a watery feel compared to other porters .

the smell though has always bugged me a little , the sour yeastiness makes me think of the old half-full cream container you end up finding in the back of your fridge . all in all , the more stouts i try the farther this creeps down my list of favorites , but still good stuff , and a great `` old standby '' in nyc where it 's always on tap , even if you 're stuck in a sh*thole .  pours a beautifully clear golden orange with a solid 2 finger head that melts slowly and remains sticky .  m : carbonation is practically nil , somewhat watery , and viscous , ethanol character .

nose is amazing like crisp suger glazed perfectly ripe cherries .  the yellow-tinted head was a full three-fingers thick and displayed very good retention as a cap . the lacing was very thick and consistent all the way down my glass .  ps : high carbonation , which can be a bit prickely at low temperatures .

smell - smells a bit like an ipa . my first thoughts were that it was very watered down .  this beer had a great color .  the mouthfeel is also unexpectedly thin - for a beer this dark i was anticipating something more viscous .

served on-tap in a clear pint glass a : beautiful amber-orange hue with thick , sticky off-white head and plenty of lace s : disappointing aroma overall -- muted and weak , especially with the hops grown on location , i thought the aroma would be heavy . floral cascade hops aroma is definitely there , but it is medium in intensity . maybe it is a function of the overly cold serving temperature , but i thought more hops and pale malts aroma would be there . t : the taste surpasses the aroma by a long way .  it 's beautiful , with a hazy gold because of the yeast and cascading lacing , and it smells and tastes estery and wheaty to start before a good mouthful of bitter herbal hops and a funky finish with lots of green apple esters .  it does leave with bit of a skunky after-taste but its a small aspect of this otherwise delicious beer , m-medium carbonation with a slight watery finish d-the taste seems to lose its quality but it does n't seem to take too much of a dive . its a very thick beer so it does seem to go down slowly .
