not much on the aroma side , but the taste is classic bock ; all malt without any real hops influence , but not sweet .  clarity was just amazing to look at .  mouthfeel is average , thin and just a bit too carbonated for my taste .

very little smell to this one some toastedness to the nose but little else is detectable .  best before 3/2009 a : pours a hazy bright golden with a massive foamy head as every good hefe should have . super-long sustain and massive lacing .  feels thin for such a high abv barrel aged beer but it is easy to drink and the alcohol heat is mild considering .

s : dried fruits , bready ... not very strong but nice . sweet ( ish ) .  2005 , bottle # 227 out of 500 pours deep rich mahogany with a dense coating of tiny ( clearly bottle conditioned ) bubbles . incredible lace coats the sides .  smells chocolately and savory taste is even and not too sweet average mouthfeel could be a bit heavier .

smell : i just had nasal sex with a supermodel . wonderful , powerful blend of belgian yeast , honey , apricot , green apple , clove , fruitcake spice , pale malt with a mild solvent/alcohol scent underneath . it 's awesome -- i ca n't get my nose out of the glass . it 's good , but it does n't live up to the scent 's promise .  i love mcewan 's scotch ale , i love its dark hue , its smooth , carmelly rich goodness , and although i never do , i could easily have more than one .  body is a bit thin , with the malt slipping quickly away under the bittering hops that dominate the finish .

smell is good to average .  a : pours a dark , nearly impenetrable black body with a perfect finger 's worth of light tan head . it 's exquisite , in the way that all nitro-tap dark beers are : watching the suds coalesce into a dark body as they cascade up the beer is nothing short of eye-pleasing .  mouthfeel medium mouthfeel with carbonation that is just over the top in my judgment .

very clean . t : the taste is hands down the best steam beer i have ever had .  this poured a perfect beautiful black leaving a nice thick tan head that lingered for a while .  bready malts and a faint aftertaste of alcohol is also present beer is way over carbonated . only thing that got to me was the over carbonated .

some lacing s- flowerly hops t - crisp hop bite up front , with malt underneath .  mikkeller beer geek breakfast is an opaque black beer with a dark muscovado colored head that gets blotchy and has outstanding retention and lacing .  belgium should make this brewery pack up and move to another country ... like france . smelled like your typical macro lager and a skunk . tasted like weak malt with a strange bitterness in the finish ; not a good hop bitterness , just a weird oily bitter flavor . avoid this swill . a black mark on the reputation of a country that brews some of the finest beer in the world .

s- very subtle fruity hops , not much else .  the beer pours into a gorgeous cascading whirlpool of goodness . it really is a sight . the head is snow white and thick .  excellent flavor , with a great two-row maltiness up front and a great pine and semi-citrus hop flavor at the end that sticks . there is a bit of hop roughness to the beer that hurts the finish , but it 's still not bad going down .

nothing real distinctive in the smell .  pours out pale golden straw and sits bright light amber in the glass with a large white head . perfect .  this beer contains the same yeasty , yummy taste as other delirium beers . as a series , their three beers do n't go out of their way to be different from the others . in my opinion , tastes just like tremens with more color ( it looks like carbonated jack daniels ) and more seasonal flavor ( smells of strong caramel and tastes much more tart and spicy than other deliriums ) . had this a month or so ago in a 750ml bottle from a local pub , and it was labelled `` noel '' . to me , it tasted slightly different , or maybe because that night it was my first beer .

the smell is rather muted considering the style . some chocolate , but what i really notice is an ice box odor ... hmmm , odd . awesome balanced taste : notes of coffee , caramel , cream , spicy bittering hop .  pours a dark black color with a thick creamy medium colored tan head that leaves lacing all around the glass .  its has a light mouth feel for a stout .

if you are not a fan of fruit beers i suggest you try this one . the smell does have a strong apricot smell . but you get a feeling that its a fake extract and not apricot puree or some thing close to natural . there is a malt scent that is quite assertive as well .  drank from a bottle into my rodenbach tulip , bottled last week of january 2011 ... looks great , a super dark dark with amber , shiny . the head is tope , great retention and lacing ... the aroma is equally nice , very hoppy ( light car pissyness and a hint of citrus ) but balanced with some spicy rye notes .  the carbonation is very low .

smell : clean , light aroma of leaf , earth , faint bubble-gum .  poured this into a duvel glass and was taken aback . a beautiful pillow white head on top of a semi cloudy golden ale .  medium bodied slick mouthfeel , slightly cloying .
light caramel smell with a hint of grass .  pours a beautiful good .  m : where it falls the shortest with a light-for-style body and overcarbonated .

smell is not all there , i expected a little bit more . taste is excellent ... a light beer with a complex taste that is somewhat supprising .  very attractive hazy dark straw color with a big frothy head and gobs of lacing . this beer looks perfect .  split with the wife at the eccentric cafe in kalamazoo , michigan . looks like a wheat beer with absolutely no odor coming off the brew . very , very wheaty , to the point of being a bit of a turn off . more cherry & less wheat would have been a better combo , methinks . this got actively unpleasant as it warmed - the aftertaste was a killer .

not too much in the way of aroma . i noticed a tiny amount of rich malts but not much else . beautiful taste . extremely rich malts , extremely sweet but not at all cloying .  great retention and great lacing .  its been awhile since i have had a uk beer so i decided to go with this yorkshire porter today , poured a clear deep amber/brown with a thinner but well formed head that left two nice rings of lace as it settled into a soapy-like mass atop.love the aromas alot of things going on very roasty with hints of wood and smoke a real nutt elemant shows thru as thit lighter bitter chocolate as well.the mouthfeel was a little sharp and maybe not as full as i would like but the flavors are very nice highly roasted and quite dry and woody thee is a touch of molasses-like sweetness underneath a dark roast coffee aftertaste lingers.outside of the mouthfeel there is nothing to say bad about this porter , roasty and dry , very tasty .
the nose was light overall .  pours a golden orange color with a large fluffy white head and good retention .  m- good carbonation .

s : very faint whiff of roasted coffee , caremel , t : mix of roasty malt , some prune , some tartness .  a hasty pour into my urthel tulip results in a well carbonated , clear crimson beer with a massive , frothy light tan head with great retention . as the head recedes , it leaves a ton of lace . pretty !  the mouthfeel has decent body , ok carbonation .

on-tap at several places the appearance and smell are n't anything particularly special , but it does have a nice golden color and decent lacing . maybe it 's that special hop they talk about on the package .  golden with pillowy inch + head . bubbly lacing and constant , constant beading .  taste- almost the same as the smell with a malt/roasted taste up front with a strong coffee finish . overall i like this brew . one of the most significant coffee smelling and tasting brews i 've had . good stuff

smell : not as fragrant as i thought it would be . plenty of dark sugar and fruit with a fair amount of holiday spice ( nutmeg , cinnamon , allspice ) in nose with also just a hint of citrusy hops . the fragrance was rather muted in my opinion . taste : starts nice and malty with caramel and dark brown sugar sweetness that is followed by a good dose of spices .  rohrbach maple dunkelweizen is a crystal clear brown beer with a huge , smooth , waxy , light beige head that has outstanding retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , carbonation high .

the smell was predominantly chocolate with a mild hint of coffee .  presentation : it was poured from a 14.9oz/440ml nitro or widget can into an imperial ( nonic ) pint glass . appearance : it pours slowly and extremely foamy with an abundance of tiny tan bubbles . after a minute or so , the bubbles settle on top of the beer which is a lovely honey amber colored liquid . the head that forms is supper creamy , slightly oily and light tan in color . the lacing slides down the sides of the glass just above the head .  average body for a stout not too viscous but the carbonation is a little low , makes you work to get the flavors out from the alcohol background .

armoa is very mild , a little roasty , very true to the style . a little roasty and malty upfront , with nice residual sweetness , coats the mouth and leaves your mouth looking for more .  pours very dark brown/black with a huge tan head , fades at a slow rate and leaves some good lacing .  mouthfeel : others have pointed out that nuova mattina falls short delivering a creamy mouthfeel . it is highly carbonated and too harsh .

smell was slightly resinous and a bit bready , okay i guess , but very mild .  | 5.8 % abv | 2011 brewer : birrificio del ducato style : saison / farmhouse ale glass : crystal mug appearance : honey-gold with a righteous plume of angelic white .  mouthfeel is pretty fairly light with decent carbination .

the aroma is not very strong at all , typical of canadian lagers . smells pleasant enough though , not offensive .  pours a murky reddish-orange . i love when ipas look like this . gorgeous .  as it warms to maybe 50-55f , really no bitterness/hoppiness can be detected at the finish and i 'm immediately ready for another sip . i think the `` fleeting '' nature of this beer ( disappearing lace , no lingering bitterness ) contributes to the lack of feel -- but i suspect that is n't so much a goal for brewers of this style , so i do n't want to ding it in this category . this ale is at least on the level of samuel smith 's oatmeal stout and could have another or two .

aroma is too weak . light fruits and wheat . in all seriousness , this beer is very poor in the aroma department . but i do n't drink beer for its aroma alone ... the taste rules over all .  what a great looking beer , so dark and the head is big and beautiful and sticks around with some lacing .  as far as mouthfeel , it was rather carbonated and had a bit of a bite going down , especially when it was at its coldest .

very drinkable and well-crafted beer for its high alcohol content , but not at the `` elite '' quality of some other belgian triples . slightly sweet , yeasty-alcoholic smell . taste was full with a good amount of sweetness and malt , finishes with a pleasant alcohol taste - nice , long finish .  pours an opaque brown-black with a thick , tan head -- looks very inviting .  mouthfeel is tough .

not much aroma that i can pick up , a touch of sweet maltiness though .  an aggressive pout ( i was in a hurry , dammit ) made a unbelievable snow-cone pile of tan head on top of a chill hazed amber orange brew .  i absolutely love this beer . i hate the commercial light beers like bud light , miller and coors but i want to drink a flavorful light beer to save a few calories . sal fits the bill perfectly .

the mild malt and spice nose should be stronger .  this beer came a beautiful glowing well blended brown and red with a fluffy off white head that left a good deal of lace behind . simply one of the most beautiful beers ive ever seen .  m - overcarbonated , light bodied for the style , but really good .

nose was rather dull , a light roast , hints of caramel malt , hint of piney hops . i was more than pleasantly surprised by this beer , church key is not usually high on my list of breweries worth trying . roast , espresso , hints of oats perhaps , an odd creaminess that seems in line with an oatmeal stout , mixed with a slightly piny bitterness that leans way to the british hop variety side with a pleasing , long finishing bitterness . like a well hopped english stout . nice caramel sweetness , hint of brown sugar . i really dug it and would gladly order another pint .  a : really pretty beer . extremely rocky with good retention and lacing .  beer is thinner than i would have expected , or liked , but the flavor is there and the taste is long lasting . if it had a richer mouthfeel this beer would be top notch .

a little roasted or toasted grains in the aroma with a definite nuttiness .  dogfish aprihop poured a amber color , witht he perfect head , an absoulte picture perfect looking beer , it had a strong hoppy and apricot smell to it , however the taste was horrible , the apricot was just wayyy too overpowerfully , and it just did not mix in well with the hops , and it is a hoppy beer , i found it really hard to drink one , a rare disapointment from dogfish head .  creamy head and taste . drier than i expected yet not too hoppy ; which makes me happy ! the color is the dark murky chocolate you expect from a good stout , but lacks the `` fall effect '' one sees in guinness for example . overall a nice drinkable and easy on the palate brew !

s : the smell is underwhelming , with muted grapefruit citrus hops and slight sulfur . t : begins with spicy , and lesser floral , hop aromatic flavors that energize the palate but fade quickly .  appearance this beer is black as night with a huge , volcanic head that literally covered the inside of my glass . awesome !  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin side , but drinkability is excellent .
s : malty , mildly grassy hops . not very powerful .  pours a swirly dark brown , turning into pitch black with a huge two finger head .  m- good carbonation . a little watery for an imperial stout .

the aroma has adequate pie spice , not much pumpkin .  appearance : the pour into my chalice gives a full , 1.5 '' off white head , like a light meringue , that tslowly falls back into the glass . full lacing is left behind , and a great layer of bubbles remains on top throughout . the beer is a medium-dark amber in color .  m : less smooth than the iv ; it has a rubbery booze component that i do n't care for . otherwise fine .

nose is amazing - chocolate malts , roasted coffee and vanilla team up for a sweet , rich aroma that has to be one of the best i 've smelled . taste is quite good as well .  appearance : deep thick jet black , with a big fluffy medium brown head that leaves huge lacing . pretty much exactly what an imerial stout should and can be .  feels too carbonated and light in the mouth . just an average mouthfeel though , not too bad .

delicious sweet upfront caramel flavor that is replaced with a nicely balanced smokey and hoppy flavor that is accompanied with decent carbonation to drive this taste into a crisp , refreshing finish . overall i 'm pretty happy how this drink interplays with the album . this beer hits all the scales ( high and low ) to allow me to feel the album .  appearance- darker golden pour , huge ass chunky pock marked head . beautiful lace streaks and chunks all over .  the body seems a little thin in my opinion , but otherwise , this is a substantial beverage all around .

aroma is negligible , no matter how many times i check .  a : perfect in apperance , pours an orangish/red color 2 finger width frothy white head , excellent lace down the glass s : smell is fruity and sweet .  taste- light medium to medium bodied . the only drawback would be that the body was not very thick as i was expecting . nothing bad , but nothing really amazing either .

it had some fruity-ester smell , but not as much as some .  appearance - this is indeed black as night with an incredibly dark head . either way , the depth of color along with the terrific lacing that it left on the inside of my chalice earns this one a perfect score on appearance .  well done porter ... .looks the part with a creamy tan head atop a black body ... a very nice aroma greets my nose..roasted and sweetish ... milk chocolate as well as some subtle coffee notes milk chocolate and roasted malts are the big players on the taste but the java notes become a little more pronounced ... body is creamy and smooth and slightly thin ... i do n't exect regular ol porters to be high gravity monsters so this is fine with me ... it really drinks easily and quickly ... .

the aroma is a bit sour ( i think it has a metallic smell ) .  pours almost black , with brilliant , blood-red highlights that are only visible under direct light . pretty tan head that lasts and lasts .  m - lot 's of carbonation is there making this really move . unfortunately it 's to the point of almost being painful . medium body . it 's sort of an odd one because of the carbonation .

overall an attractive beer , but very little head retention s- right off the bat i get some caramel and roasted malts , ca n't really smell vanilla right away . overall , nothing too special but also inviting .  a - one of the thickest heads i have ever seen , looks like lemon meringue pie ... also reminds me of a giant thunderhead with a tornado of carbonated bubbles going from the head to the bottom of the glass that will not quit . very cloudy yellow as the head begins to settle .  f - medium body but carbonation is very weak .

s : some bitter yet pleasant hops but that 's about it . boring .  pours dark chocolate brown with a thick dark tan head .  this beer is supposed to be a german style pilsner . the first pilsner that the brewers den has ever made . the first thing one notices is the hops . a little bit too much hoppy aroma , flavor and bitterness for a true german pilsner but a great version of a american style craft brewed german pilsner . dry hopped with halletauer hops . another great uwe-beer .

my wife and i recently took a trip to the cape ann brewing company we had several beers but my favorite was the fishermans brew . with a nice mouth feel and good body , i found it easily drinkable . it did not have a big head but i dont believe this detracted from the taste . i prefer my beers a bit more hoppy though and would have liked to taste a bit more hops . the bartender was also the brewer and we we 're able to pick his brain a bit which was also a big plus for us new homebrewers  this is one beautiful looking beer . looks like crystal clear stained glass that has been liquified and topped with a creamy head .  thin body , decent carbonation .

aroma is actually a little weak , i can smell a bit of the roast and a bit of the pepper .  lacing is awesome and so is everything else .  more of the same in the finish , kept triggering my gag reflex medium bodied , slick with moderate carbonation , skewed way to sweet , needs some alcohol burn to mitigate this horrible drinkability .

a pretty unpleasant smell .  the crusher pouring out of a bomber into a duvel wide snifter at bob 's bar in columbus , ohio appearance : intensely black . a beautiful shiny black .  the body does seema tad watery , i would expect more fo a `` fullness '' , but overall i feel the beer is a great scottish ale , overpoweringly malty , no hops that i could detect and pretty much no smoky presence which i can appreciate , since i 've had one too many smoky sottish style ales .

what a clean crisp refreshing lager this one is . very well balanced and just the right amount of carbonation makes this a stellar lager . outstanding ! ! ! !  clear deep burgandy tone . nice looking cream soda colored head .  m - sharp carbination starts off this beer , and turns almost tart . it seems young .

the smell was faint hops , almost no smell at all .  with a vigorous pour you get a beautiful effect . almost two fingers of rich foamy milk chocolate colored head , that lasts long and leaves lace as it fades .  m/d : a light body that is fairly creamy .

smell was inhibited by the lack of head . faint/sweet . taste was complex and full . medicinal qualities were evident . overall the best porter i have tried .  insane that i got a 16oz pour in a pint glass , but i 'm not complaining . light tan head with an nitrous tap quality , solidly lacing the glass . incredible .  mouthfeel is thin with just moderate carbonation .

i got some fruits immediately ( some apple in there ) , followed by a decent dose of hops . a little sugar as well . smell was very complex . the taste revealed darker fruits than the smell . this one started strong with a bountiful appearance and complex aroma , but it hit its peak too early .  pitch black with a large 3 fingered rocky chocolate colored head . charred aroma .  mouthfeel is pretty thin as well .

s : the dominant smell was a sweet malty aroma , and there was maybe a slight hint of non-floral hops . t : the beer tasted very similar to how it smelled .  fantastic lacing & head retention smell : slight fruittyness taste : nice hoppy bittterness & caramel up front .  m- a little on the thin side and a little under carbonated . overall i thought this was a good octoberfest beer , spot on for its style , besides its mouthfeel .

s - it smelled of sweet cranberry with some tart notes . not much else here . d - this is a very nice lambic .  i always look forward to the fall and winter season beers that boston beer puts out ; winter lager is my favorite . pours a beautiful dark copper color , with a nice head that retains throughout .  mouthfeel is pretty average , but not annoying . carbonation 's good , body on the thin side .

on tap at lucky baldwins in pasadena . a nice foam cap easily regenerated upon swirling . malt character is very clean and beer is nice and crisp with medium carbonation , and some bitterness in the finish .  leaves a crazy big and foamy beige head of three-plus fingers , with excellent retention , and it leaves webs of excellent sticky lacing .  m : pretty darn thick and syrupy .

s : the aromas are not bold ( though this one has sat a year ) but what is there is rather nice . nice sweet brown sugar with notes of cinnamon and nutmeg . a light fruit juice aroma that i ca n't quite put my finger on . t : wow , this is one wonderful brew .  a serious black hole of a beer . a dark , burnt 1 finger mocha head forms and sticks around . great lacing as well . the best head i have ever encountered on a beer .  m - nice light carbonation and creaminess , but the body is a little light and watered down .

s : toasted malt , hint of chocolate . t : strong biscuity flavour , lots of rich english malt and minerality .  purs a nice , dark brown color , with a slight dark red color around the edges . 3 finger head , with really nice lacing throughout .  it 's rare that i ca n't even stomach a beer long enough to get a few sips down . this beer gave me one of those rare moments . the smell was a sour , and the taste was dirty and skunky . i did n't want to waste the pack , so i made a couple of michelada cocktails . they were actully quite tasty.. nothing like worcestershire and tabasco to make something taste better !

but , geeeez , what a wonderful aroma lurks underneath the mess . tangerine and grapefruit along with rock candy and toffee . pears and apples , raisinbread , and a meadow of wildflowers add to the divine nose . mouthfeel lacks carbonation ( it must be on top ) , but is medium bodied and has a unique fruity apple hops bite . taste is well balanced and very complex . much of the aroma is reflected in the taste , so i will simply say that this is one unique pale ale .  pours a very beautiful glowing golden amber into a chalice . this beer is a combination of the unearthly and southern tier 's belgian trippel .  id love for this to have a heavier mouthfeel , but this is a darn good session beer for a cold night .

first had this on tap at sturbs durring mn craft beer week . aroma of pungeant leafy hops , mildly hemp like with a spice and touch of aspirin . although there are faint aromas of the last two , the aroma is not subdued by any means , good hop aroma . breadyness present as well with a slight amount of caramel sweetness .  a - pours an amber-orange with two finger medium head .  s- old coffee grounds , very roasty t- coffee , roasted malt and vanilla , with a slight oak detection m- thick but not bcs thick , however your mouth will be coated in flavors .

despite its billing as a coffee-brewed stout , the smell of this brew is fairly unremarkable and is perhaps a bit yeasty . what this beer lacks in smell , however , it makes up for in taste .  pours a clear amber-orange in color with a dense whipped cream like , pure white head . it does that whole `` reverse cascade '' thing too . impressive pour .  m : sharp at first , fizzy , but lights up as you hold it . still , a bit strong and that cuts down on how much you can have . d : i had 10oz with no problems , but a second might have gotten bothersome due to the fizz .

s : quite a malty smell . caramel ? t : very sweet , but in a good way .  appearance is a clear orange to amber hue , head is a huge mass of effervescent foam that mostly sustains , great lacing all over smell is moderate caramel and toasted malts intermixed with fruits , toffee , and light sugar sweetness taste is mostly toast and roast malts , the toffee comes in midway as does slight caramel and bittering hops , finishes dry and malty with a hint of alcohol mouthfeel is light-to-medium bodied , thin and watery texture , mild carbonation drinkability is high , this is an amazing beer and what i would hold to be an exemplar of the esb style , alcohol is well-masked and this is well in the the session range , big props to the guys from the craft beer radio podcast for hyping this beer !  mouthfeel is medium-light .

the aroma is light , mostly light noble hops .  pours a very nice burgandy with a tan head that is thick and rocky . in certain lights this brew appears to be brown , but i like it better as a burgandy .  unfortunately , the flavor and mouthfeel do n't fully deliver on what the aroma suggested . this is still a tasty beer but it 's a bit thinner than i hoped for and has a much stronger roast presence than i prefer .

aroma : a bit of a tang , along with a small bit of a soapy smell . very nice .  a : poured a one fingered head while being a beautiful amber with carbonation rising . the carbonation is rising throughout the snifter equally which is rare for carbonation rising and some carbonation even sits at the base of the glass . this also laces beautifully down the glass . this even come in nice and creamy because of its great lasting head .  thanks kplynch for the bottle . color is orange amber with a variety of floral hops hitting the aroma . it 's on the lighter side , but tasty . just not really living up to the imperial in ipa . i 'd call it a well balanced , smooth ipa with notes of citrus and floral hops ...

the menu stated `` this hefeweizen is made from over 50 % wheat malt and has a clove and banana aroma and flavor . nose is lacking , some wheat and faint citrus with banana .  tight , creamy bubbles and great retention and lacing .  light-medium carbonation and medium bodied . piney hops and paint thinner nose . flavor starts with sweet malt but quickly goes to hop and finishes with a paint thinner aftertaste . overpriced at $ 1.50 for a 12oz bottle from manchester wine and liquors manchester , ct .

fuggles are used , but although i could taste them , their presence in the aroma was minimal . there was n't much malt content in the smell either , in fact there was very little smell to talk about .  this looks like a perfect power beer .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , with a little creaminess from the malt being nice , but not quite enough .

s - nutmeg , brown sugar , and molasses . has that new belgium earthiness about it that i 'm not a big fan of . the nose does n't do this beer justice .  very possibly the most gorgeous glass of beer i 've ever seen . this beer pours a dark crimson rose with a massive pink head that leaves just little lines of pink lacing down the sides of the glass . it really is a pretty beer . top notch i 'd say .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin .

aromas of dark roasted malt and vanilla ; some underlying sweetness as well the taste was less than adequate .  had this out of a bottle poured into a dfh pint glass ... a : copper color with a nice 2 finger white head . the lacing on this one is fantastic ... s : smells of floral hops and sweet malt .  mouthfeel is fuzzy and fairly light and chablis-like with a slightly harsh lemony tartness on the tongue .

smell- light roasted coffee beans , very light .  pours black as night , dark tan almost brown head . huge head , settles to a 1/4 inch thick film of dense foam and nice lacing .  m - fairly light and not all that carbonated ; really could use a bit of extra body .

smell - i know i 'll smell lovely lovely pacman yeast before i even open the bottle .  poured into a glass with an incredibly dark and thick pour .  the only place i would knock it down is in the mouthfeel .
the aroma is more malty with some pine notes .  tall fluffy khaki colored head . great head retention and small chunks stick to the inside rim .  mildly thin body , but not alarmingly so .

bought a 22 oz bomber from papago brewing back in november for $ 4.95 . smell is average , a bit grainy , nothing much noted . mouthfeel is very full and lively . rogue has produced the best lager i have ever sampled !  thin , low on flavor , but undeniably sessionable irish dry ___ a : matte black body with dingy ruby highlights topped with a very persistent one finger extremely creamy buff head . the well-known reverse cascade effect is beautiful to behold .  mouthfeel : light for darker beer . nothing special . but as in mouthfeel , nothing here will blow your brains out .

not much in the aroma department . medium to full bodied mouthfeel with low carbonation .  had this at annie moore 's irish pub in roanoke , va. a beautiful looking brew with a brilliant copper color and huge 2-finger off-white head and great lacing .  m : medium bodied , but the carbonation is lacking .
aroma is a mild yeast with some malts .  pours a golden color with creamy off white head that it retains very well .  m : light to mid bodied , little watery at first bit smooths out as it warms up .

smell is of tame mild hops and crystal malts .  pours an opaque dark-chocolate brown with a thick , creamy fine-bubbled pale tan head .  mouthfeel this beer is a bit thin for what i expect from an imperial stout .

rather strong and `` fuzzy '' , that same fuzzy scent you get if you were to put you nose directly on a fresh peach and sniff . an interesting nose for sure . i liked it . flavors of apricot and citrus fruits , peaches , light bready malts and a kiss of hops melded together to form a really nice , above all refreshing beer .  750ml corked , caged , foiled , and boxed bottle dumped into the matching tulip 23/10/11 a a bright glowing yellow with the tornado of bubbles barfing off the bottom , foam starts off large and slowly falls to a brain like looking island never really letting the liquid see air , lacing is hard too miss s lots of belgian yeast with some big notes of spicy , grassy , and floral hops and citric hops too boot and this bottle has a 18 months on it , pretty impressive t even more fruit with a slight pine aspect on top of what i smell with zero booze m a little foamy but that my only complaint about this beer o great stuff that 's going too kick my ass any second now now the 30 $ question ... it 's a big price tag and a fancy box but i doubt i 'd buy another at that price .  it 's very refreshing to the mouth ( do i say that about all the beers i review ? ) , with small , present carbonation and what i 'm finding to be a lighter body than i expected from a wee heavy . by virtue of this lighter than expected body , however , this is an extremely drinkable beer .

smell : the scent is relatively clean . there 's minor sweetness from the malts but the beer 's scent is n't very powerful or exciting . taste and mouthfeel : as far as macro lager goes this is pretty damn tasty .  pours with a huge white head . great lacing and retention .  m - slick and slightly thin .

aroma is trix or fruity pebbles cereal . also citrus , especially orange , and a little bit of spice , like old and not very potent white pepper . the first bottle was okay but annoying , second bottle awful , and every one after that abominable .  into an imperial pint glass , pours a dark brown that shines ruby through a light , a generous 1 '' head of off-white foam settles to a quarter inch , and leaves bubbles around the glass .  mouthfeel-par the course for the style , maybe a a little watery thin but nothing that really impacts the drinking , besides , it 's a wit , it 's not supposed to feel heavy .

it left no laing as it dropped , but lacing was later seen on the sidewall as i tipped it for a swill . s- this fizz in this beer penetrates your nose leaving me with reminders of new years ... champagne and sparkling cider . faintly smells like beer . t- very unique with only hints of what i expected from a triple ( i had to double check the bottle , and yup , its a triple ) . i has flavors very reminiscent of a wit beer . no spice , no banana .  the kbs poured a rich black color .  the body was medium full and just a bit less than expected from an imperial stout . missing body for an imperial stout , it is nonetheless a very nice an drinkable beer .

with this beer , the hops just kind of say `` hello '' and then the malt takes over things . s : i do n't get much from the smell at all , just a bit of bready malts . t : the hop presence is sufficient , but no where near dominate . thankfully the malt character is excellent , featuring sweet biscuit , caramel , and a bit of black tea like bitterness . o : this is a fine ipa that i would drink any time , even though it 's not exactly my favorite example of the style .  big three fingers of off-white head , fading to a thick cap with great retention and maybe slightly patchy lacing . looks more like a nice stout than a bsda or black ipa .  mouthfeel is flattish and thin , does n't really compliment the chocolateyness .

not much of a scent , though , very little to detect beyond some roasted grains .  it pours out a beautiful beer with a tall head that recedes to a nice thick film and great caking to the glass . it is an amber color . as soon as i open the bottle it has a strong salty hoplike smell that hits me in the face .  some bitter to this as well there is still some hops to it a little syrupy but there is some carbonation to it so it is bearable .

faint hop smell and malt . a lot of the aromas do n't show . what i do get is a little bit of bread and a floral smell . sweet and bitter right away . this is probably the smoothest lager around ; incredibly easy going down . the taste is unlike any of your macro beers and blows a lot of craft lagers away .  pours a very dark , almost black amber with some reddish tones to it . a very sticky map covers the glass as you drink .  i would have expected a little more body in this beer . a little skinny for my tastes .

s : nothing special . unroasted coffee beans , malts , some chocolate , and perhaps some barley .  a : clear , light amber color with two fingers of super-dense white foam head that demonstrates a stubborn persistence . lacing is heavy on the glass .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts almost sweet but hops dominate , boring , finish is dry and slightly bitter . brewed aug 12 , 2005 . $ 1.79 for a 330ml bottle from lina 's beverages painesville , oh .

black as the ace of spades s : it smells like a pale ale . some mildly sweet malty aromas but the hops stand out , smells a bit of grass and may be some citrus .  the head is truly fantastic , and the lace clings tenaciously to the glass all the way to the bottom .  mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side , carbonation level is appropriate for the style .

pours out a dark orange , w/ a really thick light peach head , takes a bit to fill the mug . kinda gives off a herbal smell , a bit of pear in there too ( at least that 's what it smells like to me ) , though that does n't stay for long .  a - black with dark brown highlights . dark khaki , thick , creamy head 3 fingers high on the first pour .  pours black but with some deep red highlights with a slight off-white head that is gone in a flash leaving nothing behind , milk chocolate is very prevelant in the aroma with a little smokiness and a roasted coffee hint.nice deeply roasted flavor with big doses of cocoa and smoke , alot of flavor melding going on but seemed a little light in the mouthfeel department otheriwise a top notch brew.a easy drinker with alot of flavor needs a little tweaking to be great in my opinion .

but i was at grapevine and the olde ale had just arrived that day . but the aroma is , surprisingly , not bad .  ruby red beer with a light pink head . head has good retention and leaves a layer of sticky bubbles down the glass .  mouthfeel - medium..maybe a little on the more watery side , but still creamy-ish .

some tart aromas and some bitter herbal notes . not much here . great clean flavors here .  color is a beautiful deep copper , almost red .  hahahahahaha bourbon my as- . this beer tastes like the worst cake frosting i 've ever had . body 's not bad either if you can get by the taste .

smell- faint , and i mean faint , wheat . smells like kashi autumn wheat cereal .  a fantastic extra from a fantastic trader rhong187 a really dark burnt chocolate with a dark mocha head that caps a two fingered head that does n't look like it is going to be going anywhere anytime soon . as the beer gets drank and warms down , head stays and turns a deep ruby red alot of carbonation coming from the bottle and gives this beer a real live look .  mouthfeel is pretty sharp and fizzy from the bubbles . average kind of body , but mostly just bubbly .

s : initially , i get a wet dog smell but that fades quickly into a nice nutty coffee flavor . very nicely done , minus the wet dog smell in the nose .  a - beautiful burnt orange with copper tones . off-white , foamy head that took several minutes to simmer down to a small ring . ample carbonation that held throughout the long life of the beer .  m - syrapy with a decent carbonation .

sweet malty nose ; pacman yeast is obvious .  pours a & gt ; 2cm head of cream-colored foam made up of fairly small bubbles . this gives the head a very dense , pillowy appeal to it . head descends gradually , but never fading completely ( remains a 0.5cm cap on the body ) leaving enormous amounts of lacing .  mouthfeel - low carbonation .

there was nothing saison about this beer .  decent retention , a good amount of lacing . excellent clarity and a brown/reddish color .  it starts out thin with the wheat malt taking center stage then gets spicier as it goes . it finishes with a lot of banana and touch of yeast that lingers a fair amount for a lighter beer . the rest : a solid , tasty wit ; it checks all of the boxes of the style , and does it pretty well .

very nice looking brew . the nose was watery - not much here at all . the mouth was slightly heavy but clean , and very prickly .  this looks like a piece of modern art . the crack & glug action presented me with two fingers ' worth of explosive bone-white foam with moderate retention . color was a beautiful golden-yellow with ne-plus clarity . liquid sunshine in my glass !  mouthfeel : medium body with a bit of oil that leaves a coat .

a pleasant wintery smell , although slightly weak .  -very black body with a tall , fluffy brown head with a nitro look to it . good lacing as well -at first it is mostly bourbon ... as it warms , chocolate comes through as well as some roast , vanilla and some warmth -milk chocolate throughout the taste .  m : yeah , i guess .

s- light smell of hops , more pine than grapefruit . not much else in the aroma .  highly attractive red-amber color , clear with a dispersed flow of miniscule bubbles , the head one finger deep but stays at that depth for some time .  surprisingly dry finish in the back m - a bit think , could use some more bubbles or hops to round out the malt a bit .

complexity builds and alcohol taste diminishes after initial sip , leaving a roasty taste with a chocolate kick very good beer . i like it alot more than the world wide stout and find it much more drinkable .  draught @ obriens san diego the beer in its comforting pint glass appears black as midnight , the head a soft chocolate crown , the lace a concealing curtain to drape the glass .  mouthfeel - kinda effervescent . nothing exceptional .

the spoetzl boys have done it again ! this beer smeels good ; not that overpowerering wet barley smell you get with some strong beers , but a light kinda fruity smell , almost like an apple cider .  pours like 3000 mile used motor oil black body hosts an almost three finger rocky chocolate brown head that has nice retention . leaves scattered lace .  mouthfeel - average crispness , moderately thin body , i 'm okay with it .

smells of every imaginable hop aroma - i was blown away by the bottle version and somehow on-tap it 's even better . i love the way this smells . tastes similar to how it smells , just not quite as intense .  pours black as night with nice ruby highlights around the endges when held to the light , has a nice thick tan head .  m - medium body with a pretty smooth texture , but mouthfeel is a little thin for a porter . body is a little thin , but the aromas and flavors are quite pleasant .

slight scents of yeast . nice smooth feeling .  the orange copper color is brillinat in my glass , and the head formation and retention is great . great lacing too .  this was highly carbonated which produced a slighlty unpleasant tingling mouthfeel .

smell is butterscotch and a hint of roasty coffee .  appearance : deep , clear red color with a very excited , very foamy white head that lasts forever . once in the glass this is a very impressive looking beer .  m- a thin body- fully attenuated with no carbonation at all ... which is normal for the style , particularly when served by cask . quite possibly the best kriek lambic i have ever had !

a clear amber beer with an off-white compact foam that leaves nothing on the glass . a rather faint smell of oatmeal biscuits and a hint of oranges .  cloudy , nearly opaque , deep red-tinted mahogany hue with a dense light tan head that slowly settles to a thick , rounded cap , leaving behind absolutely solid lacing . as the beer moves down the glass the solid lacing continues .  first of all , any beer that has rock , paper , scissors bottle caps is a shoe-in in my book . this beer pours nicely to be a nice golden -yellow ( this is actually the first time i have drank this not straight from the bottle ) small head , disappears right away . tiny bubbles , smell of good malts . great drinkability great beer , great brewery , great price

the aroma is okay with some caramelised malt and slightly metallic hops playing on the nose . not a lot really going on here .  flawless visuals , a cloudy , light reddish brown color with a hefty , almost creamy in it 's thickness froth .  mouthfeel : medium bodied . low carbonation .

despite the dry hopping , the aroma is very faint . ive honestly never had a beer that tasted quite like this .  pours a hazy goldish orange with a super firm , thick and pillowy head that last forever . this is a nice looking drink .  the taste is about the same , with a distinct nut flavor . goes down pretty easy , but there is a lot of carbonation here , and you can distinctly see many small bubbles rising up from behind the brown color . overall , this is a pretty good beer , and a nice looking one . i recommend it .

the smell is unfortunately faint , but there are hints of grain and hops .  pours beautiful as a stout should with a fuzzy active milk chocolate colored three finger head . body sets in the glass like a big black opal .  aside from the dry end this is an easy to drink beer with an average mouth .

very slight blueberry aroma . flavor delivered a little more than aroma , was a nice amount of blueberry , doesnt hit you hard like some others , just enough there for you to enjoy , but not get sick of .  pours with lots of thick cascading light tan head that settles out to about 1.5/2 inches . body is black with some cherry brown around the edges and looks like good clarity .  m - heavy , almost cough-syrup consistency with light carbonation .

s. pine hops and a bit of malt . not an overpowering nose by any means .  very nice lacing . o : the appearance of this beer was outstanding . beautiful !  the body seems a bit lighter than i would have expected .

aroma : spicy black pepper hops aroma that is a little unexpected , lacking some of the more floral aspectas of other american ipas .  it poured ebony black . with a thin white head that dissipated .  the mouth feel is a bit light for such a porter .

my first hunch was that the spars artesian waters may have enhanced the big fluffy mouthfeel , the terse rocky crown , and regal lace adorning this pale ale . cascade hops are alleged to provide aroma , but my pint delivered no smell at all , perhaps due to the ongoing hops shortage .  pours a sizable , 4-5cm head of medium sized bubbles , light tan in color . beer is dark red-amber in color , transparent , and with lots of carbonation . lacing is a sheet of bubbles that fades to a thick string over time .  m - medium bodied with higher than average carbonation . it looks and feels a little chalky .

raspberries ? t - very light aftertaste , delicate chocolate .  pours beautifully , golden , with the head of a root beer float , great lacing , plenty of activity . the beer will pour clear until you add the yeast from the bottom , then a haze .  maybe a bit watery because of the low alcohol content ? ? ? but samuel adams boston lager is about the same abv and to me thats more full bodied and a better malt backing .

the smell is malty and brown sugar like . not really sure .  this beer has the most classic pour in the world . the cascade was fast , beautiful and entrancing . it 's a classic beer but i prefer beamish or murphy 's for a more pleasing dry stout experience .  there is very little carbonation , so the mouthfeel reminds me of a generic malt beverage .

great lacing & good head retention smell : slight hints of licorice t : big time choclate followed by slight fruittyness & toasted grain , plus slight iron notes . finishes fruitty with slight iron notes mf : rich & slightly creamy very drinkable , really enjoyed this .  pours a very good looking dark amber color with a large creamy slightly off white head which leaves plenty of lacing clinging to the glass .  it seems to say , above , that it 's cask ... it was certainly carbonated when we tried it - just not highly carbed . a bit light in the mouthfeel like all of the brutopia beers we tried .

not much in the aroma department here , maybe a slight hint of alcohol , spice , not much .  poured a perfect beautiful amber/orange color into a mug with 2 fat fingers of off-white creamy fluff head with good retention , and quite possibly the best sticky lace rings i have seen to date , all the way down , just pure awesome .  i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . kind of a mild coconutty taste , almost pina colada like ? i 'm going to revisit this one for sure whenever i get a chance .

seems like a lot of the winter warmers i have been drinking lately have been a little heavy on the hops . this one has a large malt body with just enough hops to keep rom becoming sweet .  absolutely gorgeous golden color .  mouthfeel - a bit of a strange after taste but very crisp .

s - i smell coffee , some alcohol and chocolate , and something else , not sure what .  beautiful translucent amber-orange beer , with some great head retention/lacing .  the only real complaint i have with this beer is that it is just too thin ... i do n't buy that this is an ris ... if this was just an american stout , the thinner body would be suitable , but it 's just not on an imperial stout .

medium bodied . starts malty and sweet but dry , crisp but smooth finish you can call this a complex beer . $ 6.90 for a 750ml bottle .  pours from can a very dark auburn . orange highlights , a thick , creamy looking head , two-fingers thick . beautiful beer . first time i 've ever seen a decent head on a welli , must be the can .  medium bodied , but has too much carbonation for my liking .

hoppy aroma but rather subdued .  pours an ominous black with dark brown head that is thick & creamy . simply amazing appearance .  the mouthfeel is a little thin for the style but its still a fairly minor flaw .

a : beautiful clear golden elixir with solid sticky 2-finger white head with good retention and solid sheeting lacing . s : the phenolic character is a bit much for me and it seems enhanced by the coriander addition . there is also a slight rubbery , meaty aroma that is not too appealing . the pale malt sweetness does come through with some time , and the hopping is firmly herbal .  bought a few extra as well . excellent pour , a thick foamy white head that lasts ages and leaves thick lacing on the mug . nice deep golden color .  slightly dry malt/biscuit finish m & d : slightly thin mouthfeel , but overall a nice beer .

low aroma . some sweet malt . smooth body-has that soft `` creaminess '' you find in a great pils . very drinkable . damn good beer .  a : vibrant clear gold with about a cm of dense white head , great retention , heavy lacing , this one looks really nice !  surprising amount of carbination gets you with the first sip , it foams up in your mouth . but the body is alot less than i was expecting ... not think , just mostly carbination on top of a thin to medium body.. ? the flavors linger on your tongue , mainly at the back sides .

the aroma is decent . it boasts primarily of pale malts and lager yeast with a mild hop scent .  huge pillowy foamy head that takes its sweet sweet time to drop off , atop a deep copper colored brew . thick lace is left everywhere as i drink .  m - murky with a low carbonation and a lingering sour .

the beer is quite aromatic , with sweet honeysuckle complimented by a tart citrus character ( mostly oranges ) . disappointing , after the overall high caliber of this brewery 's other beers and the awesome aroma . i poured most of it down the drain .  pours black into my over sized wine glass . crazy thick creamy brown 3 finger head after a gentle pour .  mouthfeel/drinkability- a very thin beer in general , the carbonation breaks early in the mouth , then goes quickly and smoothly down the throat .

raccoon red has always been my one of , if not my favorite offering from rock bottom since the first time i sampled it out in seattle . medium-bodied mouthfeel with a good amount of carbonation . what baffles me most about this beer though , is the ambiguity of flavor . the finish is the most intruiging aspect , i think , of this beer though . if nothing else , it 's just a good session ale .  pours an amber color with a nice creamy head that stays a long time and leaves a lot of lacing .  light bodied , and somewhat flat , though perhaps that is just this bottle ?

chocolate aroma with some smoky charcoal notes . overall , pretty disappointing .  this thing is black . blacker than the blackest metal ! it reeks of hops ... reek being a great thing ... it almost smells of an imperial stout ... the bottle calls it a black ipa ... this site calls it an american strong ale ... what the hell is this thing for real ?  makes it look like a blue moon ... i dont know just dont see the drinkability and mouthfeel to be good at all ... it was one and done for me ... .

the smell is light malt , light hops , and something .  the beautiful cascading effect that is experienced after pouring is a treat for anyone near the lucky drinker of this beer . i put a flashlight behind a glass of this in the dark and could see a very faint red/brown light .  it 's pretty light bodied with a low level of carbonation .

the aroma is very malty , not quite enough hops to really stand out .  poured into a pint glass coffee black with a glowing tan head that was present until the glass was empty and even left some foam behind .  very little carbonation , the beer feels light but also dense .

s-not much of a smell at all . i was afraid that i was going to be disapointed , but ... t-wow !  a : looks absolutely fantastic .  mouthfeel was slightly on the thin side , not quite watery , but close .

it 's not urine pale like most macros . this is such a pale yellow it makes me think , `` now , this is a real session beer . '' i 'm not getting much in the aroma but i think that 's more b/c of the bar and less to do with the beer . this is good . nice beer to sit back and session for awhile while playing pool or skeet ball .  *takes breath* appearance- four fingers of light chocolate brown head grace this ridiculously fabulous looking beer . the sheer density of the crown is stupefying , with large craters rather than bubbles marking its surface . like some object from space , it looks like a chunk of ice or rock from the outer limits .  however the taste is more mellow than the smell and easier than expected to drink . it would go great with dark meats such as beef and pork . not something to drink often but a great change from the usual and like nothing i have ever tasted . it is without a must try .

s : plenty of spiciness from the wheat and yeast , but not much else . underwhelming . t : far , far better than the smell : big wheat sharpness , plenty of yeasty spice , and some nice fruit flavors as well ( apricot and lemon ) ; some cinnamon on the finish , and just a bit of booze on the aftertaste.. quite complex and thoroughly enjoyable .  a : pours a bright glowing golden with a huge frothy bright white head that slowly faded into a thick rocky film that left patches of sticky lacing down the glass .  the mouthfeel is thin .

a-nice golden amber color , pretty hazy , two fingers of thick white head , nice lace left behind s-big toasted caramel malt nose , not much in the way of hops coming from this bottle t-sweet caramel malt up front , hint of toasted malt , some citrus and a good bit of bitterness throughout m-full bodied and thick , pretty smooth and quite crisp d-its pretty well balanced for an ipa , which i actually do n't like .  i 'm usually not much for appearance ratings to begin with , but this thing looked gorgeous - thick , ruddy brown head that stood 1 '' tall on a 3 '' pour in my tulip glass .  the carbonation is just a bit prickly , it is n't the fullest , but what should expect . this one goes down smoothly , with the only turn-off being the carbonation .

not much to smell . this had a very easy drinkablity to it , and at that abv , you could make this an all day session beer ... which i would . i thought it had a slight honey/citrusy flavor , nothing overwhelming . dry finish . good stuff , i would say slightly tastier and more pleasing on tap . pat  appearance : the best looking beer , gold with streams of bubbles , huge head and good lacing .  m : somewhat thin and slick ; however , you feel the heaviness in your stomach halfway down the glass .

a very interesting beer that sat really warm in my stomach -- the `` winter warmer '' is definitely the best way to describe it . appearance : dark coppery red ; a nice 2 finger head that was thick and pillowy -- the carbonation was clearly visible and looked like it was going to last throughout the drink . smell : could n't get much out of it at all -- there was a very slight hoppiness to it as it warmed , but nothing overly discernable . taste : bitter , cinammon is very pronounced and that added to the slight sting on the tongue from the bitter . the spiciness was very interesting and the physical effect of it on the stomach makes it more worthwhile -- definitely a seasonal drink though .  appearance this beer is gorgeous . it is light , hazy yellow in color with tons of good , healthy carbonation and a white , monster , foaming head that stayed until i drank through it .  it has a surprisingly thin body for such a bourbon and malty beast . also the carbonation is a bit higher then i would like for the style .

nose is sweet and hoppy , but with a slightly unpleasant piney note . not sure what it is , but it smells a bit off .  bottled in hilo on the big island , the first thing noticeable about this beer is the crazy foaming head -- super tight and tan , jus ' like da ' wahines out on the sand . i found this brew to be very malt-forward which surprised me considering the aggressive head retention . pouring more volcano into my glass sends up plumes of amber and golden turbulence within the red ale .  should you drink this warm or cold ? when it 's cold the flavors are : dark chocolate , coffee , heavily roasted to burnt malt , and bitter hops . when it 's warm the flavors are more like : sweet chocolate , maybe some sort of fruit , coffee , heavily roasted malt , and not so bitter hops . i perfer the sweeter chocolate , not burnt malt , and less bitter hops flavor when it 's warm .

nose was bitter , with nothing else jumping out at me at the time .  pours black with a great tan head with lots of thick body to it . outstanding lacing leaving webs on all parts of the glass the brew touches .  the mouthfeel is quite thin , but leaves a good chocolaty flavor on the back of the palate .
oxidized smell , but some sweet malt as well ! toffee malt notes .  looks like big red in a glass .  m - medium , slight carbonation , blah .

s - not much aroma . hint of malt .  i can hardly see the beer underneath a gigantic foany and frothy cream-colored head that obliterated my glass ... dark-brown caramel-colored hue underneath the immense top ... strong aroma of cider , sugars , and alcohol noticeable ... red bottle logo specifically states `` 9 % alc./vol. '' ... the taste also complements the hefty abv with a noticeable alcohol presence underneath flavors of figs , prunes , malts , caramel , vanilla , and raisins ... not my favorite beer from de dolle , but a worthy sample nonetheless ... good , creamy and rich mouthfeel , but drinkability took a hit due to the noticeable alcohol both in the flavor and taste ... also present is an undeniable essence of syrup , mollasses , and a medicinal-characteristic in the flavor ... different ... worth a try ... as a side note , for a belgian strong dark ale , this is a rather bitter depiction of the style with an apparent toffee flavor included ...  the aroma is hoppy and earthy with some fruity notes , reminds me a bit of orval in this sense . the flavor has a nice character of fruity hopes and a mild malt sweetness , but the beer is dominantly dry . there is a very mild tartness here but generally the beer is dominated by a blend between some spicy yeast notes and pleasant hop bitterness .
s - smell is clean , but almost completely void of any flavors .  one of the most impressive shows of head retention i 've ever seen .  the body of it was rather thin .

s : bready malt with a hint of alcohol . d : very drinkable , heafty for sure , but also drinkable .  burgundy color , with a full and creamy foam that lasts .  m - not bad , but a little thinner than i was hoping for .

smells doughy with a bit of teriyaki ? theres also a bit of citrus and pear but i still get a bit of teriyaki , but not in a bad way . much maltier than i expected in flavor with noticable alcohol . im thinking this would go well with a smoked gouda .  the dark brown liquid shines with strobe like flashes of ruby red .  not very full in the mouth , a bit thin in my opinion .

i expect the regular ipa aroma , but this one is subdued - seems just as malty as it does hoppy .  it was a dark and stormy beer ... brew was dark and had a rocky light brown head attachec . left an amazing lace on the glass documenting every sip .  m- a solid amount of carbonation coupled with a lighter body makes this drink overall a little too light for my personal tastes .

now quaffing : ephemere - apple presentation : 12oz . i always anticipate anything new i get to try from unibroue , which is absolutely a world class brewery . the nose is faint with an apple sweetness . this is a very balanced beer with a definite apple theme that is not overdone . overall this is a very unique beer that is extremely drinkable .  loved the color ... dark caramel , with a rich look and feel to it .  it feels just a bit watery .

smell : mild - alcohol is detectable , but through the smell alone this is not an overpowering element . pleasant , peaty finish , somewhere between a cheap porter and a complex english dark ale .  thanks to darthkostrizer for this bottleshare pours a real nice clear mahogany color with a solid frothy tan head . excellent retention and large creamy lacing .  mouthfeel is flat feeling and a little thin .

there 's not much to say about the nose on this beer ; there 's a bit orange blossom fruitiness . overall , this is a very enjoyable ipa .  pours a very clear but very dark scarlet , clear enough to se through but dark enough to soak up a lot of the light . buttery tan head froths up out of control and sits there as if it were a solid object . it leaves frothy , thick lacing behind , and absolutely refuses to diminish to less than a full finger throughout the glass .  m- mouth is a little on the light side for a stout .

s= the smell is not quite as intense as i would prefer , but it makes for a nice search that reveals smokiness and carmel . t= the is a great red . the spicy , hop and bold , malt balance is warmly welcome .  black color with a brown head that retains well and has excellent lacing .  ( m ) - a very high carbonation level .

smells like ... well ... . i ca n't really get a good whiff of this stuff for some reason . mackeson 's is probably 3 times as thick as guinness , murphy 's or beamish .  the beer poured into a chalice clear medium orange/amber with a tall and white frothy and spirited head that fell slowly and then lasted to lace the glass .  mf : thin for a baltic porter , the big flavor makes up for this , medium carbonation d : this beer has a ton of things going on and i must say it is well executed .

the ideal looking pilsner . corn and adjuncts dominate the aroma , but they do n't carry quite the same unpleasantness that macro lagers have . the stenching smell of corn syrup becomes overly sweet . this is a damn fine pilsner .  it has a beautifully creamy head , sitting atop a slightly cloudy light golden orange body . the retention is better than i`ve ever seen , and thick lacing is left on the sides of my chalice .  looking at it you 'd expect a stout , smelling it you 'd expect it to be sweet - it 's neither - and it feels thinner than expected as well !

nothing special in appearance , kind of cloudy burnt orange , and the nose is pretty subdued , too . but let 's be real .  gorgeous . almost looks like the ultimate kriek . just perfect .  mf - medium body , very creamy , light carb .

5/5 s : yeasty with a burnt/chocolate element . 3/5 t : nice balance and complexity . 3/5 overall impression : another great beer from bell 's . the complexity in taste does this for me , and despite the abv ( 6.0 % ) and the full body , it 's very drinkable for a stout .  the color combination between the beer and the head is terrific ... looks sexy as hell .  m : smooth and creamy , though lacking the body found in non-nitro stouts , not bad though , a fuller body than guinness .

this was my first try at a scotch ale and i found that i really liked it . the smell and mouthfeel were nothing special to me as it smelled and felt like a typical malty beer .  a - an inch of creamy white head sits on top of a pale golden-orange beer . the head has some legs and sticks around for awhile . it leaves plenty of sticky lacing as it settles .  m- not a bad mouthfeel i just felt it to be average . light on the tongue , a little too dry and yet somewhat of a lingering aftertaste .

s : nose is burnt malt , a slight coffee bean sourness , faint chocolate , and liquorice . not anything out of the ordinary and not particularly aromatic . t : dark fruit flavors engulf my senses from the first sip .  good thick , 1/2 inch head with great retention and great lacing .  appearance : very cloudy , much more so than an average wheat beer . smell : smells faintly of hops and strongly of yeast and fermentation . it tasted a lot like a bad experiment of mine where i mixed some peach cider with some yuengling because i was sick of drinking yuengling . the only difference was that instead of having a peach flavor , the flavor was more like mixing apple juice and a wheat beer . very difficult to drink since i resented every swig .

are n't unfiltered beers simply beautiful ? the smell revealed hints of spices that i could n't quite place , but certainly enjoyed . the beer tasted terrific -- full-bodied , slightly sweet but not too much , and a hint of fruitiness .  poured motor oil black , produced a thick impressive tan head , featured excellent head retention and produced very nice lacing .  smells slightly watery faint tones of chocolate malts and coffee good although slightly watery tastes of slightly toasted coffee and powerful malts chocolate is also in there mouthfeel well carbonated yet slightly watery some of the best drinkability i 've experienced in a stout however this comes at a cost and the cost happens to be its mouth feel , taste and smell overall its a pretty good drinkable stout it really is not very good unless it is poured from the tap i 'll order at a pub if i want a stout and they do n't have a good micro brew on tap

smell is not so pleasant and possible the lowest score i 've given any beer for smell . it has a skunky , malty , grassy and a corny smell . combined it kinda smells like piss , i hate to say that but its honestly the best i can do .  uncaged and uncorked , this poured with a nice sexy yellow-orange and a poofy , survivable foamy head .  pretty average looking . somewhat listless and a touch thin although i would imagine that it could translate better on cask .

full aroma . not overpowering , but nice . taste : hits you hard on the front and back end .  you got to love the appearance of this , pours out black with a creamy body that cascades and rises to the top creating a tan immovable cream head leaving the black as day brew behind . though something with substance , these are as drinkable as bud light to me .  body was reasonably light for the style . perhaps the aggressive carbonation helps with this .

the smell was great , high notes of carmel and a nice sized head made this a quick favorite of mine . this is the first oktoberfest beer i have ever had and i would def .  pours with a huge , frothy , slightly off-white head . long lasting and leaves a beautiful lacing down the glass .  mouthfeel is surprisingly light for the style . very little carbonation makes this one almost too easy to go down .

s : pretty tight on the nose , i am getting white spices , and some tree fruit .  light brown to off-white head . great retention .  finishes dry with light floral hoppiness m : light bodied and medium carbonated .

s : subdued yeasty aromas with a bit of spice and citrus . not very strong on the nose . t/m : the taste is spicy , yeasty , hints of spice that liven up the front end .  this beer looks great . i just sat and watched the color transform from a blonde coffe color to jet black . the head was a good dark khaki color . now that i 've said that it looks cool , i 'm not that impressed .  m : very light ; low carbonation d : good great beer , so glad stone is in town !

750ml , corked and caged ... cork reads 2002 vintage . the smell is something i do n't really like . it smells a bit citrusy and spicy but has an acrid foul twang in it as well .  appearance- beer pulls a hazy golden with a spiderweb pattern across the top .  mouthfeel i kind of like the mouthfeel to this one .

s - very light . as it warms up , more pronounced . light hops and some deep malt aroma .  pours a deep gold to very light amber color . excellent frothy head that persists for a long time . would make an ideal ad for a magazine advertisement just from the looks . aroma is very clean .  almost zero hops .

s : pretty subtle . dark fruits and juicy grapes and plums . mouthfeel and smell are a bit weak , too .  looks impressive with sheets of cascading lacing on the glass after every drink .  this is an epl through and through . do n't be persuaded by the pilsener title . i had it after a holsen which is a real grain bomb . neither beer is that great but this one seemed inferior . and compared to holsten permium that is n't saying much . i you like stella artois or heineken or something like that in a can then go or it , but it is n't too good .

a nice fluffy one finger red brown head coats the top of my beer and leaves a lattice lacing on the glass . s- aroma is weak but i get hints of brown sugar and sweet malts . some caramel and/or toffee rounds it out . t- a nice caramel and toffee type of taste .  this dark lager looks beautiful with its clear dark amber body and good-sized beige head .  medium-bodied , the froth translates into a shitload of mouth foam , almost got ta shut yer trap to keep it in . more blunt than refreshing , tries to lift but too bottom-heavy and spreads across the tongue . as sweet as bitter , and truly nothing brutal about it .

smell was fairly faint , but from what i could smell , there was the chocolate , roasted aroma that you usually expect from any ris . the chocolate , roasted flavors were the most prominent as was in the smell . also picked up some moderate notes of oak , and some slight notes of vanilla .  visible carbonation , this is one fizzy looking beer ! pours with a thick creamy and towering white foamy head . heavy and sparkling lacing . wow , perfect example of the style !  it feels a bit light in the mouth , but the finish is sharp , bitter , and with pine flavors from the hops . mouthfeel is average .

the smell had a metallic smell to it mixed with a cocoa smell .  poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 1/2 '' tan head over the slightly cloudy reddish chestnut brew . head holds on with a miser 's grip , leaving incredibly thick layers of sticky froth .  its actually too carbonated for this type of brew .

it smells faintly of grapefruit hops , and not much else , even as it warms .  exceptional appearance !  pours a nice orange/ruby color with a thin head . it has a nice bitter `` bite '' to it but it 's not overwhelming . some citrus fruit with a hint of some darker fruit , maybe plum ? weird , i know . i could n't defiantly drink a few of these over the course of a night .

smells like citrus . reminds me of summer and we 're in the middle of a grey november day , so that 's nice . smooth , well-balanced taste , but perhaps a touch too bubbly .  a-pours a dark as night black with a coffee coloured two fingered head . lacing is incredible . the cap lasts the whole way down as well .  3.0 m : lighter medium to medium body . carbonation is a bit too aggressive and further takes away from what is n't very creamy to begin with .

aroma - fruity and citrusy , almost like soap or detergent . a mish-mash of hop aromas , resulting in an okay blend .  a : pure black beer ( dark enough to not see through ) sits underneath a creamy , rich , ashy-beige head that is very thick . very appealing !  a little bit of sweetness also from the yeast taste : there is a very interesting dark fruit flavor profile going on here with raisin definately standing out as the main flavor mouthfeel : medium body with really high amounts of carbonation typical of lost abbey beers overall : i really dont care for lost abbey and their high levels of carbonation in their beers .

i was rather excited by the smell with aromas of brown sugar and sweetened syrups .  crystal brown `` loverly '' color . quite effervescent - copious amounts of sea-foam looking suds .  mouth feel is medium bodied , but i think it could use a bit more carbonation .

s- my very first impression was that this smelled like a pilsner . it is not a very fragrant beer . there is some hop aroma to this , but it is kind of on the lighter side .  looks very appealing .  this is way to watered down for me . mouthfeel and drinkability : finishes somewhat dry . this brew also has a super light body with higher levels of carbonation-okay , these are appropriate for the style .

s- faint aromas of malt and wood . you get some wood and whiskey right on the nose , along with the earthy hops and bready malts of the base beer .  very dark black pour , maybe hints of dark brown around the edges . seemingly opaque , with a perfect light brown/ash colored head that sits lastingly above the beer .  m : the feel is a bit thin for the style but the creaminess from the carbonation is the best redeeming quality .

smell - citrusy grapefruit hops taste - surprising good . very smooth . d- very refreshing pale ale .  it pours an almost opaque black that 's capped by an extremely creamy chocolate-colored head . but the best part is the effect given by the carbonation as it 's reabsorbed into the liquid : it looks like an hourglass , the brown bubbles `` falling '' down into the black abyss at the bottom of the glass .  the body is full , but lacks the richness or creamy aspect that the best versions of the style possess . carbonation is just a touch too active for my taste , it borders on being a distraction .

the beer presents a nice malty smell , but nothing extraordinary here .  the pour was dark amber , almost red with a creamy , tan-colored two-finger head .  the mouthfeel is ok - just slightly under carbonated .

a : pours almost coal black with a solid tan head , heavy lacing s : some roasted notes with a slightly sour smell that i could n't put my finger on ( vinager ? n : a little turned off by the smell , but the tast and mouthfeel make this a great sessions porter .  a - poured a beautiful and clear copper - i wish i could brew my homebrew to be this gorgeous a color and sheen .  mouthfeel : smooth , but a little syrupy .

smell : very mild roasted malt tones and hint of coffee are tough to pick up . taste : roasted malt , coffee , dark bitter chocolates , raisins , and a hint of licorice show up late .  pours a beautiful dark black colour with tan creamy head .  mouthfeel is lacking , but the flavors are right on , carbonation is complimentary .

smell was typical of the style . so typical that i ca n't even really remember what the aroma was like . nothing stood out here .  a : the beer is a deep dark brown color with a reddish hue , creates a dense , foamy , tan head that fades slowly and leaves a very thick lace on the glass .  a- i had it in a bottle so i ca n't say . also this was the imported munich gold version s- smells like awesome sauce t- the taste is kind bready with some sweet maltige m- not much slides right on down d- goes down the hatch with ease overall i really like this juice !

s : do n't get much smell at all . nutty maybe ? - best i can do . d : very drinkable . too drinkable for the alcohol .  a - if looks could kill ... . very inviting .  very little carbonation in this beer . the mouthfeel seems pretty unexceptional it 's pretty smooth with a medium body .

this beer starts out very mellow with a very small bouquet , but wow what a surprise on the tongue , i was really impressed with this ale .  a-pours a beautiful ruby red with a thick , billowy cream colored head . there is some cascading and lacing left on the glass . i ca n't say enough how beautiful this beer looks , its amazing . s-grapefruit stands out the most from the hops .  m : medium to thin viscosity with low carbonation .

s : not much of a nose grabber with what is inside . m : relatively full , nice body and balance for such a hopped up pilsner . d : very drinkable , maybe could have two at the most in one sitting . i 've never had any other imperial pilsners before so i can not do a comparison . i really like hoppy beers so this one gets a thumbs up from me . recommended for those who like hop filled bitterness .  a- thick black with sticky carbonation on the sides and a huge frothy creamy tan head . beautiful looking beer .  sharp carbonation in the mouth feel . not a very friendly mouth feel but it is very drinkable .

smell is terrific - pears dominate but do n't overwhelm .  appearance : copper amber with a very nice caramel tone thicket of head , lacing forms a thck collar that continues to leave intersipping full rings .  that settles into a nice thick lace covering most of the glass yes it 's a chocolate stout and the aromas defiantly back it up lots of sweet chocolate aromas some earthiness to it along with some hint of roasted malts flavor 's of dark chocolate are dominate not overly sweet with a coffee backbone it 's got this mocha thing going on the mouthfeel is medium to thin would have liked it a little thicker this is really one of the great chocolate stout 's especially for under $ 5 a bomber well worth the experience

the initial smell of cascade or citrus hops where strong . the hop smell quickly disappeared and the smell was a little like a light beer .  i may be a little biased , but i love to just admire and look at beers this black and opaque .  light bodied . a very good tripel , but i would like to see the carbonation toned down to improve the mouthfeel .

the smells were of cherries and corn malts .  amazing , huge , fluffy , foamy nut colored head is sculpted and precariously teetering well out of the rim of the glass . damn thats sexy . well crap .  appearance : like beer smell : beery taste : like pils in germany mouthfeel : beer-like drinkability : i did n't see jane stop until they stopped bringing it i 'd say its an excellent example of the style .

smell : typical porter . a little chocolate , a little coffee . a good porter with typical notes of most porters with nothing special that leaps out .  as it calmed down it looked great . could n't really ask for much more . for an american ipa this seemed to lack the floral/citrus appeal , the cascades seemed light .  it 's definitely tasty but perhaps a tad less complex and more straight forward than i would have liked mouthfeel-very low carbonation though a tad prickly with alcohol heat , rather thin body for an ris , could definitely stand to be plusher and more viscous .

it has a light aroma of roasted malt and molasses .  it was 3.35 euro for 0.5 l. slainte ! a : hazy straw , fluffy white head , lots of lace .  mouthfeel is light bodied and a bit undercarbonated overall , which is my only real complaint about this one .
