s : the aroma is too light with only tart apples , spicy yeast , pears , alcohol , and herbal hops coming through . t : yeast and light phenolic notes are most apparent at first , but the spicy hops , apple , and vinous qualities really come out with some time and air . even though a chalice is pictured on the bottle label , the next one i try will be from a snifter to try to capture more aroma .  poured out of a cork and cage bottle . really dark brown .  m : thin viscosity ( bordering on being watery ) and moderate carbonation seem out of place here .

aroma - malty , some smokiness and coffee aromas . some yeast influence , but brief . not bad , just not inspiring . great .  this beer pours an opaque black with a nice amount of creamy light brown head that lingers around for a while .  m : light in body . on nitro , this would be alot creamier ... but it 's still damn good .

took a sniff and really did n't smell anything .  pours a deep brown . no , dark brown . black colored brown . a coffee colored frothy head appears with decent retention and lacing . outstanding .  it 's very easy to drink , crips , and light , but it 's a bit thin in character & feel .

hoppy with a touch of citrus , this beer has some kick and an exceptionally smooth finish . if i had to pick something to quibble about , it would be the smell . but the finished product is very impressive ; i would n't change a thing .  a very large head , especially for a barley wine and one about a year and a half old . this thing rivals the best of the belgians with that head . with the fuzzy lacing , this is a very attractive beer .  somewhat of a small bite to it from the carbonation .

nose is somewhat muted though with some grapyness and fruit . maybe a bit on the light side though , and definitely weak in aroma .  classic stout appearance , with a jet black body and a creamy tan head . excellent retention and lacing in sheets . flawless .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly light and so is the body .

a good plain strong beer smell .  from a 500 ml brown bottle . massive head development on the pour , a solid foamy mocha coloured entity with amazing retentio that settles very slowly . the body is deep pitch opaque black , faint almond nimbus when held to light .  medium-full bodied , but was too flat , very smooth .

smells dusty . pleasantly tar-ish .  appearance - caramel , dark amber , deep and comforting after a long week . small but solid cap of medium cream colored head . impressive sheet lacing on the side .  m - very light and crisp .

the aroma is dulled a bit . i do n't know how old the bottle is but it does n't quite strike a chord with me . decent flavour .  pours a very clear moderate golden color with a huge white head and tons of sticky lacing as it goes down .  the feel is a little too thin .

smell is the most disappointing aspect here . not bad per se , just underwhelming . a bit of funk , but not a ton .  ultra thick white foamy head . insane lacing . never heard of this before but based on previous reviews i included this in my order.. way to go ba .  mid palate is substantially thin .

s - not much at all . some malt base . t - nice thick malt with bitter balance .  a : pours pure , rocky , belgian-looking foam , which fill glass and then some . eventually the head recedes , leaving spectacular brussels lacing and beer that is clear deep gold .  i felt this beer was too carbonated and hence it was too slick and creamy in my mouth .

aroma : huge fruits , detectable from a few feet away . huge , prominent hop notes - pine needles , grapefruit , some orange zest - and lightly roasted to mildly toasted malts - caramel , toffee , and even some chocolate - round things off . only the faintest hint lf alcohol as things warm . a very complex nose . taste : lots of dark malts - the typical roasted coffee/chocolate combo , the same roasted caramel note that was in the nose - and piney juniper berry notes . drinkability : felt this one after a while , and it is up there , but overall it 's a very complex , drinkable brew with a lot of really great flavors and aromas - highly recommended .  this stout is so black that light can not penetrate it 's depths , seriously , i tried to shine a green laser pointer thru it .  mainly a flattish mouthfeel .

the nose is a muted citrus with light tropical notes and a solid bready malt character .  looks awesome for a white beer in the glass .  it 's slightly watery , but refreshing and finishes a little dry mouthfeel is pretty average .

s - mild aromas of chocolate , clove and anise . t - nice mild chocolate and medium to long roasted malt flavors . ~ this is a the kind of stout i would go out and drink through an evening .  pours a very dark brown with a red tint when held up to the light , medium size creamy light tan head , excellent lacing .  the mouthfeel seems a tad too watery as well .

honey , caramel and dark roast coffee taste . not alot in the nose , slight hint of coffee .  bottle : poured a deep cloudy orangey color ale with a huge foamy head with perfect retention and great lacing .  feels a bit thin in the mouth keeping this good beer from being a great beer .

i 'm not really getting anything special in the nose . some roasty toasty ness .  poured an opaque , black color with a light brown colored head that was frothy and covered in small bubbles .  my sister always goes on vaction to mexico and says this is her favorite beer . i collect 40oz bottles have about 150 in my collection , so when i saw this in a mexican resturant i was happy to say the least . i got my chance to drink this beer and add a new bottle to my collection . beer was smooth and pretty good for being on 4 % alch , was suprised that it was dark in color . taste was like other mexican beers , but i liked this more , due to it being `` rare '' only problem is the price i paid $ 15.00 for this 40oz bottle .

it has a very light scent that is sweet . you can really smell the alcohol in this beer .  bottle into a snifter appearance- pour is black with a 2 finger tan head . when held to the light nothing is entering this , just deep dark and beautiful . leaving good sticky lace . appearance wise , this is perfect for an impy stout .  mouthfeel is average , not too thin , and i think appropriate for this beer .

aroma leaves a little to be desired . not bad , just not all that complex . grain is all i 'm getting . a very full bodied and flavorful brwon ale .  poured a nice orange amberish with a nice 1 inch head that left great lacing throughout ... smell was pleasing , floral and citric hops and a little maltiness in the background .  mouthfeel is very light , a little watery , with a somewhat crisp feel to it .

slight fruity aromas and a sour , yeasty smell bounce off the malts in the nose . the hops are extremely subdued .  looks awesome ! s : smells super roasty with bitter chocolate upfront .  the taste was even worse , vinegar , old cardboard , just really gross . i do n't know if the keg was abused or really old but this was one sorry-ass beer . this was truly bad and i only finished it because i wanted to catch a buzz before my flight . i should have asked for a replacement .

on-tap at flying saucer , raleigh nc ... attractive brown nectar with a thin almond head . aroma is rather weak : some pale malts , caramel , a bit of hops , and not much else .  lots of lacing . beautiful , simply beautiful .  drinking one of these right now . not the best beer i 've ever laid to my lips but by the same token its much better then some . as you drink it you notice it does n't have alot of flavor going on , a little wheat flavor , but it 's not unplesant . overall it is pretty sudsy . smell is also like grain . fairly good to drink and light enough to multiples of

another entry into leinenkugels chick beer marketing scheme.it pours a cloudy slight orange with a somewhat fluffy head , artificial all the way through nothing seems to be balanced at all here way too fruity most people say it tastes like fruity pebbles and i agree virtually no balancing bitterness , smells very similar to how it tastes . just too fruity for me .  dark frothy head that diminishes to a fine layer .  taste : very little carbonation .

aroma is surprisingly muted .  a- pours a hazy , luminescent orange liquid with a thick and craggy white head that has great retention .  the hop character , however , does n't overpower the malt and barely-there vanilla . m : not that noticeable to me , but certainly not offensive . the malty taste with a little bit of hops really helps the beer .

retention is very good and there is nice soapy lacing down the side of the glass . s - the aroma seems somewhat muted but i can pick up on the rye mixed with your common stout qualities ( chocolate , coffee , molasses ) .  hold it up to the light to see something really incredible . an amazing looking beer .  the flavor is almost worse ... .damn near made me gag . just a weird fake cherry sweetness that is so cloying it is disgusting . honestly , i ca n't give any more detail because i could n't stomach another sip or smell .

s : not a lot jumping out at me on the smell . maybe a little banana and wheat . i definitely could taste the banana though .  pours a very dark brown with a frothy head that lasts forever .  im sure this loses ratings for its thin palate , but taste wise this is spot on . more roasted coffee flavors and a touch of smokiness . an imminently sippable brew . nicely done .

aroma does n't reveal much with faint hints of dry hay , cardamon , ginger and cocoa . flavorful , spicy with juicy hopiness , light malt , spice -- mostly ginger and clove -- and apple .  a : gorgeous orangeish-gold with 1.5 fingers of frothy head . perfect .  m : light , and not as smooth as porter should be . after taste is great , mouthfeel is n't .

smell : upfront it has a wine-like tannic with some acidity . i was a little put off by the nose though , does n't seem to match well , but an excellent beer nonetheless .  good retention and great lace .  mouthfeel is a touch light for my liking , but i 've come to expect that .
s : nice moderately grassy hoppy smell .  bottle dated 2/9/11 a- dark black with a nice tan head s- coffee smell with some roastiness .  m - i honestly could n't say .

the aroma was not really distinct so i give it an average . however , the taste is very full which i like personally ; it has notes of hops , a little malt , a little fruity and a little sweet ; a real nice blend .  black with a thick head built by a classic stout reverse cascade a tasty looking tan head .  m : it feels light- to medium-bodied on the palate and has a light amount of carbonation .

it poured a very nice chestnut brown clear ale with a cream coloured head that lasted throughout the experience . the smell was fairly non-existant , but was more than made up for with the taste which was a very pleasent maltiness with a nice subdued sweetness . alcohol not in your face ; overall a very nice ale with good `` drinkability '' .  pours a gorgeous rich amber color , with a off white 2 finger head .  m - thin body and light carbonation .

s : smell is underwhelming for a iipa , but leaves some caramel malt and citrus hops .  appearance was good , i gave full marks as i 've never seen a beer that did n't look as it was supposed to . a creamy head that lasted the entire beer .  m : very light carbonation but there is just a bit to give the beer some levity .

s : not much to speak of here . faint phenolic character ... fruity notes . t : complexity is evident and enjoyable .  this beer poured a large head that was tan , creamy and had fine sized bubbles . the hue of this beer is dark brown and the lacing was fair .  moderate carbonation and a light , slightly watery mouthfeel .

aroma was not strong at all , but the taste of it makes up for that quite easily .  a total stunner in the glass : the color is black black and more black , seriously giving any huge bad-ass stout a run for its money in terms of color . the head is an ultra-creamy thing , looking like the froth on top of a root beer float or something .  m - bubbly and medium on the tongue .

mild aroma . good fine head with lots of lace .  pours dark , very dark , brown color with light , light , brown frothy 2 finger head .  ( from notes ) i picked this beer up while living in dublin , i poured it from a .5l can into a pint glass ... a : a nice roasted dark brown nearly black color , with a tannish head , decent lacing ... s : the smell is pretty weak but i am getting some faint burnt malt and slight coffee ... t : the taste is about the same except more fully roasted flavor ... m : smooth and watery ... d : a decent beer from guinness , but once you have had their special export to belgium , you wonder why they make anything else .

light chocolate and smokey aroma with coffee notes .  pours a golden yellow with a centimeter of foam and a geyser of bubbles nearly turning my glass to a boil and maintaining the head to the last drop . beautiful .  the finish is on the dry side making for a real crispness . the only bad thing i can say is that it 's kind of thin body wise but it 's still a nice ipa .

looks a bit intimdating , or maybe i just read into the marketing to much ... s : hop smell is dominant , with stong caramel notes . not as intimidating on the nose . t : this is where its at .  as with mia & pias other lagers , spring lake is clear with a solid , over-the-top head of dense , white duff . the head begins at a full finger and holds well for some time . this is an amber lager and is suitably colored , though in bright light , a ray of yellow shines through .  mouthfeel left a little to be desired , carbonation was mild and the liquid was relatively thick reminding me more of a juice i would drink with breakfast than a beer .

a light brown nitrogenated head about 1/4 inch deep persists for the duration of my imbibing . the smell is the only ordinary thing about this beer , for it is minimal and hints of chocolate . the taste is complex , with a strong chocolate presence , competing with brandy , vanilla and malt . it is very drinkable and is one of the very best beers anywhere .  a- pours out a deep bronze color with two fingers of head that leaves gorgeous lacing .  the carbonation is pretty average , the body decently weighty and fairly smooth , and it finishes bone dry , a bit of herbal bitterness hanging on .
smells lightly hoppy and malty , not much there though .  the looks are perfect for this one folks .  a bit sharp and overly carbonated , and thin bodied .

nothing special about the smell -- maybe i 'm getting sick ? nah , just not a strong nose on this one . tastes really nice . very light on the spices .  a terrific looking beer .  tastes great , but the mouthfeel is a lot thinner than i 'd like for the style .

big aroma of resinous , citrusy hops sting your brain . taste does not try to hide the alcohol - in fact it showcases it . brown sugar taste in more present than i expected from this brew . hops prickly on the tongue . although i would not mind the alcohol and bittering hops knocked down a notch , this is still a wonderful brew .  avery mephistopheles stout bottled on november 2008 without a doubt the darkest beer i have ever seen ! this vivid black beer also has the most appealing head on any beer . it is very frothy and looks like thick chocolate cream .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is one of the most drinkable beers around .

wonderful hop and caramel aroma that i enjoy so much i could use it as an air freshener in my house .  this is a very attractive brew . very dark , almost onyx black , but some hits of red with shown to light . inch head that looks like the coffee froth atop a well made espresso .  its actually really tasty ... hints of booze throughout keep you honest but this is really nice ... one of the most luxurious mouthfeels ever in my opinion ... it feels thick and creamy and coats the mouth on the finish very nicely.. overall , another winner ... i do n't like it as well as the first one of the series but this is really nice

the aroma is perfect , of a light sweetness mixed with toffee , malts , syrup and nutty flavors .  sample from bottle ; bottled on 1/22/09 a- poured carefully from bottle to yield a huge foamy , well-retained , cream colored head . as i refilled the glass throughout the sampling , the head became less foamy and a lot more rocky ( proteinaceous ) . the body was a hazy copper color , with lots of active carbonation visible from the sides and top of the glass .  superb . d - this is a tasty beer , but the fusel alcohol character and high alcohol in general make me appreciate it less fully .

big waft of bourbon is the first noticeable aroma followed by chocolate , light coffee and burnt caramel . smells amazing ! flavor is nice blend of chocolate , roasted malts , dark caramel , bourbon , vanilla , booze , and oak . definitely the roastiest strong ale i 've ever had . carbonation is very light but it 's nice and does n't really need anymore for this style , but a touch more would be welcome .  it looks absolutely beautiful in the glass , with a ruby brown color that really catches the light nicely .  soft , creamy mouthfeel smothers my tongue with flavor .

strong complex aroma that waifs out of the glass that is rich heavy fruits , burnt caramels , and maybe a little oaky , earthiness .  looks great ! lots of tan head that crowns about two fingers , along with a dark copper colored body , which has no haze in the aroma and taste i get metallic hops , a good bill of roasty malts that equate to a slight coffee and toffee quality , and a hint of chocolate .  mf : thick viscous body , creamy mouthfeel , low carbonation d : i have tried many of dfh 's wild experiments when it comes to unique ingredients , and found that some of them fell short and ingredients got lost ( theobroma comes to mind ) .

s : fresh nose , alot of tropical fruits , pineapple , citrus . fantastic nose ! t : taste similar as it smells ; tropical fuits , pinapple and citrus .  a- dark caramel orange with yeast floating around causing a hazy looking beer . massive frothy head with huge bubbles and great retention builds and retains well .  insanely smooth , creamy , and slick body with light-medium carbonation .

i drank this from the bottle into my rochefort glass ... the beer is a cloudy very nice looking peachy orange with a watery head white head that is gone fast ... the aroma is super nice , very matly on the front with lots of orange and peaches and balanced ever so lightly on the finish with some grass and hops ... the taste is also very good , does n't quite live up to the aroma . there is some of sweet on the front not enough to really balance this beer .  rochefort 6 pours into my orval glass with a huge creamy head . it has a rusty brownish color . the one thing belgians do very well is make some damn good looking beer ( and tasty too ) .  mouthfeel is just superb . satisfying .

the aroma was delicious . i really wish i had had more time to stay and get another glass of this stuff .  ( bottle ) : pours a dark dark brown body , and a big foamy off-tan head , with good lacing and is somewhat lasting .  m : very nice . well carbonated , creamy , smooth , and very full bodied .

aroma brings bright layers of pink grapefruit , lemon zest , mj , apricot , tangerine , etc ... this is one great smelling beer . this ipa has nice balance between bitter and flavor in regards to the hops . not quite as bright and juicy as the aroma led me to believe , but rather , a little rough around the edges , which is n't all bad in an ipa .  a- this one pours a beautiful ruby red colored body with a finger of bright white head on top . head lasts a while and leaves behind solid rings of lacing . perfect .  mouthfeel is amazingly smooth . almost creamy , but not annoyingly so . very good . overall it 's pretty good , the mouthfeel is great .

very balanced and great complexity . definitely shows its age . the nose on this beer is absolutely amazing . one of the most dirty , stinky , and funky gueuzes that ive ever had the privilege of smelling . however , taste wise , its not much different than a well-aged classic gueuze .  draught @ papago the beer pours a deep brown to black color with a purposeful and creamy chocolate brown head , the lace thick and concealing .  i love the rich , silky smooth feel .

yummy berries !  huge frothy dark tan head ... sticky and clinging lace adorns the glass .  mickey 's ice has an amazing mouthfeel to it , one of the best in my opinion . the carbonation comes on strong then fades to a creaminess .

nose : cafe au lait aromas , sugar in the raw , some fennel notes , sage , really complex . palate : medium-bodied and really herbal and dry . serious beer and seriously dry for a stout . drinkability suffers due to its heft and spiciness .  ) my ba 1 year birthday beer a - absolutely jet black used motor oil color , yielding nothing else no matter how close i held it to the light . dark brown head , one of the darkest i 've seen , fades to a patchy eighth inch . lots of little lacing bubbles .  mouthfeel : this is where it shines . smooth and heavy and very warming .

smell : outstanding nose , one of the best i have smelled . floral and sweet . an absolutely delicious smell . taste : grapefruit and flowers with a nice bitter finish and aftertaste .  moving on , it pours a really beautiful glowing , reddish honey with a pillowy beige head .  mouthfeel is on the dry side with effervescent carbonation that contributes to the crisp clean finish . its a fascinating brew that manages to be both crisp and refreshing yet still rich and satisfying .

the aroma is huge pineapple . ive never seem so much pineapple in a wild or lambic before . the pineapple dominates , but there are also notes of grapefruit and mineral as well as a light funk . the initial taste is pineapple with a light tartness .  a : golden body , large dense white head with very good retention . lacing is also great .  this pils is somewhat maltier than average , and the ensuing mouth feel is amazing . i never thought a pils could be `` creamy '' and light but this one was that , and if not , then very close .

smell is fragrant and wonderful like fragrant burnt sugar with hints of orange . mouthfeel is pretty smooth , very nice .  appearance : jet black , nearly opaque brew with dense head of foam .  m & d : perfect carbonation make the mouthfeel nice , but the alcohol limits the drinkability of this beer ... not that i could n't easily drink a few of these in one session ( if only ! ) reccomended !

the smell was very complex , many different things happening and really reminded me of hoegaarden which i have really taken a liking to lately .  the beer is unlike anything else available ; and they introduced the nitrogen pour to the world . people find it to be heavy , thick , rich and strong when in fact it is light , thin and low in alcohol . of course , it does have a certain mouthfeel from the nitro head , and it is roasty . the u.s. version is pasteurized and has an alcohol content of 4.2 % by volume ( budweiser is now 5 % in most states ) .  the mouthfeel on this beer was truly exceptional . i 've never had a beer with such great viscosity that managed to avoid being sticky .

no scent me or my friends could notice . very disappointed .  big eggshell head . brilliantly clear .  the body is nearly full with a surprising and delightful prickly feel . excellent carbonation level . really , quite nice on the feel .

a good solid swirl leaves a thick , oily sheet along the sides of the glass . hugely complex nose with chocolate , smoke , vanilla , earth , pine , citrus , and licorice .  poured a dark , dark brown with a mocha colored head that was very thick and left behind lovely lacing . bubbly and intense , the head did n't go anywhere for quite awhile .  spices are well balanced by the soft sweetness , mouthfeel is outstanding .

this is a terrific ipa ! great head , great lacing , and sweet , malty , and citrus smell . drinks unbelievable . not many ipas better , if you can find one .  pours an opaque black with one finger of frothy mocha head and speckles of sticky lacing on the tulip .  much better balance on the palate . crisp , clean feeling with just a bit of drying on the finish .

s- this beer smells great ! lots of herbal and grassy aromas . hoppy but not overpowering . the perfect amount of hops . overall this is an outstanding example of a great style and one of my personal favorites .  a fantastic looking beer .  m- full bodied but does not dominate your mouth , it is silky and smooth on the tongue . great balance and good carbonation .

this brew smells heavenly . t. taste goes right along with smell . this is a great tasting beer .  two inches of light brown head with nice retention . the thickest of lacing . this looks perfect .  m - mouthfeel is great . a medium-full body with good carbonation . perfect . d - the thicker mouthfeel makes it slightly less drinkable .

the aroma of this beer is exceptionally interesting . at first i thought it to be very earthy , and then spiciness comes through with cloves and coriander dominating . wonderful , and once i read up on the hop , an excellent introduction to the character it can provide . very nice , but a little too alcoholic for a 4.5 carbonation is low and the alcoholic character affect the mouthfeel & drinkability .  bottle , served in a wine glass . hazy pastel orange , champagne streams of carbonation . creamy whipped meringue foam that lasts forever , leaving impressive irregular peaks and crags that rise above the rim of the glass .  for a supposed potent*ipa* i expected a huge blast , but it is light refreshing yet surprising t. sweeter ipa , nothing too extreme , dry finish on the tongue with an exceptional mouth feel .

beautiful fruity citrus orange hop aroma !  a : looks exactly like the hefeweissbier , dark golden color , hazy , massive 3-finger foamy head that lasts forever and leaves good lacing .  the taste is an initial malty sweetness , followed by bitter hoppy alcohol , followed by dry chewiness . this brew has a great thickness and presence , and the carbonation is not too much to interrupt things . excellent .

strong citrus hop presence collides with a simply outstanding earthy-sweet malt nose reminiscent of caramelized onions mixed with brandied cherries and rye . sounds gross , smells sublime . well , it 's really sweet , bordering on cloying in fact ... but it 's saved by the hops . actually , it 's more than saved as it 's quite good , especially once it settles in and you 're able to adjust to it .  not much head at first , however after setting the glass down the head flows down into the beer for an awesomely presentable beer . color is almost black with a dark head .  good body and perfect carbonation .

what a fantastic smell to this one . a bit lost there ... it 's a good ipa but it 's not quite as well rounded as i 'd prefer .  dark gold in color , but zero light coming through . really impressive for the abv .  amazingly thick and perfectly carbonated .

nose is all apples . amazing that such a huge and heavy beer can replicate the smell of fresh apples . still , a phenomenal brew . just like every other incarnation of marshall z , this beer is thick and syrupy .  i 've actually got an 09 , 10 , and 11 in my fridge waiting for a verticle , though i 'll probably wait till i 've got ten years worth 2011 vintage pours beautiful copper with 2 fingers of tan head , fair lacing on the glass with a thin layer of bubbles top the beer that stick around forever .  4/5 m : very nice . perfect feel .

nose : sweet hoppy smell . all pine and pineapple .  the appearance is as good as they come .  m - the body of this beer with the carbonation is perfect . tiny bubbles , so you have that nice creaminess with a fantastic , medium and not overpowering mouthfeel . d - because there is so much coffee slammed into this beer , it leaves your mouth a little dry and overwhelms the palate , so i 'm good after one bottle .

s : compared to elder this is much less piney , however has a much stronger fruity/citrus aroma . strong notes of various citrus , pineapple , and mango . strong fresh hop smell like no other . t : not quite as mind blowing as the aroma . flavor includes strong tropical fruit and candy notes .  overall , it looks very sexy .  the mouthfeel is fantastic if you sip and swish ever so gently .

smells sweet and malty . smells like a nice scottish ale .  this is by far the best looking wheat beer i have ever seen poured into a glass . the head is a very thick frothing white foam that slowly resides , leaving an ample amount of bubbly lacing .  gentile mix of flavors , not super complex , but with an incredible silky mouthfeel , and an oragne glow that makes it look great .

very appealing nose of dried dark fruits , raisins , prunes , dark chocolate , strong vanilla , and some leather too .  and huge chunks of lace that sporadically cling to the glass , gorgeous !  fantastic creamy and full bodied mouthfeel .

it has a wonderfully complex aroma which consists of plums , oranges and a hint of toasted marshmallows . very drinkable .  by blackberry so this will be short . beautiful pitch black with dark tan head . lots of hops in this dark intense beer .  m-this is full bodied , extremely smooth , very inviting on the palate , it is quite creamy and carbonated just right .

really impressive . complex as hell with everything blending together well . straw and musky funk up front . brett comes through much better though .  this is a great looking beer - substantial off-white head that lasts throughout the consumption , and a glorious , rich red color . it really looks like christmas in a glass .  body is creamy and rich , with mild carbonation , pretty strong abv , but alcohol is not dominant in the taste i enjoyed this beer the more i drank , very impressed .

smell : the aroma is full and robus . the funk , lemon zest sour , and musty notes are so well developed and complex . mouthfeel : the explosive carbonation kind of detracts from the experience for me . this also lightens the feel of the body overall : even though there are some great notes in the nose and the complexity is there , the flavor really can not kick this into another  kulmbacher 's moenchshof pours nicely to produce a thick amount of head .  wonderful . i ca n't imagine drinking this all night but this seems as though it 's one of the few beers that would be right at home as a food accompaniment with a seven-course haute cuisine meal .

smells wonderful . hops , and some hints of malt .  pours with a massive amount of bright white head , and has a perfectly clean and golden straw colored body .  finishes warm and fruity gain with a very sweet exhale that is not quite cloying but just perfect . thick bodied with a light carbonation , goes down easily .

estimated at 200 c purchased at : super saver pennington , nj for $ 3.00 aroma : amazing , chocolate , syrup , heather . visuals : beautiful design , deep brown , mostly opaque , thin white head , little lace . overall : a real disappointment , more of a brown ale than an imperial stout , not a repeat , not a favorite , little value , medium craft .  the bottle was filled to the brim and looks like it might have leaked a little while shipping , so i decided to crack this one open the day after i got it . being so thick and having the bottle so full made it tricky not to spill when pouring . there was about 3 fingers worth of a deep brown head that clung to the sides of the glass the whole way down .  m/d : velvety smooth and a sensational full body . warming alcohol sensation is just right and is not too hot .

nothing terribly impressive about the aroma ; in fact , there was n't much of a smell to it at all ( or , at least , none that i could detect ) .  a golden mostly clear slightly hazed body with a masssive rocky head that actually climbs it 's way out of my delerium tremens snifter . excellent retention !  mouthfeel is top notch though , smooth as hell , velvety , chewy and creamy , medium-bodied and showing a perfect amount of carbonation .

solid caramel malt in this as well , this smells magnificent . hints of alcohol detected as well . d - very drinkable , great stuff here .  a : very dark and delightful , a wonderful looking stout .  the taste , and mouth feel are amazing . the taste has a very nice fruity hoppy flavor , followed by a nice bitterness . the mouthfeel is creamy , and as smooth as a silk , with just the right amount of carbonation .

lost abbey tasting glass a - medium-to-dark amber , with a decent brownish head , but not much lacing s - toffee and brown sugar , with a hint of apricot t - sweet malts are present right away , but it 's also noticeably watery .  pours a beautiful red-amber , crystal clear , with a nice fluffy tan head of fine bubbles leaving good lacing .  m : as great as the bottle was , as you can expect , the nitro-tap was a homerun . so incredibly smooth and creamy , one of the best mouthfeels i 've had .

amazing . the taste is full of cherry as well , and just a bit of tart flavors going on .  the pour was a dark mahogany with a three finger head that very slowly dissapated and left a thick foam on top of the beer throughout the drink .  m/d - mouthfeel is great , this beer briefly coats the mouth but then almost cleans it 's own flavor out of your mouth and has a slight aftertaste .

s : not much going on . subtle malt sweetness with a hint of grassy hops .  poured a deep and clear amber color with a huge off white rocky head which remained for the duration . a beautiful beer .  for the style , mouthfeel was superb , and drinkability was too .

s- an amazing smell . really amazing . dark fruits , cherry . delicious dark milk chocolate- fudgy . o- an incredible smelling and tasting beer , but not quite perfect on the mouthfeel . still a really awesome beer .  a- pours a deep brownish hue with a creamy , 2 finger , light brown head that sticks around for a long time .  incredibly smooth and goes down easy .

smell is powerful and complex , but i 'll try my best . sweet with caramel , brown sugar , some chocolate and some raspberry . it also seems quite vinous , i get hints of port and sherry . i also get a bit of alcohol in the finish , it 's not hot , but it is there . an exceptional beer and definitely a sipper , this is certainly worth seeking out .  a : pours a murky , hazy , fully opaque yellowish orange color with a good inch of stiff , fluffy , off-white head . excellent retention and copious amounts of lacing .  perfect . overall , i think it 's really nice beer and i 'm enjoying it .

the ice axe was enjoyable and easy-going , but was not what i was expecting for a west coast ipa . the aroma was mainly sweet fruity esters typical of a british ale yeast , with a fair amount of malt , but overall rather mild . there was very little hop aroma or taste , certainly not the bright citrus or pine flavors often found in oregon , just a bitter firmness to balance out the finish , nothing in your face .  it was a very bright golden color with just perhaps a bit of haze . great lacing . i ca n't imagine a better looking specimen for the style .  m : you tell this is a big beer just by the feel , it 's almost like i 'm chewing it with each sip . the carbonation is right on as well and finish has a touch of dryness ... perfect for a dipa .

the most impressive thing about this beer was the aroma , and i can not even describe the complexity of it ... fruit , nuts , and deep molasses is what comes to mind .  it pours a nice dark brown with reddish hues and a foamy off-white head that billows high , has great retention , and recedes with exceptional lace . this is perfection in appearance for this style .  taste & mouthfeel : crisp moderate body , perfect level of carbonation not to tamper with the smoothness .
the smell is fantastic . dark brown sugar and caramel .  pours a surprisingly deep color , beautifully clear tawny amber .  taste & mouthfeel : so creamy smooth , malty on the palate .

the scents are amazing ! i notice a woodsy , kind of floral or piney smell , with a great hoppy undertone . man this smells good . mouthfeel is definitely better than average for an ipa -- balanced , yet light , intricate nonetheless .  visuals : beautiful packaging , fort knox , black , opaque , thin tan head , intricate lace . overall : hard to tell what this even tastes like after the mikkeller black , but the quality shines through .  very velvety , creamy lactic mouthfeel . the aftertaste lingers big time w/ yeasty stickiness .

the smell is what i liked best because of the caramel & chocolate , smelled like the worlds best desert .  first things first , it looks great in a glass ! wonderful bright copper color .  a : as others have said , its an opaque black ; the head is tan , and leaves a very slight lacing along the glass s : coffee , dark chocolate , spices , and alcohol ; only wish the smell was a bit stronger t : the flavor is intense with chocolate , caramel , and dark fruits followed by a spiced aftertaste ; it is only slightly bitter and there is no alcohol apparent in the taste m : carbonation is perfect ; definately does not feel watered down d : at 13 % alcohol any more than two drinks is excessive , and one may be the perfect number overall , its a great beer .

smell is awesome with a hint of sweet malty carmel , coffee and anise .  first off , i rarely care about the appearance of a beer , but this one looks perfect . it 's ink black color caught my eye as i was pouring it .  the taste and mouthfeel save this one . quite a difference in mouthfeel , but still wonderful .

the nose is super fresh and fruity , floral hops and mango . there 's a nice roasty finish that just seals the deal for me .  wonderful big white head , nice and fluffy , lingered leaving lots of lacing . nice amber body , lots of small carbonation bubbles come to the surface .  mouthfeel : wow this is a big beer with some nice carbonation on it . drinkability : well the alcohol taste was a little bit too much , but its wonderful mouthfeel just blew my mind .

terrific . mmmm ... yeah , this is really nice . a masterful job here .  appearance : ruby with chocolate hues , though this beer takes on brilliant strawberry pink hues under light . pours a big one inch head , with sticky lacing and good suds . the development of the beer under light is pretty unique and impressive .  mouthfeel is perfect - medium body , plenty thick , nicely carbonated .

aroma is amazing , very complex for any beer . overall this is a very good offering from one of my favorite breweries and i think it has amazing complexity that is best enjoyed over a long period of time , letting the beer warm a bit and change over and hour or two .  this pours a great copper color with a creamy white head .  a - this one is pitch black ... nothing light about it ... the head stands one finger and is brown and creamy ... falls into a ring slowly ... the lacing only showed for the first 1/4 of the beer s - right off the bat you can pick up the juniper ... it shows itself with lots of fresh pine aroma ... i 'm thinking a christmas tree or even gin ... there are also notes of roasted malt lingering in the background t - the beer went through a few different changes as i sipped on it ... first sip brings a bright blast of fresh pine from the juniper ... it mellows out in the middle and the finish is full roasted malt with coffee and chocolate mixed in ... now , as the beer warmed the brightness of the juniper faded and became more apparent in the finish and the malt was more apparent at first sip m - full bodied ... this one is thick and smooth ... great cask feel ... roasted flavors coat the palate and the juniper adds a nice bitterness d - i like regular tenfidy and i think this is a perfect brew for winter ... it would have been great to have around christmas time since it smelled like a christmas tree ... nice complex flavors with roasted malt and bright pine ... i think it was served a little too cold but that let me notice the changes in the beer

again , wow . fantastic .  i love watching the nitro separate out into the espresso looking foam . the beer itself is a nearly opaque black . looks great . the smell suffers a bit from the nitro , it seems .  the mouthfeel was incredible . very creamy and smooth .

complex in the nose . similiar to an old ale . lots of vineous qualities . dried up malt , english hops , alcohol , cherries , and bits of bitter chocolate . nose finishes meaty , with figs and subdued whisky . aggressive and young . very good beer now , aged in a bottle for a year or 10 would put this beauty over the top .  despite being pumped off a cask , the clarity is striking . showing off is a color as deep , varied , and impressive as a well-stained piece of fine , dark mahogany . the head is soft , even , and leads to good lacing , especially for such a low gravity ale .  good moderate carbonation and a crisp , dryish , oily slick , chewy , creamy smooth full bodied mouthfeel .

the wonderfully strong raspberry aroma is all i can smell .  this beer looks amazing . the smell reminds me alot of shiner bock , but much richer , ca n't say i am very impressed with how this smells though .  m = heavy , heavy body , luscious creamy feel , great mouthcoating . one of the best mouthfeels i 've ever experienced in a beer .

absolutely excellent scent . t : dry cocoa powder , dark chocolate , and some fresh oak . o : one of the best smelling imperial stouts i 've ever had , and the taste was good too , but just not quite as good as it smelled .  the pour was pitch black with a good , beige choppy three finger head that slowly dissapated and left a thick beige lace on top of the beer .  carbonation is perfect and really adds to the beer .

a great aroma . reminds me of a brisk fall afternoon near halloween .  a- straw colored with a thick white head that faded but left a thin layer of white on the top . great lacing .  perfect balance of sweet and bitter with a creamy smooth mouthfeel .

odors of malt and lemony-citrus are present , as is somewhat of a decomposed hop like smell .  incredible retention and beautiful lacing .  m : rich and creamy , exactly what i want in a stout of this magnitude . perfect carbonation with some bitterness for bite .

s- the aroma is absolutely fantastic ! the nose is very floral with a hint of mint and spices . very complex . t- the taste like the aroma is floral with some spices and the alcohol really does n't stand out very much at all in this one .  crystal clear honey body with a generous 1 finger medium density just-off-white head that retains beautifully and leaves loads of lace .  mouthfeel is exceptional and creamy . this is what makes this beer so spectacular imo .

the aroma was delicious , orange and grapefruit , apricots and floral hops , amazingly inviting . the flavors were also spot-on for the style , huge hoppy kick heavy on the oil and pine , followed by the solid malt backbone and a bitter finish .  looks great . moderately clear , dark amber color and reddish hue .  m - very rich and full , reminds me of double bastard . dry with a nice low carbonation d - very well rounded , a little dry but bery easy to drink overall a great beer .

the smell is like chocolate and fresh ground coffee beans.what a great taste .  a : this looks so great : dark brown/black , with a very large , pretty longlasting , brown head - the head is great ! ! !  the mouthfeel is excellent as it makes an otherwise sweet beer crisp and the lingering carbonic bite lends a lot to the drinkability .

smell is sweet and very fruity , scents of fig , apple , tobacco brown sugar , rum , brandy , raisins , and dates . extremely complex , too much really , it is like a mouth full of fruit juice concentrate .  a- a dark drown , with the head lasting for a good 5 minutes . looks great in the glass .  this beer excells in it 's mouthfeel .

aromas are incredible with this one ! rich medium-body with smooth texture and finish . overall , a very well crafted porter . extremely complex and delicious . will definetly be looking for this one again .  a : insane head on this one . looks great in a duvel glass .  mouthfeel : extremely smooth and crisp .

typical pale ale aroma . nice taste , some subtle citrus hints in there .  a fantastic looking beer .  m : thick , syrupy viscosity with light carbonation -- exactly as a beer of this style should be .

has an incredible aroma , bar far the best part of this beer . really nice . taste is very interesting combination af amber ale and pale ale . balanced and slightly flat , but still a pretty good beer.. very drinkable stuff .  an absolute beautiful presentation in a snifter that words truly fail and fall short in description . spongey patches of lacing leave a nice calling card .  tingle on the tongue is amazing . at 8 % abv , this goes down nice and easy .

it 's a combination that works incredibly well . at first the chardonnay does n't come through so well , it 's more of a vinous acidity that blends with the funk .  poured in my struise glass this beer looks absolutely fantastic . what a big head with a very nice red/brown fluid .  the mouthfeel is excellent . very smooth , with just a little effervescence that gives it a certain crispness . good taste and a perfect feel make this a very drinkable beer , but with the high alcohol content , you 're going to want to take it slow with this one .

this is a great smell for a beer -- a strong ale with sweet pineapple ( not tart ) , burnt raisin and roast hits .  this wicked brew is topped with a big creamy , frothy , three finger head . outstanding appearance !  this beer has one of the best mouthfeel to it .

not getting a lot of `` unfiltered '' on the first pour , but that 's to be expected . thankfully , the aroma is a thing of beauty : juicy , resinous hop cones dripping with notes of grapefruit and pine . ( and i like it . ) all of this gets balanced with a sizable malt presence that suggests sweet toffee , caramel , and a hint of butter . sticky hop oils attack the tongue and roof of the mouth with a near-wooden pine note , while yeasty tropical fruits linger in the finish . overall , i found squall to be fairly typical of dogfish head 's brews -- innovative and tasty , but ultimately lacking the elusive 'finishing touch ' that elevates other breweries into the upper echelon of the beer world .  reviewed 1/17/2007 ( 750ml bottle ) : pours a dark red/brown/black . tannish white head , very fine bubbles , creamy looking . good lacing .  fruity , yet stinging ... sweet , delicious , spicy , tantalizing ... taste ... fantastic texture , floods the mouth with flavor , excellent weizen graininess , raisiny , figgy fruitiness , doubled up with richness ... each gulp brings waves of sensation ... i find myself liking this more as i go ... it 's punishing , though , flavorful , yet stinging and slaying , a serious threat to sobriety ... a bold attack on the senses ... the perfect nightcap ... just the thing to knock me out and send me to slumberland .

very nice .  pours a shade darker than pale yellow , amazing head and head retention , lots of sticky lacing and a lively carbonation .  perfect consistency neither thick nor thin , but to silky to be described as simply `` medium '' .

the smell was terrific , strong alcohol hints but definitely a lot of chocolate in there too .  pours a pitch black color with a small brown head into my tulip glass .  carbonation is pretty much perfect , and adds just the right element to the brew .

the smell is great almost like a chocolate shake .  the beer poured a dark cordovan with a gorgeous tan head .  the mouthfeel is excelent on this one though , very smoothe and crisp and very drinkable .

so bitter that it puckered the mouth and seemed sticky while at the same time not having enough malt to balance out all the hops . also extremely boozy , especially as it warmed .  black storm looks like one of the thickest , most viscous , oily ris 's i 've ever come across . no light getting through this opaque body , which nears jet-black and is capped by a fat , burnt toffee-colored head .  creamy and luscious body and wonderful layered complex flavors . pale malts , lead into corainder and tropical fruits with a yeasty belgian spice induced finish that lasts into a tingly carbonation with some hop bitterness . very nice .

both are evenly noted and very distinguishable . pretty impressive . a pine smell to the hops .  750ml capped and sealed bottle . appears jet black .  full , oily and creamy body with moderate carbonation .

really impressive hazelnut aroma when your nose gets within a few inches of the glass . taste are just as strong and bold . exceptionally clean finish which leaves you wanting more .  i totally loved the color and the difference in it from the dark orange at the tinner bottom part of the glass , to the brown at the thicker top . it poured with two finger creamy colored and textured head with average retention which left good lace on its way off ... s - dominating yeast and banana aroma , with some sweetness in the back of it .  very drinkable and actually light in alcohol ( at 7.5 % ) for the size and richness of the mouthfeel .

aromas of spicy candied pralines , red hots , licorice and lots of citrus esters and also honey after some time in the glass . very tasty now but will be curious to see how the hops and alcohol fades and whether more fruit and secondary flavors come through over time . very nice beer overall .  was a beautiful rich and golden color ; looked like a killer ipa .  great smooth mouthfeel..creamy .

the nose is so vibrant and complex , it may be simpler to list what is not noticed . grapefruit , mango , orange rinds , pineapple , lemon , grass , and flowers are all easily discernible aromas . i 'm sure there are more lying deep within but i ca n't just sit here smelling this beer all day . sweet honey and mild citrus fruit flavors start each sip with notes of mandarin oranges and grapefruit and a slight grassiness in the background .  ..on the open , thick cream like tan foam started oozing out of the bottle . the head is quite good , but the lacing is exceptional ! .  m : spot on with the mouthfeel - very thick and almost chewy , with just a hint of alcohol towards the finish .

i 've never smelt a beer like this before and really enjoyed it .  sunday 's chores are doen and looking to rest up for the start of the week ... decided to tap into the dogfish iba ... .and it is quite nice ! the color is supurb with a deep dark rich amber ... basrley can see light through it .  absolute delightful mouthfeel , silky smooth .

( note - the bottle opened without any hiss at all ) the aroma was well done with a strong malty presence and dark fruit aromas of raisin , plums , and a dark chocolate impression . the flavor was not quite as impressive as the aroma . the flavor was somewhat alcoholic and that was a detractant . the aroma was rich and complex and the flavor had a good complexity but was lessened by the alcohol presence .  moderate pour into a chalice yields a huge chocolate-brown head over a an opaque black body . looks oily and thick as it pours . ca n't get the whole 12 ounces into this half-liter chalice -- too much head . lovely , lovely beer .  very soft carbonation that makes it feel creamy and silky smooth one of , if not , the thickest beers i 've had . love it .

decent brew that smells fantastic , but fails to deliver on taste .  a- black , brown head , thick , oily , leaves lots of lacing s- sugary malts , coffee , alcohol t- malty sweetness up front , some roasty earthiness going into a great finish/aftertaste .  mouthfeel is thick , chew , viscous .

smells sweet and ... .murky somehow .  awesome retention and structure . the beer was a very dark/murky brown color that looked like rugged/worn leather .  d - i love the dessert like chocolate and cream notes , and the mouth feel is outstanding . a really well done brew , but i do n't think that i could take more than one ... it 's a hair to sweet imo .

the aroma is delightful ... huge scents of figs , raisins , cherries , citrus with a slight alcohol twinge if you linger the nose . slightly bitter and dry in the finish and so wonderfully kind on the pallet ... could think of no better way to finish off an evening .  deep , black-coffee brown with an incredibly dense burnt sienna foam cap , just thick as all get out .  this exhibited a creamy mouthfeel .

s - the smell is delicious . malt , biscuits , dark fruit like plums and raisins , and alcohol . this is clearly more of a british barley wine than american .  a - pours murky brass , tons of white head , stays for awhile . cling lace looks like it is digging in for the long haul .  a light bodied beer but incredibly smooth . leaves the palate feeling dry , making this an excellent strong summery beer .

smell is neat , rich and malty , raisins , caramel , grapes , brown sugar , some biscuit , a touch of chocolate milk and light roast , lots of sweet fruit , a bit herbal , pretty intense chile/pepper aroma , pretty spicy .  a big fat foamy off-white bubbly head with great retention and superb lacing .  it 's mild to medium body with the really great mouthfeel makes me want to swish the beer around my mouth before swallowing .

smell : wow . loads of anise , port , dark chocolate , espresso , cabernet sauvignon , and raisins . awesome . taste : alas , my nose seems to have misled my tongue . overall , fairly acrid and not very good . mouthfeel : flat carbonation and surprisingly thin body . but from this experience ... i can not recommend it , no matter how pleasant the aroma .  once in the glass from the tap , a beautiful color fils your mind , a perfect not quite brown , honey amber tone with hints of gold . perhaps the best looking beer in the world . strong lacing and great head , beautiful roasted flavor that im sure would be even better with age .  the mouthfeel is exceptional , big thick viscous and sticky and is amazingly velvety over my palate . really quite incredible .

s : the nose is great . it is almost reminiscent of the cantillon funk smell , which is great . smells very tart and sour . overall : it is a solid gueuze , smells better than it tastes , but it is still good .  awesome retention and lacing as ive come to expect from hotd beers .  surprisingly full mouthfeel with lots of carbination ... .almost creamy feel .

s - caramel , toffee , apples , and alcohol . very potent , as you can smell it from feet away . good , but i was expecting a more complexed taste , maybe ? feels good and easy going down .  excellent retention and a smashing amount of heavy lacing . this is just a beautiful beer .  the mouthfeel is fantastic , crisp , clean , refreshing , but tasty as well . highly dirnkable , i think drinkable best describes this beer .

s- perfect . a hop monster being over taken quickly by malty goodness . t- amazingly hoppy and bitter , but still almost balanced by caramel malt that makes it delicious .  a : poured a nice deep yellow with a two finger head that left beautiful lacing down the side as it subsided .  mouthfeel was great . this beer went down smooth and easy .

beautiful nose t - great complex flavor comprising smoked meats , dark fruits and apples and various barrels .  this one pours a nice opaque black in the glass with nice a tan/brown head that has good retention . a perfect picture of a stout .  m - the feel is as smooth as i 've ever had . unbelievably impressive ! the feel of this beer is really what sets it apart from every other dubbel i 've ever sampled .

tons of pine and with mangoes and other tropical fruits . smells great . taste .  a - awesome head ! ! ! pours into crazy shapes ... brew is cloudy orange/amber color . lots of great lacing .  mouthfeel : full side of medium bodied . silky smooth . overall : as always , a beer with a world class mouthfeel is going to be treated kindly by me .

aroma is absolutely delicious , malty and sugary , caramel , fruits , plums and prunes , very close to the aroma of a port wine . it lasts a long time , and all the way to the end i keep smelling this . already very impressive , i will hold the rest of the case , still feels like it has room to improve .  true black body is topped by a thick chocolate milk foam head .  m - this has a medium body and medium carbonation .

smells of piney , spicy and floral hops , touch of citrus , unbelievably fragrant . tastes of sweet piney like malt with a good spicy backbone . a very pleasant surprise , the nose on this beer is incredible , everything just works together beautifully . not as dry and crisp as a traditional pilsner , but i really enjoyed this interpretation .  a vigorous pour yields a fast-falling one finger head , large bubbled . it forms a nice glass ring . the body is a wonderful near-opaque black , with ruby highlights only when potently backlit .  mouthfeel is awesome . smooth and slippery with perfect carbonation .

sweetness abounds on teh nose . beautiful ! a powerful beer on the palate with an abundance of toasty malts , sweet berries , and the rest of the nose .  an amazing looking beer .  bready yeast also comes across the nose t : again sweet sugar , yeast , dark fruit like notes of raisin or prune , just a hint of the kirek in the backgorund m : mouthfeel is super smooth . beer has a medium body and nice carbonation . finishes extremely clean .

the smell is fantastic . super complex with vanilla , bourbon , toffee , caramel , brown sugar , and sweet dark fruit .  pours mahogany with a thick creamy off-white head .  m : completely smooth and wonderful . d : very easy to drink .

i smelled chocolate on dark fruit . overall , a very nice porter . not quite the most complex porter i 've ever had , but it was extremely drinkable .  visually this beer is flawless . sticky cement lacing .  a little bit too boozy , but it is incredibly smooth .

smell is of dark fruits , raisin , sweetness , a little bit of coffee .  orange/amber color , with a thick creamy eggshell white head ( we 're talking this could be used as a pillow ) , that leaves amazing amounts of lacing down the glass .  luscious creamy mouthfeel .

aroma is strong and inviting , caramel malt balanced nicely with orange scented hops . i really enjoyed the luscious aroma or orange/tropical hops and sweet malt . it 's a very unique pale ale , and i was glad to get a chance to try it ...  pours a deep amber/copper color with a huge fluffy white head that shows great retention and lace .  mouthfeel was very thick and rich . i almost wanted to chew it .

d - the aroma of this beer is fantastic , but the flavor does n't quite match . overall , it is quite a good beer , but at nearly twice the price of rodenbach grand cru it should be even better .  this beer poured really dark with a thin head as about as dark tan of a head as you will ever see .  perfect carbonation .

d - the flavors are good , the aroma great , and the alcohol is n't too high .  the look is truly exceptional - this glass came to me straight from the vat and the reverse cascading head was exceptionally thrilling to watch as it created a huge beige head . the lace on this glass created an almost completely formed sheet that clung like glue to the glass .  really a great beer that has it 's hops really balanced , and the silky smooth malt mouthfeel balances wonderfully with bitterness of the hops .

smell -- rich malty aromas , faintly sweet .  poured into a stemless tulip glass with two inches of ivory head that dissipated within a minute or two . leaves heavy lacing along the glass with striations that create some beautiful patterns on the top of this tawny-ruby body . tight bubbles remain on the top as the drink progresses making for an all out beautiful ale .  the mouthfeel , on the other hand , is wonderful : creamy , smooth , full-bodied , with moderate yet lively carbonation .

not much nose but that seems alright to me . krombacher pils is one of those beers that one needs to come back to after trying different brews - it brings you back to basics !  it has a nice dense tan colored head that is just sitting right on top of the beer . great lacing down the sides of the tulip glass .  mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and thick for the style .

the aroma is phenomenal ( smells a lot like my recent iipa homebrew ) , and i 'm picking up on cascades and simcoe hop usage , as well as lots of tropical fruits ( mango , starfruit , kiwi , and banana ) . finishes a bit stale , with a cardboard-like off flavor that outlasts the hoppiness .  a : pours a clear red color , 2 finger width head with great lacing down the glass s : real sharp spicy piney hop scent .  mouthfeel : nice thick body , very silky smooth texture with a small hop bite .

utterly fantastic aroma , ultra creamy . an aroma to get lost in , just one of the finest ever . flavors of coffee come out more in the taste , cut with a generous dose of cream .  another solid beer from anchor . deep dark color , thick tan head , nice lace .  thick chewy mouthfeel that coats the entire tongue and a little burn as it warms .

s : wow ... the smell was amazing , i could taste it without even drinking it .  it eroded oddly and left big soapy dollops and sticky sheets of lacing - impressive . the body was an orangy gold color and it had a light haze .  mouthfeel : best mouthfeel of any wit i 've ever had ; this has the milkshake-thick , smooth mouthfeels i 've heard described as ideal for the style .

ok retention and lacing ... the aroma is very unique and enticing . a great balance of some many things going on , smoke , sweet oak , scotch , vanilla and dark chocolate . however , this is still pretty good .  pours a hazy dark gold with a huge creamy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  full bodied for the style , definitely one of the fullest dipa 's that i 've ever had . nice carbonation levels as well .

i love it . smooth mouthfeel with ... somewhat dry finish .  i got a growler of this fresh from the brewery and i 'll be a sinner if i say that this was not one of the finest beers i have ever had . thick pillow head that retained wonderfully .  very dark with no light coming through and light head n : nose has lots of chocolate and sweet malts and a touch of hops t : starts with lots of chocolate and coffee , some sweet malts but very slight , a touch of hops are prevelant , some oatmeal taste as well , it 's got a sweet earthiness to it which is somewhat unique , a slight bitterness shines through m : it has a velvet feel in the mouth as it slides around , very thick and smooth f : a touch bitterness comes out in the end with the nice stout and oatmeal taste , coffee lingers on the back of the tongue , it has a sweet quality to start but gets drier as it fades and finishes really dry , its got a great smooth feeling in the mouth to go along with the great taste final thoughts : a great stout , it would be great if it was labelled as oatmeal or irish stout since it seems to have qualities of both , but listed as imperial it makes me wonder since its lacking a lot in the hop category .

theres a wonderful aroma of sweet grapefruit . overall , this is an excellent and extremely enjoyable pale ale , with its low hop bitterness and strong citrus hop aroma . i love it . i highly recommend this beer .  poured from a 12oz bottle into a pint glass a : pours a dark brown , almost porter colored darkness , with a thick 3 finger+ head . there was a strong amount of lacing throughout and the head stuck around .  very smooth and full mouthfeel .

i treated myself to a bottle of this sweet stuff . as for aromas this maybe the most aromatic beer i have ever had . tootsie rolls and chocolate pop tarts is what comes to mind . good but not great . oh and tampa bay stunk up my parlay today too ..  from notes reviewed on 11/19/10 : bomber poured into a duvel glass , best by 4/17/11 a : golden orange , clear , huge 3 finger foamy white head that looks like pillows of clouds bursting out of the glass . great head retention and lacing .  it is very smooth with a nice medium to full body . i was most impressed with the mouthfeel . every part of your mouth will be involved in the feel of this beer as it awakens all your nerves right down your throat .

the beer was one of the occasional guest ales there . appearance : amber-coloured , with foamy , lasting beerhead , but not 100 % clear ... smell : nothing special to write home about -- not noticeable maltiness and quite faint in terms of all kinds of notes ... taste : nice ! very balanced and very fulfilling .  it pours a bright , clear lemon color with voluminous white head that billows out and leaves fine lace all over the glass .  maybe a peachlike taste in the mix , but honey and herbs are the main ones i sense , mouthfeel- super smooth and low carbonation . very creamy and velvety . nice !

nose was milk , creme , coffee and vanilla beans .  pours a nearly black color with a thick and frothy mocha hued foam . retention is superb , as is the lacing . for a non-imperialized stout , this is about as good as it gets for appearance .  looks like a stout should , dark and opaque , not quite black , with a slight tan head smells like burned caramel cookies tastes like coffee with the forementioned cookies great mouthfeel , not too chewy i could drink a couple of these

one of the better smelling beers i 've come across .  a-pitch black with a thick tan head s-smells like a black ipa .  '' the mouthfeel was silky , the body full and the carbonation perfectly soft . enjoyable , but it 's really an american stout contrary to the label at the bar .

grapefruit notes from the hops dominate upfront , followed closely by a bit of sweet malt . yep , this is certainly hoppy .  jet black with a livid light brown head that remains for at least five minutes .  mouthfeel - full-bodied , velvety smooth , and creamy with a semi-dry finish and moderate carbonation .

fantastic . t - right along with the smell ; cascade hoppiness , but extremely well-balanced .  black brew that has a red tint to it when held to the light . thick light brown head that clings to the sides of the glass .  m : leaves a nice stickiness that is not overpoweing .

aroma was of smoky bacon , hint of dark fruit as well ... intriguing ... taste was smoky up front , hint of light hops , some malt ... but the smoked flavor predominates here .  a - pours with a ridiculous amount of tan foam that takes forever to dissipate and leaves a good amount of lacing .  this really has the acidity and fermentation of kombucha tea , giving it a great , crisp mouthfeel .

after a moment of warming up in the glass , the coconut aroma starts to become very powerful . tastes like toasted coconut and vanilla .  it pours to a dark golden amber color with a few continuous jetstreams of bubbles rising to the top to support the delicate off-white head .  mouthfeel is perfect . smooth and creamy , light carbonation , just absolutly terrific .

the smell is pretty awesome . just a thick rich , perfect scent for the baltic porter . it is a nice beer , the flavor could be better , but overall it is enjoyable  appearance : beautiful , golden , clear liquid with sparkling , bubbles that rise to a frothy head .  very creamy and full bodied , perfect carbonation to keep it moving .

aroma has a lot of citrus and almost tropical hops , very potent and absolutely amazing smell . taste starts out with the same fruity taste as the aroma , almost entirely hops with a touch of malt .  this is what beer should look like ... medium orange with a incredibly mesmerizing swirl of carbonation that doesnt quit for anything rising into a thin 1/4-inch but cozy blanket of off-white puckered foam .  medium bodied and oily . simply exceptional .

very slight smell of malt and a light hop aroma . the taste is spicy and slightly peppery with a very pleasant hop bitterness at the finish .  this is advertised as a `` pre-prohibition '' pilsner . yellow and slightly hazy with a white head .  velvet mouthfeel ; tongue coating and heavy .

the aroma is eclectic ; the wood of the aging barrels is up front as is the sweetness of the rum . it has a very `` island '' character to it .  the beer is a slightly hazy gold color with a thin bleached white edge layer of head .  excellent mouthfeel .

smell could be better . much better than budweiser for many reasons : taste ( not as `` bland '' ) , texture ( does n't feel like your drinking club soda ) , and smell ( does n't smell like cement ) .  500ml bottle bought from gapwines , belfast ... poured a very pale straw yellow colour with a slight haze ... white head poured pretty loose and frothy then faded to wispy coating with thickish edging .  burly , viscous , lusciously dextrinous mouthfeel . outstanding .

s - not altogether inviting to be honest . sweet malts , graininess , and a whole lot of nothing else . easy to drink and inoffensive .  12 oz green and yellow aluminum bottle . pours out golden yellow , with a creamy marshmallow white head .  first thing i notice is how incredibly smooth this beer is - wow ! highlight of this for me was the drinkability - just ridiculously nice mouthfeel .

or so of this , though the nose is incredible .  pours light gold in color with no head forming on the pour at all .  this is really a very good beer : the finish , the mouth feel , the carbonation , the body , are quite exceptional . it 's the taste .

some carbonation present , as well as a good deal of yeasty goodies at the bottom of the glass . smell : the aroma is incredibly complex and refreshing . up front you get that belgian spicy yeast character , but i 'm also detecting some tart fruits like apricot , orange , and maybe some grape in there as well . there is some alcohol detectable and some underlying dark fruit presence that gives the smell some serious depth .  water vapors rising from it after and very aromatic of the tart cherries , mulling spices , and a little malt . color is maybe suffering as it 's got some brown in it - kind of a reddish brown .  m. incredibly smooth .

s - smell is by far the best feature of this beer . a nice piney , peppery , smell hits you as soon as you pop the cap . d - well , this beer is super drinkable , every day of the year . hot , cold , in-between , it does n't matter ... it 's smooth , refreshing , and smells awesome ! !  poured a medium amber color with a one finger off white topper which soon turned into a thin film and left no lacing to speak of .  the beer looks thick and chewy , but the texture is perfect for a brown ale .

actually quite complex when i dig deeper . vanilla makes itself present as well as a little wine musk . t= really really nice . great tartness in it that is a refreshing bite but it is n't the only component of it .  it has the average golden color was the lowest point of fat tire .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it is slightly carbed but still rather flat .

fresh hops with a grassy/piney scent make a strong first appearance . not sure if this is even possible , but the smell seems to die off rather quickly , and the fresh hop scent is gone .  pours an orangey garnet with minimal head retention .  super dense , thick , creamy and full bodied .

a great smelling ipa . smooth , almost fruity flavor , high hop bitterness in the back , some sweetness up front , nice palate connectivity .  a- dark amber beer , a fine white head that fades quick s- clean nose , a piney hops aroma ( very strong ) , undertones of biscuit .  perfect creamy texture and good body and carbonation .

the aroma was amazing . smells like a perfect roast of coffee . also lemon zest and coffee bean aromas . overall , this beer is awesome . i really enjoyed this beer and i plan on buying more of it , if i can still find it .  hazy golden amber . thin , white head that quickly becomes patchy .  feel is very nice - medium bodied with plenty of carbonation . the carbonation makes the beer feel so smooth in the mouth .

s : fantastic big malt t : american sweet malt , the hops have faded substantially , to be expected , slight caramel .  poured a dark reddish brown into my st. bernardus goblet . the head was smallish and did not have great retention .  the mouthfeel was medium-to-full , which was amazing for a co2 pour and i even did a double take at the taps just to be sure .
smell is rather disappointing . not a lot going on .  a - pale gold , with a short-lived head , no lace .  very nice .

it smells of bubble gum , and kind of fruity . the flavor is of citrus hops , which overpowers any other flavors that try to be present , except for a slight acidic flavor .  with a helping of off white head . not the best retention .  mouthfeel : light and airy . the perfect match to the flavor profile . well done .

the nose is beautiful . molasses , coffee , oats and almost a berry-like aroma .  the appearance is deep golden with a copper hue . the head is rather small but ok for the style .  the texture is creamy and smooth . the carbonation that provides the ample head is very subdued , giving a solid finish with a beautifully crafted feel . in my estimation , it is close to edmund fitzgerald , which before this , had blown every other porter that i have tried out of the water .

in particular the genuine hoppy aroma ( i think i detected cascade hops amongst others ) , was sublime and a true feat for a new zealand microbrewery . big floral and herbal bouquet with some yeasty and grainy notes . there was also a sourness in the finish which was n't very appealing .  pours a dark brown color with a thinnish light tan head , fades fast and does n't leave any lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel - very smooth , the wheat is doing its part here . good crispness and medium weight really help enhance the flavors .

beautiful cherry red , and perfect cherry in nose that wafts cherry a few feet , cherry lace . tasty , a bit of woodiness , not too tart.second to new belgium in authentic and complete taste . solid real and unique .  a : about as black as stouts will be , but this one is a little thin in the head / head retention . some strings of lace . reasonable , but not great .  the mouthfeel was amazing , drinking the beer it had the typical bite of aftertaste that normal ipas have , but i took a drink right when we left the pub and i still could taste the hops about twenty minutes later .

amazing smell , roasted coffee , milk chocolate and heath bar . very earthy-mild hop character that is more pronounced than i have experienced in a porter , but it is pleasant . biscuity consistency with each sip , malt forward with a heavy roasted presence .  a - one finger of white , fast fading head .  mouthfeel : amazingly prickly carbonation after all this time -- a nice counterpoint to its velvety body .

it 's very similar to pliny in aroma and i consider that the ultimate compliment . great flavor to complement the aroma .  pours with quite a bit of fizzy foam that settles quickly leaving little lace .  the best part . smooth as butter , no alcohol detected . fantastic beer , the barrel aged version i 'm sure is outstanding .

smell is a big whiff of dunkel bananas and bubble gum . not to sweet and the banana taste practically punches you in the nose . mouthfeel is watery .  2002 vintage served at 68 f fizzy tan head dissappered immediatly after pouring this .  a fantastic creamy mouth .

s - wonderful aromas of honey , pears , lemon peel , floral hops . i really like this . t - smooth , controlled sweetness . d - just an awesome beer , i 'm so glad i can get this locally now !  bottled early august , 2011 a : pours dark brown with a finger of tannish foam which falls over a couple minutes to a sheet of the same . spotty lace .  love the body on this one . on lighter side of moderate , but the oiliness from the hops makes it somewhat slick and the softest carbonation fills it our gloriously .

very unique aroma for an amber . extremely sessionable and unique ale but the nose leads you to believe it may be more complex than it ends up being .  any negative rating you read for the pennant ale is probably coming from somebody who does n't enjoy british style beer , and may not be familiar with brooklyn brewmaster garrett oliver 's style . this beer is brewed in the british isle tradition , with scottish maris otter malts bringing the classic biscuit flavors associated with this style . the malt is married with brooklyn 's house ale yeast , which brings considerable depth and hints of fruit .  very smooth and creamy mouthfeel with a nice medium body .
smells incredible , good enough to eat !  poured from bottle into tulip glass a- another dark brew with a decent head that disappears quickly .  smooth and creamy body .

i 'll be honest , i did n't smell anything . it smells like an empty glass . maybe some dark malts , but nothing stands out .  a - deep brown almost black with thin brown head ; low retention ; no lacing s - sweetish with dark roast , maple t - sweet at first then increasingly roasty ; some yeasty , bready action then sweet herbal honey finish m - low carbonation ; smooth mouthfeel ; short , sweet linger d - very good overall ; great mouthfeel ; on the sweet side but balanced pretty well ; i could finish a bomber of this easily  mouthfeel is extremely smooth and velvety .

awesome . taste- greeted with the normal citrusd peel , but more emphasis on grapfruit zest and some malts .  a - pours a hazy golden hue . nice 1 finger head that does n't waste any time disappearing .  exceptionally creamy mouthfeel , medium body .

sweet hop nose . full juicy/piney ... very piney hop flavor and fairly well rounded . spicy , somewhat medicinal yeast .  12oz bottle poured into a guinness pint - fridge - 2009 appearance : a twist off cap whispers as i crack it . the beer pours a brown color with red highlights . a 1/2 '' light yellow/ivory head surfaces and shows a little bit of retention . not much lace left behind .  superb feel .
this is wonderful . t- a lot different than the smell .  pours a light amber color with a small , quickly-dissipating head .  very full , creamy body that 's quite impressive for the abv .

appearance - clear golden brown color with very nice 2 finger frothy head smell - wonderful citrus/hops scents .  a-gold with a tint of amber . thin cream head . fairly light for an ipa s-impressively strong hops and citrus presence . m-medium carbonation with a great creamy finish d-hmm i actually like this a lot ... .i 'm very confused by the other peoples ' reviews ... the taste is n't too complex but its otherwise a great drink . i could have many glasses of this with complete satisfaction  the texture is perfect , though .

i spent a lot of time taking in the complex aromas that hit the nose with this one . i was able to pick up loads of the toasted malts but also hints of apple and honey , and various spices i could n't single out . the complexity on the nose played very well balanced on the tongue . the alcohol hits , but it is very well disguised by the heavy ( but nowhere near overpowering ) malt sweetness .  a- dark copper with some light orange in the middle when held up to light , small head that does n't hold up .  the mouthfeel is very much like drinking liquid chocolate or marshmallow fluff . so rich , creamy , and very full in the mouth .
