copper to gold ... lots of light flickering through and a rocky 3/4 '' bright white head ... aroma is awesome ... truly great . some spicy cinnamon and grassy hops ... herbaceous in a very cool herbaceous way with a a hint of basil and nosefull of dill . peppery and delicious . awesome .  gorgeous barleywine . soft , cloudy orange amber in the glass with a small head that disappears rather quickly .  mf : silky and smooth but without compromising its thickness , which is needed as a foundation for the abundance of flavour . not too wet or dry , but the perfect balance between . not a unique mouthfeel , but an expressive suitable one .

very balanced . really great . most pumpkin ales smell like pumpkin and spice , this one spells like a baked pie . a more than solid representation of the style , though the taste was a slight light down after the amazing aroma .  made an average appearance , poured a barely opaque ruby hued milk chocolate brown with a small foamy off-white head that quickly settled into a thin lacing , moderate carbonation .  rich and creamy flavor . mouthful is sweet and chocolaty and flavors get strong with more time in mouth .

minimal head retention & lacing s : raisins , dark candi , charred toffee & oak t : boozey raisins , tropical fruit , dryness & more booze up front . charred toffee , pineapple , oak & vanilla as this warms . finishes dry , with more toffee , booze infused apples & raisins mf : syruppy with minimal carbonation , too hot booze-wise not a huge fan of calvados , liked the norman cider better .  a bright white head faded from a quarter to nothing rapidly .  with thick molasses and velvety feel to balance a bold and alcoholic content , this one hits me with a lingering hoppy bitterness on the finish of strong malt presence . seriously strong , often incapacitating ... but ever deliciously so !

the aroma was very floral and complex , reflecting an array of different hops in use . it did not taste quite as good as it smelled and was notably acidic but was still quite enjoyable . the mouthfeel , carbonation and body were all very good for the style .  a : murky brownish with a beige head that vanishes quickly .  very rich , creamy mouthfeel is offset by a lightness at the back of the tongue and roof of the mouth .

smells like a lemonade/orangeade mixture but in a really inviting way . not sweet or sugary like the aroma would suggest but that just must be from extreme dry-hopping and the oak somehow . bitterness is perfect , no traditional hop aromas , no earthiness , pine , woody , flowers , just fruitiness . crazy .  definitely not my favorite style of beer but it keeps me coming back for more . the beer is golden with a very thick white head .  the mouthfeel is great , perfectly coating .

aroma is amazing and wonderfully enticing ... .initial nose of marshmallow s'more 's , tons of milk chocolate ( damn if this is n't the most chocolate-iest stout i 've had that is n't brewed with chocolate ! '' ooof ... let me regroup myself ... ok , much better , thank you . never overbearing , completely balanced , satisfying , very drinkable . i love this stuff .  this pours a light hazy amber color with just a thin rim of white .  mouthfeel is perfect .

aromas of sour cherries , malt vinegar and rhubarb come across very strongly with subtle notes of vanilla and rich chocolate fudge ( likely from the oak ) in the background . as it continues to warm , i pick up some definite cheese aromas as well ( fresh gorgonzola comes to mind ) .  bottle pours a golden orange , cloudily unfiltered-looking brew below a minimal amount of head , light to no lacing along the edges of the pint glass .  a- black body with a brown creamy head , nice retention and lacing s- chocolate , coffee , roasty t- nice roasty malts , molasses , chocolate , coffee and a bit of hops at the finish m- creamy , full-bodied and velvety smooth d- awesome mouthfeel and complex malts make it great !

s - wow . this has got to be one of the best and funkiest noses ever ; it is amazing what the brett has done the the olfactory aspect . not the same type of 'wow ' as the smell elicited , this is more of a shocking letdown . the flavor is nothing like the nose promises . it is not that its bad , but it is definitely massively underwhelming . but it smelled so damn funky and fruity !  pours into a pint glass with a black color and small brown head that disapates quickly .  great mouth feel it 's carbonated perfectly making this a great beer .

this is a hop bomb , so bitter , it 's a bit unbalanced but very hardcore . this detracts from the drinkability . awesome brew .  has a nince dark copper color , but had little to no head at all .  mouthfeel is perfect , medium bodied with a champagne silkiness that is delectable when swirled .

s - beautiful light tartness , pronounced blue cheesy funk . really great nose t - nice light tartness , some cherry .  a- pours a deep brown with a thin head and not much lacing . i remember this beer pouring & looking better than this .  mouthfeel - superbly smooth and creamy , especially due to the carbonation . overall drinkability - this beer is all about the smoothness of the mouthfeel , and inoffensive characters .

smells simply fantastic !  appearance : the thin white head quickly disappears leaving a few bubbles behind . the beer is a golden , light amber color .  mouthfeel : no real aftertaste ( remarkable for a malt-heavy beer ) , carbonation is excellent and it plays well on the palate .

s : this beer has a overwhelming aroma . it 's extremely rich , yet smooth . one of the sweetest beers i 've ever drank , but it is still well balance and taste exactly how it smells . definately a sipping beer .  pours a murky maple syrup body , not much head , but some webby film . lacing has an average hold . nose is very full and really inviting .  abundant flavor , lush , vibrant texture .

this is a really nice stout obviously rich with strong coffee aroma and flavor . the aromas are huge . like a big piece of double chocolate cake and an esppresso . a very drinkable stout . too bad it 's just a seasonal .  chouffe houblon dobbelen ipa tripel is a very cloudy , pale yellow ale with many particles and a huge , white , rocky , foamy head .  m - the best part of this beer .

the major component i got was a sulfury smell ... kind of like the brewer had eaten beans the night before if you get my drift .  yellow with an orange hue , and a thin white head that fades quickly , leaving some patchwork . decent lacing .  much lighter body than the bottle of extra stout i just had ; also a little more tart which was what i was looking for . roasted malts and hard water . mouthfeel is where it really shines . smooth like silk . goes down like water .

aroma : light spiciness aroma . very clear . spiciness keeps things interesting and dryness makes it goes down easy .  appearance : cloudy . medium off white head .  a- very murky , tan head , and faint hints of a red hue on the outer-most parts of the glass s- muted nose , that such of chocolate pop tarts t- marshmellow , chocolate , cocoa , raisen , over ripe cherry and a nice little chunk of bitter bight m- creamy and gorgeous . this beer is awesome .

nose is fantastic : huge and sweet , dried fruit , cotton candy , maybe some aprioct and kiwi in there too . surprisngly light alcohol , given the abv . overall , a delicious and really unique saison . maybe not one i 'd go for every day , but an excellent beer nonetheless .  served in a tulip from a bottle . nice head that disappears quickly .  mouthfeel : creamy smooth medium body with superb carbonation . swallow is velvet . tasty and the mouthfeel is truely a dream . goes down easy when you enjoy slowly .

aroma is sweet with notes of cloves , candy , and overripe pear . it 's a very nice belgian , but it 's certainly not a dark ale . that they grow all the ingredients themselves is very remarkable . it is a very nice effort at a belgian , but the lack of a real hop profile makes this simply too sweet for my palate .  served in a tulip . mayhem displays a dark russet-chocolate body with cola colors at the edges . no visible head or carbonation , even with a good swirl of the glass .  full body , incredibly velvety smooth feel with silk touches and superbly pleasant on the palate .
the aroma is quite pleasant - fresh citrus and hops are very noticeable .  knocked it off out of the bottle due to lack of glassware .  body is smooth , lightly creamy , and beautifully sparkling .

smell- flowers , belgian hops , honey , and candi sugar . extremely fragrant and balanced , with a superior fullness to the aroma . taste- a most graceful and balanced display of all ingredients , with not a single element outdoing the others . very good , but not perfect . outstanding and well worth the money .  yeasty notes fill the nose . soft of the palate , high level of carbonation makes this oddly smooth . no foam problem with this bottle , not much head at all actually .  mouthfeel is super creamy , milkshake like .

earthy oaky aroma with a lot of oaky tannis , vanilla and a huge b ourbon presence . this beer has an amazing nose resulting from the time spent in the barrel . lots of chocolate malt underneath the sweet bourbon character . i took in the aroma of this beer for several minutes before even taking a sip . slightly watered down but still a complex , quaffale blend .  a decent , light-bodied golden ale with a mellow spicy hop character that seems to come from noble hops like saaz . pours clear and blond with a firm head that settles to slight ring of bubbles . no lace .  m : elegant mouthfeel , the beer is simply not cloying which i was astounded with .

s - pungent , fruity hops that are reminiscent of jaialai ipa . d - very nice , the malt and hops are perfectly balanced , especially in the aroma where the fruity notes perfectly compliment the sweetness of the toffee and caramel .  muddy brown with a craggy foam . bubbles burst and spittle into a thin skim .  the carbonation is perfect . d-very drinkable , my dad and i shared the four pack , would have loved to have more .

s : the aromas of sweet vanilla and caramel hit you right when you open the bottle . amazing to say the least . not much of a hoppy aroma . smells like a great dessert beer .  as i expected , it was like a little piece of heaven . medium golden color , not much lacing .  mouthfeel is exceptional and there is nothing objectionable here .

the aroma is very assertive with candied fruit , sugared hops and a touch of alcohol . the hoppiness has faded in this one a bit . a really nice way to end an evening .  i poured this from a standard 12 oz bottle in a pils glass and immediately was reminded of why i like heineken . this particular bottle poured with about one and a half finger of head that withdrew fairly quickly and left some minor lacing .  there is the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .

it looked and smelled incredible . the taste went off the rails , tho .  pours a clear golden yellow with a lively white head that forms nice , but thin lid on the brew after a while .  smell : malt , coffee , alcohol , & toasted grains taste : toasted grains , licorice , coffee , bitter choclate , and hops bittereness in the tounge mouthfeel : damn , talk about smooth , great balance and carbonation .

smell is very spicy to say the least , lots going on , orange peel , lemon zest , coriander , pretty citrus , a full aroma for this witbier . taste is similar to the smell , very citrusy and spicy , lots of carbonation though typical of the style but could be toned down a bit , very light hop bitterness if any , crisp and easy drinking .  pours a clear golden/yellow color with a small had that could use some more retention and lacing is ok. aroma is well ... apples .  incredibly smooth , despite lingering bitterness .

big aroma of spearmint , grapefruit , lime zest , and wild flowers from the hops ... hint of bready caramel malt and esters in the back . hoppy after taste with a fume of alcohol . this beer has a full on grasp of the style , a great beer all around .  a fairly aggressive pour leaves a very small film of white head on top .  feels great . 5/5 d : yes , for the style and abv , it is .

s : strong hop smell that resonates lychee and tropical fruit sweetness . kind of like the smell of lychee jellies that you buy at an asian supermarket . d : good drinkability .  a - pours murky honey with not much head , settles to only ring . not much lacing . m - medium body , good carb and coating , great balance , considering the flavors dealt with .  mouthfeel : excellent . thick yet balanced with the carbination .

really spectacular aroma that calms my annoyance at losing so much beer . it comes together beautifully . delicious taste that just barely fails to live up to the aroma .  hefty pour reveals thin white head that quickly disappears to just about nothing . looks like a refreshing , lighter beer .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy and everything i could ask for . the tartness keeps pulling you in like a siren , and i am totally captivated by her song .

smell : sweet malt and fruity esters are big , a tartness is present as well , phenolic , very nice , complexed and balanced aroma .  it showed average carbonation , average head for a scottish ale , and minimal lacing , but it did n't look quite right .  the mouthfeel is unlike anything i can recall in recent memory . such a thick creamy texture like i 'm drinking thickness of marshmallow cream with the weight of a large marble .

one wiff of this garden-like beer will smack you with hops , with a touch of ginger scent in there . spicy hops .  growler pours more brown than red . ruby red with gold highlights when held to the light . some haze .  nice creamy mouthfeel , thick and pleasant and well balanced flavors of sherry , burnt carmel , toffee , roasted bananas and ripe stone fruit with hints of walnuts .

smell is muted and faint . what i do get is malty and sweet .  pours from the bottle a cloudy red color that is quite appealing if not for the haze .  the beer featured a very pleasing and creamy mouthfeel .

smells fucking amazing . giant sticky hops , pineapples , roses , and marijuana . like mixing centennial and cascade hold them up to your nose and breathing deep . tastes good . very good . the hops are more aromatic than anything , and the smell serves to blot out much of the amazingly sweet maple syrup malt that takes over most of the start and lasts throughout the middle .  this beer poured a clear brown color with a cream colored one finger , rocky head which quickly resided .  mouthfeel is very nice , i enjoyed it a lot .

it smells so fresh and amazing . t- mostly crisp , bitter hop pine and citrus .  2005 bottle , fun graphics , from spiritus fermenti amber and red body , looks prety nice but poor head retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel is wonderful for a beer that is this bitter .

smell is orange peal and grapefruit . spectacular aroma . first sip is a powerful blend of orange and pine . dreadful . this was so promising but i hesitated on each sip thinking about how bad the finish was .  pours a bronze orangish hue , minimal head , probably from a slow pour , and what little head was present does not stick around for very long .  m - perfect mouthfeel .

the aroma is perfect with great nutmeg , cinnamon , and clove notes . aside from that , delicious . rarely do i feel that i can drink two fruit beers back-to-back , but i certainly could have done so with the pumpking ... that is , if i did n't have a breakfast stout on deck .  comes in a 1l growler combo-bottle - has a swing-top cap , and a crown cap . interesting bottle . pours an orangey-gold , slightly hazy , with an orangey-tan head .  mouthfeel this is real good for an ipa or dipa , pretty full and creamy , enough heft to match the zip and zing of the hops hopslam also wins for aftertaste which has a long linger yet is not too strong .

s : belgian yeast , touch of brett , pears and apples . a little spicy floral hops on the back but funk dominates .  bottle - color of prune juice , with no head - nose of broth , paprika , oatmeal cookie , vanilla , malt , iodine , and raisins taste of raisins , dried apricots , madeira , sweet , and slight wood - body thick chewy , and silky aftertaste of raisins , and malt  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

nose is delicious , really quite extraordinary , giving that lovely oaky vanillin american stout character of coconut sweetness , obviously without the straight oak . it 's a phenomenal nose . so full , so complex and so incredibly luscious and delicious . i 've rarely had better . taste is smooth and full , and again extremely well mingled between the sweetness of coconut and chocolate , and the slightly more astringent roastiness . overall , a fantastic beer , and a wonderful drinking experience .  fairly busy aroma with aspects of wheat , malt , lemon and , other fruitiness , but also a characteristic sam adams quality . gold with mild cloudiness . drink has a nice thirst quenching quality and a flavor that , while mild , holds many tastes , including the base of wheat , but also some citrus acidity and a little sourness .  this coats the palate with a burbon goodness . just the right amount of carbonation .

the aroma is wonderfully complex , with notes of dark fruits , spice , yeast , molasses , bubblegum , and caramel . beautiful . on the palate , predominantly fruity , with big spices coming up toward the end , along with a growing alcohol burn .  decants a dark an lovely black with a thin creamy head that was rather shortlived to say the least . overall not much to look at .  the texture was excellent , not too thick or thin .

smell : powerful coffee bean aroma . luscious milk chocolate compliments the mocha superbly . taste : the flavor is dominated again by roasted coffee . overall : i was pleasantly surprised as i was n't expecting such a good beer . very good blend of a traditional porter and robust black coffee .  a : amber orange , hazy , no head s : there are citrus and floral/pine notes present but not pungent like other ipas ... looking forward to the taste t : very mild hoppy/floral taste , a hint of honey , and a citrus flavor throughout .  a - golden crystal-clear , the way a pilsener should look ; frothy , dense head with sticky lacing ; tons of carbonation s - fairly underwhelming ; from what 's there , detect dry-hop and sweet-malt presence t - dry , bitter hops at first ; gives way to sweet malt flavor , with just a touch of creaminess m - light and creamy ; delicious ! d - so easy , like throwing back bud light ; i could easily down 5-8 of these

750 ml bottle , lot d , bb date july 2013 . a pour into tulip creates effervescent , murky pale orange-brown body with yeasty floaties , topped by abundant white head that sets to a fine veil . the aroma is fruity and spicy : fully ripened melon , tropical fruits ( mango in particular ) , spiciness that comes from either phenolics or adjuncts , floral hops and spicy alcohol .  12oz brown bottle , i really dig the graphics on this one . quite frankly im a bit too eager to drink the bastard to look very hard , though . not as opaque as i had expect , looks like a decent ipa . a very clear burnt orange with just a hint of amber . not a whole lot of bubbles coming from the bottom of the glass , but theyre definitely there . not a whole lot of lacing action , but there is some . the amber is almost an afterthought .  ( m ) mouthfeel is balanced and superb : substantial enough to linger on the palate without being too heavy . it 's very smooth due to the subdued carbonation yet there is a slight alcohol warming sensation - which i do n't mind at all .

the smell is exactly the same as a pumpkin pie coming out of the oven ; it 's not so much a question of the spices associated with autumn , i detected an actual baked pumpkin aroma .  poured into a mini tulip it forms a decent head that fades rather quickly into small islands .  the body is perfect . honestly .

a familiar smell i 've come to love from quads . complex . complex as hell . pretty good alcohol presence . outstanding beer none the less .  a : pours a dark orange with a finger of off-white head that recedes into a thin layer with little lacing .  3.5 m big thick beer , very heavy on the tongue . really nice .

a great aroma though .  cloudy . peach color with slight ring of bubbles.. probably a result of hard and fast pour . speaking of peach , the aroma is overwhelming with the fuzzy fruit .  silky smooth and creamy mouth feel . such body without being cloying .

( s ) - a bizarre smell ; orange and lemon peel ; a spritzy-like fizzy lemon/orange drink ; its like tang/lemonade/and sprite at the same time . very odd . ( t ) - agian , like the smell , this is very different and bizarre .  dark amber color .  huge taste and mouthfeel . lots of bitter hot chocolate taste and viscous almost chewy feel to it .

no real lacing but it does have some legs smell : smell is decadent ; probably one of the best smelling non-sour beers i have encountered . overall/drinkability : one of the best-smelling non-sour beers i have encountered , but the high abv and hugeness of it really detracts .  appearance : pours an extremely dark brown , with some light coming through when held to light . less than a finger of light tan head formed after a pretty hard pour , and that dissipated pretty quickly . kind of disappointing in the looks department , actually ... smell : holy crap , this is a beautiful aroma .  m ) rich , almost slick . rich , long mouth coating .

strong belgian scents , hops . this one really wafts . taste is sharp carbonation , almost foamy . nice beer , but for the price it 's not worth it .  it looks pretty good except it 's full of big particles floating throughout . it looks like pulp floating in there .  clean warm finish m- syrupy full mouthfeel , creamy and warm d- i 'd be great having one every night in the winter

i do not find the beer to be as tasty as the nose indicates , but it is still a damn fine pumpkin ale .  pours a light transparent copper color with only a thin cap of head . little to no lacing . overall a solid beer and quite drinkable .  mouthfeel - perfect , the creaminess remains with a twinge of bitter , very hearty and drinks like a filling snack .
very attractive smell . they could make this into a perfume .  golden/amber pour , some yeast floating around .  the mouthfeel is great . what a light and delicate brew .

it 's interesting , strong citrus aromas from start to finish .  freshness stamp seems to read 062701 a decanted pour reveals a slightly hazy muted dark copper color with a one finger slightly tan head .  mouthfeel was great , smooth .

lots of sticky lacing coats the side of the glass.. aroma - strong sweet fruits ( definite pineapples . grapefruits and some passion fruit ) , creamy vanilla , very light maltiness , sugary / honey notes , some spiciness / pepperiness , some cloves , yeasty notes , floral hops , some grassiness ... taste spicy fruits ( apples , some pears , light pineapples and grapefruits ) , nice spicy floral hop bitterness , light sugary sweetness ( not as sweet as aroma would indicate ) , vanilla , light pale malts , light biscuity hints , some alcohol coming through ... mouthfeel quite sharp and dry although some smoothness comes through afterwards ... light body ... pretty refreshing and drinkable considering the strength ... overall an excellent beer . probably my favourite chimay brew ps - have also had this on tap at the mort subite bar in brussels . also had slighty more spiciness to it ... .  a : average redish to golden color .  perfect mouthfeel for an ipa.. substatial , chewy but not syrupy.. drinkable but nowhere near being called 'light ' .

nose smells bad -- acrid , macro , not what i want in a wheat at all .  750 ml bottle , a : pours a light amber with a real mild white head , fair retention , no lace .  the mouthfeel was awesome . just perfect subtle carbonation .

the aroma is breathtaking . a beautiful balance of oak , sweet malt , and dark fruit with a layer of very clean smelling whisky gently overlaying the rest of the aromas . just marvelous . unfortunately , the taste fell a good deal short of the ethereal aromas .  one of 4 beers on the menu at a favorite neighborhood restaurant . a : golden color with a good amount of fizzy bubble haze . minimal head , though i 'm guessing i can chalk that up to the waiter 's delicate pour .  wonderful body .

perhaps a hint of light caramel or breadcrust , though it 's very subtle . no hop aroma . overall : while the beer is somewhat lacking in aroma there is a pleasant tie-in between the malt sweetness and noble hop flavor and bitterness .  good carbonation , little head retention s- smoke . while i would normally suggest pairing a beer in this style with salmon , here i am thinking perhaps chocolate cheescake or perhaps bacon wrapped apricots .  perfect mouthfeel , actually .

12oz can into wide snifter . lager . s- corn ? as inoffensive as you can get . everywhere , cheap , and processed .  a big thanks to tim ( sliverx ) for hooking me up with this . a-cooper amber cooler with very thin carbonation . thin head no lacing . reminds me of a great barleywine that ages well .  the body is amazing and really makes this beer absolutely stunning to go along with its big hoppy flavors . it 's oily , greasy , beefy , big bodied , and largely bold , with a crunchy , grabbing , snappy , zip line long bittering tone of a ton of orange oils and pine oils .

smell- wow . i would venture to say that this beer showcases hops better than any other beer i 've ever had . oh , and again with the honey . taste- again ... wow . weird for a dipa , but very very good and interesting , as they remain just whispers in the background . mouthfeel- simply superb .  appearance : murky honey-like color with very active carbonation . forms a huge offwhite head composed of large bubbles .  good , creamy body with a low-medium carbonation is very nice for a ba imperial stout that is not overly sweet .

man , this stuff smells great . i think i 've been smelling it for 15 minutes now ... taste . starts out good , but there 's an herby , floral bitterness in the end which i did n't enjoy very much . after being one of the best smelling barleywines i 've come across , i was bummed to find that the taste did n't live up .  turbid , carmelized orange color ... interesting ... never seen one like this ... head is gone almost immediately .  m - very creamy . just a small sip seems to coat the inside of the mouth very well .

s : this is one of the best smelling brews i 've come across in the summer ale category . i 'm not sure what kind of hops they added in the aroma portion of the brew , but it 's outstanding . unfortunately , it 's the best thing about this brew . t : really good . for a summer ale , it 's great .  2006 ( about a year old ) appearance : poured dark black ... like there 's any other kind of black ... could use more head and lacing .  loving the mouthfeel .

a bit of a soapy aroma was the first thing to hit the nose , followed by pine and citrus hops , some caramel malts , and a dry hop .  well , it certainly is yellow - as yellow as lupulin dust . yellow snow is otherwise shy on the suds , perhaps as a result of a tired pour . this is a fine ipa though it 's not rogue 's finest moment .  incredibly easy-drinking and gentle on the tongue . the penultimate english pale mouthfeel . there is so much to love : subtle and well-rounded , both quenching and engaging , plus the mouthfeel is impeccable . i feel foolish for not having tried this sooner .

smells absolutely wonderful . very sweet but not overly malty or boozy . overall , an amazingly good dipa , and at a great price - i believe i paid $ 7.99 for the bomber at binny 's .  a-orange color with medium white head that dissipates quickly . light lacing that vanishes as well .  the mouthfeel is perfect -like a cloud in the mouth , and i could no doubt doubt drink this all night..especially in a tiny village with some locals by the fire in a 17th century pub ... .what a treat .

330ml bottle served in a pint glass.enjoyed on mar11 orangish light amber.yellow froth , dense & lasting.small bubbles.chill haze.high & intense perfume profile.on palate lemon zest & resins.very smooth bitterness at first sip but increasing in the middle.medium carbonation.abv is not felt.good & refreshing drinkability .  very tasty , slight malty alcohol flavor , but well balanced with the hops . it 's a little over carbonated - an easy 12 oz pour into a pint glass produced enough head that i needed to give it time to finish the pour .  mouthfeel is smooth and velvety with carbonation perceivable at the very end of the swill .

the nose is strong plum , figs , prune , dark chocolate , coffee , brown sugar , wheat , just lots of sweetness in the nose . the taste starts mildly bitter with a grapefruit crack of bitterness , this is very interesting ... .it feels like a fruity belgian beer combined with west coast pungent hops finished with a porter 's roasted barley like quality .  pours into my pint glass a hazy peach color .  the mouthfeel is almost the best part of the ale . full and velvety .

just an enormous complex smelling stout . bits of flowery esters float around as well .  so , this pours a little flat into my tasting glass , a dark red-brown .  silky smooth , nice carbonation , and thin enough to drink a few of , but not so thick as to let you notice the 7.4 % .

smell is huge . molasses hits up front , dominating all else . everything is taken to the next level by the great alcohol aroma . taste is sweet , fruity , and boozy , nowhere near as complex as the smell . super roasted , the only balancing factor is the bitter alcohol on the finish . drinkability is actually quite good , if you 're in the mood for a strong old ale . overall , not the best i 've had , but a good beer nonetheless .  pours with a nice thick black body , but with a thin head , much thinner than most stouts .  m : the carbonation is gentle , making for a perfect silky , but thick , body .

it has a terrific aroma , fresh , floral , strongly hoppy . outstanding nose ! good though . hops were good , a bit more balance would have been better .  presentation : it was poured from a brown 1pt .9oz bottle into a pint glass . appearance : it has a hazy yellow body with a thin white head . the head quickly fades to just a small ring of foam . lacing is minimal and slick , sliding right down the sides of the glass as i drink .  the body and finish are absolutely luscious considering this is a 4.5 % abv j-beer out of a can .

smell is big , fat , and rich . only that gorgeous nose is enough to keep you going for more .  a : pale straw in color with thin white head that quickly dissipates . extremely sessionable .  mouthfeel is where this beer delights ! so smooth and round , you want to swirl it around in your mouth ! mmmm .

a- the beer poured with a minimal head that had nice retention at least , beautiful lacing is due to the extreme amount of hop acids in this bad boy . s- oh my goodness , i went to a homebrew store recently and i smelled some of the hops , this smells like cascade and centenial . not those hops in a beer , it smells like i have a baggy of hops and i am sniffing it , it is glorious ! t- eh , the hops are a little much , i am looking for a beer , not hop soup , this tastes very fresh , as if the hops are still in my glass .  hazy deep golden . thin off white head .  mouthfeel is really exceptionally creamy and smooth . it 's full bodied , oily and just exceptional on the tongue .

to me this beer smelled exactly like a medicine cabinet .  this cloudy yellow ale pours with a small head and no lace . average presentation , but the nose says otherwise -- i get bread and orange peel .  also was surprised by how creamy this went down . this is a pleasure on the tongue .

the aroma is mostly sweet roasted malt with some caramel notes and just a touch of earthy hops . the sweetness that the aroma promised must have checked out early , becuase i ca n't find it at any temperature in this beer .  a : a hazy light brown color with a thin tan colored head .  its well carbonated , and very smooth . however , i found the beer very interesting solely on the smooth mouth .

aroma - monstrous amounts of roastedness , wonderfully intense coffee and chocolate syrup . a heady layer of alcohol floats underneath it all , pushing the flavors , enhancing them .  the beer is black as anticipated . produces very intermittent and spotty lacing .  extremely smooth , like mink or sable .

for a fruit beer it is exceptional in smell . smell is of pure fresh blueberries .  pours hazy orange with an average , fizzy , off-white head , somewhat lasting with fair lacing .  mouthfeel : omigaw , it 's so creamy . so very , very creamy . `` luscious '' is the word that comes to mind .

i really liked the nose though . i would suspect that was derived from the guava .  appearance deep orange in color ( maybe like honey ? ? ? ) with a smallish head that went down quickly .  mouthfeel/drinkability- the mouthfeel is absolutely stunning , slick and smooth with the perfect level of effervescence .

the nose was really quite amazing . banana , spice , phenols and wheat . quite an amazing non-german weis beer smell . the taste on the other hand was quite a bit different . light and very smooth . so the smell is amazing . like fresh german weis , or a belgian like leffe .  this pours a transparent medium amber with a half finger head dying away quickly leaving no lace .  its thick and syrupy and full of body and character . the alcohol warmth is soothing as it makes its way to the back of the tongue , leaving a sweet resin .

s : though the body is lacking any type of foam on top , the aroma is very rich of dark fruits and berries with nutty undertones . it has a very pleasant balance between sweet malty caramel and bitter floral hops . t : very sweet and bubbly on the tip of the tongue with a nice contrast of bitterness on the back of the palate and sour on the sides of the tongue .  pouring was somewhat uneventful . there was almost no carbonation , so there was no fizz , and no head . given that there 's no foam to interfere with delivery with that aroma .  m : silky smooth . wow i am impressed with the smoothness of the beer .
s - delicious bready , malty aromas .  pours a hazy brown almost an amber color with good head and some lace .  the mouthfeel is perfect for a doppelbock .

very balanced . easy drinker .  a - copper brown body with half an inch of creamy beige head that reduced to a swirly patch and thin ring of retention , leaving no lace around the glass at all .  first sip reveals a rich and firmly textured beer of elegant character . an encore presence by the hops closes out the taste in a long and seamless finish . faultless balance , beautiful complexity both in the nose and on the tongue make this beer , in my opinion , a perfect desert beer or soothing winter warmer .

decadent as well , somewhat like chocolate covered cherry cordials . absolutely fantastic in the nose ! syrupy and mellow with buttery brown bread and nice fruit : apple , berry , citrus , and fig . sweet and woody and not terribly pronounced provided the outstanding nose . mild hops and vanilla with a ghost-like smoke note . very complex and earthy but rather understated . very nice however . a unique and enjoyable rendition of the style .  a : clear , dark maple with less than one finger of diminishing off-white foam head . no lacing remains on the glass .  feel is thick and creamy , with a light carbonation of fine bubbles that help give it a velvety character to it . this is a damn fine beer .

puns aside , this is an incredible-smelling rauchbier - the rich , authentic , pungent smoke is literally the only thing i can smell , and that 's perfect . t : smoke , smoke , smoke , wood , smoke , malt , smoke , smoke , bacon , smoke , cake , smoke , spam , eggs , spam , spam and ... sorry , got carried away there . nice . notes : awesome rauchbier , but not quite as awesome in the end as i found their urbock to be .  it has a clear , medium amber color with a decent head that dissipates but has a well retained lacing .  actually a very good mouthfeel , for this style .

awesome aroma . pine and citrus , candied orange , grapefruit , resiny , fresh hops . for such a great aroma the taste is very dull . d - very strange combination . everything great about the aroma just disappears .  appearance is a bit disappointing on tap as there is no head .  the mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and coating , leading to an extended finish that eventually coaxes out some espresso and a final touch of nuttiness .

wow , this one smelled great . tastes of caramel , vanilla , bourbon , wood , nuts , raisins , and a light earthiness .  poured into a tulip glass . dark golden color with a quarter finger of head .  body is refreshing yet almost full in its thickness and rich , creamy carbonation . overall it 's damn delicious and a great collaboration ; no surprise that there 's yet another beer with the dogfish head logo on it that i love .

the aroma is loaded with dark toasted malts with caramel , toffee and dark fruits . wow , the malts seem to explode into your nose . the taste like the aroma is dominated by the toasted malts with plums , toffee and caramel . wow , this brew is nothing short of delicious !  appearance - 3.0 a lot darker than normal for a hefeweizen , almost looks like a dunkelweizen with three fingers of creamy off white head that quickly reduced to a single finger . appropriately cloudy .  rich and textured in my mouth , i really enjoyed this beer , but would n't be able to handle more than 1 in a setting .

the aroma has a very nice fruity almost flowery quality to it , that blends nicely with the hop background . a nice and complex aroma .  ruby chestnut hue , with a light haze . initially thick head readily recedes into a thin , meager beige ring .  dark coffee , bittersweet chocolate , toffee , dark wheat bread , smoke , spices that are tough to identify but clearly at work ... all mingled together in perfect measure . super smooth and velvety , although not what i would call creamy . largely because the body is n't a heavy one , but this texture comes with a terrific caress that does not leave me wanting .

scent is a pleasant combination of spice and citrus with a solid sweet , but not overpowering bready and carmely background . first sip is predominately mild spice and tropical fruits , the spice intensifies as it warms , yet the citrusy hop presence fades slightly , the sweet and bready carmely background does not come through until the beer is almost at room temperature .  i wish i was joking and usually like to give brewers the benefit of the doubt , especially for a first visit or tasting ... but this offering was completely disappointing . i really like the atmosphere of the brewery so i hope they continue to reinvent their recipes and find some real winners . def try their strong belgian , `` the gift '' ... .very nice !  moderate carbonation with a strong sticky pine aftertaste make it very very enjoyable . very strong , flavorful , and pleasant .

s. wow , this is one of the best smelling ipas i have ever had . amazing . t. not nearly as smooth as the nose indicates .  orange , with a thin , bubbly white head that fades a little , becoming patchy . this strikes me as an excellent fall beer , but still quite good in the summer .  m- super creamy and smooth . the carbonation level is perfect . a nice clean and crisp aftertaste .

it smells freakin ' awesome and tastes excellent .  pours a merky browinsh color with a film as a head . no lacing which is weird for an imperial ipa aroma is nice and hoppy but malty as well .  full , fluffy body .

very pleasant . t- the wheat comes through very clearly , with a dab a honey to make the brew less aggressive .  this one poured out a slightly hazed ruby-orange-amber color .  m - i had it on tap , carbonation was perfect . a refreshing balanced beer .

the aroma , while a little faint does have a distinct hint of vanilla . damn good porter .  pours red-amber , with limited carbonation and no discernible lacing .  m : creamy , milkshake like , full-bodied , spot on carbonation , very well done .

the smell is light for an ipa .  pours into a streak , mud cloud in water brown with cherry highlights . half inch head quickly recedes into thin , whispy collections of foam on either side of the glass . little lacing to speak of .  body and carbonation are excellent for style .
there was not much smell other than hints of grain .  a - 1 finger fizzy white head that dissipates quickly but leaves a thin layer on top .  unbelievable smoothness , with a slight bite .

huge aromas of buttery nuts , woody breadiness , creamy sweetness and an overall strong aroma that is just beautiful . heavenly smells and a creamy character that is drool-inducing . a relatively relaxed brew , honestly , despite it 's blue-blood title . intriguing and unique , to say the least . spritzy would n't fit here .  wonderful pale yellow color with big bubbles that disappeared as quickly as they usually do in japanese lagers .  mouthfeel is perfect , goose island is the best of the best in this regard .

gravity cask @ gingerman in nyc . s : wet and juicy citrus hops all over the place : pink grapefruit & tangerine . has a sweet and really fruity malt background . t : loads of sweet pink grapefruit up front and then a big hit of juicy hop bitterness . d : had this on gravity cask , second day the cask was on .  pitch black in color ; essentially no head aside from a few brown hued bubbles here and there .  mouthfeel is stunning . thick mouthfeel , but super creamy ... like a properly done oatmeal stout .

aroma of honey and lavender . very complex and almost reminiscent of a west coast barley wine . aroma is dominated by pineapple with hints of peach , vanilla , and a little raspberry . definitely the fruitiest non-citrus aroma i 've ever smelled from an ipa . taste is just mild sweetness , then a huge clean bitterness , with a feeling of a bitter tea finish .  11.5 ounce in tulip a : brown , thin head .  mouthfeel is rich , smooth , and silky . soft carbonation .

but this beer , the bouquet is fantastic ! and let me set this straight , `` bouquet '' is not a word i use normally but this beer has brought me to a place where `` bouquet '' was the word i needed to use to get my point across .  a : no head , some bubbles .  mouthfeel - creamy , silky smooth . fine , vigorous carbonation .

s : a balanced display of strong lactic and acetic notes , aromatic malt that seems floral and complex , and yeasty fruit . the addition of volatile oak , building in the nose as the beer warms , represents the perfect addition to round out this beer 's aromas . no alcohol is detected .  a : pours a cloudy orange with a tiny tint of red . ridiculous white and fluffy head .  m - perfection , i love the way this feels .

nose : i do n't know if it was just the serving method , or the area i was in and the associated ambient scents , but the nose on this puppy was weak at best . mainly hops with perhaps a little citrus , but not a whole lot of anything . the flavor really helped me move past the weak nose and allowed me to appreciate the full glory of this beer .  this pours a deep brown with an almond head that thins to a cap and then to nothing with no lace .  very nice on the palate a very full and pleasing mouthfeel .

overall a nice stout with a great nose .  this time it was poured into my favorite goblet ( moinette ) , so here goes : golden-yellow body under a weak head that disappears quickly , nothing amazing visually .  pours a rich crimson color with a creamy off white head that stays put thru out the duration of drinking it , deep caramel aromas along with some milk chocolate quite sweet.absolutely sublime creamy mouthfeel just glides down smooth , flavors of caramel and brown suger hit ya up front but there is a decent dryness midway keeping it from getting to sweet.i wouldnt say earthy maybey more herbal in the finish , its quite heavy a one or two and done for me.this is a doozy a great winter beer , it would real warm ya up , not that i need that down here in nc .

granted , i was stoned at the time ... smell ? pumpkin pie . cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkins , awesome . taste ? damn this was a good beer .  the bartender poured this one into a glass for me , and it was a nice rich caramel color , but no head to speak of .  f : rich as hell , and creamy . head is pillowy , with good retention . d : damn good , gets better and better as it opens up . admittedly it 's a completely different beer , completely roast obsessed , but still ... raspy is better , and cheaper ... and that 's really the bar for a ris , in my humble opinion .

smell - wow , nice strong hop smell , also quite fruity , hints of orange and grapes are present . really great smell . taste - pretty darn good , starts out with a hoppy citrus taste that makes way for a powerful hop bitterness that sticks with ya .  deep ruby brown ale here with little in way of foamy head .  love the feel in my mouth .

2010 vintage aroma : a big toffee-like maltiness , some chocolate cake batter , a bit of vanilla , and some floral hops . definitely a brew that kept me smelling for a while before tasting ! very strong , well-carmelized brown sugar supported by an extremely hoppy foundation . i also noted a bit of bubble gum-like phenol , more smokiness , and some alcohol toward the finish . overall : definitely worthy of its reputation . i think i learned with this one , though , that i definitely prefer the fruitiness and complexity of a british barleywine more that the american style .  dark brown color .  m : the feel is incredibly creamy and medium bodied . one of the nicest bodies on an oatmeal stout i have ever had .

it also smells fantastic . tons of chocolate and sweet , roasted malts .  smuttynose winter ale is a hazy , tawny brown ale with a thin , khaki head that leaves decent lacing on the glass .  excellent mouth feel as this is full , creamy and smooth not too much more can be asked from a brew like this .

aroma : amazing fruity head on pineapple and malt . totally out of style , but totally yummy . taste : complex and heavy pale malts , slightly sweet tropical fruit .  pour brings an orange-copper body with a slight white head and just a very minor touch of lacing .  mouthfeel/drinkability- silky , soft , and seafoamy ... the texture in the mouth is liquid perfection , beginning very smooth and quickly gaining subtle carbonation that just hangs right in there for the duration . a wonderfully simple , yet complex beer that needs to become available in north jersey soon .

s : smells amazing ! hops immediately hit the nose and give you a first-hand experience of why it is called `` hopslam '' .  a : poured amber colored with a finger head and a little lacing .  the real beauty of this beer is in the mouthfeel . it is full and lush - velvety and slick . could n't ask for better .

s- malty heaven . i love the sweet malty aroma and will sometimes just sit and enjoy . how cool that a beer smells this strong . t- malty sweetness up front with dark sugar notes . sweet in a very good way ... but hops keep things in check . this is far different . very good !  poured dark brown in color with a very thin , fizzy and spotty head .  mouthfeel : medium body with colossal carbonation make this an incredibly creamy beer . de dolle gets this perfect for me yet again .

a very delightful smell . some traces of malt in the background , but this is all about the hops .  appearance : poured with about 1/4 '' white foamy head that dissipates quickly . drinkability : this beer , despite its lack of head , is an excellently balanced beer and very easy to drink on casually .  m ~ refreshing and spirited mouthfeel . truly exceptional .

wow this is a wonderfully floral blend of citrus hops that warns of hop balanced sweetness and really gets the mouth watering .  a : medium cloudy amber color . very small head that fainted rather quickly which was a tad disappointing because i like bigger ones on wheat beer ( a weizen glass could have helped with this probably ? decent small lacing .  m - light carbonation and rich mouthfeel . a very fine dopplebock in mouthfeel d - although i 'm sensing some alcohol the sweetness takes this thing home .

very aromatic smell - some floral , lots of hops , light citrus - all backed by pine .  this golden beer was quite nice . clear in color , ok carbonation but not much head .  a very smooth and creamy cask ale , that goes down very well .

smell is big and complex , much improved from the younger beers in the series . sumptuous creamy chocolate , sherry , vanilla , peaty smoke and oak . mmmm ... . earthy dryness in the finish .  good black color without much head to speak of .  very smooth . the lubricious mouthfeel enhances the drinkability ( for a barleywine . ) i love the combination of chinook hops and caramel and munich malts .

aroma is quite amazing - it smells like a fresh baked pumpkin bread or cookies . has a really rich spiced bready smell with a nice blend of spices . too sweet and just way too much in general .  '' can into tulip pint . nice clear orangey gold color . two fingers of white head , decent retention , little lace .  palate : full bodied and medium carbonation . great feel . full bodied and enjoyable .

still very complex , i thought it smelled great . not quite as complex as the smell , but still very good . m - medium body and low carbonation , very smooth and easy to drink . i thought the smell was outstanding and quite complex . would love to drink again .  sampled : 5.28.06 appearance is the light pale hazy gold with a minimal head without much retention .  mouth- full , creamy mouthfeel . fine carb .

the malts smelled of moderately sweet grains and plums . there was a big hop profile here as well . they smelled of light citrus , orange in particular . the taste mirrored the smell , with the addition of some pepper and a bit of alcohol .  pours almost milky-pale yellow , cloudy . thin white head on top fizzles out fairly quickly .  m - has a lovely and distinctive soft quality .

nose is classic stone yeast with a great floral hop kick . overalll , it was damn good . i thought it was almost an ab light with some added pine and less citrus , and no hop double kick to the palate , which works well .  loose , off white head that settles to an outer ring . cloudy unfiltered looking copper body with an orange glow at the edges .  carbonation feels perfect . this beer is also easy to drink .

the smell was very light , with a bit of malt and a hint of sweetness .  pours a medium clear brown , copper tints with a short , thin white head .  very smooth , almost velvety mouthfeel . excellent brew , but the 8.4 oz bottle is entirely too small .

smell is surprisingly great , huge roasted malt aroma with just the right amounts of chocolate and coffee in the nose . a very solid everyday porter , ca n't believe i have n't gotten this more often .  just typed up a full review but due to the poor servers on this site , when i entered it it timed out . will say this imo , is a special beer .  just perfect . this is one of the better stouts that weyerbacher has done .

a : pours a very dark amber , can barely see through it , thick white head , copious lacing around glass s : loads of aromatic hops in the piney variety , some citrus , little to no malt presence ( dominated by these delicious smelling hops ) . this has an excellent smell ! t : taste pretty much matches nose , a walloping of piney hops with a little more depth than what i could smell . has a nice spicieness to it .  appearance : poured with a large off white foamy head composed of large bubbles , which dissipated quickly leaving almost no lacing . the beer is slightly hazy with a orange/yellow golden color .  velvety and soft-spoken , yet deeply sexy . more to the traditional side .

the smell hits me before i even pick up the glass . foresty hops burst with grapefruit and cedar galore , while a huge balance of luscious amber malts drop notes of caramel-coated apples , peanut toffee , and sugar daddies . slight booziness , too . a big , chewy malt profile piles toffee and caramel upon a toasted nuttiness . an aggressive hopping takes hold mid-palate , dropping raw , leafy hop notes that suggest pine and citrus peel . finish of booze and more hops , with layers of dark fruit and rum all the way down . mouthfeel is thick and somewhat harsh , even for stone 's insane standards . nice carbonation level , but the aggressiveness could stand to be toned down a bit . congrats on unlucky number thirteen , stone , and here 's to 13 more !  very quick head , no foam , and very little bubbling .  biscuity sweetness , a boisterous alcohol presenece , and nearly perfect on the palate ... a little too expensive to drink on any sort of regular basis , but quite a treasure if you find it somewhere .

s - juicy hops galore ! pineapple , mango , honey dew melon , flowers , sticky herbal pine , slighlty toasted graham cracker , caramel t - toasted caramel/toffee malt , floral hops , candied grapefruit , grapes , pine resin , hops turns soapy mid palate while finishing spicy . as a hybrid dipa/imperial red this shines . the nose on this is intoxicating . it 's almost a sensory over load . it has a nice malt backbone and drinks easy for the abv .  pours a clear golden color with a decent head that settles to a small lacing . typical looking pilsner .  extremely thick mouthfeel .

wonderful aroma , smells like a strong hefeweizen , wheat , clove , banana , honey , bubblegum ? my first wheatwine , and it was quite nice . i 've been impressed by terrapin .  a : this beer was a cloudy medium brown color . there was a small head with slight retention .  the body is just about right , medium , with a smooth as satin mouthfeel .

aroma is amazing with the hint of cherry , of course . beautiful amber color and pours well .  the beer 's appearance is an orangey yellow , with a moderate amount of carbonation . the head is white and relatively thin , and has a soapy quality to it .  body is rich , creamy , smooth , and damn near perfect . another excellent offering from d'achouffe .

really good . t : pumpkin pie and spice again .  poured from a 22oz into a pint glass ( shared with coastiefish ) appearance : quite dark , rich brown color , and poured 'thick ' but not too thick .  mouthfeel : exceptional . creamy and syrupy with an intense peppery hop finish .

absolutely fantastic . taste is surprisingly sour .  12 oz bottle served in standard pint glass a - orange-tinted amber ; hazy ; scant but lasting off-whit head m - medium body ; nicely carbonated .  mouthfeel is very rich and full , nice amount of carbonation .

soapy white head that dissipates quickly . s : i expected the grapefruit greeting of the ipa , but my nose was met with citrus combined with tropical fruit , almost a pineapple or mango and hint of floral . t : same blast of citrus and tropicals ; finishes a little bit quickly , without a lot of bitterness or drying , which i missed . a really fantastic beer and a lucky find since i understand hill farmstead is not found much outside of vermont .  355 ml bottle , thanks jon , a : pours burnt orange with a mild white head , average head retention , no lace .  m : probably the crowning achievement of this brew . perfect carbonation and a nice smooth feel .

very , very enticing . the taste is grapefruit rind , bready , biscuit malt , some pithy tropical fruit , and a bit of pine .  the beer had a hazed golden/orange color to it with a -finger of bubbly white head . retention was good but lacing was only spotty . whoa !  m : incredible bitterness that lingers , with a great crisp carbonation and bone dry .

the nose is excellent . there are wonderful orange burst hop aroma , some piney evergreen citrus notes , some sweet maltiness underneath , and some hoppy florals too . the nose on the beer is very enticing and pungent , i only wish the taste were as nice as the aroma .  a : pours jet black with a thin crackling tan head . head disappears immediately , leaves nearly no lacing s : smells of sweet pumpernickel and a hint of burnt caramel .  mouthfeel is creamy and exceptionally full , yet really heavy , on the lighter side , and very soft . mouthfeel was clearly the biggest beneficiary of the addition of the bivalves .

the aroma is on the lighter side but very balanced and nice . it starts off very sweet , some wonderful sweet chocolate notes with some vanilla with a finish of coffee .  a : poured golden amber with a thin off white head w/ no persistance / lacing .  mouth on this one is perfection . somehow light and airy despite the thickness .

the smell was way off , i barely could detect the hops behind the malts .  dark brown with minimal translucent colors when held to the light . little head ... about 1/2 in . that reduces to nothing rather quickly ... no lace ... wonder if it is my glass , but i doubt it .  mouthfeel/drinkability : this beer feels pretty creamy in the mouth , and is just a touch heavier bodied than i expected , actually . excellent .

the aroma is very good , i think it smelled a lot like french vanilla coffee with cocoa , very very good .  from a 22oz bomber , poured a couple of shades darker than straw yellow , but not quite orange , with a thin white head that dissipated rather quickly .  it was lush , creamy , smooth , rich , decadant and full . a very full bodied stout with a low carbonation .

smell : gorgeous hop bouquet ... juicy ruby red grapefruit , pungent green hops , light pine/spruce , sweet tropical and passion fruit aromas . one of the best smelling iipa 's on the market - hopefully this shows up in madison and stays cheap ( saw the oat for 2 $ more in madison today than in chicago ) taste : strong iipa here ... quite a bit boozy , moderate bitterness , ruby red grapefruit , citrus and lemon , tropical fruit , strong caramel malt presence , christmas tree ... yum mouthfeel : moderate bitterness , medium body , lingering bite drinkability : pretty good  pours dark mahogany with a 1.5 '' tan head . not much lacing or head retention smell : big malt roastiness and cofee notes taste : fruitness is quickly overan by toasted malt assualt .  an absolutely fantastic mouthfeel .
this beer has a remarkable scent . it smells like starbucks coffee .  appearance is really nothing too special , particularly . below average head , golden straw color .  gorgeous mouthfeel .
aroma is fantastic . best smelling ipa ever ( believe it or not ) !  pale straw in color , with a moderately sized , bright white head .  the mouthfeel is very silky with no aftertaste .

dry as the day is long with a rich , complex hoppy nose , long in earthiness and fruit with pine and cotton candy . on the palate this is a bit aspirin-y , a nice , medium body and a finish that 's almost crackling with resin . less than pliny the elder , and it 's far superior to their standard ipa ( `` far '' being relative , that 's a solid beer as well ) .  a - cloudy dark orange body holds a smallish off white head . decent retention with some sticky lace .  still it is very full bodied .

complex and excellent scent . taste of vanilla , oak , hops , alcohol , and clove .  a : slighly hazy gold body with only the faintest hint of a thin white head . nothing to retain , and no lace . i 'm ok with this headless pour , though , since it means i get to take full advantage of the small glass .  the mouthfeel is wonderful . silky smooth .

s : wonderful . the coffee is much more pronounced than i remember . o : a wonderful beer .  beer is a cloudy orange-honey color without much visable carbination .  goes down incredibly easy with a silky mouthfeel .

smell is of super hop juice , citrus , grapefruit , pine , herbs , and black pepper . from the samples i 've had , it just seems to be a bit watered down . it 's a let down from getting excited with the kick-ass aromas to actually getting to taste it .  a : solid black with no head .  this is a tasty beer ... m - a good thick and creamy full bodied beer ... d - a little expensive for my liking ; however , definitely something worth picking up if you have n't tried one before .

a hard pour of this rosewood colored beer produces aromas of tea , ale fruit , dark stone fruit , red cherries , blackberry , baked bread . amazing eggshell colored frapped rootbeer float style head that totally laces the glass . taste is more tea with a chewy amber malt body , metallic red ale twang , and floral to spicy hop bitter in the drying finish .  pours dark copper with ruby highlights . when held to the light i get a look at a lot of suspended particles ( probably yeast ) which is a bit odd for the style . a thick , light tan head gradually dissipates to a stubborn lacing on the surface .  smooth on the way down and a very dry finish . this stuff is heavy and good .

its massively enticing and one of the best i 've come across on an imperial ipa or any other type of beer . the flavour is very good , but not as vibrant as the nose . that said , this is still a solid four out of five in my books . this is a very nice imperial ipa , but i 'm gon na go against the flow and say its not in the very top tier for the style . the nose held huge promise , and while the flavour delivered on some of it , the vibrancy was a bit lacking . i 'm sure this would be a killer fresh on tap .  aroma : raisins , figs , grape , a touch of solvent alcohol appearance : pours a murky dark brown , low carbonation , very minimal head retention .  very low carbonation contributes to the smooth feel . full bodied , minty , earthy finish . satisfying sipper from skilled craft brewers .

a : pours an orange color with small head , slight lacing down the glass s : smell is amazing ! ! very citrusy hop scents abound . very slight biscut scent as well t : slight biscuty taste up front with a citrsy bitter bite at the end m : medium bodied oily mouthfeel d : this tastes as fresh an ipa as you could get ... i 'm sure its not ... i live in washington and its brewed in pa ... great beer tastes just like i 'm at the brewery .  a - as expected , medium to dark brown , not much head nor lace .  feels like heaven in my mouth ; it 's silky with an appropriate yeasty zing .
however the smell and taste was excellent . it tasted of roasted coffee and raisins .  l - black color with a thin brown head that vanished in a few minutes .  thick smooth mouthfeel , very silky .

the scent is overwhelming with the bourbon but upon swirling the complexities come out . although this scent reminds me of my ol ' grandad/jack daniels days , i can also detect deep wood , vanilla , coffee and a hint of black pepper . this is truly spicy but also has a mix of syrup and caramel on the initial sip .  bottle into red wine glass . pours a pale gold orange , with a thin , soapy off-white head .  m : incredibly smooth and creamy .
smell- very fruity . huge smell of pineapple and citrus .  a little dark with no retention .  the mouthfeel was perfect , i kept swishing it around my mouth on every drink .

complex aromas make it very unique . is this a red beer or a light nut brown ?  poured a cloudy deep copper color with moderate head that fell to a long lasting ring .  love it.5.0 d fair plus drinkability as this is a huge beer , one that i could probably only have one of .

the aroma is intoxicatingly rife with pumpkin pie and whipped cream ( graham cracker crust included ) . cinnamon , nutmeg , ginger , and pumpkin pulp all blend harmoniously into one of the more potent-smelling pumpkin ale 's out there . the flavor starts off bold and full of pumpkin pie notes , while a delicate lactic sweetness quickly gives way to a spicy booze onslaught . however , this was certainly an interesting craft beer experience , and easily the `` greatest '' pumpkin ale i 've tried .  a - really cloudy with no head or carbonation .  the mouthfeel i think is perfect for the style .

smell has that strong nice balance of rich malts and floral hops . a nice enjoyable hearty ale .  i tried this one on draft at the flying saucer in addison . the beer came with a minimal head and no bubbles rising .  mouthfeel is incredible , maybe an even better quality than the taste .

also get passion fruit and a general fruit medley - outstanding . the nose is also a little woody , like cherry wood . downright impressive . solid medium mouthfeel - good body and medium range level of carbonation . taste is more green fruit , vs. the smell which was very rouge . a great beer all-around and very drinkable .  porus a rich chestnut-amber color with a minimal head that is reduced to a soapy rim after a couple seconds . mild lacings and no retention .  ( m ) - great carbonation level & balance . very smooth going down . sweet & rich but is balanced with nice lemon citrus plus a nice wheat-like neutrality .

s : wonderful , joyous sultry oak scents .  appearance is goot , kinda like darkish brown with a tin of light to it . makes you wan na drink it just looking at it .  the mouthfeel is exceptional . nice and thick tasting .

s- smells frickin amazing . its like mostly grapefruit and a bit of caramel and a hint of pineapple . still snorting in the gorgeous aroma of this beer which i hope never ends .  poured a dark amber color . very thin white head .  i honestly would think this a stout or porter , rather than a bsda ... m : this is soo smooth and nicely full bodied , its literally coats your mouth , and leaves your mouth wanting another sip , just perfect ... d : well this beer is still a little hot , a year or two would make this even better .

s : huge grapefruit nose . some wildflowers in the background . best ever ! t : very smooth . hoppy to the end . d : very drinkable ... maybe too much so .  a- average yellow appearence , no/little head or lacing .  mouthfeel great creamy thick milkshake like mouthfeel with medium-light carbonation .

complex sour with tropical aromas . nice lacy appearance in the chalice with good carbonation in the mouth . what is that suddenly familiar aroma ? i flashed on cutting a passion fruit in half and smelling it . more nose of pineapple guava . one of the best and most interesting beers i 've tried this year .  pours a light honey gold color with almost a greenish hue . a white head soon turns into a ring .  very tasty indeed mouthfeel was very alive great carbonation with it 's light in the ass body and a very easy drinkability can enjoy anytime of the year .

the good - the smell on this thing is crazy good . sweet citrus - mostly grapefruit .  quite beautiful really . gently poured this formed a soft airy bubbly tan head which surprisingly disappeared quickly giving it a rather flat appeance .  mouthfeel is wonderful . creamy with smooth carbonation .

neutral aroma .  poured a much oranger color than i expected -- not too different from the color of their twilight ale -- closer to an amber than a traditional brown ale . very nice initial khaki head , but it dissipated to almost nothing -- a thin ring leaving some tiny sudsy bubbles on the glass but no lacing .  the carbonation is spot on , it carries the beer extremely well on the palette . this drinks like a slightly hopped up brit but not so much to kill you with hops .

the flavor is like the aroma with a tad bit too much bitterness but still very good . the palate is smooth but not as thick as i had wanted it to be .  appearance : nice clear appearance , good orange/brown color .  thick and chewy with all the perfect elements . the real stand out for me was the mouthfeel .

the smell is pleasing , if straightforward .  poured from a brown 22oz bottle into a rougue revolution pint glass . jjdga poured a slightly hazy amber with a two finger off white head that fizzled away to zilch in a couple of minutes . aromas are much appreciated after the lackluster appearance .  mouthfeel is top notch , so smooth and light yet complex at the same time .

nose is fantastic - heavy pine forest ipa notes mix with wonderful grassy spicy wet hay and plum earthy sweetness . taste is a bit subdued compared to the smell , but still good .  this is a really really fun beer , a really shining example of a cali belgian ipa from a good ( but not great ) brewery . i 'm really liking their special releases though , this and lucky 13 alt are great for the style . pours underwhelming , a bit too clear for this type of beer and not enough head/lacing ( no bottle conditioning i 'm sure ) but since i 'm judging it on the style got ta knock it . the taste is really good for a very west coast belgian ipa ( cmon it has 73 ibus ! great beer , not the best of the style but really liked it .  very smooth feel to this brew overall .

s - really impressive aroma , oak and alcohol , also fruity and caramel-like notes .  brown , mahagony , russet , with ruby highlights . head is miniscule and lacking . what is present is a tan ring around the collar ( or rim for this matter ) .  had a nice , velvety texture that reminded me somewhat of trappist ale , but without the bite of alcohol you would encounter .

the aroma is quite complex and very appealing- grass , a bit of pine and citrus , some hard to identify floral and spice notes , yum yum yum . grass , lemon , and ... watermelon ( ?  dark , syrupy brown with almost no carbonation into a goblet . i hear this is not normal , maybe a bad batch as far as carbonation goes . a livelier head and mouthfeel would definitely improved this slugger .  mouthfeel is the creamiest thing i have ever tasted . ridiculous full body and amazing texture to this beer .

the aroma is unbelievably complex . i love the cheesy/cherry taste !  beer pours golden with large head that soon fades to thin and transparent layer .  great mouth feel and easy drinking , starts and ends dry ( without being bitter ) , but gives up a fair amount of sweetness in the middle .

smells really good . appearance : golden color , nice white head , clear .  a - dark ruby red color , black as night in the glass . nice mocha head , that disapears much to quickly .  felt great , and was easy to drink .

i get the strong scent of deep woods to begin - green , piney vegetation , quickly followed by the continuing characteristic from their holiday beer - a thick and wonderful spicy gingerbread . no year is ever an outstanding beer , but it never lets you down either - consistently good .  main st. describes this brew as a porter fermented with saison yeast , and that pretty much nails it on the head . poured a very dark opaque brown ( almost black ) w/ no head .  nice mouthfeel of solid carbonation .

smell is intense , the oatmeal and coffee dominate the scent .  i had a 1oz pour from the nbt guys . take this review for what its worth , but there were n't many reviews , so i figure a review of a 1oz pour is better than nothing . the smoke reminded me of like a peaty scotch , but not really in a way that i liked ( and i am a huge ardbeg lover ) .  m - very creamy ; a superb feel .

smell is very nicely aged , deep aromas of molasses , dark fruit , and anise , with a boozy warmth if you look for it . amazingly complex , it 's right up there with the best . taste is very strong , sweet malt at first , then a hit of boozy flavors that i can only compare to jagermeister .  the beer poured a slightly hazed golden/orange color probably due to the use of some wheat malt . the beer made only a half finger of white head that dissipated quickly , but surprisingly still left a lot of nice lacing .  m - fantastic . perfect amount of carbonation , just enough to tingle the palate , complementing the sour flavor .

this one raised my expectations with the strong nose . the pour was mediocre clean dark yellow with an off-white head that lingered . the nose was strong with hops , citrus , and acidity that floating up .  the beer poured a cloudy golden/honey color with only a finger of white head and only minimal lacing .  mouthfeel is great . super dry , well carbonated , and smooth going down .

aroma is quite fruit forward with pineapple , pine , grapefruit , malt still comes through though with hints at caramel and biscuits . taste is an amalgamation of flavors and aromas coming together to form one badass beer . all aroma 's transferred into taste , pineapple and mango coming through swinging in a sweet nectar . awsome as always .  it 's appearance is light orange with a whispy fading head .  very neutral , no real taste at first . ) it had a great mouthfeel .

rolling , dry bitterness on the finish . o - a big , bitter , gorgeous looking ipa with a great aroma . the ibu 's are a bit harsh , but if that 's your bag then you 'll absolutely love this beer .  dark brown in color with reddish mahogany tinges . thin , bubbly , off-white head which dissipates in no time . nice carbonation , with a bit of haziness .  medium bodied with soft and delightful carbonation in a smooth , creamy body . hands down the best in the series thus far in terms of body .

fantastic nose tons of citric and flower .  pours a huge head . big rocky frothy root-beer-float head on top of a little bit of golden orange . roll back the carbonation a touch , please !  m : absolutely the best part of the beer .

not in a bad way just not as unfiltered as i would have expected . overall it is extremely enjoyable . one of the better beers that i have had this summer .  light passes through when held up to a lamp as a very dark red . slightly assertive pour yields almost no head . average at best .  it 's full bodied and smooth with a very clean finish .

it smells very rich & velvety , though i 've never actually smelt velvet . the rare beer that actually smells better than it tastes , & the taste is excellent .  poured a nutty brown without much head and a lace that did n't stick .  it pours a brilliant gold , and the mouthfeel is very thick and chewy .

smell is fantastic , a touch of booze mixed in with sweet , sweet roasted chocolate . good beer . right now the components are there for a top-notch brew , but they 're oddly disjointed & vying for attention rather than complementing one another .  poured a very cloudy , hazy medium brown color with a little off white head .  mouthfeel is awesome . full , luscious , and smooth .

beautiful and strong aroma . t - some booziness .  a - pours dark brown with a tan head that dissipates quickly . a bit underwhelming , visually .  mouthfeel is very appetizing - just the right amount of smoothness and carbonation .

it opens up with a beautiful floral hop aroma that is sweet and begs you to take a sip .  pours a rather still orange-amber hue with almost no head .  m - nearly full bodied but despite that and the abv , it is extremely smooth and leaves just the right amount of flavor behind leaving you wanting another sip .

hood uses over 3oo pounds of pumpkin and winter squash per batch of this beer . the squash is then roasted to caramelize its fruit sugars and is brewed with a judicious blend of molasses , cinnamon , allspice , nutmeg , and ginger . pumpkin ales have a long history of being brewed in colonial america . this beer smells and tastes like a-1 steak sauce , and though this may sound odd ( and unappealing ) , its actually intriguing and palatable . this is a fun beer with great appeal .  pouring into a glass results in a ruby red color with barely any head .  body is perfect for the style , rich and semi-thick with restrained carbonation .

it smells fantastic , the hops dancing with the roast barley . a great idea , really , very impressive . it is the rest of the beer that fails to deliver .  a : dark , almost opaque with a small amount of coffee color peeking through the edges small-medium head dissipates quickly and leaves little lacing .  the carbonation level was perfect . the body was exactly what i wanted- not too watery but still very drinker- friendly .

fresh citrusy , fruity , floral hops dominate the nose with some fresh doughy malts underneath . quite good via 16 oz can as well .  appearance : poured a light golden color , clear . one finger white head , with minimal retention . good carbonation . not much lacing at all .  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect . perfect thickness ( almost sludgy it is so thick ) , extremely chewy , with subdued carbonation . flawless .

s-tropical & citrus fruits and hops dominate . i could have sat there for 10 minutes with my nose in the glass , but many beers to get through on this night so i carry on .  this beer pours a cloudy golden orange hue , with some stringy chunks of sediment , and a thin cap of soapy white head , which disappears in an instant , leaving no lace .  mouthfeel is exceptional . big , small foam mouth , which smooths down , edgy all the way -- but never sharp .

this horribly misplaced smell is probably not coming from the beer itself but from the glass or , more likely , from the thick wedge of lemon spewing a harsh acidic fragrance into the air . the tweaked , excessive bittering lacks appeal and that smell is just too much to take .  pours darkish copper , absolutely sparkling clarity , and a quarter inch head that fizzled instantly to nothingness . a perfectly placid surface remained and zero lacework .  unique and quite charming , with some tasty complexities , yet easy to drink due to it 's wonderful mouthfeel .

s- big amount of port , scotch , whiskey , even a little hint of bourbon , and of course a huge amount of oak and vanilla . t- huge alcohol with a nice big chocolate body to back it up . all the aromas come in and a sweet dominating caramel body . very nice and complex . m- full chewy body that is really oily with no carbonation at all . d- i think it is really good but not easy to drink .  pours a clear light gold with a bunch of little floaties from the bottle conditioning . not the best looker .  m - thick and creamy , very full bodied . complemented by the right amount of carbonation .

s- very complex sweet fruitiness like pear or apple , resinous herbs , sticky hops toasty malt , cleanser , alcohol , and something i ca n't quite put my finger on . the aroma of this beer is truly remarkable and i expected it to carry over into the taste .  poured into a tulip . the beer pours like a big solidmass of oily black with no head . no head means no lace .  very refreshing .

it smelled fantastic . t- the beer tasted less pungent than it smelled .  the appearance was hazy , as expected in this style . i was a bit disappointed with the poor head retention . while the head lasted , it was an off-white colour . no lace .  the mouthfeel is some kind of amazing . this brew is thick , chewy , ultra creamy smooth and goes down like heavy cream . if you like your imperial stouts with an unapologetically brash , bold , slightly raw taste , but with a refined , well-mannered mouthfeel , then you 'll enjoy expedition stout immensely .

an impressive cask stout . slightly subdued aroma , with light coffee and smoke .  pours a rich golden color with a fizzy head , disapating to nothing , leaves no tracing .  mouthfeel is absolute satin .
