the moderation of the roastiness of the coffee is perfect . so damn good . taste is nicely roasted as well with a great malt foundation and an immediate iced coffee flavor . so now , bx is my favorite coffee smelling beer , while speedway remains my favorite coffee tasting beer .  bottle : poured a dirty beige color ale with a large fluffy head with ok retention .  medium body with perfect amount of carbonation .

fragant , great nose . t : caramel malt , molasses , red wine with a hint of soy sauce .  wonderful farmyard stench and strawberries , some public toilet smells ( but in a good way ) .  m : close to perfect : rich , thick and creamy .

smells like hops first , then rye and a bit of medium caramel malt . beautiful nose . i 'd go crazy if i smelled this but could n't drink it .  it 's colored like most belgian darks , but it has an immense amount of floating material ( what i thought looked like hop petals ) .  m : fairly high carbonation with a great body . the body is absolutely spot on !

smell is excellent on this imperial ipa .  dark brown color where light shines through ... barely . solid two-finger finger that dissipates slowly and leaves nearly no lace mild aroma of soft semi-sweet chocolate ; reminds me of fudgesickle .  the mouthfeel is perfect . the carbonation , weight of the brew , taste and viscosity are all well matched .

aroma : a really great aroma , stylistically . drinkability : just a very good , very solid , very drinkable oatmeal stout .  smells a lot like coffee bender . brown body with reddish hues . small head left quickly and did n't leave any lace . very easy drinking beer .  you can `` dig '' this one out of the corners of your mouth ten minutes later , which is to me the ideal feel of the style , this beer feels great . d- this guy could probably use at least a little while in the cellar , as it is so intense in malty and hoppy , it could stand to chill out a bit .

on the back side of the aroma profile is some floral hop bitterness to help balance this out ... it has a very inviting smell overall that i hope leads to a likewise flavor . i love the aroma as i 'm drinking this beer !  overall , i was pleased . appearance : i drank it out of the bottle , so i did n't really get a good look at it .  very creamy mouthfeel , very sweet .
smell is fantastic , floral hops and a sweeter citrus smell fill my nostrils with goodness .  the beer was pretty normal looking but did not smell like an ipa .  m : lovely viscous feel . perfect .

the nose is quite amazing . this is a thick , full bodied beer , very sweet , very sticky , but loaded with very nice oily and estery hops that are delightful . there is a very thick , sweet , caramelized maltiness , there is a warming booziness , but liqueur like sweet .  ( a ) - pours a hazy golden orange color . produced some white froth .  perfect mouthfeel for this beer .

s : dark fruits , mostly plum with some hints of vanilla and caramel maybe even a bit of belgian style sugar in there . a very pungent punch in the face that does n't disappoint . damn near perfection to my pallet . seek this one out if you are a barleywine fan .  a -- nice light brown color . decent head that goes away fairly quick .  carbonation is moderate with a medium-full body yet still decent drinkability . the one thing that really stands out with this fest is its remarkable smoothness , definitely the smoothest octoberfest ive had .

this is a tough one to grade for me since its a pumpkin ale , and i hardly noticed any evidence of pumpkin in it . smell and taste are very similar and are just like fresh ginger snaps right out of the oven .  i poured this beer into my tumbler at 50 degrees . the beer was cola colored especially with the amount of carbination stuck to the glass .  mouthfeel is beautiful with sweetness up front followed by a sting from carbonation and finishing with a crisp dry bitterness .

a giant tan head forms and for the first time ever i 'm almost worried about my snifter overflowing . smell : fruity and tart . hay , apples , and cherry . this was awesome and i 'm glad to have a whole growler of it .  pours off-yellow with a little orange in it - no head whatsoever .  coats the tongue just right , insulating it from the alcohol .

whatever it is , it 's complex and wonderful . t-nice balance of a stout ( i know there 's a trace of that in here ) with subtle sour characteristics : seems to be cherry . very nice finish .  the appearance of this almost reminds me of killians ( my old mainstay ) , due to it 's lack of head , and deep orange coloring .  outstanding mouthfeel ! d - drinks like a champ for a ris at almost 10 % abv !

s : chocolate , a lot of it . giving it a vigorous swirl a very rich dark fruit ( cherries , raisons ) comes through , but with that nice chocolate over top of it . taking another , larger , swig the alcohol in the beverage stands out a bit more , and i get a nice warm coffee finish . m : i am a bit disappointed for here , it is a bit thin for what i was expecting from this this , but it coated the mouth nicely it just did n't have the thickness that i was expecting .  pretty much pitch black with a light tan head that is fairly compact and somewhat persistent .  this has a wonderful mouthfeel which i absolutely love .

huge cherry and oak on the nose , followed by an earthy mustiness and barnyard funk . a bit boozy . a damn fine flemish sour ; ranks with the best .  poured into a pint glass from he bottle very average looking beer light off amber with a nice head that disapates quickly leaveing a nice laceing down the glass smell is supurb big hop nose with some sweeter fruit notes and come more lemon citrus flavor is amazing as well the hops are huge in the front and middle that gives way to a nice bitter finish and a small hint of sweetness at the very back end .  very smooth , exceptional mouthfeel .

smell : slight scent of caramel and hops . taste : hop presence , malty and some caramel .  pours black with a thin tan head . it left a little lacing at first but not much overall . my only criticism is i would have liked a little more head retention and lacing .  m- huge in the mouth chewy , creamy , and smooth . mild carbonation . nice clean finish , indicative of the nice alcohol levels .

great big roasty aroma , a bit of chocolate .  cantillon zwanze 2011 pours a solid burnt orange to light red . there 's a wispy bit of white foam that serves as a head , but there 's not enough of it for me to even observe any lacing or head retention .  m - almost syrupy . i love the mouth feel .

i love the dark coffee and chocolate aromas . toasted malts and rich deep chocolate fill the nose . i can detect a light hint of alcohol as well .  mudpuppy porter pours a black color , with very little head .  m : perfect ! coats the mouth great ... slightly creamy , with the right amount of carbonation to bring out the flavors .

has a great pumpkin bready smell to it , as well as some spices .  pours a nice mahogany colour with a thin light tan head . poor head retention with not even a thin film present after about a minute .  i love it .

smells really really good . beer is medium bodied and has a good hop character to it .  a- a clear orange liquid with some amber hues .  super smooth and creamy body that glides down your throat like butter . so smooth and delicious that i had finished 3 pints in less than a half hour .

very minimal smell - some floral notes , but otherwise not much coming through .  cloudy amber orange , but the fizzy short head dissipates quickly and leaves virtually no lace .  mouthfeel : wow is this stuff smooth . very silky and perfect carbonation .

immense aromas of alcohol , vanilla , burnt malts , woody hints like oak , dark chocolate . overall , this was an intense beer for me and it had some great qualities .  the pour is a mostly hazy with a brown color and definite amber/red highlights . a decent head that does dissipate over time as well as the lacing .  mouthfeel is really very rich : like a good stout on the palate , smooth and full , thick and chewy , but it 's got that pilsner crispness .

smell : that great balsamic vinegar aroma was present , but with an extra spicy cinnamon in a quelquechose kind of way , with a touch of musk and just enough alcohol to make me think i was smelling an old bottle of perfume i found in some dusty attic .  a- a pale golden color that pours with a small head , and several small bubble trains ( like champagne ) . m- a medium body , but i had this crazy sensation of tiny bubbles running through my mouth ... kindof like the micro-carbonation you get with nitro beers ... this strange carbonation seemed to give it a much creamier texture than i would have expected .  the mouthfeel is smooth thick goodness . a heavy beer to say the least .

proclaimed as an american pale ale on the label and one sniff would validate that - a beautifully strong cascade aroma .  pours a dark brown with a thin frothy head that leaves way to soon .  ever so rich and creamy in the mouth with soft and forgiving carbonation . medium-full in body .

hop aroma galore ! ! this beer has a nice copperish color a decent size head . the aroma is amazingly floral and zesty hop bitterness .  appearance-a very pale ale that pours a bit cloudy . you can mix it with another type up drink and create something called a `` dirty ho ''  smooth and oily with moderate carbonation - great mouthfeel .

bomber into a snifter a-deep orange with a nice white head that floats on top for a while ... the bubbles are there but not over the top ... s-caught me off guard ... u can really smell the sweet and dank amarillo hops and the citrus from both amarillo and cascade from the dry hopping ... really surprised this stood out in a wild ale ... the funk is here with the acidity ... t-semi sweet grain starts this off then follows with the twang ... the sourness and the wood take over the middle ... with a little acidity ... .the funk is def there seems this is very brett forward with a good amount of must to even out the sour ... finishes extremely dry.. m-thin but i imagine that is from the maturation in the wood ... the carbonation is perfect and the acidity doesnt wreck my palate or my stomach ... .very very dry ... . o-a very good sour ... far superior to last years la folie ... .but not on par with erics ale ... .quite pleased with it ... will go back for more..  appearance : pours a near clear , light copper-toned body with a relatively fast-lived , white head .  m : quite thick moderate carbonation , love it .

s - it has a very pungent sweet aroma . smells great ! m - full in body with light carbonation .  pours a clear ruby color with a small khaki colored head that quickly settles into nothingness , looks flat .  thick , creamy , chewy , and lush , but with just enough carbonation - everything the style should be .

s : holy hell this smells good . rich cocoa , vanilla & oak .  poured out to a cloudy burnt red color with very low carbonation . a short lived head bubbled down to just a thin layer of foam after less than a minute .  this did not effect the mouthfeel at all it was perfect as is .

great fresh hoppyness in the taste , great green grass smell , pine , together with some apricots , i would say , and some milky chocolate malts .  i have to admit that i bought this beer because of the bottle , but i am very glad i did . it poured with very little head and what there was quickly went away .  m - good and thick in the feel . the finish is fantastic .

smells of citrus fruit ( grapefruit , orange ) , sweet malts lie underneath . very unique aroma . i said , `` summer strawberries in a hay field , '' while my brother said , `` watermelon bubblicious . clean with good carbonation ; tickling but not overbearing . an easy ale to dring with a great mouth and a top-notch nose .  excellent beer . i was forced to try it this summer as i searched for something decent among the bcm at the local gas station near the beach . this style is usually a bit too hoppy for me , but after about half a glass - i was really enjoying it . bitter yes , but probably appropriate for this style .  m : they nailed the mouthfeel on this .

aroma is wonderful ... full of nutmeg , cinnamon and everything that is pumpkin pie . for a pumpkin ale , the abv is rather high , but they have covered it very nicely .  this poured coke black in the glass with only a hint of head and no lacing .  fantastic creamy full mouthfeel .

the nose kills me it 's so good , making me very excited for the first sip . i could just stick my proboscis all the way in to the bottom of the glass and drink this through my nose it feels like . definitely a winner . great yeast character in both smell and taste .  it was a nice mahogony color with a small half inch head that dissipated rather quickly . no lacing during the drinking period .  the mouthfeel and the drinkability of this beer are the stars for me , it was so smooth and almost milky ( in a good way.. not like gagging thickness or anything.. just very smooth ) .

s : this beer kicked me right in the nose and said hops ! ! ! m : super bitter , it says so on the bottle , not my preference , but it truly lives up to this , the rating i 'm giving this is very generous .  a - pours a nice golden color but with almost no head .  this one comes together nicely as it warms and the , big , sticky , thick , creamy mouthfeel is a big highlight .

perfumy and very fragrant . spicy fragrant taste .  a deep ruby pour , not much head to speak of . does n't lace the glass and is all around uninspring quite frankly .  m : mouthfeel is awesome ! slick , heavy and chewy . it gets fluffier and chewier as i swirl it in my mouth .

the aroma is amazing with strong fruity hops and maybe even a hint of coffee ... although i may be crazy .  somewhat hazy honey-yellow with a white head and poor retention .  the mouth feel is outstanding , to the point of being lip smacking and among the best i 've had .

what a complex smell ! t - lots of lemon/lime citrus flavors with a light malty sweetness that finishes very light and refreshing ! d - due to its incredibly strange flavor profile , for me , this beer 's drinkability is not as high as it could be .  sweet orange and citrus taste with a good amount of light malt and amber flavor . very well balanced , drinkable and light american pale ale despite the perhaps little too dry finish .  wonderful mouthfeel .

bomber poured into a gruss aus munchen mug ... both received from zorro in the beerfest bif a- deep orange with red highlights ... big pillowy off-white head that leaves great lacing on the way down and takes a while to subside ... looks delicious s- intense and complex with some elements atypical of the style ... big sweet fruits ... caramel malty goodness ... spices ... clove ... raisin ... and big earthy grassy hops ... smells like a great oktoberfest but bigger and hoppier t- similar to the smell ... but everything is soaked in booze a little too much for my taste ... finishes with a hint of toffee and chocolate ... burns a bit on the way down ... still tastes like an oktoberfest though m- tiny carbonation bubbles feels good on the tongue ... despite the heavy sweetness it does n't feel syrupy ... medium bodied d- limited by the booze and the burn on the back of the throat this is an interesting take on the style ... and one i 'd love to try a different version of  pouring it into the glass allows for that pineapple note to really come into focus . pours cloudy , but clarifies into a mostly translucent hard amber -- by which i mean the amber that entombs certain prehistoric insects . an ivory , two finger head is produced that leaves no sticky lacing .  good balance of sweetness and alcohol warmth full body creamy mouthfeel rich is a good word sippability is great would n't mind having a few of these for special occasions

i could not smell much of anything . maybe some faint hops .  pours a clear and crisp very pale straw color topped by a fizzy there-and-gone white head . enough funk to make things interesting .  feel is thick yet subtle soft and a fairly easy clean finish . this beer is a politician : drinkability talks an easy talk but once this gets going , the abv will lie and before you know it ... . thanks to our fellow ba resident calvinist geofffromsj who astutely taught me today that `` jesus saves , moses invests .

an absolute gorgeous keeper . the nose is intense and vivacious with cinnamon , sour apple , lemons , and oranges . tart . quite saison like in nature . candi sugar , earthy yeast . cider . tropical fruit facade on the nose continues in the palate with a carbonation wall that obscures the malt flavors . cider . wife likes this more than any saison she 's tried .  yellow and imperturbable . s : hoppy ... creamy-tart . t : really darn good ! i 'm very happy with this beer .  mouthfeel was outstanding . the lush , creamy and full body was absolutely amazing .

smell is quite strong . i could smell it after the pour from an arm 's length . very bitter and hoppy , slight sweet malt aroma .  500 ml bottle pours hazed dark amber/brown . managed to keep the sediment in the bottle this time .  mouthfeel : great creamy , smooth mouthfeel .

s- excellent nose . sweet pineapple , citrus , grapefruit/orange , hops . m- medium bodied , but very smooth . light oiliness . d- awesome . i love the complex flavor .  presented to me in a standard american pint glass the beer was a very light brown almost orange color topped by one finger of white creamy head .  m - perfect carbonation in a perfect medium body , godly smooth .

the overall aroma is one of the best hop-focused pale ales that i 've come across . m : the initial bitterness followed by the mix of hop and malt is quite pleasing . as an ipa fan , i enjoyed the hoppier aspect that was later balanced out .  this tied for my favorite beer at gabf last night . i ca n't comment much on appearance based on the sampler cup , but the combination of citra hops and grapefruit peel was amazing . the aroma was unmistakably citra , but there was a nice amount of grapefruit in the flavor . definitely not a standard ipa but excellent nonetheless .  m : very smooth , sticky , and thick . light to medium carbonation .

smells phenomenal . vanilla , oak , a tart undertone . awesome aroma . tastes nicely tart .  12 oz bottle app- golden color with a one finger white head . sm- maybe apricot , but it maybe the power of suggestion .  the mouthfeel is incredibly thick and creamy , chewy enough to bite down into .

s : fantastic floral hop aroma that only dry hopping can produce ! t : the hops have done more than just produce great aroma , they are prevalent in the flavor as well - and not just bittering . i love hoppy beer and this was no exception . a nice smooth base ale , perfectly accented with earthy flavorful hops . great ale !  southampton enjoys a well-deserved reputation for their belgian ales , and now i know why ... the cru pours light amber in color , quite clear and displays a low head that dissapates fairly quickly .  m : this beer is full and lush . it is almost chewy . the carbonation is noticeable .

s : great smelling beer . extremely herbal , coriander , yeasty and fresh like a spring breeze . if the beer tastes half this good i 'm in luck . d : too many spices added , detracts from the flavor of the beer .  pours clear clean golden yellow , transparent with a ring of white foam .  the body of this beer was exceptional , thick , clean , and enjoyable .

smell : sweet roast , mild vanilla , dark fruit , cinnamon , and some warm bourbon .  rich gold appearance with a trace of a fluffy 1/8 of an inch head that lasts for a short time and laces practically not at all .  the one characteristic of this beer is its incredible silky smoothness on the tongue . the beer is moderately carbonated , medium bodied , and just wonderful on the tongue .

amazing nose . some definite funkiness from the brett and sour fruit , mixing with citrus . m - medium body and moderate carbonation , pretty nice . d - a very nice saison with brett . i thought the nose on it was amazing and it was very drinkable . would love to have again .  next to no head forms on the pour .  m- very creamy , milky texture .

the aroma is pretty soft and inoffensive . there 's a faint sourness and a more obvious wine-like aroma . as the beer warms an unpleasant vinegar aroma comes forth but it does not dominate .  not much of a head ; dirty white in color , and it fades fast .  palate is perfect , rich and chewy .

the aromas seem a bit subdued .  a yeast milkshake , but a good one . must have been getting down to the bottom of the keg , but still quite good . lots of citrus notes up front with citrus and perhaps a bit of cassis flavor ? very smooth , almost milky with the quantity of yeast in suspension .  the mouthfeel is superb : sticky and chewy but also very creamy , with fluffy carbonation .

s- citrus hops , and they are strong and awesome . getting some nice tropical fruits in there as well . fantastic . d- pretty good .  i am a fan of dry beers , and this is a good one . it is light and refreshing , just perfect for a hot australian afternoon . in this review i must provide this warning to all drinkers : setting this beer on the ground hard , bumping it against anything , or drinking improperly while the bottle is near full will cause it to erupt like a volcano , covering you , your furniture , pets , and loved ones with beer .  the body is surprisingly thick and coating with a rich slick mouth feel .

the smell on this beer is very complex . overall , it smells like an arts and crafts store around christmas time . absolutely fantastic . unfortunately the taste is not as great as the smell .  a : poured a dark black color , small head that dissipated very quickly , no lacing .  this beer is full bodied and velvety smooth . it is a little high in alcohol , but the smooth mouthfeel and nice flavor would go a long way .

appearance : pitch black with low head retention smell : hughmugus creamy caramel aroma . amazing ... roasted malt , subtle coffee/chocolate , taste : tastes liek it smells and reaslly does capture creme brulee .  pours a dark chestnut brown . not much head from this pour .  mouthfeel is great .

smells good ... real good . sweet chocolate , touch of roast , lactose and some definite oatmeal . one of the best smelling oatmeal stouts i have smelled , hits all the right notes . taste does not quite live up to the nose , but still a decent offering .  pours a dusky , golden-peach hue with a bit more yeast haziness than is appropriate for the style . plus , the minuscule egg-carton white head recedes quickly to a thin wisp and ring of foam ... not much lacing or retention .  mouthfeel is so silky .

s : huge , overpowering piny aroma with underlying citrus ( tangerine , nectarine , apricot ) . the hopping certainly boarders on a dipa . t : plenty of resiny pine , tangerine , nectarine , assertive bitterness , brown sugar and toffee . d : very drinkable for a brew of this size .  pours a hazy gold orange with almost no head . a little off color with it 's haze , but really not bad .  m- the mouthfeel is fantastic . full bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

pours a hazy golden color with maybe the best aroma of any beer i have had wild tart raspberries waffle batter , man it is right on with the aromas how did they do that ?  served in a foothills pint glass that is mine to keep a crystal clear copper orange with a thin head that diminishes to nothing .  medium carbonation and fairly full bodied ; with a huge creamy and slick mouthfeel , that drinks super smoothly for being over 11 % . big creamy and lush body ; with a very dessert-like flavor profile ; without being cloyingly sweet .

a-orange/amber ... leaves a nice lace on glass as i drink s-great aroma ... tons of toasted malts ... also some candied toffee ... i guess that is what toffee is : ) ... some caramel notes too ... very sweet aroma and a fresh hoppiness complements perfectly ... great smelling beer . t-where the nose is malt forward , the taste is more balanced ... some good hopping to this ... a citrus like grapefruit rind bitterness is evident..but it mingles nicely with the great malt backbone.. m-medium bodied ... .seems sessionable but still loaded with flavor .  redish two finger head that rapidly disappears and leaves no lacing .  palate- chocolate milk with some espresso , toffee and campari bitterness , a touch of winy acidity , and a very creamy mouthfeel .

great aroma , you get oak , wine , grape , some nice earthy leathery tones , a bit of funk . nice body . all i know is when i first had it on tap i sessioned it hard and loved it .  pours a dark golden yellow with flashes of red and green tint . a slight film for a head with slight lacing . there is a large malt presence with some orange , and peach in the nose .  damn this is one thick beer ; milkshake is about the best way to describe it .

s - amazing aroma of oak , wood and vanilla notes . o - this is a fabulous brew . outstanding aroma and flavor . really great beer .  pours a very slightly hazy light golden orange color with golden yellow hues and a one finger foamy white head with decent retention , only slowly fading into a lasting ring . minimal spots of lacing .  mouthfeel is fantastic , super thick and syrupy , perfect for the style .

s- very wonderful aroma here . very nice hop smells come from this .  a- half inch light brown head , weak head retention and no lacing . the beer is a dark caramel red color that is beautiful in the light .  love the mouthfeel . smooth and creamy through the swallow , with a very mild , slightly dry finish and pleasant aftertaste .

the aroma is awesome . a great mix of spices , mainly cinnamon and nutmeg . the actual scent of pumpkin plays only an ancillary role , but that 's fine given how appealing the overall aroma is . pumpkin comes through in the mid-palate , but it 's quite subtle . pretty remarkable that this is an 8 % abv beer . it 's maybe a touch too thin , but still pretty decadent given the sweetness and minimal carb .  i had this on tap and it poured a nice and copper with a decent thin head .  m. thick and heavy , strong and chewy , with plenty of carbonation .

the smell is intense . if you like hops , imagine a normal ipa and multiply that by ten . a potent warning to stay away if you ca n't handle it . excess , thy name is hop 15 . this beer is about hops . once again , insanely rich grapefruit , sweet caramel . this tastes like pine smells . mad citrusy with alcohol swimming around .  drank this on 5/28/09 . part of the excitement was the fact that i was even able to get this in california . a- opaque , spritzy , little to no head to speak of s-spicy , belgian-esque ... . the was a delicious beer that made me look forward to every sip .  mouthfeel is really silky , solid , and smooth in the carbonation .

smell : very malty with a bit of an earthy hop note.also , a strange ( as in unpleasent ) funk note .  12oz brown bottle , no freshness date or lot code to be found . decanted carefully to leave as much of the yeast behind as possible . still slightly cloudy , very well carbonated with tons of streamers rolling up from the bottom . small white head 's not really to style .  a nice , balanced beer with a clean taste and a smooth , exceptional mouthfeel .

aroma was dull and earthy . good enjoyable sweetness , not overpowering , really liked how the kg brought out the malt sweetness , but still need something in the hop department to make this beer truly one worth recommending to the average ipa fan out this way .  average sized soapy white head that fades quickly to a ring over a very clear ( initially ) , golden body with plenty of carbonation flowing up . with 2nd and 3rd pour , it got considerably more cloudy with the yeast coming into play .  taste : toast , caramel , white pepper , coffee bean , tons of malt , chocolate , banana , vanilla bean , ripe strawberry - the most flavor i 've gotten out of a brown ale mouthfeel : soft , calming mouthfeel with nice smooth tannins leaving the mouth coated with a slowly vanishing flavor profile that 's rather fun to dissect .

silky smooth mouthfeel , incredible floral/citrus hop aroma . taste = too much orange .  poured into a snifter at 45 degrees . appearance : a one finger head that is ivory , creamy , and frothy , with poor retention .  mouthfeel , exceptional , like champagne ... exactly , close your eyes its champagne .

s- smells nutty and rich , a really delicous smell . it is very deep and amazing , i could drink it again and again .  i remember the beer being a bit too much for me then thus the less than stellar review . taste : spiced banana , clove and wheat notes . i could really sit and drink this all day . slight wheat presence . ap : a clear light gold . the head disappeared quickly and there was hardly any lacing .  beautiful mouthfeel -- really does n't overpower as it fades to a nice hoppy finish .

served from the bottle into a nonic glass a- poured a very clear lighter amber color with a two finger soapy head s- huge aroma of cinnamon , ginger , citrus , and floral notes . this smells like christmas at home t- big on the cinnamon , ginger , citrus and honey notes , great balance among those flavors . a beer i look forward to every winter . very good out of the bottle , even better on tap .  street , now chuo park avenue , outside gate two kadena ab , okinawa . i really like this beer . this is a great hot weather beer and brings back great memories .  leaves very thick lacing , almost like a nitro s_toasted bread , caramel , not very strong t_burnt toast , chocolate coffee beans , no real aftertaste m_ultra-smooth and creamy , so mellow , balanced , very little carbonation .

the aroma is a of light herbal yeasts , with pleasant fruit notes . there is a definite musty , skunky undertone .  330ml brown bottle , best before sep 2012 , poured into a 'hoegaarden grand cu ' stemmed tulip . good reddy brown colour , head soon left leaving a tan coloured collar and a few pieces of lacing as the beer level fell .  mouthfeel is magnificent . again , like a thin syrup .

this is the most unusual and most pleasant smelling lager that i ever had the pleasure to inhale . i loved it . there are lots of flavors here for your tongue to enjoy . the best part is nothing over dominates .  a - dark brown with hints of ruby when held to the candle light . this one supports a head that is only a half of a finger before reducing quickly to a collar of flimsy tan foam .  the texture is creamy and silky .

smells great , black licorice and sweet molasses malt . a little pine coming through on the nose now too . flavors remain unbalanced and even a tad harsh on the front end .  the 1998 vintage of this beer pours with no head , just a slight flourish of carbonation and a slightly murky brown color .  m : perfect mouthfeel , light , crisp and very refreshing . excellent carbonation .

the nose is the most distinct pineapple aroma i 've ever got from a beer . ipas often give off vague fruity type aromas , but this one is very obviously pineapple to me . wow . bits of citrus and piney hops combine with the fruity pineapple to give this beer a robust , flavorful hop profile , backed by a nice sweet vanilla type malt bill .  pours dark orange with a head that is reminiscent of a b-movie .  mouthfeel is lush and satiny smooth as the beer effortlessly flows down . mellow carbonation adds to the ease of drinkability here .

smells absolutely fantastic . super-hop odor with sugary sweetness too .  short lived head and virtually no lacing .  m : for some reason , the mouthfeel is great ! perfect balance of body and drinkability .

the first smell brings pine , oranges , more citrus and puts a smile on my face .  pours a merky brown color with some lighter tan hues throughout . a off white colored head left good retention but limited lacing .  medium body with a wonderful rich texture that is soothing in the mouth . just enough carbonation to keep things lively .

smell : a smorgasboard of aromas starts attacking you from the moment you open the bottle . chocolate ( s ) , coffee , caramel , alcohol hitting on you with no mercy . fantastic ! i love it anyway .  well , the beer pours looking like an american wheat beer .  m- creamy , thick , and very rich on the palate .

) with other hop nuances and malt to balance it out , very nice . taste-spicy hop at the beginning and then balanced out by some caramel malt finish , huge hop hits on the end of the toungue , very nice .  dark brown body , nearly black . light tan head , pretty minimal , decent retention , small amount of lacing . ideally i 'd like a little more head , i even poured vigorously .  m : mouthfeel is perfect , rich and creamy .

the nose is brilliant .  ) taste : just too syrupy ... lambic was overpowered by the taste of del monte canned peaches in heavy syrup . lambic tastes come forward if you let it relax in your mouth for awhile . quite metallic . drinkability : would have been even easier to drink had it not been so sweet .  the mouthfeel fits this beauty of a beer - it is thick and pleasingly rich . the full amount of suggested aging did this beauty wonders .

the smell is off the hook ... piney hops that just are incredibly inviting . the taste is more subdued , with a mellow citrusy hoppiness that just begs for another sip .  had this beer out of a bottle poured into a pint glass ... a : nice dark amber color with a small white head that quickly dissipates ... s : nice malty smell to this one , some caramel notes and touch of sugar ... t : the taste is much better than expected , after having the original grolsch , but still not overwhelming .  the mouthfeel is full , warming and fabulous . flavor is full with lots of yummy esters holding hands with the sweetness and the fininsh is where i get the coriander .

a-full and wonderful piney , resiny hops full the nose with some faint malt in the background . nice lacing .  notes from 5/14/10 pours a hazy dark brown with a slight red hue . head and lacing are nearly non existant .  palate : a perfect 5 overall : rather murphy's-esque .

aroma is definitely the highlight of this one , loaded with piney hops . pretty one sided , but a nicely done , highly addictive smell . taste is bitter pine with a light malt presence to back it up .  hazy and deep tangerine hued with a small off white head . not big on head retention or lacing . scores : appearance 3/5 , aroma 4/5 , taste 4/5 , mouthfeel 4.5/5 , overall 4.5/5  really fantastic mouthfeel - silky and full on the tongue .

really wonderfully complex . body is medium with a velvety smoothness and a lively carbonation .  poured into a sam adams imperial tulip glass ... 2010 d bottle . a- pours pitch black ... 1 1/2 finger fizzy tan head that disappears quickly and leaves no lacing ( kinda like cola ) . not much to look at and admire . other than the fact that it 's nothing special to look at ... it sure is something fantastic to smell , sip , talk about , and appriciate !  mouthfeel is perfect for a porter , chewable but not too much , this is a meal in a bottle .

nice aroma . such a unique smell . constant honey with lots of cinnamon and ginger in there too . all in all , a unique , above-average winter seasonal with a great smell , cinnanninnanim .  poured into a chimay glass appearance : 1 inch head that goes quick , cloudy , red/brown in color , high carbonation smell : grape , dark fruit , bread , and a touch of apple taste : dark fruit , apple , belgian spices , and bread mouthfeel : semi-sweet and tart , high carbonation , light bodied .  awesome thickness , yet not throat-closing thickness -- more like smooth milkshake thickness , where carbonation does n't feel like bubbles , but simply a collective , chilled push down the throat .
wow . just wow .  pours a very cloudy golden orange . one finger of fine bubbles shows decent retention and leaves some patchy lacing .  m : pretty much perfect for me .

s - hops , hops , hops , citrus , grapefruit , sweet orange , and a hint of pine . some slight caramel sweetness might be coming through , though that could just be the vast amount of hops playing tricks on me . malt is well balanced . sweet caramel malts balance out the bitter middle .  pours an orange amber with a slight head . the lacing and head retention are minimal .  excellent body that just coats your mouth .

it started as sugary sweet , candied apples , a pleasant musty characteristic , and some spicy black pepper in the background .  well , as did evel , let 's give it a whirl . the brew pours to a yellow bronze with a nice creamy head .  mouthfeel/drinkability- just when i thought the perfect mouthfeel of a belgian ale was locked up with tripel karmeliet , this beer dazzles with a sublime , gentle texture that lasts throughout the entire duration in the mouth . absolute perfection , it further emphasizes the already impressive quality of the beer .

s : very chocolatey , pleasant nut , cotton-candy esters , dark caramel , herbs & a hint of citrus . d : very good , but a little big to session .  pours a deep gold with a pretty small head .  indulgent , creamy mouthfeel . and i really ca n't get over how pleasurable the mouthfeel is .

aroma is my favorite part of this beer ; rich bourbon , vanilla , oak , cookie dough , etc . balance and subtlety of the aroma is remarkable . flavor is complex balance of chocolate , vanilla , oak , bourbon , and mild dark fruit . blending of the fresh stout with the barrel aged component takes most of the sharpness off the finish . otherwise this is an incredible stout from green flash .  the pour produced a nice 1 finger head of tan colored foam that was relatively short lived . there was little to no lacing evident . the color was medium mahogany , and the clarity was slightly turbid .  tastes much like it smells and goes down really well with a creamy texture and some lively carbonation playing with your tounge .

light and sweet smelling . taste : lots of lemon like on the nose . tart and sweet . definite kudos to the smell over the taste .  a : deep dark brown to black in color . no head but a sparce line of bubbles barely formed a ring around my glass . no lacing .  mouthfeel is also top notch . low carbonation that goes down very smooth .

smell is just exceptional . a sweet juicy hop aroma fills the air above the glass .  appearance : a hard pour into a pint glass ( where 'd my pils glass go ? ) reveals a thick head which quickly dies down to nothing . no lacing on side of glass either . slightly hazy lemony yellow color .  near perfect carbonation and body .

pours a clear yellow pils color , great big chunky white head at first , but it goes down and there is n't much lacing to speak of smell is pretty interesting , grass , flowers , tons of belgian yeasts , dust , some slight lambic smells actually not sure if that is brett or not , i think the flower may be elderflower as it smells similar to the cantillon mamouche , some lemons also , it smells awesome taste is a slight letdown from the smell , i was expecting some bold flavors but it is quite subtle .  this beer poured a deep cloudy amber color with absolutely no head to speak of .  mf - this it where this beer shines the most to me . very nice carbonation that tickles your mouth as you savor it . also reminds me in some ways of an eisbock albeit less vinuous and more carbonated and roasty .

this is one of the nicest smelling glasses of beers i 've ever had the good fortune to stick my nose into . sweet caramel , dark fruit , some bready yeasty goodness .  served from a bottle 3 months before best enjoyed date . ok appearance , orangish color with yeast present from bottle conditioning . very drinkable , this is a great beer .  thanks to ba greggy for this one . the beer is very thick and smooth . not overpowering but just the right feel . the only thing that i have a problem with is the fact that this beer is so thick and rich , there is no way i would be able to drink more than 2 of these in one sitting .

very pleasing , very playful like a baby pig with wings ... good persistence of aroma .  appearance : pours an almost clear amber color with a small layer of off white head that goes away completely .  mouthfeel is perfection , smooth , crisp , with just the right amount of carbonation ... and the tartness in the finish leaves you wanting to pour more of that big bottle .

the nose is stunning , with milk chocolate , brown sugar , hazelnuts and lots of brandy ( in case there was any doubt as to what i was drinking ) . still , that 's really just nit picking ... . very impressive and quite different from the bourbon barrel version . excellent stuff .  ibu 's 16.0 tawny red-amber with minimal head . mouthfeel is sticky , round , lip-smackingly full .  m - this is what really sets this beer apart for me . incredibly creamy and thick mouth feel .

aroma is amazing ( it was perfect when it started but as the beer warmed it fell off , still giving it a 5 ) . it is so hoppy , piny and wonderful overall . no harshness , the level is strong but not overpowering . its great . beer is medium to light in a body with a creamy mouthfeel .  a - deeper than cola , capped with a wispy tan head and leaving small streaks of lace .  m : i have to say that this was the most impressive aspect of this beer . oftentimes porters end up a little too thin-bodied , but this one had a very full body , and combined with the very nice carbonation made this a pleasure to drink .

absolutely beautiful aroma that reminds me of the finer czech pilsners , not that that is surprising . in short , a superb smell . the taste is harshly bitter with almost a hot pepper bite .  bottle at 42* into a franziskaner weizen glass . a : this pours a bright golden color with a half-finger of fizzy white head that dissapates quickly .  mouthfeel is excellent , coating and thick with well-done low carbonation .

on tap in a pint glass at the draught house in austin a : dark dark dark black ... resembles strong coffee - thick creamy coke float colored head disappears but really sticks and laces the glass all the way down s : coffee pecan chocolate malt ; strong complex coffee smell is one of the best features of this beer - the nose is very rich and complex t : the taste of roasted pecan ( that flavor is almost not recognizable/identifiable at first ) starts and lingers til the finish - coffee - dark chocolate and earthy wood smokey and somewhat spicy ( like bbq ? ) a lingering secondary malty sourness m : instant tingle of carbonation followed by medium bodied creamy-ness and warm resonance on outside of tougue - really spunky and sparky carbonation while maintaining the porter style d : the flavors and feels make you want to savor - that may slow you down but it drinks very easy - but as i probably could n't drink 4 cups of coffee in a row i probably could n't drink more than two in a row the roasted pecan start and finish in nose and taste is a bit fuller more discernible and pleasing when warmer surprisingly well done and complex for small local brewery  it 's non existent . i do n't really care for wine but this smells great ! tast is very similar to red wine , though far more sweet .  the beer didnt quite taste as good as it looked , but it was still quite pleasently sweet and i highly enjoyed the creamy mouthfeel it had .

s : the most delicious hops aromas that i 've smelled to date are pouring from this brew . this is balanced nicely with a sweet candy/bubblegum aroma and hints of citrus and alcohol . the taste is better than many beers , however , i felt let down after the great aromas . m : full bodied with just the right amount of carbonation .  appearance : dark amber/caramel in color -- no head , minimal carbonation smell : raisin , cinnamon , alcohol , and sugar taste : raisin , cinnamon , caramel , alcohol-especially towards the end , and sugar mouthfeel : medium body , smooth and sweet , then a harder alcohol tasting finish drinkability : this is a another unique tasting beer that needs to be drunk slow because of its high alcohol content .  mouthfeel was perfect for me ... .slightly tingly , but at the same time silky smooth and gentle on the palate .

this is the best smelling beer i have ever had , ever in my life . it smells like fresh brownies just pulled from the oven , so good ! soon though the carbonation naturally dies down and it 's a very pleasant taste , quite sweet though not too much .  2003 version , bottle no 08746 , 250ml bottle into my rochefort glass . the beer is a medium , watery , muddy unattractive brown with no carbonation , not that any was expected on a 7 year old ale ... the aroma is strong and very nice , caramel and figs jump at me right away . overall just very sweet ... even after 7 years this is pretty alcoholic , ca n't imagine what it would taste like new . lots of brown sugar and prunes in this . pretty good , oddly reminescant of a stronger , alcoholic , and watery trappist quad ... the feel is too light and watery for me without must lasting flavor , a slight warm finish ... fairly easy to drink for 12 % . overall , this was pretty good for an old ale , a little strong right now , even after 7 years .  m - very full bodied , nearly stout full .

s - wow -- fantastic aroma . a sweet , malty scent with fresh fruit characteristics . a definite oaky scent here . t - when that oaky scent turns into a flavor it makes a beautifully round beer .  a - just under one finger of dirty white foam , with a tinge of pink appears on top of the slightly hazy , reddish brown body . it settles quickly to a thin film with a few fish eye bubbles .  high carbonation . probably the silkiest body in a dipa i 've ever encountered .

enticing aroma . probably the best aroma of any beer i have ever smelled before . vibrant fruit notes ; apple , pear , berries and cherries along with a maltiness of cookies and caramel .  a - pours a beautiful golden copper , hazy thanks to the unfiltered status of the beer . unfortunately , the 1-finger head vanished without much of a trace , leaving a small collection at the top of the beer to remind you of what once was . no lacing ... s - surprisingly sweet at the first sniff , with a bitter , hop kick backing it up .  m : i love the low carbonation as it works really well here .

sweet citrus , fresh sliced oranges and tangerines hit the nose in the initial blast . later on it becomes more `` green '' and herbal , still extremely resiny and pungent . best belgian ipa i 've ever smelled ... though this one has a decidedly american slant .  clear copper with thin head and little lacing .  the body is light , clouded amber with a perfect fluffy mouthfeel delivering high quaff quotient .
smell was yeasty , sweet and fairly mild .  a decent american wheat beer .  the mouthfeel is perfect for a stout .

there 's also almost a medicinal smell to it . by far one of the best smelling beers i think i 've come across . i had random smell flashbacks over the next few days ... t : just like the smell , dark candied fruits really dominate .  bbxxii arrived to our table in a pair of deschutes snifters ( i 'm going to have to purchase a couple of those one of these days ) with a thin wispy froth ring atop its dark brown body with cola tan edges . no lacing showed up throughout the drink . taste showed off the strong ghana semi-sweet chocolate ( with an emphasis on the sweet ) that kept the beer from being bottled . it 's a shame this was n't bottled due to the visual appearance .  the mouthfeel is exceptional -- thick , chewy , syrupy , andincredibly smooth .

smell is amazing ! wheaty graininess , bready , malty , with a hint of coriander spice , and some lactic tartness . it smells like a wit should .  and for that matter , where is the damn carbonation ? not even close . bright orange with obviously no lacing .  smooth creamy mouthfeel , it 's a satisfying brew for my palate . very good stuff .

the nose on this brew is outstanding , strong hop pressence with a little bit of citus , and if your looking for it malt .  i am sure that since i got it 5 months after it 's release the hops are muted , a. amber brew with some chill haze and a 1 finger head . some lacing and moderate bubbles .  mouth is silky smooth with a full body a great carbonation , did n't go flat like alot of darker brews have .

pours pale yellow , smells like stagnant water , feels somewhat sticky in the mouth , and it is difficult to swallow .  a - very flat and unimpressive . nice deep brown color . not too much head to speak of . no lacing either .  it 's pretty full bodied and very smooth with a clean , dry finish .

smell - 5.0 powerful and very , very nice . smells of liquor soaked figs , overripe plums , aged port , damp wood and burnt sugar .  it pours a crystal-clear amber , with a thick finger of noisy , tan head that reduces to a thin cap and leaves little lacing .  mouthfeel is very rich , smooth carbonation .

solventy alcohol and toffee are all i really pick up in the aroma . it 's odd that i ca n't pick up the coriander in the aroma , because it 's actually quite prominent in jacobites flavour .  the bottle was transported just prior to consumption but the haze is certainly not all yeast . a very slow pour results in a huge rocky head . about as much head as liquid . taste and mouthfeel are good and great , but the hazy appearance needs work .  creamy , smooth mouthfeel goes excellent with the flavor profile .

it starts off mellow , but bites when you swallow , and leaves a seriously skunky aftertaste . the weak smell hides the underlying acrid taste . its one of those tolerable beers when ice cold , but overall its mediocre at best  poured into a tulip on 6/27/10 dark , almost murky brown though held to the light it has a coppery crimson hue . very thin layer of foam ; no retention halfway through the glass .  light to medium in body , with significant carbonation , and an amazing palate to mingle with the generous abv make the mouthfeel very impressive . one of my favorite styles , and certainly one of my favorites amongst it .

boring . smell : excellent ! you can smell toasted carmel sugar . it goes well with the smell . however i believe it 's missing something . something very small but important . winter ales need the full package . overall ... buy some ! it 's worth it .  1/6 inch head of an off-white color . poor retention and poor lacing .  m : incredible mouthfeel .

aroma is huge coffee with some vodka and vanilla , overall very strong and wonderful . flavor is again coffee , alcohol , and vanilla .  this brown ale pours a nice dark amber color . very clear .  mouthfeel is phenomenal , like liquid velvet down the throat , and with a good bit of carbonation to tingle the tongue .

really a wonderful smelling beer . really fantastic . nice , big fruity nose . very mellow flavors , but very nice .  i love trix and i really enjoy this beer . i have poured it in a glass and there is nothing unique about it 's appearance .  i do n't find much to be said really , excellent balance , medium body shows a perfect carbonation to my liking , quite creamy lager , pretty crisp dry herbal hops finish .

the nose had a lot going on , big juicy orange fruit and dried apricots . you could also pick up the big caramel and buttescotch scent . the finish had a nice hint of vannila and soft caramel .  poured much clearer and with less head than i expected . got ta love the bottle .  taste the weizen gives way to the bock as it warms mf : medim/heavy bodied with low carbonation & nicely balanced drinks very easy for the abv , a really nice weizen bock .

s : one of the best ipa aromas around with tropical fruit hoppiness of mango , pineapple , and passionfruit , coupled with pine resin and floral notes . pale malt with a little medium crystal sneaks in there to provide a little resistance to hop deluge .  a : standard pour produces a .5 finger foamy white head with poor retention .  m : the feel is super creamy which makes it near full bodied . this is the biggest difference between this bottled version and the on-tap version i had last year . the mouthfeel was a huge step up .

the aroma is exceptional , and the bourbon notes are packed with vanilla , dark fruits ( raisin , fig , orange peel ) , and a touch of chocolate . i would have liked there to be a touch more chocolate n this one , too , but its still a fantastic beer . in my book schlafly is 2-for-2 with big , bourbon-aged beers , as their barleywine reserve was equally as impressive .  a : muddy reddish-brown body with a half in chi of coarse tan foam . ok , but uninspiring .  mouth feel is absolutely fantastic with light carbonation and small bubbles .

the smell is a lovely , earthy hop breath with pine and citrus close behind . there is some malty sweetness that creeps in as you inhale , along with leafiness .  poured from the bottle into a pint glass , beer is a deep amber color with an almost non-existant head .  m - smooth , a delicate sudsing that tickles the palatte , and quite refreshing with a subtle warming effect from the alcohol .

very complex hop aroma . there 's fresh citrus , honey and marmalade . overall , an engaging ipa i 'll probably return if i do n't get around to an attempt a brewing a clone .  pours from the bottle a thin , nearly opaque black with almost no head .  very nice dry finish . overall super smooth and super crisp mouthfeel .

this really released the great smells with this beer . the nose is spicy greatness .  a : poured with a nearly black color , like light is getting sucked into it . no head , barely any lacing .  very nice mouthfeel .

smell is heavenly . a veritable bouquet of every smell that makes a dipa good . grapefruit , tangerine , pine , grass , flowers , you name it its in here somewhere .  pours somewhat hazy reddish brown with a small light beige head that quickly recedes .  smooth and full mouthfeel .

s - this beer smells amazing . if you enjoy the smell of smoke and/or smoked things you will find this aroma exciting . t - the smokiness is most prominant , with some swet maltiness underlying .  poured a red copper color , with no head , but had a potent hoppy aroma .  creamy , oily , perfect weight .

smell is slight skunk and earthy , not a lot here .  pours a ruby color with a moderate head that falls fast and does n't leave too much lacing on the glass . the color seems wrong on this one .  simpler flavor and wonderful mouthfeel enhance the drinkability ; but it is slightly boring .

s : perfect ! candy-sugared-bananas-and-pink-bubblegum-yumminess ! very nice .  a : i poured a bit into a cup and it poured an interesting light shade of orange .  m- full bodied , creamy , thick luscious mouthfeel .

) s : rosy , hoppy , and luscious t : very sharp , bitter hoppiness ; this is a very complex imperial amber ; streaked through with sweet grapefruit ; alcohol and hop content gives the power of a dipa . a very inviting beer , very powerful .  was not disappointed in anything but the colour , which looks like standard american macro stuff .  mouthfeel is highly pleasurable , with perfectly gauged carbonation .

a very nice pumpkin aroma with many spices to smell . overall a pretty good seasonal worth trying . it took me a beer to get used to the taste but after that its pretty good .  hopefully the `` authorities '' in new york pull their heads out of their asses and worry about more important issues . appearance : very little to no carbonation . in and of itself not a a big deal . less hops shine through as well than `` lump ... '' . this is one of those beers where understated flavors blend well to form an easy drinking beer with enough flavor to keep things interesting . plain , yet glorious in its understated beauty .  mouthfeel : medium to full bodied and incredibly smooth . just a hint of carbonation tingle .

then there is the smell -- noble hop heaven . layer upon layer of delicious hops . the taste is similar to the smell : a lot of hops .  into a pint glass , it poured a cloudy maple brown with one finger of beige head , average retention , and decent lacing .  mouthfeel is about the creamiest i 've ever had a beer feel . drinkability is great too .

wonderful rich coffee nose . cocoa , campfire and sweet cream/milk chocolate . outstanding .  disappointed head formation , just a few bubbles on top . light copper colored body , nice and clear , not much carbonation coming to the surface .  the mouthfeel was the best part of this beer .

the smell is divine . i hope it tastes just like that . very nice . coffee up front , but not overwhelming everything else , a solid amount of hershey 's kiss in there ( the dark chocolate ones , ha ! ) , then the roasted malts come roaring in like a posse of fbi agents in a bad climax to an episode of miami vice .  live review 12oz bottle poured into delirium tremens tulip a-murky brown with almost soda like tan head that dissipated rather quickly into a thin ring .  a great , thick mouthfeel makes this beer very satisfying and drinkable .

it 's not that the style itself is hardup , but rather if chimay did an ipa , it would be this . nose - great nose . hints of vanilla and almond once you get past the hops . good belgian nose , you know what you 're getting into .  on tap at bob 's into a pint glass ... pours a light brownish red , pretty clear on the edges , a light off white head that has ok retention , not much lacing ... light aroma mostly malty caramel , bitter citrus fruits and only a hint of rye , which is good in my book ... taste is decent , a pretty hoppy rye with a malty backbone .  mouthfeel is full and round .

t - taste is a bit of a letdown , although it 's still quite good . more buttery oak and pale stone fruit malt character . d - this is really quite excellent . tons of flavor for the lower abv , pleasant texture , and a superb aroma . another quality hill farmstead offering and one i 'd love to have again .  growler of rompo pours a dark orange with a small 1-finger off-tan head . reduces quickly leaving a minimal ring of lace .  on the palate , this beer is very much alive still with plenty of carbonation , a full body , and a super-long finish . the alcohol is almost non-existent on the palate , leading to a very balanced and easy-drinking ( although fairly heavy ) beer .

the nose is quite fantastic , rich and complex . brown sugar , vanilla , vinegar , oak . very complex . cherry skins , ripe berries and a buttery chardonnay character that reminds me of depuration , this beer is mildly funky . pretty insanely drinkable , this !  appearance : no head retention , dark amber colour , not really pale looking at all smell : delicate flowery hopps , very inviting taste : immediate strong bitter taste which eases off after a few seconds , and then the malt begins to show itself .  m : full bodied with an awesome carbonation feel .

the aroma was intense . quite sweet overall . chocolate notes dominated . a nice mix of dark chocolate and powdered cocoa . somewhat bourbony and boozy . the lingering finish was very roasty and hoppy , with the hops being leafy , piney and sharp . overall , the beer was rather pithy , dry and bitter on the back end . the mouthfeel was creamy and smooth yet noticeably thin for the style .  appearance : pouring this yields a fairly typical looking beer , reminiscent of an unfiltered wheat or hefe . color is orangish .  creamy mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is very creamy and chewy .

pineapple , mango , wheat , yeast , flowers , toasted grains , very sweet smelling , lots of resin , alcohol is n't very high but you can smell it t - the taste is a more pungent form of the smell . there is a toastedness at the end as well m - sticky , coats the mouth in sweet , bitter fruit flowers that last for a while , so does the resin d - for being 8 % it 's pretty nice and balanced . there is tons of hops and tons of malt . despite that , it is still very balanced final thought - $ 9.49 is way to much . but it is excellent !  a-pours a cedar tinted amber . forms 3 mm head that disappears in seconds . no lace on glass .  mouthfeel was excellent . very slick and smooth , almost oily in fact , with a medium/thick body .

been waiting awhile to make a first review : poured into an oversized wine glass ( winter 09-10 bottling ) a : dark brown with 1/4 inch coffee coloured head which stuck to side of glass and only dissapeared about halfway through drinking so far great s : chocolate , coffee and burnt nuts , i love the smell of russian imperials and this one is no exception t : strong coffee taste with a rich chocolate aftertaste , no over sweetness in begginning , nor any substantial bitterness in the end m : a bit to bubbly for my mouth , i prefer more flat versions of this stout d : at 10 % alc , it is definately noticeable , but served at around room temp its very drinkable , at the usual half hour per bottle pace i consume a r.i.s.. however i 've found dogfish head 's world wide stout at a higher abv much more drinkable , albeit harder to come by as a canuck .  pours a slightly cloudy yellow with white head that fades completely .  incredibly smooth and creamy in the mouth .

rich notes of floral hops , bready , caramel malts , brown sugar , tropical fruits , and a buttery alcohol note . amazingly complex and intoxicating , and i have n't even taken a sip ! the body is gooey and thick , with an invigorating alcohol bite to the finish that pairs with a lingering bitter hop note .  pours a deep , deep dark brown .  creamy , almost soupy mouthfeel .

very nutty aroma with some surprising chocolate smells . t : caramel malts with some surfacing hops that balance the sweetness nicely . o : very good , i only had a single 19 oz .  slow pour into a chalice yields a one-finger tan head over a dark brown almost opaque body .  but the nose is fantastic-and the mouthfeel is exceptional . another great brew overall by ccb .

poured into my duvel tulip ... well , as i open this one , i do n't hear a pop , fizz or anything ... uh-oh ... pours a dead black , thick looking ... like used motor oil.. with no head or carbonation at all ... absolutely zilch ... hmm.. hope this is ok ... this may be the loveliest aroma on a brew that i 've ever experienced ... loaded with rich chocolatey malts and coffee and vanilla , this smells world class to me ... maybe this will be ok ... well , i was right , there is no carbonation at all here and you can tell ... this could be ridiculous but you can tell its pretty much flat ... what i do get are some tasty chocolatey malts and coffee and sort of give you an idea of what this could be ... i did n't totally discount the brew but i could n't give it the high scores that it might deserve either ... this is probably the only bottling they will ever do on this so its unlikely i will ever try this again and that 's a shame.. i 'd love to have another shot at this ...  poured an orange amber with a white head that barely lasted .  mouthfeel is very good and creamy with good carbonation levels .

aroma is wonderful , bakers chocolate , roasted malts , pretty darn strong , semi-sweet , deep , dark , burnt cookies or brownies , milk chocolate , chocolate milk , all coming across with a super nice dryness . one hell of an excellent porter .  a : dark murky medium to dark brown body with absolutely no head on it . even with some vigorous swirls i could n't get any head to form . naturally , no lace or retention either .  mouthfeel is big and full , very smooth and satisfying .

wow , this has a really nice and pungent aroma ... funky , earthy hops and a burst of fruity citrus in the form of sweet tangerine/nectarine . love it . distinctly sweet tangerine/nectarine notes , underlying resiny hop bitterness and supporting citrus notes . had to have two in a row , definitely unique and drinkable .  pitch black body with zilch head .  notes : well structured , perfect mouth feel with a german like pilsner flare .

i smell the grape , but i do n't taste much of it . the aroma is really weak , but there 's a balance of what appears to be light crystal malts and grape .  12 oz bottle poured into a wine glass . a : orangy-amber in color , typical of an ipa . almost identical to the 90 min .  big , smooth , and slick . this is a particularly rich baltic porter . very dark , dense , and well crafted .

s - lemon , orange , coriander ... pretty standard wit smells . it 's a very very highly dominated by lemon type wit .  brown like you would expect , with no head .  mouthfeel is superb , very rich and creamy , gently coating the palate and then closes with a clean , dry finish .

smell & gt ; yeast , orange , cinnamon , white pepper ( seriously.. it 's strong enough that i guessed it and noted the scent with a few questionmarks beside it in my notebook ... , and then read it later on the menu ... no cheating for this lass ) taste & gt ; sweet , wheat , hops , spice . refreshing . peppery hang with perfume notes . nice even . not my bag , but very drinkable .  a - pitch black . dull .  texture is silky smooth and it does n't feel nearly as strong as it actually is .
fantastic . t - big and flavorful .  pale copper in color with low clarity .  massive body , and silky smooth . fruity , creamy , wine-y , and then comes a stiff roast/coffee crack of the whip .

wonderful aromatics ! overall impression : a wonderful holiday tradition .  appearance : hazy golden brown . the beer had a very active head , intense carbonation that disappeared about 3/4ths the way through the beer . a small ring persisted , but did not lace the glass . some citric flavors come through as well , as the beer warmed , i noted an orange taste that was pleasing .  mouthfeel was incredibly creamy .
wow ! ! ! nice . on second sip the honey really is apparant , very nice .  a : amber with a thin eggshell head .  mf is creamy , and quite nice .

smells of creamy grapefruit citrus . delicious ! yeah , citrus creme reigns supreme on the nose .  draught @ ctriver brewers fest : this one poured a fairly clear , orangish-golden color . there was a small white head to it .  it possesses the best mouthfeel i 've yet to come across , rich and velvety , it just rolls over the palate and tongue , and goes down incredibly smooth .

almost no nose at all ; just hints of wheat and a light honey sweetness .  the beer pours dark red/brown/black , depending on how it is held to the light . the only signs of head is the slight ring around the edge .  the mouthfeel is where this beer really , really shines .

very inviting . flavors were mostly sweet , with fresh-from-the-vine honey crisp apples , nutmeg , cinnamon , and a touch of marachino cherry juice . solid on the drinkability meter for a 9 % beer - good combo of aromas and flavors , but the aromas were the real winner here .  standard golden yellow with a frothy white head .  it marries hops with malt in a beautiful way and the mouthfeel is pleasantly grainy . it 's mouthfeel is flat-out perfect and it 's taste is wonderful .

s : lovely perfume-like odor .  appearance : hazy amber with a sticky white lacy .  could be banana..pretty complex smell for me to pick out everything present.. t -- belgian yeast shines through beautifully ... fruity and extery with just very small hints of hops to balance this one out very nicely ... as with the smell the amount of tastes here i just can not begin to describe yet ... i will have to re-review again when i train my palate more m -- very smooth and bubbly ... fills your mouth and coats your tounge with taste ... but it is not a sticky coating ... just a full bodied taste.. d -- i could drink a few of these but would eventually have to switch styles to something very bitter since the belgian styles arent my favorite ... but i enjoy having a few due to the complexity of the flavors and they arent usually as strong so i can have a few in a row ... very tasty i will grab a 4 pack next time im out..

aroma was a beautiful array of fruits , just the right amount of sweet caramel , and floral hints for good measure .  5.2 % abv a basic : light yellow body with minimal head . no frills look really .  t - bananas , caramel , and mild dates swim around sour-yeastiness and vanilla , concealing well the alcohol that lies beneath ... m - very , very smooth , medium body massages the palate and dries the cheeks . d - nice , very nice , do n't know if i 'd get it again , but very nice .

the smell is awesome . very complex without being overwhelming .  late may smutty vs. berkshire maibock battle translucent golden orange color . thin dense head that was pooped by half glass .  mouth : first thing to comment on is the tiny carbonation that tickles when it enters and , as it moves through the mouth and warms , becomes creamy and chewy . excellent mouthfeel !

very rustic labeling , i like it . the smell is unique . it has a ton of citrus an coriander , it almost smells like a wild witbier .  dark mahogany brown bodied , very small tan head takes off quickly .  the lack of carbonation really helps the mouthfeel of this .

nose is sweet with orange peels , cloves , coriander , a real mlange of flavors and aromas , start is sweet and the grain profile delightful , top is light in its feel to the palate .  poured into a chalice it forms an easily managed healthy head that leaves minimal lace . solid brown body with some amber highlights on the outer edges .  the mouthfeel is the best part . lush , creamy , and thick despite the deceiving pale colored body .

very artificial smelling and tasting beer . the aroma in particular is just repulsive ... .  sampled on 3-28-10 pours a very clear golden yellow color , with bubbles rising to the top . a filmy white head hangs around the whole time .  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is outstanding . medium bodied , with just the right amount of fine carbonation .

if i were to mention smoked salmon , mocha , and fruit cake to someone , they would probably say yuck , but it really works in this beer . the mouthfeel is big and creamy , very good . the drinkability is pretty good as the alcohol content is n't too strong .  a - nice black color , dark tan head . reddish see through color at the edges . not quite dark enough imo but its only the look s - vanilla , boubon , soft oak , ahhhh ... t - vanilla , bourbon , soft oak , sweet malts .  taste is very smooth with a great mouthfeel .

thanks to the crew at drakes for makin a hoppy beer i could enjoy and drive home after 4 of them . lots of citra hops in the aroma which sets you up for an ipa but surprise this great tastin beer is under 4 % really great session beer , if you like west coast ipa's try this one , just dont expect finishing kick .  pours a faint yellow , with very little head , and absolutely no lacing .  m - carbonation cleans the palate nicely , the tartness and funk does n't linger long . the carbonation is just spot on , love it .

bananas , cardimon , cinamon , dry ripened plums , maybe some cherries . an outstanding beer . nice lacing down the tulip .  upon opening the bottle i noticed a rather clear appearance , but the smell was heavenly . it was not pungent like a bud light or something along those lines , but light , and with a pleasant strawberry aroma . while i imagine pure drinkers might be ashamed to have this in their hand , i really recommend forgetting your pride for a minute and giving this amazing brew a shot .  mouthfeel is the best part about the rasputin - just the right amount of chewiness and the malt and alcohol linger heavily on the sides of your tongue .

t - much like the smell ; flavors of milk chocolate , cream , bread , and a touch of dark roast somewhere in there ; no detectable hops at all ; lactose all the way through leaving a very pleasant , mild aftertaste - when i breathe out through my nose after drinking i can smell the same , lovely aroma that comes out of the glass m - super smooth and creamy texture ; medium body with light carbonation d - extremely drinkable milk stout ; smooth and creamy throughout ; i like this better than duck rabbit or terrapin 's milk stout  poured with a nice , tight , small , off white head that quickly subsided and no lace .  lingers long and leavs a soothing feeling on the palate .

but the aroma was fantastically delicious . how in the world do they think these things up .  just released , batch 2.. brown fancy label . 750ml cloudy yellow with a heart of orange haze . lumpy bubble crust thin atop this brew.. not much to look at , really .  mouthfeel- silky smooth with a creamy feel as well .

s : wow , there 's so much going on here it literally made my mouth water when it got to my nose . butterscotch , vanilla , milk chocolate , caramel , brown sugar , sweet malt , toffee . t : a lot like the nose , only the alcohol hinders the intensity a bit and mellows the flavor profile into a smooth transitions and the overall taste sensation of a chocolate-y boozy , malted creme brulee . o : this beer is good , but i would n't call it great . i 'll defiantly be buying it again but not in bulk .  33 cl bottle pours a slightly murky chestnut mahogany body with very little head and no lace to speak of .  creamy medium-full body with soft carbonation .

s - really , really nice aroma . huge dark fruit aromas that present themselves sort of like booze soaked dates or raisins . almost like a barley wine , great . t - yeast shows up alot more here with some more of the spice . just wish it 'd live up to that aroma . a decent ale from leffe though .  a - cloudy light brown/red hue with minimal head and no lacing . carbonation looks good .  mf : masterfully fizzy but light and balanced .
sweet hoppy aroma with malt accents .  the beer poured a dark reddish color with very little head .  the mouthfeel is incredible on this beer .

very nice impression to begin . very good . g ; eat offering from dark horse brewing  poured from a 12oz glass into a clean pint glass . it poured clear and copper hued with only an 1/8th of an inch of head that quickly shrank away leaving a slight lacing across the top of the beverage and ringing the glass .  great mouthfeel , full bitterness balanced with light maltiness .

nelson is west coast ipa incarnate , and i 'm just talking about the aroma : fresh pine needles and citrus rind pair up to wallop the nostrils something fierce . with the freshness of a dryer sheet and the hops sizzling off this thing in waves , there 's nothing not to like about the aroma here . there 's a spiciness to the flavor that points to the rye used ; it 's an earthy and very bright graininess , electrified by the nelson sauvin hops that give it even more vividness . bitter , vinous , earthy , bright , spicy and fruity , all in equal measure .  a : pours a cloudy yellow to white color with a nice white creamy head which does not disappears totally and leaves many lacings in the glass s : smell is a must !  this is a big bodied , chewy brew with medium carbonation , and a full palate .

a - pours a murky rust color with just a bit of foam that left a layer of small bubbles on the surface s - not alot of aroma , just hints of light sweet malt t - malty backbone with fruit hints , there is a bit of a funkiness to it that rounds out this one m/d - alot lighter than i was expecting , nice flavor and mouthfeel , but nothing too overpowering .  750 ml bottle , a : pours a cloudy light yellow , with a fairly dissapointing head , not really much to look at compared to other wits .  creamy , full bodied feel to it . really outstanding .

aroma of hops , spice , coriander , lemon , and some grapefruit . although for being a wheat beer this is somewhat of the mark but for an interpretation this is excellent . citrus overtones , with few hints of bread . overall this is great .  king henry pours a clear , almost pitch black dark amber . head is just a wisp of off-white that dissipates quickly . decent for the style .  the mouthfeel is delightful . up front the beer is very rich and the oak really shines through with this age on it . nicely mouth coating , and the intense finish with a great deal of carbonation and bitterness refreshes the palate for another sip . love this beer , 2010 and 2011 review to be added another day .

s - awesome . delicate balance of dark fruit .  took a growler of this home from john harvard 's in pittsburgh . a : pale golden in color , very clear . seems a pretty solid pils .  mouthfeel is terrific . great , rich , creaminess . completely coats your mouth .

i love the nose on this beer ... huge milk chocolate aroma with strongs notes of vanilla too ... great nose ! ! pours a deep , drak brown with a lot of black in it ... tan little head ... mouthfeel is creamy ... i would n't call it thin , but it is not full-bodied ... call it the lighter side of medium ... feels good in the mouth though ... no problems ... .taste is heavy on the milk chocolate ... .i also get some of the vanilla but that is actually stronger on the nose ... hopping is low , but that 's fine with me ... .drinkability is good and bad ... i love drinking this right now but maybe a bit too rich on the sweetness for more than a couple.. overall ... i think this would be a great desert beer with brownies or something like that ... the biggest negative is the thinner mouthfeel ... the biggest positive is the great nose ... .  from a sampler : pours a murky gold color with a medium white head and thin lacing .  m : this is where this bottle shined . a thick , and almost cream-like mouthfeel .

the aroma is incredible ! i 'd heard that nelson sauvin smells almost wine-like , but this is amazing ! ( looking on the label , it actually says that . ) delicate , fruity , floral , this is a beautiful aroma hop .  i was slightly disappointed when pouring this beer into the glass , as it had a small , fleeting head and was a clear reddish color . after beginning to sip , however , my disappointment left about as quickly as the beer 's head .  the mouthfeel is astounding . with all the charged up carbonation , i was expecting a soda like fizzy mouthfeel , but i am pleased at the silky smooth , well rounded and succulent body of this ale .

had in 120z bottle poured into pilsner glass nice copper color during and after pour , good 1 finger head with some lacing , the smell , wow , it reminded me of a nice caramel custard with a cup of coffe .  poured into a shaped pint glass pitch black with brown edges and a dense chocolate colored two finger head that was gone by the time i had put away my bottle opener , left no lacing . if only i had access to this on a more regular basis ! smells and tastes great , has a good texture and a decent appearance but is one hell of a beer overall .  it finishes with with an apple like flavor accompanied with clove and a little pepper m - one of the richest feeling beers ever !

a bit of a disappointment given its amazing aroma but still very good . mouthfeel : medium-bodied and well-carbonated .  had this beer several times this season , so had forgotten that i actually had n't gotten around to reviewing it ... a : poured with a small head that dissipated quickly to a thin film . no real lacing to speak of . body is an amber/brown color , and almost completely clear .  mouthfeel is full and velvety smooth with a crisp finish that could n't be better .
