smell was incredible . i really enjoyed the chimay blue which had similiar flavors but without the dryness .  a : clear yellow with low white head .  mouthfeel is excellent . it 's creamy and almost chewy .

juicy , insanely tropical fruity aroma dripping with notes of sugared orange slices , mango , pineapple juice , and pear . the belgian yeast is subtle in its spiciness , which i appreciate . malts are mild , with some bread and cereal notes . a bit soapy , but it 's forgivable , especially since the hop flavors are still big enough to linger long after each sip .  golden amber , slightly hazy , with a white collapsing head .  the feel is right on for the style .

aroma-this beer has such a phenomenal hop bouquet-super floral , piney , light resin , big citrus with notes of grapefruit and lemon-this beer just plain smells awesome . lurking under the hops is some nice support from the malt , with toast and caramel peaking through . the flavor is good , but the nose just blows other beers out of the park-it smells incredible . love this beer .  just a little head on it , with a bit of lace around the rim . brew is a light , clear , copper color .  mouthfeel : light-medium bodied with a super slick/silky and creamy feel .

s. i get some citrus and floral hops and rye t. first thing i taste is floral hops followed by some sweet malts and finishing off with some citrus , primarily orange and grapefruit .  reviewed 8/31/2009 ( bottle ) : orange clear color body , small creamy off-white head , diminishing .  carbonation is spot on and really helps lighten the mouthfeel .

s - very complex ! grape , sherry and port wine-type aromas are dominant , with hints of raisin , nuts and esters . alcohol is apparent , too . very sweet altogether . m/d - hardly any carbonation . i look forward to trying another one a year from now !  can , generously donated by a buddy of mine , as a cloudy , amber-brown . one inch head of dense , rocky foam that settles very slowly . the only drawback from this beer 's appearance is that it 's color seems a bit too dark for an ipa . smell is very hoppy with spicy , evergreen aromas .  m : mouthfeel is very nice .

huge aroma , complex , malty , yeasty , dark fruity . very , very nice but not exceptionally complex .  poured into my brand-new fantome tulip . a- golden yellow , thin head , tiny bubbles on the outer ring .  mouthfeel is thick and substantial , and you can definitely detect a chewiness from the yeast . very satisfying ; i will have this again .

reinaert packs a wallop in the aroma department . brett notes and plenty of em strike first . it 's still quite impressive , though .  arrives a pretty light color for a german hefeweizen .  touches of carbonation throughout , the mild breakups of tingling yield a remarkably smooth bevvy .

aroma : the smell is quite unique . a mix of orange , yeast , and fresh apple blossoms with a very floral , strong bouquet . there is some banana notes in the taste , along with the yeasty smell noted earlier , but very pleasant . perfect balance between malt and hop , so neither is very evident , allowing the more citric , floral , yeasty tastes to come through .  ap - pretty much no head .  molasses and toffee sweetness m - rich and chewy caramell . low carb form the bottle and slightly dry d - wonderful !

s - incredible . i 'm a fan of hoppy beers , so this is right up my alley . lots of great , citrus-y hops . based on the smell , i was expecting a pretty powerful hops flavor , but it 's actually pretty nicely balanced . nothing to write home about when compared to the taste and smell , but definitely not a negative here .  disappointingly thin , creamy white head falls to thin layer over a dese , cloudy , honey-colored beer .  mouthfeel- creamy and a bit thick . super smooth and very drinkable .

the aroma was mostly wheat from the bottle , but when poured the cherry was very prominent .  the beer is a hazy pale golden color , not quite as cloudy as some wits i 've seen . head was about 2 and a half fingers thick and pure white with poor retention .  mouthfeel : a very creamy , very smooth ipa . carbonation is perfect . body is malty and medium-bodied , and aftertaste is mildly dry .

very sticky and malty nose , lots of sugar , blueberry , and fig .  a : pours like black , well-used motor oil ; dark tan head , no retention or lace .  quite possibly the best mouthfeel i 've ever experienced in any beer .

s- huge dank rediculous hop aromas . big woody floral pine hop aromas blend with a high alpha hop oil aroma . big cat piss and a note of lemon zest . d- very drinkable and rediculously hoppy .  pours a golden yellow with a nice amount of head that sticks around a while but not annoyingly so like your drunken uncle .  mouthfeel is very luxurious and pleasant .

definitely one of the top 5 hop aroma beers i have ever consumed . it is so so so inviting from the aroma . i totally love beers with this full citrus hop aroma . the taste is totally different than the nose . it makes you think initially that it will be bitter and hop centric but then the malt character makes a huge stand and controls the main flavors your tongue perceives . it is quite pale malt dominated and i really appreciate this because overly resiny beers make me gag . i could pound this to no end which is dangerous considering the abv , lucky it is quite high in $ $ $ so this will limit my consumption . this is a very tasty and simple straightforward dipa .  3.0 a : lightly hazed dark orange amber color . just half a finger of frothy beige head that fell quickly , leaving no lacing .  fairly soft but noticeable carbonation , thick creamy mouthfeel just like chocolate milk .

wow i have to say iam really enjoying this alot more than some of the others that have reviewed this beer and iam not even a huge fan of the style but iam warming up to it a little more.poured into a small tulip glass a hazed peach color with the chunkies and floaties coming at the end of the pour a clingy two finger bone white head leaving broken bits of lace as it settled very slowly atop.man where to begin in describing the aromas of this beer lemon essence and ginger are what i notice at first then as i dig deeper a very root-like vegetable note comes through almost like radish or turnip i think the first time i have ever come across that in any beer , a leafy hop presence rounds out the aromas with a hit of medicinal essence.alot of the same stuff hits the palate although not quite as complex lemony and citrusy with a hint of funk and clove a big herbal finish , the lemon seems to linger on the back of the tongue for quite awhile.wow just a mad good american brewed saison honestly it may be my favorite of the style i have had , there isnt alot of funk so purists may not be so keen on it as me but hot damn i love it !  poured from a 22 ounce bottle in a wine glass a : deep black , thin head , no head .  soft and very creamy feel , this is a dream to drink .

the aroma is a somewhat weak blend of earthy malt , some nut notes , a bit of chocolate and hints of roasted malt as well . the flavour captures all of these things and does it a touch better than the aroma , but it 's still fairly average overall . the aroma is very weak and fades in and out , the taste has some promise but is bland overall and it 's just not something that i 'd go back to .  pours a very cloudy gold color with a nice big white head . looks more like a hefeweizen than an ipa .  this is the mouthfeel i yearn for in every brew o- very glad i got to sample this one and will most likely re-review it once i have more barleywine experience .

s : smells delicious ! funky , belgian yeast and and cloves with hints of citrus , fresh fruits and sweetness .  appearance 3/5 very dark brown and clear with garnet highlights and a medium head that dissipated into a thin collar rather quick and left some lacing .  mouthfeel is crazy smooth and thick .

aroma was absolutely excellent , wheat and honey , heavy on citrus and clove , vanilla and grassy floral hops .  clear yellow , with a large head of foam . there was no lacing left on the glass .  mouthfeel is excellent ; creamy with just the right twinge of foam .

aroma : smells amazing . tons of grapefruit and sweet cotton candy in the aroma . drinkability : this is an amazing ipa , full of great west coast hop aromas and flavors . it 's easy drinking , and quite delightful .  ' the brew was a walnut brown with a thin cream colored head atop it . little retention or lacing .  mouthfeel is chewy and creamy .

huge flavor in the nose - as advertised . brew smells great . brew is thin , crisp and very bubbly . the taste is n't as impressive as the smell . decent . pretty good brew , but once the novelty wears off it is not really something i could session .  mediocre retention , spotty lace .  perfect carbonation .

what a nose ... huge espresso , black currant , dark chocolate ... and that special , unique character that brings to mind the dark lord itself . a beast of an aroma . taste- bittersweet chocolate and the roastiest of malts , with a robust backbone that carries all the flavor throughout the mouth ... the finishing hop blast lingers on for days . mouthfeel/drinkability- thin and easy like a true ids , but not nearly as impressive as compared with the massive head , nose , and taste . it would be easier drinkin ' if the ingredients were downplayed , but then where 's the fun ? this was a real treat to sample , and at 5.25 % i ca n't believe this lasted for 2 years in the cellar . another sheer pleasure from three floyds that deserves praise for its incredible character .  pours a nifty orangish color with average head .  m. thick and creamy in the mouth and high carbonation for style . i actually like higher carbonation in all of my beers so this is nice .

a : pours a clear straw body . s : very spicy nose . i am not a chili connoisseur , so i ca n't pick out which varieties i 'm smelling . but it 's spicy . it 's incredibly spicy , delivering waves and waves of heat and burn , but in a pleasant way ( i like spice ) .  2006 version pours copper with 3 fingers of sand colored head . some lacing & head retention s : sweet malt & brown sugar t : sweet malt with hints of caramel & brown sugar up front .  m- medium/high carbonation . fairly smooth .

opaque light yellow brown with a light orange hue . smell is huge -- fragants of sweet honey , mellow almonds , nutmeg , etc . fairly balanced between other flavors -- some nutmeg , cloves , a touch of cinammon ?  poured on tap into a pint glass this beer pours a deep black in color , but where is the head ? said film is soon swallowed by the sea however , not to be seen again .  light , crisp , refreshing body and feel- would be great on a hot day .

smells and looks nice , but as far as taste , this reminds me of drinking colt 45 when i was 19 .  very nice three fingers of head after the pour , but no retention .  it also has a delightfully creamy texture such as a cream ale might have . trade route 's promotional profile for this beer states , `` it goes with everything or nothing at all .

a : pours pitch black , good sized tan head , lots of lacing down the glass s : smell is very stong chocolate and coffee .  ( a ) - pours a clear yet dark reddish color that produced a decent gray-ish colored head that dissipated quickly . minimal lacing .  good rounded mouthfeel the only other positive .

the smell is very strong of raspberry , though the taste itself is of beer mixed with raspberry seltzer water . there was a high ephervesense that really detracted from the enjoyability of the beer .  instead , i got this pefect , autumnal fruit beer , which , though it smells kind of like apple jacks , had an exceptional mouthfeel , and a rich apple kick that coupled nicely with the astringency of the lager . really good stuff .  m : nice feel to this , pretty heavy body , good amount of carbonation .

appearance - 1 1/2 to 2 inch head with a amber/dark brown body smell - very fruity , with hints of cinnamon ( i think ? ) taste - the taste is nothing like the smell .  2005 bottle pours a nice dark amber/brown color , with a thin tan head . retention is brief , and despite my efforts i ended up with quite a bit of sediment , most of which quickly settles out . looks like others have had a better-looking pour , so i 'll give this one another chance later .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

s- the aroma is fresh raspberries with a dry finish . there is a very faint note of bitter hops that enhances the raspberry aroma . as it warms there is a very faint earthy note but it is nothing like a `` wild '' yeast aroma . d-the beer starts of nice with big red raspberry aroma and appearance so i was expecting to be blown away with fruit flavor . it started off very exciting but then lost ground quickly .  pours very dark , but not dark enough that light does n't escape . white head , lots of carbonation , and little lacing .  mouthfeel : sits in the mouth well . great carbonation level though .

bold peach nose aroma that seemed refreshing and well done . the girl next to me ordered one and requested another beer remarking , `` this is disgusting .  poured an almost clear golden-brown with a fairly substantial frothy head that subsided quickly but lingered in some form the whole time .  mouthfeel is a medium with good carbonation .

looks pretty light on the pour , very little head that 's gone quick . smells very strongly of hazelnut , maybe even kind of peanut buttery .  pours a distinctly amberish hue , with a thin head with moderate to low lacing and retention .  well bodied for such a low abv beer .

s : lots of tart , sour aromas on the nose at first followed by some musky , funky barnyard aromas .  a : golden yellow with a bubbly head that dissipates quickly and leaves very little lace s : beautiful cherry nose with floral hops subtle banana and vanilla aromas t : nicely balanced grassy , banana and tangy cherry flavour with an alcohol snap m : creamy , medium body with good carbonation and an oh-so-smooth finish d : a delicious pilsener from the country who does it best !  m : mouthfeel is fine . nice striking , but well balanced acidity . smooth carbonation , a medium-bodied beer .
it feels very uncomfortable .  clear , still orange with a fat 3 finger head that fades over time . no lacing , decent retention .  light/medium mouthfeel .
s- the smell is pretty spice dominated .  kinda opaque body , no head on my one ounce taste .  m & d - mouthfeel is nice due to viscosity but the tart twanginess is not attractive .

aromas of cranberries are very strong up front with a slight grainy smell as well . ca n't say that i enjoyed this brew much , i think they would have been better off foregoing the lambic and just making a cranberry ale .  poured into a pint glass pours an amber orange with a minimal head that leaves no lace on the glass .  abundantly carbonated but not harsh .

s : smell is promising , get a huge jolt of pine and citrus on opening the bottle , once poured a mint and spice mix comes out . hop flavours are overall tasty , but were definitely muted , compared to what i expect in this style , prosaic compared to what is coming out of san diego right now . has good pine notes , but too much peppermint takes over in the end , making the flavour 1-dimensional and boring .  a-brilliant , crystal clear golden yellow with the lightest hint of an amber tint . spotty white foam dissipates to nothingness . seems to loose a little of the hop zing and the look was dull ... but i still liked it !  one positive is the full bodied presence of the malt , although the carbonation comes across as lighter than expected .

sweet aroma , heavy with fruit and a touch of candy , and a hint of bakery .  poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass a : brown-black with thin light-brown head that dissapates quickly but leaves a fair amount of lace s : chocolate , faint coffee , and nutty aromas supplement the roasted malts -- smells delicious .  pretty good for style .

aroma-light hops show minty and noble character .  clear , pale yellow body , one-bubble-thick head , large bubbles rising lazily . head retention is lousy but there are some curtains of lace ( ! ! ) clinging to the sides of the glass halfway through .  it is very smooth , though , although that 's one of its few positive notes .

smells good . chocolate covered cherry candies and hints of blended whiskey .  poured from a 22oz bottle into my pint glass with nearly no head at all .  f - medium bodied with good carbonation , refreshingly smooth .

smells lightly of brown sugar , some faint tropical fruit and spices -- coriander and ginger , producing a little tingle on the nose . tastes bitter , which is a surprise given the nose and the style , and mainly of bitter grapefruit rind , bordering on bitter melon .  pours a very light orange / yellow color with extremely light ( almost clear ) yellow highlights .  mouthfeel : smooth , dry , and clean - very good .

s : sharp sour acidic aroma is the first thing that grabs your nose . mild raspberries , pool toys , modest wet straw and moldy funk . seems to lack any real depth of a typical lambic .  pours a cloudy yellow .  m : medium body . moderate carbonation that finishes with some fizz on the tip of my tongue .

a pungent , pleasant smell . the dark fruits take center stage which include both dark raisins and burnt cherries .  a - served with a hazy , deep orange body ... the head was small and faded quickly ... it settled into a spider web cap ... not much lacing left behind s - this one is sweet and loaded with juicy mango ... it 's pretty one dimensional but it 's a great nose ... reminded me of a candle t - the sweetness sticks around from start to finish just as the nose suggested ... the hops come in towards the back end of the beer ... there is fleshy mango in the middle and it actually comes across a little earthy ... these flavors are reminding me of fruity pebbles m - medium bodied ... mild bitterness ... sweet , but not cloying ... cereal finish o - i heard this was a step up from the first attempt ... i 'm a fan of this beer ... a great nose with some great flavors going on ... like i said it smelled like a candle and tasted like fruity pebbles ... i 'd order this one again  there is also some roastiness and it has a good mouthfeel . overall i do n't get this beer , i personally do n't care for carbonated nyquil and i also do n't see how this is a pilsner .

smell was smokey and pleasant . i was a bit startled at the level of smoke aroma and it was all i could detect .  poured into a pint glass at 37 degrees . appearance : a medium amber color with copper hues . the clarity of the beer is clear and slightly hazy .  smooth somewhat creamy and drying mouthfeel , i have had much creamier kolsch and want something hoppier as well .

simple , but pleasant . taste : very similar to malt liquor .  no label ; yeast collection ring and cap announce brewer and beer , respectively . this poured out a perky peach-yellow with minimal sediment .  creamy smooth , heavy , and warming . super sweet , lots of whiskey ... not as complex as it should be since the bourbon flavors pretty much mask most of the malt .

smell of overpowering mint , dark chocolate , roasty malts and a sweet presence of residual sugars .  a - brown body that allows just enough light through to say it does . a pale , light , airy head seems rather quick-lived but rising carbonation continues to contribute to its maintenance . t - the chocolate darkens in the flavor and seems to even reach a coffee tone .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a lively carbonation that sits on top of more of an underlying smooth slickness . besides the look and body , this was pretty bad .

very little aroma . what i pick up is slightly vegetal . very , very dry and crisp .  the first 6 i bought carried the famous yellow label , and i 've gone though a few more since then . i 'm still waiting for the day i can get a pint with a batch of mussels .  the mouthfeel is exactly like sprite .

there is an immediate burst of fresh , flowery hop aroma with faint hints of coffee and malt .  poured into a tulip glass . very light orange , almost yellow-orange in color with a minimal white head that dissipates quickly .  md-thick body and mouthfeel . appropriate carbonation .

there are some great tones of apple , pear , and cider on the nose of this beer , as well as a heavy yeast consistency . i definetely did not like the taste of this one too well , especially compared to other unibroue beers . it has a strangely ice-creamy flavor , which is also reflected in the thick mouthfeel .  a : poured a cloudy yellow color , looks a lot like a wheat beer .  mouthfeel : nice carbonation level , medium body , smooth texture .

instantly smells of coffee but if the brew warms a little it gives more malt aromas .  poured from a twelve ounce bottle into a tulip glass dark , cloudy brown in appearance , with a short head of foam aroma-malt and spices taste-spice notes and roasted malt-very smooth and well-balanced overall , a well-balanced , flavorful dark ale .  the mouthfeel is good . moderate carbonation .

s : moderate sours and aroma of a wet band aid . spices are obvious throughout , more so when a bit chilled . not inviting .  despite pouring a hazy , golden color , it has little in common with the more typical golden belgian ales . poured very little head , and what was there disappeared quickly .  the carbonation is medium , as is the thickness of the liquid . an ok lager , a good thirst drencher on a hot summer afternoon .

s : so faint , maybe a slight smell of hops , but nothing prominent , so right on to the drinking . t : this beer does n't taste much .  a : pours a cloudy orange/amber with yeast sediment floating around . produces 1 finger of head that dissipates quickly leaving behind great lacing .  great brewery , terrible labels . this beer smells exactly like fresh paint . but then it really got to me and ruined my whole heresy experience . smooth and reserved heresy is an introvert in the double stout world .

bottled on 9/12/02 sampled 2/19/04 aroma has slightly sour notes but it 's got a stale flat empty not good smell too .  33 cl bottle into an orval chalice , a : pours a ruddy sepia with small white head , solid retention .  at the least the mouthfeel is , typical of apas , nice and creamy .

pretty good . light roasted malt flavors greet the tongue , followed by a milky sweetness .  pours a very dark mahogany brown with no head at all except for a ring around the edge of the glass .  finishes fruitty & dry mf : light/medium bodied with minimal carbonation drinks okay , should 've known a beer this low in abv would n't fare well with it 's trans-pacific journey

the smell is of luden 's , which i enjoy . the flavor is super syrupy and thick with a cherry candy flavor .  looks similar to other kolsch 's i 've had as well as a typical macro . white head with ok retention but not much lacing .  a-black color , finely carbonated off white head s-a hint of yeast , some roasted malt t-hints of bourbon with a touch of bug spray and brett yeast funk m-smooth bodied , very creamy , nice d-the bourbon sting is a little too much for me o-did not care for the combination of brettomyces and bourbon stout .

smell citrus and hoppy ... very hoppy .  alpha pours a nice golden colour with a bit of a carbonated head that settles down in relatively short order . my only complaint with this beer is the weak head and minimal lacing .  good tingle all over the tongue and a bit in the throat .

the aroma was great so i was expecting more .  45-50f a : cloudy , deep straw body ( apple juice ? ) with a big white head that rapidly dissipates leaving no lacing or cover .  taste is quite spicy and flavorful , there 's some nice dark malt character to it , and a nice creamy mouthfeel with light but sharp carbonation .

also a strong tartness reminiscent of lemon juice.. reminds me of nb le terroir with just a touch of sweet melon . o- awkward beer for sure- one of the most unconventional i 've tried actually .  pours a cloudy dark amber/copper with a small light tan head , good lacing .  m- assertive carbonation , light body and fairly smooth .

s : slightly floral with strong notes of lemon and citrus . just a touch of hops .  wow , finally flying fish released this ambrosia of the gods ! flying fish , please makemoreof this and more often ! the pint glass came to me without a hint ofhead or foam , which lead me to believe what 's up ? after a sniff of the top of the glass the sweetness came back , and after a long , deep sip , the maltiness and the hint of bourbon traveled to my satisfied belly ! ! !  medium to full bodied and smooth .

as i poured this dark rich liquid into my clear beer mug i was struck by an overwhelming sweet aroma . while i usually like my beer with a sweet overtone , this one was just too much .  a : pours a dark mahogany with sightly less than one finger of head which quickly dissipates .  mouthfeel= good mouthfeel drinkability= average .

oaky , with sweet malt , vanilla and a little whiskey . nice effort , but not for me .  it is very smooth and defenitly a beer you can drink all day or night . the only thing negative i have to say is that it seems more like a summer `` hot day '' beer than one to drink on those cold late winter and early spring nights/days . so in my opinion it should be a summer seasonal instead of a spring seasonal . i highly recommend this brew and do n't you dare put a piece of orange in it ... save that for the white ale 's ( belgian wit ) of lesser quality such as coors ' blue moon .  mouthfeel is actually pretty good .

there 's a bit of grapefruit on the nose , but ultimately the smells of pine and citrus dominate . relatively typical ipa notes -- -sort of reminds me of the north west .  orangey yellow color , pretty clear .  the texture in the mouth is quite good , remaining effervescent and enjoyable throughout this tasting .

oz bottle of this from bottle king in livingston for about $ 5.99 , and i must say , coming from a high-caliber company like rogue 's , i really was n't too impressed with this stout sample ... expected more , and was let down by an overall lack of flavor and complexity ... appearance was about average , poured a jet-black , ebony color with minimal tan head ... smell was complete with burnt , dark chocolate , espresso , and liquorice aromas ... taste was typical stout , with dark-espresso and cocoa flavors that was more bitter than sweet ... taste seemed pretty watered-down and somewhat more bland than i was expecting ... definitely had much better stouts before this , and the overall taste was more average than anything else ... i would n't say this was a bad brew , just was n't to my liking and not one i would try again ... would n't recommend this one ...  appearance : pours a orange gold with creamy white head that leaves lots of spotting . notes : first off , i 'd never buy this based on the package if i had n't heard of it - it looks cheap and designed for tourists .  ehh.. let me start by saying i adore irs 's . the anise , in my humble opinion makes this beer taste absolutely terrible . do n't get me wrong , you still get the nectar like , frothy delicious chocolate experience in the background , which is almost good enough to save this beer for me . theoretically the sweet/bitter flavor of the yeast should play off of and enhance the chocolate and coffee flavorings , but it does not . a change in proportions could make this a great , unique brew .

s : a nice malty aroma of mocha and cocoa .  aromas can be described it one simple phase/image : dark chocolate brownie batter with a dash of bourbon . the taste begins with succulent dark chocolate and burnt brown sugars with substantial cocoa powder and lesser notes of vanilla , earthy/woodiness and alcohol . the mouthfeel is full with adequate carbonation for the style . the finish is slick and silky . overall , this is another extremely solid beer from a brewery that i have not been disappointed with yet to date ; granted i have only had their brewer 's gone wild series beers ( so their brewer 's select series basically ) , so maybe i am not the best judge because i 've only had their best stuff .  medium bodied with sufficient carbonation .

boozy nose with with some decent roast and chocolate character .  this beer looks light for a pale ale . a cloudy golden color . thin , dense white head .  viscous , almost syrupy but thankfully not cloying , with little noticeable alcohol .
pumkin scent with strong doses of cinnamon .  dark brown color , no head on my pour .  finishes fairly clean with a good mouthfeel may have to try this again .

smell is very intense with sour notes and decent fruity funk and reminds me of a barnyard on a damp day .  '' the beer poured with almost no head , my friend remarked that it looked like cola .  it has a good mouthfeel , thick but creamy , goes down smooth .

very fresh , clean , and aromatic . the aroma is very tantalizing and one of the better smelling ipa 's i 've had the pleasure of sniffing in a while .  a : poured into a pint glass : no real head to speak of , but a nice orange-amber hue , a bit lighter in color than i 'd expected .  i hate that most of beer advocate disagrees with me about this but i do n't get the hype over this beer other that the fact that it seriously looks like motoroil and has a super thick mouthfeel .

smell : floral notes with a deeper and more dank earthy-malt aroma . taste : funky , bitter , nettle-like taste with malt background .  a : super dark black/cola with no light getting through . absolutely no head at all and therefore no lacing .  i liked the mouthfeel of this beer .
it actually smells quite good .  a very small , almost white head sits on a cloudy , dark red-brown beer . full of big , pale chunks of float .  body is good and so is carbonation .

awesome aroma . pours a cloudy dark orange color , some nice head with decent retention . very smooth- from the smell , i was actually expecting a more pronounced hop flavor here , but regardless , this is an excellent ipa . mouthfeel- appropriate carbonation , buttery , clean . drinkability- i could drink this one all day .  pours a dark brown , with minimal head to speak off .  m : good , a pleasant heaviness that does n't become too viscous or clinging .

the aroma is pleasant - noticeable pumpkin , some spices - clove , cinnamon , and nutmeg ? overall an interesting brew , the aroma is nice , but the flavor is n't .  coppery-orange murky body with an ivory 1-finger head . lots of particles in suspension , including some fairly large chunks . good sheets of lacing left behind .  mf : medium bodied , fairly smooth , with just enough carbonation to keep it interesting , but not too much to give it an undesirable crisp flavor .

s- the nose is nice . vanilla is big , but it walks the line between vanilla bean and extract sweet .  a - pours a dark copper amber with a small , bubbling white head .  mostly yeasts with minimal hop notes . taste : for a lager , not too bad . smooth inception leads to yeast , hops , then smooth and rounded end . almost methodical in its sequence of flavors . overall : pretty drinkable ; good for barbecues and other events that require a well-balanced lager as to not overwhelm the taste of other foods .
sweet and quite pleasant . p/m : emptiness .  poured into a tulip a . beer pours a dark brown that pretty much looks black .  the mouthfeel was a fluffy consistency .

smell is yeast with some raisin and plum .  12oz brown bottle . ) poured a hazy gold . fine bubbled head about one finger .  on tap at vintage 301 last night , poured a very ; ight lemony yellow with a tight formed 1/2 finger white that was gone quickly.faint toasted aromas along with a whiff of vanilla but its quite faint.the mouthfeel was nice and creamy and went down smooth , flavors are pretty heavy handed vanilla and some light toastiness almost like a vanilla wafer.eh it isnt bad for what it is but its not my thing .

s : not what i had expected . cherries smell tart and at the forefront of the beer . interesting . t : abv is way to naked here .  the beer pours a veritable tea color with minimal head retention and lacing .  incredibly astringent finish that just keeps lingering until the next sip . mouthfeel almost is pretty viscous .
s : nice malty , hoppy aroma that seemed fitting for the seasonal .  a : cloudy amber color that was much lighter than i was expecting .  the mouth is smooth -- light to medium in body .

the smell was good with a nice bready yeast fresh bread smell , but that is about the best i can say about this one . will not buy again  slightly hazy amber body with hardly any head to speak of .  carbonation level is high , giving the body fullness but also making it lively on the tongue . flavor profile is a bit exotic , with grapy/berry fruitiness , spice , and molasses . thins out on the smooth and moderately brief finish .

the aroma is of just what the name implies , hops and apricots , along with some caramelized malts . the two together seem rather harsh . it 's flavorful but i did n't find it too tasty , goes down ok , not too filling , good kick , unlike many fruit beers , this one does n't use the fruit flavor to try covering up the fact that it is still a beer , but this is definitely not a beer that i would want to drink again .  ha pours a dark brown with a thin tan head . not the best looking beer .  nice , fairly full mouthfeel .

n : very good pumpkin aroma along with caramel and light spices ( mostly nutmeg . ) t : the spiciness is upfront with cinnamon and nutmeg .  got this from bottletrek , bbd of 06 08 pours chestnut/ebony with 1 finger of tan head . average head retention & lacing s : chocolate & roasty malts t : chocolate , a bit of iron , slight herbal hops up front .  m - smooth , decent body . a respectable mouthfeel .

aroma of feet in sweatsocks - very odd .  foam is thick and frothy , fading quickly and leaves some decent lacing on the glass . good looker , except for the floaties . the floaties are not palpable on the palate , thank the lord !  overall : good mouthfeel , well carbonated with a bit of oiliness .

s : very bold pear esters , some mint , apple blossoms , floral , mostly roses . l : cloudy burnt orange , nice off-white creamy head , great retention and lacing . very disappointing , especially since i loved all of their other beers .  luckily my good buddy hyland had one tucked in the very dark corner of his basement beer fridge and was kind enough to share it with me . a - poured an amber color with a bit of haziness about it . no head to speak of .  m - i really like the mouthfeel of this beer . it is perfectly carbonated and that takes over when it first hits the tongue .

imeadiatley smelled like a blast of sour fruitiness with just a hint of malt .  golden , faint haze , very thin head fades fast , not active , spotty lacing .  their is a pleasant caramel base behind it with a good creamy mouthfeel .

it has a wonderful blueberry scent , but unfortunately the blueberry also overrides the wheat beer taste . it 's exactly as good or as nasty as that sounds .  out of a pint glass at the brewery this beer was a hazy amber color . the head was one finger of off-white bubbles that retained as a thin collar and left mediocre lacing .  smells kind of like dishwashing liquid , very soapy , but distinct of certain hop combos ... or so i 've discovered over the years . there 's an even malty / big dextrin sweetness and medium-mouthfeel , but the depth of flavour is one dimensional . hops come in as a gentle bitter citric tingle on the palate , then turns into a faint tea-like character as it fades into the malty blandness . hops are a bit oily . earth flavours run through the middle . finish has some residual hop and soap-like flavours . or perhaps the way the hops played out , combined with the dull malty flavours , rubbed me the wrong way ?

s : lots and lots of cinnamon and brown sugar invade the nose at first , followed by pumpkin , red apples and bubble gum .  poured a very cloudy dark orange with a light but sticky head , lots of chunky sediment .  m - fairly light-bodied , with nice carbonation ; quite good in this aspect .

i consider this one a classic even though it is n't the most complex or flavorful brown ale . there is n't much in the way of aroma , but the taste is smooth but not creamy , sweet but not sugary .  appears clear gold with little head retention .  m - the mouthfeel is actually right on point .

balance leans towards the hops , but smells good . medium bodied and fairly flat/smooth .  pours a hazy , copper color . decent retention and decent lacing .  500ml bottle poured into tulip mar27 2011 a pours out black with some oil like globs towards the bottom of the bottle , thumbs width of mocha head quickly falls to a thin film leaving a partial ring of lace followed by some unorganized patches s worcestershire sauce and soy with a little booze and mint , not what i was hoping for t slightly better with some smoke , woody earth , vanilla , cola and whiskey but that worcestershire is hard to miss after you catch wind of it m fairly thick and creamy with just a little heat that could be better concealed but still feels good o lea & perrins would be proud , that worcestershire smell and flavor is holding this one way back hard to believe that before this hit the barrel it was one of my all time favorite stouts , i love the beer geek breakfast but this one just did n't do it for me , not a bad brew but i 'd rather drink one before the barrel aging edit : after reading some reviews i suspected i got a bad bottle and tried another .

this one pours with a huge foam head and smells good and toasty with a hint of vanilla .  pours to a brilliantly clear dark-amber with garnet highlights , forming an average-sized frothy light-beige head with poor retention and minimal lacing .  taste : light body , smooth mouth feel .

aroma : very inviting aroma of bananas , citrus and coriander . good amount of yeast in the nose too .  poured from a can into a pint glass a : a very light amber/orange with a hint of yellow on the edges , quick dissipating head with a bit of lacing s : sweet , a more sweet smell than i 'm used to with an ipa , but not in a bad way a bit of earthiness smell as well , not sure i would call it peat , but earthy for sure t : good , nice bitterness up front with a followup of the sweet malty , and a just a bit of creaminess in the middle to end , but the end note is definitely switches back to bitter o : a good beer , interesting take on an imperial ipa , really enjoyed it and like the complexity and mix of taste , malty but hard ipa as well , very good this beer has officially made me a fan of oskar blues brewery , really like this and their 'old chub ' schotch ale .  mouthfeel is medium - light with good carbonation .

smells of bright cherries hit my nose first along with banana , malt vinegar and caramel ( quite an unexpectedly interesting nose ) . and the nose was so promising ... darn .  a clear yellow/light orange with a finger of even white head .  moderate carbonation and more oak on the finish .

it looked good and even smelled decent but the taste is that of a beer that is old .  bottle poured into a tulip . ( a ) - pours a cloudy golden yellow/orange hue that produced a barely visible white head that dissipated immediately down to bubbles even after a vigorous pour .  palate : this is the best part of the beer . medium body with low end carbonation . goes down smooth with a nice little bite at the back of the throat on the finish .

aroma was actually real good . sweet apricot , granny smith apple , almost like a desert wine .  appearance : a two finger head that is frothy and foamy with poor retention .  mouthfeel smooth and creamy with a dry hop bitterness at the finish .

smells of butter rum lifesavers , dates , figs , caramel . good malt aromas ( if a bit buttery ) , but there 's only a faint hop backing .  i got no head on this pour , that made me a little sad . o- other than how this looks ( lack of head ) this is a world class porter .  m- full body with medium/low carbonation . d- i really do n't like this .

quite nice . taste was average having the proper flavour profiles for the style , but finishing up with a surprising bitterness .  a - pours a clear copper / brown color . it does appear to be lighter in color than i would expect from an amber ale . got almost an inch of head that disappeared pretty quick .  the body is fairly good .

s : banana with bitter malt , bready , reminiscent of a saison . t : a disappointment .  pours an orangish amber color with a ring of head around the edge and little to no lace .  mouthfeel is pretty nice , i would think this beer was thin , but it is n't .

smell - not a very potent odor . smells of alcohol a bit with a little bit of fruit possibly , but not very strong at all .  this beer pours a hazy golden color like most ipa 's .  m -- mouthfeel is soft to crisp with a light to light-medium body .

s - roasted malt with a little burnt malt as well .  10/02/2011 750ml bottle 1981 vintage served in a cantillon tumbler . i 've tasted a 1997 cantillon gueuze & it was too oxidized & musty ( still amazing ) a huge thanks to a gentleman in geel , belgium for finding this in the back of a basement . appearance : corked 750 , no cage , cork rotting on top after removing foil cover , carefully removing the cork a portion of it stayed in the bottle & effected the pour . crystal clear with the appropriate pour but slightly darker than a typical gueuze , think esb color . i honestly had low expectations for this beer . so glad to have the opportunity to drink this .  medium mouthfeel .

this has to be the lighest stout i have ever had . overall this is an overrated beer , just not what i would consider a stout .  just the slightest bit hazy , worn penny looking copper color with a thin , perhaps a half inch thick , frothy porcelian ( sp ? ) head .  mouthfeel is comfortable for this style and it is very drinkable if you are looking for a sweeter ( english & lt ; ? & gt ; ) styled pale ale .

very interesting . t : not terrible , but rather boring .  with all the hoopla over big hoppy beers , i 'm happy to say that i 'm a dedicated malt head , and this beer fits my tastes wonderfully . appearance : pours a clear reddish amber color . head is a thin layer of foam , no real lacing to be seen .  the mouthfeel is all right . it 's full , sticky on the finish and carbonated enough to keep the tongue tingly without providing much lift and volume .

9 oz bottle poured into a sniter - the numbers `` 05 , 06 '' are printed on the bottle - cellar temp appearance : slightly hazy brown beer . smell : caramel , malt , raisin and golden graham crackers . cinnamon , nuttiness of almond .  a : the pour is a muddy brown color with very little to no head .  mouthfeel : crisp , clean , and refreshing .

we had ephraim from hill farmstead earlier in the night which was amazing , but i liked the nose on this one even better . d - overall this was an awesome dipa and another great beer from lawson 's ; it made me really want to try more of their stuff . i 've had two of their ipa 's now and they 've both been very good . the nose was so hoppy and fruity it was perfect to me .  a : honey amber hue with thin cap of off-white head and scant lacing .  m- medium body with good carbonation .
smells great ! t : lots of hops , alcohol definitely noticeable , not very sweet , not much citrus .  pours a cloudy light yellow color .  the palate is super smooth .

s- the nose is pretty nice with some chocolate sweetness and some roasted bitterness . not alot else going on though .  black , black and black in color with a weak tan head that disappears without warning , leaving a thin layer of lace on top of the brew .  m - mouthfeels great , medium body , well carbonated and very drinkable o - not bad , not impressive either.. pretty good .

the smell is utterly different from a normal hefeweizen .  i know i 'll probably get some odd stares for this , but as someone not particularly infatuated with dogfish head beers ( though their coastal brewpub is a lot of fun ) , this is the beer of theirs i look forward to the most .  a touch of burning alcohol on the finish , shocker . mouthfeel : actually pretty full , smooth , and round drinkability : 1 can after two other beers ( earlier ) is gon na get me buzzed i think , but the sweetness means i could never have more than one of these ( even if i wanted to ) conclusion : we were having crappy beer night tonight as a joke .

this really smells like a weizenbock . big wheat malt and banana nose with a nice helping of spicy clove along with a little alcohol . delicious .  review based on notes consumed about a month ago pours a hazed caramel with a sliver of sand colored head . stays murked up , average head retnetion & lacing s : breadyness , toffee & much orchard fruit t : toffee , oakyness & hints of caramel , & a touch of boozey pears & apricots .  the mouthfeel is on the heavy side of medium bodied , and it glides down your throat as smooth as hell .

smell of chocolate with a light coffee and smoked note .  pours a clear pale yellow with a white foamy head that melted away fairly quick . if my olfactory senses didnt get within twelve inches of the glass , my optical senses would have had me believe that this was a bud light .  m/d - crisp , medium body with excellent carbonation .
smells much better as it warms .  cask at marble arch pub dark brown with off-white head that is gone in seconds , no lacing .  body is medium with medium-low carbonation .

thin mouth feel and over whelming smell and taste of nutmeg and cinnamon .  great stuff . lighter on the apple skins and edging more towards acetone , yet with a pleasing grape must edge . pours a murky ruddy amber , hazed and rimmed with off-white .  it had a smooth feel with slight carbonation and a crisp finish .

smells overcooked coffee , mild chocolate , and winterfresh .  the beer poured a dark brown , almost black , forming a very thin mocha head that quickly faded .  smooth and soft , mouthfeel alone is not bad at all .

i must say that this `` java stout '' is by no means a traditional stout . light carbonation , nice light head , sweet yet coffee bitterness comes through . as easy as it may be to tear this beer down , i would rather note that those who may enjoy coffee and a dark beer here and there will probably find this stout to be worth a taste . whether bar chocolate or dark chocolate cookies , this pairing works . just remember , this is no stout .  notched in 2007 ( larger ) and 2010 ( smaller ) - i suppose that it means that it was made in 2007 and best by 2010 ... not sure though ... in any case - pours hazy/murky orangeish amber with some lacing . pretty muddy-looking - head does n't last too long , though it holds on a bit - lacing saves it some .  mouthfeel was nice . nice carbonation with a boozey sting .

being on a real chocolate stout kick , i must say i was extremely disappointed in this beer said to be brewed with `` chocolate , molasses and lactose '' . it smelled right but tasted very average . the smell and first few sips had some notes of cocoa powder but that taste quickly disappeared and turned into a moderate imperial stout .  cigar city continues to live up to their hype . a : a subtle film forms above this deep brown bodied brew and fades rather quickly .  nice carbonation level and easy to drink .

s : hmm , abv is quite apparent and reminds me of some belgian beers , slightly sweet and fruity . cough syrup .  a- this one pours out a dark brown colored body with a quarter finger of beige head . the head vanishes rather quickly , and leaves behind random small spots of lacing .  the smell is malty , with noticeable alcohol and more hops than seem to be present in a sip . there are a lot of flavors in this mix -- fruits , caramel , chocolate -- and these flavors pack a complex punch in the smell and taste , as does the alcohol , which causes sensation up the nose . overall , it was too sweet for me , like figs buried in sugar . i suspect i would have enjoyed the malt flavor greatly if the sweetness and alcohol were taken down a notch . i do n't consider this highly drinkable : 500 ml was far too much for me to finish .

it smells fantastic , but just does n't live up to it in the taste department .  a- light orange./yellow , with a slight head s- the smell had very pronounced pine , lemon , yeast , hop , and citrus aroma . m- carbonated , light considering the amount of ibu and the initial reaction to the odor .  it tastes nothing like a real peach . i would compare it too a jolly rancher piece of candy . i do like the fizzieness , and crisp finish , but thats it .

aroma : rum , raisins , plums , brown sugar , slight latex . good hints at a belgian dark strong ale style . overall : quite unimpressive , and probably my least favorite of the lost abbey beers i 've had .  poured a cloudy orange color with little to no head .  mouthfeel was good .

it smelled of malt with hops and some vanilla . overall it was pretty good , especially considering it 's from anheuser busch .  somewhat dark amber bodied brew , two finger cream head ends up disappearing without much lacing . nothing amazing here , but its a pretty nice light beer that would be nice to have during a nice hot day .  still interesting for the genre , but certainly not one of the crowning achievements m : the mouthfeel is creamier than anticipated , not as light as the color would imply , a mild chewiness , with regular coating levels .

very light color in the glass , after i pour it , one thing that i must admit is that the smell that came out of the glass was amazing ! overall if you are seeking for a `` liquid dessert '' this might hit the spot but not something to drink the whole night .  12oz bottle poured into a sa glass a : light straw and cloudy with a fairly thin white head and that does n't last long .  mouthfeel : just the right amount of carbonation on this one which i was delighted with but the aftertaste is a bit tart .
s - extremely sour aroma with very vigourous apricot aroma .  it 's biggest fault is poor head retention .  m : light-to-medium body , highly carbonated . pretty nice .

small tan-ish head smell : very dark with raisin and fig aromas . quite interesting ... not as roasty as i thought it would be . this has a very baltic porter character .  pours a cloudy caramel color with a decent white head . retention is ok and leaves a bit of lacing but it does n't stay for the whole beer .  the mouthfeel is actually decently creamy and well-carbonated .

smells of slight hoppyness . it 's for sure not as aromatic as some other ipa 's . in fact i ca n't smell much at all in this beer . taste is great . i could session this ipa for sure because it goes down smooth and is n't heavy or it does n't wreck the palate . it could be a little sweeter imo but it 's still great . mouthfeel is great . overall it 's a great ipa .  this beer pours an opaque dark brown nearly black color .  mediumish mouthfeel , solid , almost too solid .

smell : very light on the smell . a slight hint of hops in the aroma .  smallish head that dissipated very quickly . dark gold pushing amber and slightly cloudy . quite heavy for style , yet lager crispness and a thirst quenching qulaity . interesting contrast .  i get tomato , celery , black pepper and then a wave of cedar . the hops were definitely present in it , but i could n't get past the heavy cedar flavors . sorry , but not to my liking .

aroma had a notes of chocolate , anise , coffee and fruit . the bitterness was very harsh in the finish , it covered some good flavors a bit too much .  a : really dark brown with a little bit of reddish tone . the tan head disapears quickly leaving a patchy , floating foam .  texture is quite fizzy and lively .

s- the malts are much stronger than the hops in the nose of this american barleywine . lots of caramel and toffee . somewhat fruity as well .  a - hazy medium to dark brown . not much head at all .  m : light bodied and crisp like a pilsner should be .

s - smell was unique . alcohol mixed with some sweetness and spiciness .  kind of a murky rust color with a thin cream colored head that clings to the glass on its way down .  the mouthfeel is rich while remaining light , the carbonation is much higher than expected , but it works well for this brew .

surprisingly fruity nose is the dominant feature . it really is the bitterest thing ive ever had .  pours a small white head with a clear orange body and fair lacing .  mouthfeel is good but overall this is either not good or not fresh .

a - clear golden orange body with a small amount of light tan head and a little bit of lacing s - lots of hops and grapefruit up front . some sweet and fruity notes in the back t - there are hops ... i want to say there is grapefruit as well but ca n't fully tell .  the worst part of the beer is the appearance , and by worst i simply mean it is average . i compare the head on this to the head of some big name stouts , and it is lacking a bit . head is lacy and clings well to the glass , but light overall for the style . color has more red to the black than most stouts .  mouthfeel is slick and medium bodied .

s- banana for days . malty and sugary as well . quite a smell . t- banana bread ... obviously .  has the characteristics of coca-cola , dark cola color with a quickly dissipating light tan head . a bit underwhelming . the smell makes up for the lack of appearance .  it is light in the mouth with almost an airy feel to it .

s : surprisingly like apricot jam .  pours a lighter amber color with good clarity . the head was ok with tight white bubbles .  mouthfeel : medium bodied . lightly crisp and dry at the start , smoooth and dry at the finish .

very nice . taste : more malty than anything , the hops are subdued and not very bitter , this is hardly an ipa by today 's standards .  a- thick foamy head , lots of bubbles . not a huge fan of the color , it 's like a moderately pale apple juice .  m - nice chewy mouthfeel , what i 'd expect for the style .

bottle smell is delicious , fruity , citrusy , some grapefruit and grapes , zesty . this hopping is very different . the aromas are citrusy but the flavor is more like a fuggles , or english ale , and the bitterness is very dry .  honey golden in appearance with a frothy head at first , but the head disappears very quickly .  mouthfeel is light with good carbonation .

a - pours really dark into a goblet . s - a bit of a buttery aroma , kind of a sweet pound cake . t - the roasted soba makes this a different animal than the other , lighter morimoto soba ale .  burnt orange hue , the head fizzled and retracted quickly leaving a momentary wispy centre , no ring and no lace .  m - mouthfeel is nice and full and goes down nicely d - pretty decent dunkel .

a much bigger aroma then the 90 minute . t - i really hope i just had a bad bottle of this . i will give this beer credit though with the aroma , it smells absolutely epic but the taste really really hurts this one .  appearance : very dark with just a bit of red around the edges , thin head , very little lacing .  m : medium bodied with medium carbonation .

light caramel , sweet creamy chocolate , sugary chocolate biscuits and mocha coffee redolances play on this beers bouquet , hints of barley and molasses vie for attention but are not competition for the overwhelming coffee and chocolate perfume . overall , this is a good standby sweet cream stout .  pours ahazy light straw , almost the color of grapefruit juice , with no head to speak of .  m : pleasant .

s : sweet and malty , there is a nice maple syrup note here . a touch of hop aroma in there .  its hazy , crimson-tinted brown body is capped by a light tan head of creamy foam that drops far too quickly for the style and leaves little lace about the glass .  you get a slight taste of toasted malt and honey , then at mid-palate the flavors develop from slightly sweet to mildly tangy . do n't get me wrong , i love punchy beers , but sometimes it 's nice to enjoy something a little milder . this is mild and easy-to-drink without being bland . it did n't exactly rock my world , but it was n't bad at all .

12 oz bottle poured into a snifter - fridge temp - 2008 appearance : pours a golden brown with orange highlights . smell : instant forefront of butter cream with some sharp malt aromas . sweet smelling rum makes it 's way into the fold .  soapy , dark tan head shows poor lacing and no lacing whatsoever .  fruity , yeasty smells are overwhelmed with sourness . there is some sour fruitiness up front , which is quickly overwhelmed by a vinegar-like taste , finishing off with a bit of bitterness . i really wanted to like this beer , liking more saisons , and various sour beers , but there is too much of a vinegar-like taste for me in this beer .
all citrusy hops in the nose , this a very good smelling beer .  appears a mahogany color with a small head that fades quickly .  m : mouthfeel is generally good and like most stouts i 've had .

s - lots of roastiness , roasted barley , slightly acidic , floral and spicy hops .  average appearance . not much foam or retention to speak of . very brite beer , i was at least expecting some proteins or sediment to be in here . in these regards the appearance is very average .  mouthfeel : this has a full creamy mouthfeel .

good aroma and well achieved goal .  the only thing off about it is it pours with nearly no head at all , maybe something other than a standard pint glass would fix this .  m : full body with little carbonation .

s - rich , malty , honey , and hoppy smell . the hop smell really stands out here .  poured into a tulip a pours a copper/amber/light orange color , cloudy unfiltered . small one finger whiteish head .  medium mouthfeel .

great aroma . complex and deep .  a : pours a very dark brown with a two-finger light brown head with poor retention but sticks around on the edges .  it has a very thick mouthfeel and a kind of grapefruit like flavor .

aromas are of citrus , lemon , oranges , limes , and mixed spices .  spritzy light white head that basically surrenders . unfortunately , to be consistent with other rankings i 'd have to say the appearance is rather lackluster and drags down an otherwise solid brew .  nice creamy body as it goes down .

s : malt ... not aromatic enough to get anything else . t : you got your lager in my ale ! d : easy to drink , but it could be a little boring as long as the hop aromatics remain lost .  i refer to this beer as the tabala rasa because it looks and tastes alot like an blank slate . by itself it is not flavorful enough in the slightest however with a little creativity ... if you drop a shot of peach shnapps in it circus boy tastes almost exactly like a fruity breakfast cerial and i have come to call this combination a silly rabbit ... and its pretty delicious for a bomb . by itself however circus boy is a very bland beer and definetly not one that tastes looks or pours like a hefe .  the body is creamy and light with prickly carbonation .

this seemed the closest match to the 4.8 % abv listed on the brown plastic bottle from germany ( hand carried back ) aroma : a nice spicy saaz hop aroma with a mild mineral note .  appearance is a nice amber color with a thin head and no lace .  tastes like it smells , with sweet malt , light caramel , corn , grass , light floral hops and grains ; basically it 's a lager and just ok. mouthfeel is light and crisp , with a light body , light carbonation and good drinkability ; a light a refreshing beer that basically has no flavor .

a tale of two beers ( with the same name and style billing ) last year i was lucky enough to procure way too little of flying dog 's 20th anniversary beer . where is the unfiltered quality of last year 's batch ? do yourself a favor and try rock art 's belgo-american ipa , it 's a revelation .  12 oz bottle pours into my pint glass opaque black with a very small tannish colored head . very little retention , but some lacing hangs around after each sip .  the mouthfeel was good , as it was heavy and grainy .

aromas of yeast and some malt was simple , yet pleasureable .  the brew might have been a bit dark , almost mahogany and had little head with no retention .  there is a definite hop bitterness that tries to balance out any sweetness that is left over , but gets lost in the wash. that being said , it 's bold in the body and has a pleasantly smooth but lively mouthfeel .

s : coriander and orange rind up front followed by a sweet belgian spice and yeast aroma . t : similar to the smell , there 's coriander and orange rind up front followed by a belgian yeast and spice flavor .  33cl into a tulip . pours a ruddy dirty dishwater water with spilt cola .  good and refreshing crispness in the mouth , which provided some balance to the flavor .

overall , this is a very pleasant aroma . t : some fruity banana and cloves again .  not a clue what it really was ( blank bottle ) at first but after reading the neck label , very happy to have . pours a beautiful chestnut brown which is impressive and a tall head ( a bit thin though ) . the beer seemed a bit hazy though , and the head fell very quickly .  the flavor may have been off but the body is very nice as it has a semi-thick viscous texture without overwhelming the drinker . the body allows the flavors to be conveyed more smoothly than a higher bodied beer while the carbonation is mild enough to not contribute any carbonic bite .

smells good but not really the over-the-top hop aroma i had been expecting .  arrives a beautiful clear garnet with brown tints . there is a 1/2 finger head of off-white bubbles , which quickly falls to nothing at all . a little disappointed in that . no lacing .  medium mouthfeel .

the beer has a sweet bubble gum-like smell with faint malt and spices in the background . the smell is a lot stronger than the taste .  cracked the bottle and poured into a tulip . the colour is great , but the lack of head is not .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation . pretty smooth .

smell was hershey 's chocolate syrup .  color was a pale amber-yellow , a bit murky . i had to pour it pretty aggressively to get a finger of head which faded quickly smelled of wheat/grain , perfumy honey and melon , graham crackers when i buried my nose in it .  all that being said it felt quite nice on the palate with good levels of carbonation .

like an entire pine tree shoved down your throat .  it poured very heady with a murky with a hazy-straw color .  ... the aroma is super malty , brown sugar , bread , prunes , dark fruits and grape soda dominate , a hint of yeast and alcohol on the finish . a super malty aroma , taste crushes your senses with hops and alcohol . almost makes me gag . this is so bitter , like they confused a dopplebock with double ipa . the hops are totally misplaces , trying to be creative , just ruined the beer .

smells hoppy and inviting , made my mouth water a bit .  ( a ) - pours a cloudy caramel color . produced some white to transparent bottles .  the mouthfeel on this beer is very creamy and pleasant , however this beer seriously taste like they made a guinness and then ripped out all the good taste .

okay , even before i smell or taste this one , i am dubious . think sweettart when smelling this beer .  a : clear amber orange color . light head , no real lacing .  mouthfeel is nice though , smooth and just right in the carbonation .

flat-out loaded with fragrances . sour cherry , roasted malt , english toffee , cream sherry & many others that my still-budding nose will be able to detect with more training . looks & smells like a winner , just need to let it warm up a bit .  brutes a beastly beer brewed with american barley , wheat and corn , fermented on oak for months with brett and finished with three types of champagne yeast . excelsior ! pale sunflower with a very slight haze , topped with a one-finger head of puffy white that fizzles away to a gaunt , bubbly ring .  just as smooth as it is crisp . wet maltiness , toasty with a slight tiny sugary note .

aroma of coffee and chocolate , nothing in your face just subtle . i keep going back to the aroma and to me it is excellent and getting better .  a-bright copper with a thin off-white head that flares up with agitation but quickly reduces to a thin veil and leaves zero lace .  the feel is almost chewy and very dry .

definite apricot aroma pouring through .  a : a lot browner than i expected . actually , more like a deep copper , with very few red tones if any at all . tiny rim of head , with not much lacing to speak of .  fairly full in body , awfully fruity for an ipa with distinct apricot flavors .

the aroma is very fruity and pleasant . slight grapefruit smell with the malts definitely present .  pitch black with just the merest suggestion of a tan head at the edges .  m : thick and heavy , but not cloying .

s : the nose is quite off-putting with acidic , sour grain , likely attributed to the roasted malts . the chocolate and coffee that you usually expect from the style are overpowered by the sourness and the alcohol . t : luckily , the flavor is better than the nose would lead you to believe . d : though i 'm not generally one to be a stickler for style , this beer seemed more like a bsda than an ris .  appearance : heady , pale orange in color . sediment floats around after poured and finally settles to the bottom .  the palate is smooth .

draught at brewpub , copenhagen . toasted malts , milky chocolate , banana , nuts , butter and pears in the aroma . medium-bodied with notes of toasted malts , banana and acidic green apples with touches of fudge . malty finish of over-riped bananas and fudge with disturbing notes of green immature apples .  exhibits a golden body with a reddish tinge . not a lot of head , but plenty of dancing bubbles as i tilt the glass .  mouthfeel is medium and highly spritzy with tons of champagne-like prickle .

just an awesome and complex aroma ! all of the same on the taste buds but there is also a hint of cherry syrup .  i have always been a pretty big fan of lagunitas . it is boozy but i cant say its messy . this is fairly well crafted and it seems to age pretty well .  m & d- i do like the mouthfeel , it matches the style nicely .
s : smells roasty and slightly matly sweet with a hint of floral hops .  pours a classic barleywine deep amber with no head but a nice head .  the mouthfeel is quite good .
in the nose i got a strong bananna and clove hit that i liked .  appearance was a little lacking .  mouthfeel is good .

the smell is of sweet roasted malt , nut meats , with hints of honey and coffee/toffee .  appearance : deep brown/black color with a thin , light-tan head that fades quickly , leaving virtually no lacing .  the mouthfeel was decently thick . this beer needed carbonation and some balance to it .

smells are bourbon , that 's all . tastes like jim beam , vanilla and some cinnamon at the very end , not that good . i love bourbon beers , but this beer did not have the malty backbone to balance out the booze .  poured chilled in flared glass a : solid black ; good carbonation , but very little head , dissipating quickly s : sweet , caramel , brown sugar t : sweet , creamy ; roasted barley comes through prominently ; moderately hopped ; cocoa powder overtones overall , quite a solid offering .  m : medium carbonation , light body and a nice dry creamy finish .

first smell gives you a nice fresh floral hop burst . this one started off promising but on closer examination it is lacking .  opaque black with a muddy brown head . weak retention for a stout .  really good smooth , medium mouthfeel in this one , probably its best feature .
lemon is really nice , and a mineral water background .  not really any lacing to talk about and looks slightly watery .  on the plus side , very smooth .

unimpressive start . aroma of lilikoi [ passion fruit ] literally jumps out of the glass . quite sweet and some citrus . i give kb kudos for making a fruit beer and making no bones about it ... no fruit subtelty here . overall , it is worth picking one up just to taste the lilikoi .  despite the seeming lack of head , the carbonation holds its own and provides a fresh , lively beer .  decent mouthfeel , medium-full with the right amount of carbonation ; probably the best aspect of this beer .

sam adams got the nose just to that citrus hoppy american ipa . really good use of hops with a good but tame malt back .  appearance : pours a pale , golden , hazy color , like a witbier or other wheat beer . has a small , white head that dissipates quickly and leaves some spotty lacing .  m : nicely bitter , typical ale feel with alcohol front and center , no foaming action . t : overpowering alcohol made this seem like i was having a shot , the licorace flavor and hops fruitiness were strong but a bit of a can taste and a thin malt flavor ended it .

looks like a typical straw-yellow pale lager , but actually smells of clean malts with biscuit and toast aromas .  as i arrived at the beerfestival within the first 90 minutes after its opening on the first day , i expected this beer to be very fresh , and so it was . it pours a straw or very pale golden colour , with rimmed white head and minimum carbonation .  very true mouthfeel for a lager .

smells of rich and creamy coffee backed up by sweetened dark chocolate and a small hint of roasted malts . overall the nose on this is great - if you like coffee , and the flavor is n't too far behind .  poured with a lavish brown head which was easily fluffed up with a swirl of the glass . the color was copper-almost brown and clear .  mouthfeel : fairly heavy and smooth overall : i 'm not at all sure the whole 'double wit ' thing works .

very mild smell , maybe a hint of fruit but nothing else . empty . tasty , smooth pils , quite drinkable .  pours a nice dark brown with amber hilights , a decent-sized beige head that faded away .  i dunno i expected more from this m - medium bodied with a decent amount of carbonation .

smell is very light and fruity , with a sweet almost strawberry hop aroma .  pours black but too clear and clean with reddish hues sparking like an irish red . appropriate foam ( little-to-none ) and lacing ( sporadic at best ) levels for an american imperial stout .  body is medium with nice carbonation and a semi dry finish .

it had a very hop floral aroma which i liked . they do n't say on the bottkle what hops they use , but i would guess there are large amounts of cascade .  poured into a tulip glass . a - pours a thick midnight black with a small tan head . the head dissipated fairly quickly and there is no lacing . a little light gets through around the edges showing dark brown tint .  this beer was quite thick in body but not too smooth .

smell is clean and clearly malty . pleasant citrus hop scent that is mild enough to let you smell a bit of toast and biscuit in the malt . i give this a little extra credit for maintaining a balance .  nice crisp refreshing flemish red . not as sweet as some of the flemish reds , but that helps the drinkability considerably . i would consider this the perfect beer to match to some seafood ( mussels , clams , ... ) for lunch on a hot day .  m - on the thin side of medium bodied , nice and foamy carbonation .

actually smells pretty good . very clear and light straw colored .  the appearance is nothing special , dark black , no head to speak of , but looks a bit syrupy .  nice mouthfeel with good carbonisation and te freshness of the esterpalate .

very nice . a tiny bit of simple syrup hides behind the hops .  11.2oz bottle and very fresh . at first it started to go down like a flat mello-yellow a little lemon-limon but as i started to drink the beer it became much more complex .  one saving grace for this beer is its mouthfeel , which i thought was quite good : light and not too carbonated . a poor geuze , overall .

smells really quite nice , with a distinct bit of yeast , tea-like hop , and honey-cake malt sweetness - much more interesting than your average mexican lager .  the color is a dark dark brown , not terribly pretty . this is a top-notch beer , find it and drink it !  mouhfeel is sticky with a full body and medium carbonation .

it was nice on the nose which gave my higher hopes than the label . i just bought it cuz it was kind of funny and it was a porter . it overall was very disjointed .  harvest ale 2000 review : pours cloudy mahogany reddish in color with a small beige head ; spotty lacing on the snifter .  pretty good carbonation .

let me preface by saying i love rootbeer ... pours a hazy brown to chestnut color with a 1/2 '' white head . no lacing & minimal head retention smell : sassafras & licorice up front , loving it taste : huge sassafras with hints of lemon , licorice & jagermeister or cough sryup , but either work for me . emphasis on the aforementioned overwhelms though .  pours ruby brown with a thin head that immediately becomes a slowly vanishing wispy swirl .  mouthfeel is dry and crisp , with a medium-light body .

smells like a crazy bouquet of citrusy hops , but i can still detect a hint of malt . this may have the best aroma of any beer i have tried to date . perfectly balanced . body is perfect for the style .  this is a full flavor beer and should n't be compared to the weak tasting beers of the us . it is not for the average person because of its unique taste . i have heard of the younger crowd mixing it with lemonade..yuck !  nose is a creamy butterscotch sweetness , and palate of creamy sweet butterscotch with a balanced bitter and a touch of gypsum . absolutely one yummy ale and a must try for anyone . bass pale ale has been on my list of beers to buy when the price is right . bass pale ale is a good tasting pale ale that has been around for a very long time . well , i just went through a twelve pack and lo and behold this brew has turned to banta podo , it is nothing at all what it used to be !

the nose is very perfumey . berry esters and sandlewood . earthy yeast .  the nice little head is the saving grace but to be honest not a very enticing looking beer .  head poors thick and has good retention though s - nice hoppy aroma t - strong hop flavor , but i find it unbalanced , i like a good hoppy beer , but the best in my opinion have a good malt balance m - the only aspect of this beer that i truly consider high quality is the mouthfeel ; it is smooth and dry , very good .

smell : cherry sweetness is plentiful here and easy to pull from the glass .  p : ruddy brown body , darker in the center . very small , light brown head . very fizzy . right up there with hazelnut brown nectar as my favorite brown .  the mouth feel is great , but the musty basement taste is not .

your typical looking nitro-pour stout ... very attractive looking and leaves huge amounts of lacing . s. mainly malts . i have to really concentrate to really get any smells out of it . i was hoping for some powerful chocolate smells but not much i 'm getting . t. a little better than smell but nothing really standing out . lacking sweetness imo .  had this on tap years ago at old c 's and fell in love but now this is from a bomber ... poured a dark , rich brown with a very thin off white head that diminished very quickly .  i dont know if they have sour tarts in va , but this incense of baby and elderly lambic beers has a unique flavor . it has definite lambic feel to it .

at least it smells nice - good 'n ' clovey with banana and orange rind .  appearance - 3.0 pours a finger of loose beige head that gradually reduces over a clear , dark reddish brown body . head retention is less than impressive .  the mouthfeel was good with real depth .

aromas are quite nice , very dark bitter chocolate like with a bit of a roasted coffee quality to it as well .  murky and complex ruby-brown pour , with almost no head and very still .  huge caramel malt aroma is kept in check by an equally huge grapefruit accented aroma ... simplistic , but i if you like those smells ... its ambrosia . finish is citric , grapefruity and wow massively malty . if i liked massive quantities of hops and caramel malt , id love this ... i dont though and it gets boring to me like i imagine big doses of flavors i like would get boring to someone who didnt like then as much as i do .

the aroma is clean and citrusy , a mild lemon aroma , and a hint of grapefruit .  on the back label is a somewhat disturbing picture of a drunk german man pointing at his stein . deep copper hue , very clear with a head that disappears quickly , i guess the more this ages the more the head takes a hit .  a smooth , creamy , but still slightly crisp-feeling beer , with enough body to keep a better tasting beer on par with the best of them . the mouthfeel tries to carry this one , but there 's just not much there to propel .
s- a big malt presence and a decent barrel presence .  i drank this out of the bottle because i did n't have a glass . extremely drinkable .  light bodied and smooth yet dry .
s - ginger , malts , and wheat .  surprisingly hazy for a pilsner , pale straw with rim of foam .  good mouthfeel , and went down well .

big sweet coffee , plum , raisen smell with some bitter chocolate as well . the mouth is thick and flat.. i am shocked after seeing the reviews here.. but for me it is a flat , overly intense beer that really lacks balence.dissapointing for me ... not drinkable enough to have another .  a : pours a 1 finger frothy , white head with decent retention . beer is a deep , clear orange . lacing is sparse and with little stick .  good smooth mouthful , did a good job on carbonation .

o/d - good aroma but not a highly drinkable stout . average but acceptable .  the hoppiness is very apparent from the moment you open the bottle . the hops and the carbonation synergize excellently with the milky texture . very well balanced quality beer , very drinkable  mouthfeel : medium carbonation and medium body .

smell very light , fruity hop aroma with some out of place notes of grain . this smells like a bad macro .  pours a deep dark amber with a small head that melts to nothing very quickly .  it had a very nice texture on the tongue as well as in the back of the mouth .

extra credit for this unique situation .  pours brown and hazy with a decent head . not much lacing in my glass , but there 's enough carbonation to last through the drink .  the body of the beer 's great , and pretty ideal for the style .

smell is super soft , as served cold , nothing really until it warmed a bit and smelled like rubbing alcohol .  dark brown pour with little head and little lacing , still not a bad looking beer but nothing too pretty .  emphasis on the hops really drew me in a- a full amber body of a beer . nothing but malt . you need some type of hop flavor when you write six hops on the label though m- creamy and overwhelming taste that attacks your mouth . i do like this aspect of it d- just being honest ... if your battle cry is hops , you need to have some . the unstoppable malt attack makes this not enjoyable .
