the belhaven was floral , perfectly present : not too strong , not too weak .  pours a nice clear caramel color . with the pour comes a brief flash of slightly tawny head . falls fast leaving no lacing .  i loved the smoothness , but just ca n't get past strength of the cherry . it had a medium mouthfeel that seemed extremely well balanced . my only complaint here would be that the carbonation is just slightly more than i prefer .

it has no detectable aroma hops but you get surprised a good dose of bitterness and hop flavor .  appearance- copper-ish color , very clear . white head which dissipates quickly , no lacing .  nice carbonation but remains smooth going down ... not bad at all ... this is a stout ... .by nature not all that drinkable .

the smell is faint and hard to get a good idea on , a little vinegar , an earthy , woody smell , some sweetness . i always associate new belgium with fat tire and forget that they have some pretty great brews out there and this one is one of them . i think the 2010 vintage is pretty good also and i might come back later and review it next time i crack open a bottle , two 22oz flanders bombers in one night is too much sour though .  fizzy yellowy brown in color .  m - medium bodied and slightly chewy . moderate carbonation .

the bouquet is quite appealing with a strong breadiness and light citrus notes . despite good looks and a solid smell , this only gets a slight pass .  12 oz - & gt ; saison dupont glass a ~ pours a very pale lemonade with excessive carbonation and large bubbles . not great lacing .  m : chewy . good feel .

a nice aroma of toasted malt and baked ginger snaps slightly thin on mouthfeel taste : some caramel sweetness and fragrant hop spiciness with a thin , ok wimpy malt base .  pours a very pale gold color with a small white dome and minimal lacing . kind of dull looking actually .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation . pretty smooth here . it did have a very nice mouthfeel though .

a : cloudy gold with very little head s : very fruity , strong raspberry aroma , slightly malty t : very raspberry and not much else m : very watery and carbonated , overall i felt more like i was drinking raspberry flavored carbonated water than beer d : very drinkable really not a very interesting beer at all .  pretty lousy head really . looks quite flat by the end . overall : while the look was unappealing , especially the lousy head , and the feel nothing to write home about , the nose and flavor were quite enjoyable .  milky , filling , decent carbonation and not overly assulting ... pretty decent feel .

the taste is also very beer , but that special smell is also expressed in the taste .  tuskers lager pours a slightly hazy pale yellow with almost no head .  m - fine . right where it should be . my favorite part of the beer .

winey scent , as advertised is the vanilla and perhaps a touch of raisin .  i received my beer with no head and was barely able to generate anything . it had aa clear yellow color . this beer was served too cold , but as it warmed up it became a decent lawnmower beer . i would reach for one of these to quench my thirst in the summertime .  mouthfeel ; nice almost creamy my first winter warmer and i expected more taste ...

it 's does n't have a terribly strong aroma . grains & malt , with a bit of sweetnes and hops . not terribly impressed . very drinkable , nothing offensive about this beer but nothing that i got very excited about .  pours a very pale straw color ... smells rich for a lager .  mouthfeel is very thick but a nice amount of carbonation .

the smell is of beer and yep chipotle sauce !  i do occasionally seek out an american light lager , but this will be a bit extreme for me . bottle at fridge temp into a room temp weizen glass . quick rising white baking soda fizz comes up to about 3 '' and quickly falls to a thin ring and skim of varying bubbles . surprisingly good lace on such an anemic foam . the beer is a very pale straw .  good carbonation .

s - potent smell . incredible amount of citrus power that comes from something like cascade hops . its almost sharp on the nose . earthy and grassy as well . very bitter , but does have some malt notes .  a - a very vigorous pour into a snifter yields a one finger white head that dissipates before you can put the bottle down . it 's a very pale , hazy straw yellow color with absolutely nothing on top after the head goes away and leaves no lacing .  medium bodied and highly carbonated and crisp .

best buy date is october 2009 aroma - a slight bite but 95 % of this beers nose is made of blackberry , which is nice . appearance - cloudy yello with no real carbonation visible .  appearance - cloudy , less than average amount of carbonation , lackluster bronzish head and short retention . cloudy brew that looks like an amber lake water .  t- very dissapointing . a peppery start with a soapy finish . md- thick and creamy .

smell : strong berry smell , almost medicinal taste : the blackberry taste is a bit too overwhelming , some weak malts and a similarly weak , odd bitter flavor just manage to peak through .  pours a two finger white head that fades to a ring leaving no lace . almost cloudy color .  m- good carbonation and quite smooth .

very clean , but nearly empty of flavor ; slightly sweet syrupy malts up front with hot fusel alcohol finish . the aroma is ok , but the flavor is almost entirely missing apart from the over-strong alcohol .  pours a murky brown with some amber hues scattered about . it 's uninspiring to look at , smell , and taste .  not if you like an imperial stout , no . there is a little too much pitch ( black ) in the brew . that is a yummy chocolate nose about half way through , but a little chipped too much with yeast over-all , and maybe a bit too much biscuit ? you can have both better beers and better baltic porters .

the appearance was a dark amber to almost a dark cherry wood . the smell gave minor hints of malts with little carbonation .  pours a clear light golden yellow . no head , no carbonation , no lacing .  medium-full in the mouth with soft and fine carbonation . a meager beer by all accounts .

smell definitely of blueberry with enough malt to know that this is a beer . overall i do n't believe that taste lives up to the smell .  on tap in a goose island chalice at bodega on 10/7/11 clear , pale golden color . poured no head , save a pinstripe ring of retention . meh .  the mouthfeel is nice and soft , with pleasant and light carbonation .

s - malty nose has bits of brown sugar , molasses , caramel , and something of a somewhat spicy quality t & m - big caramel and dark roasted malt hit with a defined sweetness .  pours golden yellow , and head dissipated very fast . is there really yeast in there ?  the mouthfeel is pleasantly bubbly , with just enough body to make one quite happy .
a big raspberry odor , very sweet .  a : crystal clear yellow brew , small head that dissipates quickly . no lacing .  decently carbonated beverage with a mild body .

s - the smell and flavor had the characteristic spicing of a belgian -- mild orange & coriander -- nice . t - but -- once you read this , i fear you 'll never taste it in any other way , so be forewarned -- it 's a classic coors pilsner masked as a belgian wit .  nice carbonation . clear . disappointing head retention and zero lacing .  great feel . creamy and heavy , but not in a bad way . the feel is great , but the aromatics and flavor depth are lacking .

smell : on nose , besides being lightly grainy and malty , it 's spicy and aromatic as well -- refreshingly spicy aroma mixed of wheatish note , kind of coriander seed , and even summer berry or strawberry 's lightly sweet aroma .  served in a plastic pilsner glass at the rooftop sky lounge in the hilton , virginia beach . colour wise it was a cloudy pale yellow with about a 1/4 '' of white head .  crisp , vegetable flavor but more than the average adjunct lager . nice body and pleasant aftertaste as well .

smell is actually good with malt hints .  this is only like 10 % better than the typical american swill in a can , pbr has a better aftertaste than this , the flavors are not well put together .  m : the body is medium with a moderate level of carbonation .

smell : nice tangy chocolate aroma to it with a subtle malt compliment .  a : pours a cloudy yellow-green with a fizzy 1/2 finger head which rapidly disappears . d : perhaps on a very hot day , if i were parched beyond measure , then this would be acceptable .  it is smooth , with soft carbonation . it is crisp and refreshing with a clean , short aftertaste .

sweet jesus this is an aromatic beer . had a pint of cask conditioned last night , and halfway through it my saliva glands had gone dry . this beer has a wonderful fresh hop aroma . aroma might even be too subtle a word for it . it was a powerful smell , obviously it had been dry hopped .  poured off the tap at the blue-collar dive turned hipster scene esox in b-town . crystal clear and full of rising carbonation but very little bleach white head and it showed almost no retention .  it is extremely smooth with only a tingling initial mouthfeel that smoothens in its finish .

immediately after opening the bottle , a strong chocolate smell emerges .  a : clear , yellowish , macrobrew look . m : average good , easy to drink , but unremarkable .  and lingers on my tongue . m : extremely creamy head .

aroma is earthy from black malts , with pleasing chicory notes .  pours light yellow with a moderate amount of carbonation and a frothy white head that dissipates .  the mouthfeel is creamy and the finish has a creaminess to it as well .

garlic and citrus fruit are very present . pine also makes an appearance as well as marijuana . i love it ! t : tastes almost like it smells . i do n't get much garlic , not nearly as much as the smell offered up .  has a very pale yellow color with a small head .  mouth : heavy and very smooth . good carbonation level .

bit of a toasted and floral aroma , guessing from the malts and hops respectively .  appearance : very light amber , clear , weak head , poor carbonation . behind all the hype and advertising this really is not the most interesting beer in the world .  mouthfeel is light medium and pretty smooth , crisp .

nice , mild , citrus hop smell - mainly getting orange and apricot aromas . this stuff looks and smells a lot better than it tastes .  bottle , 16.5 ibu , a : pours gold with a fizzy white head with poor head retention .  mouthfeel was smooth and medium bodied .

enticing , really . half and half infused coffee , wave of hops and bitter dark chocolate ride the malt tide into a wall of flaked oats , leading to a dry powdered cocoa fade .  poured a golden brown color with a 1 finger head that disapated rather quickly for a beligan ale , no lacing noticed .  m : full-bodied and well-blended with good carbonation . definitely a sticky feel .

likewise ale drinkers may order a smithwick 's with a guinness head . s - i rate every beers smell as average due to the fact that i can not smell t - smooth and refreshing . i am not a guinness draught fan but i am a smithwicks fan . o - p e r f e c t in every way possible  clear , average amber yellow with virtually zero head rentention and definetly zero lacing .  good carbonation .

nose is like candied pineapple ; candied fruit ; fresh fruit cake ; mouthfeel is rich and creamy and mouthfilling .  i drank this one against the expressed wishes of my good friend william pang ( queens , ny ) . pours an almost impossible clear , pale yellow-gold , with almost no head or lacing to speak of . not hint of corn , malt , hops , etc . very easy to drink , not a displeasing taste , and could definitely down a bunch of these in one sitting , not that i would want to .  md-light body with a smooth feel . moderately carbonated , but the carb sting on my tongue augments the sour .

s- big hops for a pale ale . pretty balanced in the smell . t- the comparison to furious stops here . the hops are much more muted but there is still a nice breadiness and a little bit of wet cardboard .  falstaff is typical macro yellow color .  the beer is light and refreshing with just medium carbonation , so it leans towards the smooth side .

s : a very mild smell of chocolate and smokey malts . t : heavy on the malts at first then smoothes into a nice bitter sweet drink with hints of coffee , chocolate , and caramel .  went to eat yesterday and this , budlight , miller light , coors light and fosters was the tap selection . it was extremely clear and pale with an almost fluorescent yellow tint . big foamy white head that falls flat .  mouth is good .

the aroma was very malty with a huge nutty quality and i could almost smell the butter melting in the pint glass .  poured light amber , almost yellowish-orange with a smallish head with big bubbles that quickly dissipated except for slight traces .  the mouthfeel is nice and dry with a good body and carbonation level .
aroma of hops , caramel malt , and orange peel .  a : pale , unimpressive yellow . very little lacing .  m - it was crisp , sharp and very smooth . a medium bodied beer with a dry finish .

the nose also shines.. it 's belgian sweetness accented by a unique floral combination of spicy zings and zips . for a lighter , saison style beer , this showcases alot of the darker , overripe belgian-associated fruits in the nose like figs and dates . also , a dark brown sugar syrup aroma wafts ... competes fiercely with the scents of a flower garden . this is one outrageously complex nose to wrestle with . thick and spicy ... that 's the best way to describe this . a base more suited to a bspa allows for a silky , syrupy , stomach-warming beer that insists on sipping for enjoyment . very floral character is perfumy in the way that hops are n't , and the bitterness associated can be quite jarring . almost like eating the non-edible petal of something aromatic like a rose . perhaps not the most drinkable beer due to three floyds ' patented excess , but a noble effort at a style- applause-worthy .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  mouthfeel was fine , not too thin , smooth going down .

the aroma was a tease..sweet cherry , plum , sugar , molasses , and a slight hint of citrus .  zywiec beer pours a pale yellow with a white head from a brown twelve ounce bottle with a beer thermometer that says the beer is ready to be drank if you can see the logo .  mouthfeel : the carbonation of this beer makes it super crisp with a dry finish .

a few advertant whiffs of the aroma were great , of a rich pumpkiny note , but i had trouble reproducing it when i stuck my nose right in it .  clear golden with thin soda pop head that does n't stick around or retain itself at all .  taste : just as smooth as it is crisp with a creamy medium body , not too much on the clove spiciness but it is there and holds on through the finish .

smell is brown sugar , caramel , slight pine , and amarillo hops .  the appearance was pretty pathetic and basically looked like an amber/red with weak head and lacing .  thick , smooth , lightly carbonated .

s - spices and pumpkin , seems enticing t - what a letdown ! bitter spices hit you , followed by an unpleasant sweetness .  this one was pretty cheap . clearish yellow color and thin head .  m : good medium body with a smooth feel throughout .

australian for beer ? `` australian for beer '' depends on where in australia you are . compared to american lagers it does have a nice bitterness to it . do n't kid yourself and think they drink this swill in australia though . it 's as australian as schaefer is american .  this brew has a slight malty aroma that arose from a very small head of fine bubbles and a light yellow orange colored body .  has a creamy mouthfeel and was mildly complex .

smelled pretty good , got the orange peel and the spicy yeast all up in the nose . the taste lacked a lot of what was good about the smell .  poured with almost no head at all ... dark brown almost black color ... no lacing whatsoever .  nice puckering sandy dry mouth feel . the key to the witbier style is taming the coriander ... making it present but complimentary , not dominant ... i 'll take hoegaarden thanks ... .this wit is not ddc 's strongest offering .

there 's an average amount of lacing left behind on the glass . aroma is oak , pine hops , vanilla , caramel and some citrusy hops . however , the taste is n't as appealing as the aroma . the brew tastes like floral and pine hops , oak and caramel malt , but the flavors are subtle and seemed to be watered down .  a : it has a clear and golden body with no head at all .  despite this , the mouthfeel is solid and fairly creamy with a nice dry finish .
nose was heavy sweet . a bit of floral characteristics noted .  the yellow label says it all .  the mouthfeel is at least good . very crisp and clean .

s - nice fresh pine hop smell with some malts in there too .  a light amber-red ale that pours with little fanfare , not much foam , and a peculier fruity and flowery aroma .  full bodied and slightly smooth .

the nose is full of big citrus hops , with tones of floral and grass . this is very boozy , in my opinion .  there was a time when i would find this to be a regular drinkable beer , but things have changed and made the sweet/wheat combination taste a little much for me on this one . the yellow bottle and `` honey '' title should let you know what 's going on and it is n't wonderful tho it is technically sweet .  a nice mouthfeel , with plenty of creaminess .

aroma : knickerbocker red presents with a sweet nose . there is a little woodiness in the nose as well . taste : the initial taste has a sweetness .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  very coating mouthfeel , stays with you .

s - nose is of citrus hops and alcohol .  had at the brewery tour , color was typical straw and had very minor head .  the interesting thing is that the body did not feel light ... . actually pretty full .

aroma is resiny , fragrant , minty and smoky . borderline `` off '' with a solvent like fusel alcohol feel to it .  beer on the floor and counter is poor appearance , thus the low rating there .  nice , filing carbonation , medium-high drying at the end . very nice .

nutty , roast malt aromas with slight fig or raisin fruit esters .  pours a clear , pale yellow with a minimal pure white head that dissipates quickly . this beer almost reminds of the hoegaarden white .  this was best part of this beer .

this light ale has a prominent buttery sweet aroma and flavor with almost no bitter quality and a bit of a watery body .  smell was good for a cheap brew , with odors of hops , malt , and some alcohol . this is a cheap quantity over quality beer . for being a cheap , macro made ice beer , it 's not bad .  mouthfeel is big surpy almost very full but how could it not be considering the malt in this beer .

i smell ripe fruit in the nose and hops in the background ... very nice .  unimpressive cheap beer yellow with a head that flatlines , this is a beer meant to be drunk out of the can ; ) a fruity , apply nose greets , and a sharp carbonation shakes your hand . very cheap for japanese standards and utilizing a type of green bean , this beer gets points for being interesting .  mouthfeel was refreshing and zesty .

the aroma was very sweet with a nice hop presence .  pale amber orange in colour , very lightly hazy . it 's definately not bud light lime or miller chill either , though it might appeal to the same demographics . a quality summer quencher with mass appeal .  mouthfeel is good with a nice clean finish .

the smell is straight bourbon and barrel . there is n't much going on here other than that . the bourbon is strong and boozy , what you 'd expect from a bourbon barrel stout .  12 oz bottle poured into pint glass a : straw yellow , about 1/2 of head that disappears very quickly to nothing with no lacing at all .  mouthfeel was the most notable portion being medium/light , crisp , and coats the mouth nicely .

s : heavy strong barbecue and smoke smell . this is very deceiving , smell great but thats about it .  this is a pale gold beer with not much head and liveley carbonation . i ca n't smell anything really beyond the giant lime wedge that was perched on my glass so i 'm giving it the benefit of the doubt and rating it average .  m : highly carbonated to complement the pepperiness .

n : nose actually has a lot of coffee , roast , some sweet syrupy malts , dark malts , a touch of vanilla , touch of chocolate . t : starts with a lot of coffee and roasted malts , some chocolate , some fake vanilla flavors , really fake infused vanilla ... very watery too , damn , i was excited thinking this was pretty good until the taste . terrible !  pours an exremely pale straw color with a thin , white head that 's waving goodbye .  has a fairly refreshing clean finish , and nice body .

s- almost like how i would invison a dark chocolate syrup smelling ; very sweet . also has a huge scent of malt . no real hop scent detected .  appearance is fizzy yellow , a bit of head , almost no lacing .  not very sweet . solid body with a lot of carbonation .

pours light clear copper with some really nice lacing and retention ... the aroma is is all honey , but still light . the honey has a bitterness to it which is unique . a new aroma i 've yet to come across , bitter honey ... the taste is really disappointing as all the honey on the front is gone and replaced by very bitter hops .  looks like piss with a nice head , although it dissolves down to nothing with the quickness .  m : average , fine ... . good carbonation , nice density and thickness .

it does smell nice though .  pours a clear sunshine and hay yellow . no head or foam and very sparse bubbling .  medium carbonation and a thin body that finishes mostly clean with a touch of dry euro-hops .

smells like cocoa . earthy & bready with a hint of coffee . this seems to be more of a strong porter in my opinion .  it poured into my pint glass and formed a large foamy white head that dissipated after 2 mins . it pours the pale yellow of a coors or bud , but with clouds of yeast inside .  mouthfeel : crisp and clean , it feels more like a pilsner than an ipa , which , in my book isnt necessarily a bad thing , but it is unusual . overall : alaskan made a half-way decent ipa here , but it seems much more suitable for a hot night in georgia than anytime in alaska .

but truthfully besides the appearance - which is an awesome black stout with a nice head - the smell is a malty chocolate coffee bomb , there is n't much else .  the liquid is a bit cloudy ; the colour is pale amber . the off white foam forms an uninspired finger thick uneven head . in fact , the whole beer looks a bit tired .  feel is medium body with ample carbonation .

s -- nice citrus hop nose ... oranges , grapes , apples .  it poured a hazy lemon with a fizzy white head that dissipated quickly .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . pretty average when compared to other beers within the style .

smell-a real burst of ripe sweet fruits ( melon , cantolope ) and fresh cut greenery- ie- no piney/resin or citrus notes .  pale yellow color under a fluffy head that dwindles quickly .  mouthfeel is pretty full-bodied , with good , medium carbonation that fills things out . overall , this beer has only the minor trappings of a successful one ( looks , mouthfeel ) .

has a very strong coffee smell upon the initial pour and that translates over your tastebuds on the fist sip . one of the disappointing issues i found is that flavour is lost upon successive drinks unless you allow some time to pass between quaffs .  appearance : holy crap , this beer is overcarbonated . every effort is repulsed by a tremendous avalanche of bubbles -- i waited until the head died entirely , then attempted to fill the glass several times with no success . i have no idea about quality control/consistency with watch city , but it looks like they rarely bottle their beers . anyway , other than the head , it 's a thick , cloudy dark brown .  m - not bad ( if it were not for actually having to experience the taste to experience the mouthfeel ) full and smooth with active carbonation .

nose of pineapple , brown sugar , pine and rum . taste is , in a word , hops .  appearance : served on tap it had a golden color with orange hues and a fizzy white head on it . the retention was very poor . the head barely lasted from the tap to getting the glass in front of me .  m- medium bodied , moderately carbonated .

aroma 's a delicate and complex mix of acetic sourness with some mustiness and cherry fruit ... some oak comes out as it warms .  i found this at one stop liquors in johnson city , tennessee , and had it shipped to moscow via air freight . hmm ... pours pale orange ( should n't something named midas be gold , at least ? ) under a very thin 1/3 finger off white head that fizzles as quickly as it forms . purely from the appearance , it reminds me of some pretty bad russian beers of the zhigulovskoye line .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied and quite smooth & viscous . moderate carbonation .

the smell is strong and pungent and rather pleasing . overall this is not a bad beer , but then again , nothing special either .  beer was part of a sample tray . a-gold body , white ring of a head s-strong berry smell t-again , berry upfront smell seems to cover other flavors m-medium/light d-good thirst quencher but not very good for much else .  it has a refreshing dryness that definitely aids this beer and makes it very drinkable . it is a decent beer but i wish the jasmine was complimented by hops instead of ( maybe , if they are there ) overpowering them completely .

looks , pours and smells great . the main thing was an aftertaste of cigarettes , not really sure where that would come from but it was a distinct off flavor .  a : very clear orange/yellow color with what started out as a `` soda-like '' head that disappeared .  mouthfeel was pretty good , it was medium bodied , on the thick side , and quite creamy .

the smell was the best part of this beer . this would be a good summer beer .  soapy eggshell cap has poor retention . it quickly dissolves and leaves the beer looking like apricot cider . i had two bottles of it , and both suffered from the same deficiencies in their appearance .  mouthfeel - the mouthfeel was pretty good . even tho the head was essentially nil , the carbonation was very active which was noticeable in the mouth .

s - dark fruits like blueberry and chocolate . deep maltiness amongst fairly strong alcohol aroma .  pours a pale clear orange color with lots of bubbles clinging to the glass . there is a thin white head that even with a generous pour only brought up a 1/2 a finger head and no lacing .  the mouthfeel is full bodied for the style , with subtle carbonation .

s : sour notes of over ripe dark fruits and some our bruin lactose . sweet toffee and maybe milky chocolate .  a : pours a wheat color a shade or two darker than a typical american adjunct lager with a fizzy white head -- little retention and no lacing worth mentioning .  very thick and viscous with a fairly light amount of carbonation .

smell : aroma from this beer is very faint . smells of chocolate , toffee and coffee are present .  a- bottle poured into a snifter , barely any head , just large bubbles that vanish quickly leaving a small trace of wispy lace , walnut coloring . it came across one note with lacking appearance , nose , and roundness in flavor .  even though the menu at goose island says that sticke alt is usually a unadvertised `` secret '' beer made by alt brewers in dusseldorf to reward its regulars , it does n't explain that sticke alts are usually made with more malt and hops and brewed to a higher alcohol percentage . and after tasting it , i see why . at 4.5 % abv , its is a little low for a sticke and the hops were nearly non-existent . aromas were rather off putting with a stale malt aroma dominating . this was a very sweet cloying alt with not enough hops to balance and the aftertaste was reminicient of a ringwood brew . they could just take their hex nut brown ale and call it an alt and be closer to the style .
very enticing . has a fizzy malty nutty taste .  a thirst quenching na beer nothing offensive in the least .  medium body with moderate carbonation . quite smooth .

aroma is quite nice , nutmeg , sweet pepper , some malts . unfortunately , the praise stops there .  appearance is that of light yellow spring water , typical of this style .  m : decently carbonated but morphs into a nice creaminess . pleasant .

s-chocolate and tart cherry with a roasted malt characteristic .  the beer pours a pale yellow with not a whole lot of head or anything remotely interesting .  first off , let me say that unibroue is my favorite brewery and belgians are my favorite style . that said -- dude , the smell of this beer is definitely funky . pretty disgusting . luckily , the toe jam does n't come through in the taste . it tastes like a witbier with a hint of apple . if i want a witbier , i 'll buy ommegang witte instead .

s-amazing smell of berrys but oh so sweet . t- good for the first few but after 2 or 3 its off to the dentist .  there is no head left after a very fast paced , short lived , soda like top . there is some rising carbonation which makes it obvious that the beer did not lose its seal .  m | a refreshingly smooth mouth feel with a gentle bite that keeps you going back for another sip .

smell : grapefruit , hop oil , strawberry . smells alive , maybe because of the bottle conditioning .  appearance is not good . straw yellow color pale and faint .  it 's syrupy and thick with a snappy carbonation , and the combination of the taste and the mouthfeel are not quite cloying .

smell- to me it smelled quite nice with some pilsner notes in there and a spot or two for some sugary malts , a little fruit and some small yeast .  a- not great . kind of bright yellow , not really even golden . maybe corn yellow ?  mouthfeel/overall : body is light to medium with light carbonation . pretty smooth drinking .

s : wow , seriously ? this is as tropical an ipa as i 've smelled . tons of citrus , namely orange , mango , and grapefruit . a good amount of pine encompasses the aroma providing much of the body with the pale malts . t : a little less fruity than the nose . i get a solid dose of orange , pineapple and grapefruit up front riding the wave of pale malt . good citrus flavor .  then i took a bottle of this with me on a trip to burton no trent and stayed at the queen 's in whitch is across the steet from the brewery and asked to see the brewer and was told in no uncertein terms that thay see no one and was even told of another brewer that was more freindly to visit ! we never even had a chance to discuss the bottling problem oh well i just wo n't buy anymore bottles  mouthfeel is full and syrupy will sufficient carbonation .

smell was a nice mix of grainy malts and some floral hops , plus a touch of sweetness ( orange ? ) .  came in a cool skinny can , silver and black . this pours a pee yellow with no head .  the moutfeel is big and bold , full bodied but again , overpowering on the pallette .

s : the nose contains very little of the expected fruity esters , with only a modicum of the spicy phenol scent . the dominant fragrance is mostly a bready yeast with some alcohol aroma . the scent is uncharacteristically restrained .  a very pale beer very yellow , there pale ale and there are pale ale , very pale i thought my beer was now albinos or looked liked mr. jackson . not much head , nothing much and not much carbonisations , a very dull beer to look at .  m : full-bodied , frothy carbonation , pretty smooth , easy drinking for its size .

the smell of the beer had a decent spiciness to it and got me a little curious to taste it .  pours clear gold in color with a foamy/fizzy 1 finger white head that dissipates very quickly and leaves zero lacing .  mouthfeel medium body with nice low carbonation .

the aroma is a refreshing mix of pepper , lemon , sweet spices , baking bread , melons , and bananna . its a moderately sweet , but very spritzy and carbonated beer . all in all , this isnt my choice for a winter beer , but its decent despite a few flaws .  a very murky brown with almost no head .  very clean finish and very easy to drink , it goes down very smoothly .

wow , i was thinking this might be a pretty good beer after smelling it but the flavor profile and mouthfeel were less than satisfactory .  i 've had so many bottles of rolling rock in my life i ca n't even begin to imagine . besides having a bad ass painted bottle , it is one of the most drinkable beers in my opinion .  a really nice creamy feel to this which matches the beer , not the style imo .

smell consisted of light citrus fruits that of peaches , grapefruit , apricots , and some floral earth type smells . malts can be smelled behind the hops .  appearance : yellow ; transparent ; thin white head that went away pretty quick smell : some hops , thats about it taste : light hop flavor , a very watered down beer ; i couldnt taste any wheat flavors mouthfeel : light bodied drinkability : could do a few in a night i was n't too impressed with this beer .  very good mouthfeel .

smell is burnt brown sugar and hints of plum mixed with some earthy notes .  dull less-than-golden color , head struggles very low and then vanishes completely .  m - medium , lots of carbonation , coats mouth well .
s : sour cherry , lambic smell .  opaque , cloudy orange yellow color -- looks like pulp-in orange juice . chunk sized yeast floaties .  mouthfeel : pretty good mouthfeel : full and creamy .

this beer will always have a place in my heart since this is what my friends and i would pay bums outside the liquer store to get for us ! my best friend and i were recently low on cash and decided to get a coulple of 40 's of this swill and now i know why i stopped drinking it . it tastes allright at first , but as it rolls down your tounge it has one of the nasty-est aftertastes i have ever experienced in my life !  this is the second voodoo brew that is an absolute pain in the ass to pour . you pour , foam , let it die , more foam , it takes 30 min to pour this one and by the time you scrape off layer after layer of foam your 22 oz is barley 16 . once poured it is a murky light yellow hue with tons of floaters . the retention is ridiculous .  m : light body with a very well done carbonation feel .

im all for unique craft brews . but , i have to say im not too impressed with this unibroue offering . i must admit i will probably not purchase this ale again .  like looking into a big black void . zero head . looks like flat coca cola .  m - nice mouthfeel . does n't feel thin .
the smell is full of roasted burned tones , oats , bread , coffee beans .  very unassuming . coca cola colored with no head , no lacing .  m 4 the best part . medium plus body , creamy carbonation .

smell : some soap and flowers.. very faint malts they smell sweet and toffee like , not earthy smoke . does not smell dark either , the smell and the color are one in the same except that the smell is not captivating .  appearance : looks like your typical macro lager . pours a translucent yellow color with lots of carbonation bubbles .  light body with fairly high carbonation makes for a decent mouthfeel for a summer brew .

pint glass from cask . they used interesting hops in this , as the name implies : sunflower and fresh-cut grass dominate the nose .  looks like very little carbonation , i can see a few bubbles , but not much .  mouthfeel has a pleasant sheen to it , but the flavour is either thin or phenolically unpleasant , so it does n't have much to work with .

s : fresh fruit like oranges and apples , dry hops , wheat and grains . piney and earthy undertones in the aroma . d : not very impressive , more like a barleywine style than a double ipa .  this beer is one shade darker than water . no lasting head to speak of .  the medium body is smooth and prickly , and leaves an almost medium finish - nice .

s - sour floral , more particularly roses , and moscato d'asti t - extremely sweet , followed by nasty bitterness and sour .  hazing never cleared , got worse a t the bottom of the bottle , zero head retention & lacing s : big time apple skin & some straw t : lemony & grassy hops along with some cereal notes up front .  mouthfeel : thick and creamy . ignoring the taste of burnt things the nitro rocks for mouthfeel .

the aroma is dry and roasty with a good mix of chocolate and coffee . lightly nutty also it smells quite inviting . the taste is a bit of a letdown though .  this is a very cheap beer . but out of all the cheap beers this is n't a horrible choice , especially when you compare it to the bud 's or miller 's , it is actually better .  taste/mouthfeel : medium body with nice carbonation .

nose is amazing and if i didnt know better i would have thought it was a barrel aged beer . i was really excited by the nose .  500 ml bottle from budapest , it looks like typical supermarket beer and is quite cheap .  the mouthfeel has nice carbonation but the smell is bland .

potent hop aroma emerges from the glass and i wait as the head slowly recedes ... the hop aroma is mellowed by a malt , hints of vanilla and evergreen tree smooth mouth feel , almost creamy in texture ... .then the potent alcohol hits !  pours a slightly hazy straw like yellow with a quickly dissipating foamy white head that leaves no lace . looks more like carbonated apple juice than beer .  good mouthfeel with nice carbonation that is very smooth on the tongue with a somewhat crisp finish .

it 's getting better ... t : the currant flavor is n't as strong as i thought it would be .  appearance : pours a slightly hazy amber-peach color . unfortunately there is basically no head .  almost belgian levels of malt-fruitiness . other than the foul taste , the body was decent , but the nasty flavours killed any drinkability .

smells of malt and caramel were very present , very very present . the taste was quite of hops and very bitter , alot of bitterness .  clear amber with pretty much no head .  good carbonation makes for a crisp and clean mouthfeel .

a nice , fruity , blueberry smell that was pretty pungent and pleasant . a nice , malty beer with a slight , blueberry taste .  there is nothing really special about mgd . however , it is not terrible . it is good to order at a restaraunt with food . have it maybe with a pizza as it wo n't fill you up , but it will wet your whistle and compliment your food .  i do like the creamy mouthfeel this beer has , but by now , it is too late .
smells of hops upfront , followed by a fruit and citrus aroma .  appearance : not much head , even less head retention , and next to no lacing .  mouthfeel is fine . reminds me of abrasive .
smell : faint grassy aroma . nothing too pronounced .  looked like a standard lager , yellow , almost no head , and a bit of carbination .  body is light with good carbonation .

the label boasts coffee , roast malt , and chocolate and delivers on all promises . good stuff .  a - poured a three-fingers thick , fizzy white head into a weizen glass that settles into a thick ring that lasts about halfway through and is gone , never to be seen again . the body has a light haze and is the color of yellow straw . it looks almost thin and lifeless , very dull .  m : good feel , nice level of carbonation and just the right thickness .

the smell is that of a sweet tart berry fruit .  served on-tap at hot tomato 's in new haven , conn. a : poured a very clear , golden straw yellow color with a very thin head of fizzy foam which left almost no lacing and retained pretty poorly .  taste is good , mouthfeel is quite good .

pretty decent .  appearance : very hazy brown colored . does not look appetizing .  the hops jump right out from the bottle and sting your nose as the beer pours into the glass . do n't get me wrong there are plenty of hops , maybe too much , but i think as an effort to try and dry out this beer , the brewer added a lot of simple sugars which created more alcohol , and then to counter or mask , he added more hops . the finish is dry and clean with very little lingering hoppiness at least for a iipa . i was very excited to see this brewery 's beer being distributed in ohio . we do n't see many style defining west coast iipas in the midwest so it 's a real treat to find something that stretches your palate . even though this beer deserves low marks for drinkability , its intense aroma was worth the eight dollars i paid for the bomber .
the smell was nice .  appearance : a one finger foamy bubble head with poor retention and ivory in color .  quite thick body , but also slick enough .
i liked this one a lot at the first smell and it got progressively worse as i went on .  appearance- zero head .  low carbonation with a nice chewy mouth feel . very thick !

the aroma is strong sweet raspberries and honey . i thought i might be pleasantly surprised from the look and smell of the beer .  pours a medium copper color quarter inch off white head that quickly fades to beer and a light wispy lace .  the mouthfeel is fullbodied with good carbonation .

very pleasant . maybe i got a bad bootle , but this was the bitter-est beer i have ever tasted .  extremely pale yellow brew .  feels good in the mouth , mostly sweet to start , but there is a hint of bitter at the end of the swallow .

it is rather sweet with some mild caramel and floral notes . the taste is a let down after the nice aroma .  straw yellow pour , white head , aroma was of corn , grits , mild flowers .  m : good carbonation with nice palate clearing abilities .

the first impression was very good , the aroma is very nice with some fatty acids and esters giving a blend of spicy , citrus and hop aroma .  opalescent green , with an ugly white foam full of holes .  mouthfeel is a light medium with good viscosity going down with fair carbonation .
smell : caramel and roasted malts with undertones of ripened fruit .  pours a clear light amber color , lighter than i am used to .  the mouth feel is nice and creamy .

smells much like over ripe bananas and allspice .  not much head , that disappears quickly leaving little-to-no lace .  m : lighter side of medium body , medium carbonation , light on the tongue with a sticky dry finish .

aromas primarily of rum-soaked sweetbread . no too intense but present enough to be pleasant . tastes like rogue hazelnut brown ( always good ) aged in rum barrels ( also good ) . overall , it sounds better on paper . the rum overpowers the nutty characteristics way too much .  a strong pour yields a 1/2-finger tan-colored head that completely vanishes in less than a minute . the body is a cloudy deep copper amber that looks just like apple cider . almost no lacing can be seen at any point during consumption .  medium body , medium effervescence , good aftertaste where the malt comes out after the hop start .

smells rich and fruity , like a lighter doppelbock .  slam it into a glass and you may get some head , but watch closely , because it disappears in an instant . pale straw color , some maly aroma overpowered by alcohol .  it has a medium body and a smooth mouthfeel , with the sour flavor laying on the tongue slightly . inbetween a medium and high carbonation , but fairly drinkable .

smell : nice beady yeasty aromas , with a stong background of the blueberry/elderberry .  a very unattractive pour . the beer tries to form a head , but instead forms a lace that looks like one of those bald men that try to comb what hair they have over the bald spot to cover it up . it 's an unimpressive appearance .  smooth yet thick on the palate .

i know it ai n't christmas no more , but i got theis beer and it needs to be drunk . s- has a malty nose and you can start to smell the spices up front . t- very malty and a ton o fclove flavors , almost too much .  appearance - pale , yellow-gold . short white head that quickly dissipates . a little light colored for a regular american lager .  maybe i got a sixer that went south because something was just not right about this beer . i 'm not going to go through the usual breakdown except these overall comments : i ca n't quite place what hop ( s ) were used for bittering and aroma but it had a really funky smell and taste to it attributed by the hopping . it was n't a skunk smell , which anyone can pinpoint for spoiled brew , but it was enough of an off smell and taste that makes me think the hops in this particular batch were rank . i 'm through the fourth beer over the past week and they all have tasted the same . in general i 'm a fan of what lagunitas puts out but i 'm sorry to report that this particular release has been hard to get down .
nice toasty malt and light hop aroma .  flat , uninspired appearance.yellow-orange color .  mouthfeel = very crisp overall = this is my go to cheap beer .

the smell is super skunky , funny because it is a brown bottle that is also within it 's due date .  pale straw with fluffy white head that dissipates quickly leaving hardly a trace of bubbles above surface .  mouthfeel was fine , i guess with reasonable carbonation .

lacing is ok. s : rich malt and sweet chocolate are present , with a flowery background of hops . t : light fruity flavor , almost tangy , along with a rich sugary malt , and some hop notes in the background .  a : semi hazy straw yellow , smallish head , ok lace . d : other than the chunks of shit ( not floaters , but 2 bb sized turds ) , was big time drinkable .  mouthfeel : big exploding bubbles , thin , lots of good , filling , `` evaporation '' feel . very interesting .

a-muddied copper color ... minimal head s-mild hops on the aroma ... tangerines and oranges along with more of a sweeter , candied maltiness ... some mild floral notes emerge deeper ... t-surprisingly pretty bitter ( never would have guessed that from the smell ) ... pink grapefruit is very evident ... .the sugary malt is there too but overwhelmed by the unsweetened grapefruit ... .also some tangerines m-bitter , dry ... medium bodied ... low carbonation . d-there are better ipa 's and worse ipa 's ... .too much pure `` bitter '' but not `` tasty bitter '' ... average ipa ... .not even in the ballpark with hop hearty , lakefront or bitter woman ...  it poured a cloudy golden color and it produced a thin white head with poor head retention .  m -- fine for the style d -- perhaps the union jack ipa i had before this ruined my palate ?

the smell may be the best part of this beer . the taste is something atrocious .  the pour is shocking only because your expectation of what comes from the bottle is completely shattered by what appears to be a pink soda complete with the requisite head .  mouthfeel is pretty good but at this point who cares ?

spicy aroma , notes of white pepper and lemons , grassy and earthy , coriander , bready yeast and slight caramel . i was left feeling disappointed , particularly due to my initial enjoyment of the aroma .  a moderate pour yields two fingers of fizzy white head that dies down to nothing quickly . even for a macro lager , i 'm surprised by how pale this is . it does n't become atrocious when it warms , it does n't seem to have that awful metallic macro taste ( even when drinking from the can ) , and it 's cheap as hell .  texture is pleasantly smooth so it goes down pleasantly .

i enjoyed the smell but the taste ruined it for me and the taste is what it is all about .  what a deal , that 's two more than a similarly priced can of swill ! it pours a transparent yellow with a big head that does n't last too long and plenty of visible carbonation .  mf : light and carbonated well .

presentation : 12oz brown pop top with classic sa label appearance : hazy golden-orange with a tiny bit of sediment in suspension ; decent stark white head which soon fades to a thick film and retains fairly well smell : sharp , crisp wheat notes up front , followed by strong orangey citrus and maybe just a hint of caramel malt ... very mild spice as well taste : distinct wheaty goodness , backed with a a little bit of tart lemon rind and finishing with a kick of spicy bitterness from the grains of paradise ... i ca n't really say what it is , but this beer just does n't really come together for me ... it 's like wheat , bam , then tart , then spice ; it 's like three separate ingredients , the beer does n't feel put together very well .  a- pours out a dark yellow with no head and no lacing .  the mouthfeel was full and approaching creamy .

looks inviting aroma was weak - not much to note here .  appearance : very clear and somewhat watery smell : very light , and has not distinguishing features taste : it goes down very easy , and does n't leave a bad taste in your mouth feel : it is very foamy , and develops a head easily drinkability : it is easy to drink it in succession , and have a normal aftertaste .  the mouthfeel is good though with a medium body .

a : dark rusty brown red , two fingers of light khaki head , thick lace webs remain s : sour cherry is the most abundant aroma along with a strong vinegar back bone maybe a touch of barrel t : light sweet cherry and vinegar mixed with a load of musty wet carboard and cough syrup , not much sour at all , actually rather sweet m : light body with a decent amount of carbonation d : overall very big let down , this stuff is not good , there are much better beers out there to represent this style , it will be a struggle to finish this bottle  i 'm not a huge fan of the regular version of this brew but i 'm hoping that this might give it a twist to the good ... pours a dull brown with a very murky muddy appearance and virtually no head at all ... just sorta sits there ... no carbonation that i can tell ... decent aromas of caramel malts with hints of the namesake hazelnut mixed in ... perhaps a touch of the spice present in the aroma as well but that could be my imagination .  the mouthfeel is tasty and slightly creamy for a pilsner , but i am liking it .

smell- a very nice smell . sort of smells like starbucks .  d- if you are a poor bastard like me and you wan na get drunk for cheap and smoke too then this is your beer .  m/d - mouthfeel is full , creamy and quite pleasant .

bought in a 750ml in northern kentucky , there was no head at all when poured into a goblet . the taste is not at all what i consider a belgian trippel . the lack of carbonation , abv , and excessive fruitiness remind me more of a malt liquor than a belgian style . overall i was extremely dissapointed .  a : a rusty dark brown/red color . literally no head , just a smattering of bubbles around the edges . no lacing or retention of course . the complete lack of carbonation really hurts it for sure .  mouthfeel : drying and fairly clean and light .
it smelled good , dark malt , german hops .  poured straw yellow , like a light lager , into a pint glass .  m- smooth and well carbonated , with a little zing on the tip of the toungue .

very nice . t : slightly sweet and not much bitterness .  appearance : tall fizzy head with large bubbles , a bit too much like soda . no lacing , head lasts about 60 seconds , then not a trace can be found . pale gold , a bit cloudy .  light-medium body , ideal carbonation smooth .

aromas of layers of sweet cherries and some sublter belgian yeast funk smell , with lesser bananas and clove esters . overall this is a miss for me , too alcoholic , unpleasant and even ended up being a drainpour .  appearance - looks like a traditional rye beer . murky and opaque sour brown in color . three inches of head that are quick to disappear . very musky and swampy looking .  tastes very much the same : like a slightly above average macro pilsner that has the same aftetaste as old diet soda . '' well , if nothing else , this sure as heck is a cream ale : the body is great .

sweet fruity scents , some burnt sugar notes .  appearance : i watched that pour , and was quite disappointed at the lack of head this beer produced . the color was a plane dark amber , and overall this was n't much to look at .  taste is smoooth on the mouth . nice feel , but the vanilla isnt working for me completely . seems a bit too artificial .

smell ; sugar coated , sour lemons biond with the malts . not much hop odors but hints of juniper sweetness , not bitter scents of the berry .  bottle ( bottled on 10/27/2011 ) served into a nonic pint glass pours a pepsi cola brown color . black lager ? head size is miniscule , with about zero retention . apart from the appearance , schlalfy made a faithful rendition of the style .  the mouthfeel is done well , pretty thick , with low carbonation .

robust caramel , sweet raisins , dried cherries .  a medium yellow color , with a light foamy head that dissipates quickly .  m-grainy and rough on the palate , huge carbonation to balance a creamy syrupy body that coats the throat .

huge brown sugar aroma with boozy raisins and chocolate . like some sort of outrageous rum cookie or something . syrupy raisiny flavor , plenty of booze , cloyingly sweet .  no head due to no carbonisation . beercollor is amber and beer shows lots of haze .  the mouthfeel has a medium to full body , with light carbonation .

s - a nice aroma of sweet cherries and flowers .  the doppelbock is a lot lighter than others i have had . the beer poured with a very small white head and disappeared quickly leaving no lacing . from the looks of it , i am not overly compelled to take a drink .  the mouthfeel is well carbonated , light , and smooth .
aroma is dark malt , anise , and alcohol .  appearance : quick spritzy white head that dissipates to almost nothing , pale straw and very clear .  m - great prickly carbonation , light and crisp .

actually this is listed at bjs as an imperial stout . so lets see.. pours a dark red/black body , with an off white nitro head . smells of coffee , toffee , some chocolate and figs .  the color is pale-straw , and the beer smells somewhat dirty and unrefined . its like the candy of cheap macros !  the body is on the fuller side of medium with a low carbonation level that gives some wateriness . pretty good .

still , it has a great spicy hop nose and a very decent head .  this is a sample 12oz bottle i got from an ab rep . pours an deep amber with a head that acted and sounded like a soda . popped and fizzed for about 30 seconds and was gone . carbonation goes from super heavy upon the pour , to almost non existant in an instant .  very crisp , no real aftertaste .

smell : a very , very mild aroma , oc has been robbed of its rich maltiness in favor of foam .  i & lt ; 3 deesko served in a tulip at three floyds on june 23 , 2011.my ratings are based on tasting the beer without any syrup . a : pours hazy pale gold with a head that disappears by the time i 'm typing this description . poor appearance is understandable but unacceptable . a light wheat tang shows up , though . a low-grade funk seems to play at edge of smell .  mouthfeel : thick and creamy , not nearly as assaulting as i 'd figured it would be with the carbonation level .

the nose is really quite nice , but the rest of the beer fails to live up to it .  super pale yellow produces a fluffy snow white head that dissipates immediately .  carbonation is right on and adds to the fullness of the beer , however , the `` hop '' factor of the ipa is overpowered by the malty bitter bite at the end of each sip .

s : this beer is intense on the nose . the rum barrel really stands out . lots of rum , vanilla , oak , brown sugar , nutmeg on the nose . t : this is horribly , horribly sweet . cloying , really . rum , vanilla , brown sugar .  it looks very average for the style : sudsy head that dissipates to a ring aroung the glass .  the carbonation is ideal , one of the best results in my opinion .

s - roasted caramel , some grapefruit , light alcohol , and bittering hops . the smell was good , but there was no complexity in the malts and the bittering hops took over .  this beer poured a murky reddish brown color that turns peach when exposed to light . no head or carbonation to speak of .  mouthfeel was good , as the carbonation made it 's way to the tongue and was well received .

you can definitely smell the tangerine and it does smell good , although the smell of the tangerine is greater than that of the beer .  pours straw golden yellow with a thin , fizzly head that immediately disappears to a few carbonated bubbles , then disappears completely . it smells similar to a typical macro . could be refreshing on a very hot day , but so could many others ... it claims to be craft brewed , but it is so close to a mediocre-at-best macro lager that it could almost be confused for one .  a slightly creamy mouthfeel with moderate to low carbonation is present throughout .

nose : ripe bananas , nilla wafers , lemon zest , tiniest touch of clove . taste : clove bite , peppery , sweet unidentifiable fruit ( not banana like i would expect , but maybe ripe pear/pear skin ?  appearance : pours with an average amount of head which quickly dissipates , leaving virtually nil by the middle of the beer . lots of moist lacing . pale yellow colour , lots of unusually small bubbles .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

quickly dissapated leaving a little bit of lace s - cherries dominate the flanders sour aroma .  ommegang witte is a hazy pale yellow ale with a thin white head that vanishes .  this is a fresh batch : `` the batch id that you entered '7089 ' , is a bell 's pale ale . your bell 's pale ale was packaged on september 28 , 2005 , '' but i have no idea where the hops have gone . the only hint of them is the bittering in the finish ; there is no hop flavor . it does n't taste bad , but it also does n't taste like an apa . very disappointing , especially when compared directly to founders ' superb version of the style .

smells of wonderful dark fruits enveloped in some spiciness with a strong malt presence , some phenols and a hint of alcohol .  appearance is a light straw color with a quick fizzy head with carbonation rising to the top that fades quickly .  mouthfeel : fine . refreshing . nicely carbonated .

appearance : dark brown-ish black , no head ( disappointing ) , and few bubbles smell : brown sugar , molasses , and a touch of liquid black licorice .  very pale straw , very clear , fizzy moderately-sized head .  there is a nice carbonated mouthfeel that you might expect from a lager . the carbonation has grown less as i drink it , but even near the end there is carbonation to speak of .

s : has a strange pumpkin flesh aroma , ca n't distinguish much else other than sweet malt . pumpkin is just a bit of a turn-off t : thankfully the pumpkin does not exactly come through in flavor , bready malt does show as well as a light caramel .  pours a fizzy light yellow with a little frothy head that diminishes quickly . pours like most macro beers .  m- good thick syrupyness , i do enjoy this aspect of this beer . the really only redeeming quality is the good mouthfeel .

smells sharp clean fragrant grapefruit pith and lemon peel .  this poured a very unimpressive light straw yellow with very little head and minimal to no lacing . appears to be piss in a bottle .  m : light body and heavy carbonation . oily up front , but crisp in the end . the aroma was fantastic , and the mouthfeel was very good , but in the end i just ca n't keep tipping this one back .

a good wisp and ring remain leaving some decent lacing down the glass . smell : nice , but way too muted , unfortunately . if it were n't for the overly unimpressive nose , this would be one worth writing home about .  i was at a pub in halifax when the waitress asked me if i 'd like to try a `` bud light lime '' . my fellow craft beer drinkers will certainly agree that this particular pint does not rank highly in most of the usual categories , but here is the bottom line : it is highly drinkable , pleasantly carbonated , not cloyingly sweet , and very refreshing .  the is good carbonation and thickness .

nose is a rich roasted coffee with an actual creamy character to the nose that smells very much like very fresh roasted grains/coffee and an almost sweet toasty light molasses character . pleasant and a bit unique in the nose . pleasant and a bit different .  pours a very clear yellow color , clearly a macro lager , very thin white head with a tinge of lacing but light .  mouthfeel : medium bodied , the carbonation was right on the button as soon as i cracked the bottle .

a sniff reveals maple syrup .  poured in a yellow color and with a finger of quickly disappearing foam .  m & d : refreshing and light on the texture ; while the hop bitterness is very welcome in this otherwise very sweet ale , the overall flavour is awkward and shows no balance ... more an intriguing ale than a delicious or quaffable one .

a : cloudy pale yellow in color with a nice white head , very yeasty looking . s : sweet malt with spiciness in the aroma . t : very sweet and bitter at the same time , with an orange zesty finish .  poured an unimpressive pale golden , no head or retention to speak of , smell was grainy and sweet , typical euro-lager taste , slight hops , slight malt , and very unimpressive , watery mouthfeel , i guess this is their equivalent of a budweiser , nothing to seek out !  decent amount of carbonation , which seems to fit with the flavor .

poured into a pint glass ok was a little taken by the appearnce , its a chocolate ale and its dark amber with a fizzy head like a soda , about 1 finger high and disapates much like a soda as well smells of wheat and sweet chocolate notes with some semi-sweet malt , almost candy sweetness .  a wavy copper-yellow , light burnished peach-orange tints , sparsely bubbled through the body , with an immediately and fully diminishing white head that creates little to no lacing .  m : medium bodied with a medium level of carbonation .

the aroma is exceedingly weak , being mostly light burnt toast and dirty water with a hint of coffee . even when not too chilled ( and many seem to want it cold , confusingly ) , it still lacks any character whatsoever .  pale yellow appearance with minimal head .  mouthfeel is oily and well carbonated .

yikes , this brew scared the hell out of me . has a sweet , tart aroma . this was my first time trying a berliner weiss , i hope it was true to the style , until im able to try another brewers interpretation of this very distinctive and strange beer .  packaged in oct 2006 pours chestnut/mahogany with a pinky of tan head . no head retention or lacing s : coffee t : chocolate & coffee mingle up front with dryness & toasted/singed grain .  mouthfeel : a thick , chewy feel , with little carbonation .
smell : nice aroma right out of the gate . nice aroma , but not much else .  a pale sparkling gold pour , with a fizzy and short lived white fizz .  m - it was crisp , sharp and very smooth .

smell - cinnamon , ginger , nutmeg , and a strong aroma of banana .  pours a pale straw yellow with a thin white head that disappears rather quickly . fortunately , the appearance is this beer 's only weak spot .  m - really well carbonated , yet smooth .

aroma is cherries , some roasted coffee , and a little unsweetened chocolate .  i 've found that drinking the corona is a difficult task , due to the fact that it 's mainly water with little taste ... that is until you put a lime into the top of the bottle . just under the lip of the bottle so you do n't cop a mouth full of lime , but not floating in the beer .  note : this is the review of creamy mcstout , not the cream stout . says on the menu it has a `` special ingredient to make it taste more like bailey 's irish cream . '' that special ingredient tastes like it is vanilla syrup extract , and a lot of it , and it really brings down the beer . in my opinion cream stouts have enough sweetness on their own , but this syrup blunts any of the potential subtleties found in the flavor . it was dark , rich , and smooth , but too sticky-sweet and one dimensional for my liking .

aroma is down in rating only due to it 's weaker nature . it 's not very strong ... but for what 's there ... lots of sweet milk chocolate and maltiness . not much booze deteckted in the nose at all . again , lot 's of malts present . mmmm ... tasty !  this was a pretty unpleasant drink . no sound when the cap came off , and the underside of the cap was a greyish tint , splotchy and resembled zombie flesh .  mouthfeel is smooth and warming .

the smell is lacking , and i mean totally . really weird .  it looks like the fizz you get from dissolving an aspirin . what remains is a strange looking yellow beer . a foggy piss like fluid . medium carbonation .  it has a medium to full body , with ample carbonation , a prickly middle and dry finish .

i was hoping for something better since this was going to be a mild , easy drinking beer . unfortunately , this malty mixyure has the consistantly dull feature of avery brews ... a sticky malt flavor that lingers unpleasently on my pallate .  problem # 2 it doesnt have the bright straw like color expected from a mild filtered or unfiltered wheat beer . instead it has a dark urine like color .  it 's the opidomy of light , the smoothness of velvet , and the price of mexican dreams . degrading this beer comes at a great insult to anyone with a ba , mba , phd or techinical certificate for the lessor of us . i swear the old texts , properly translated , would describle jesus actually making water into natty . it 's constant . this beer is the appertif of beers .

here comes another quick cocktail nappy review -a cloudy dark yellow brown -kinda smells like a foot that was soaking in some kind of citrus .  a finger of off-white foamy head , quickly dissipating . orange in color , murky , big chunks of sediment .  average . m- very refreshing feel .

sulphury , grassy aroma . quite clean tasting with moderate hop and malt balance , maybe a bit thin .  poured a little pale , very thin head .  m : nice , crisp , and & light-bodied as expected . goes down smoothly . carbonation matches perfectly with style .

little to no head in the glass as it was served , however the smell was fairly impressive . scents of light and sweet orange , not overpowering , but strong and stable . the beer , despite the strong and favorable aroma , lacks in taste to follow it up .  a hard pour down the middle of the snifter results in , wait , hold it , absolutely no head at all .  mouthfeel is medium to full .

some sweet malt lingers on in the nose to give this a good balance .  clear to watery and brownish .  mouthfeel , in nice and smooth for an adjuct lager , not overly dry ( maybe it 's supposed to be ) .

the smell was interesting ( a pleasant citrus aroma ) but not very strong .  in the appearance , is a pale yellow color , regular head of foam ; in the bottle says that this beer is made with 100 % of malt , thing that i agree , both in the smell and taste are lof of malt ; the mouthfeel is very refreshing , medium bitterness and light body ; the drinkability is good , very ease to take , tasty to watch soccer or to accompany light foods or cheeses .  left a very dry crisp mouthfeel .

very fruity in the nose , with a heavy helping of malts and ethanol . some of the pleasing aspects from the scent are present , and there are some tasty notes here and there , but there is way too much alcohol to make this taste good .  the color was a very pale yellow .  m - medium to full body , creamy carbonation .

above average lacing & head retention s : a little bit of grainy cereal & caramel as this warms t : caramel & grainyness up front .  i did it i tried it .. as a home brewer and beer geek i did it ..at first look its a light yellow.. not much head.. not impressed..taste was like dish soap . and limey.. smell was limey.. aonly good if you are fishing and u like coranas and dont want to cut up a lime with fishy hands  mouthfeel is good as this beer is light on the tongue and not very thick when it goes down .

smell is incredible , bright and pungent , resiny , sweet citrusy cascades , yummy ! taste is a bit of a letdown after the incredible smell , still hoppy , but not as pungent , much rounder , with a hefty dose of toasted malt . still , a huge improvement over regular mirror pond for sure ! drinkability is good , much better then regular mirror pond , but if the taste kept up with the smell , it would have been great . of the three deschutes fresh hop ales i 've had this year , i 'd rank this second , behind goshie 's and ahead of harvest moon .  pours a lightly hazed golden yellow , thin white head forms and immediately fizzes away to nothing , no ring , no lace , nothing , does n't look good in that respect .  it had a medium feel in my mouth and good carbonation .

sweet , tart and tangy , a very strange tasting brew . pungent floral , not at all agreeable .  it has a light straw color that leaves something to be desired but it does pour with a much better head than most poor man 's beer and it thins out to leave a thin layer and leaves minimal lace .  it drinks much more harshly when cold . now is all wintertime spice . and cherry , of course . otherwise , it mirrors the nose being the most palatable . whew . quite an experience and one that everyone should have ... once . props to unibroue for coming up with this , but i 'm not so sure it works .

s : aromas are of pumpkin , allspice and nutmeg , with some malt sweetness as well . t : taste is much more dry and bitter than the smell would lead you to expect . o : not a very impressive beer .  if you like cheap and drinkable beer that still has some sort of taste and substance , this is definitely for you . while it has the characteristics of macro lager written all over it , it just has that little extra quality that makes you say `` hey this is n't half bad .  smooth moderate mouthfeel and not too filling - not a bad beer , too .

smells like dark fruits , raisins , malty with some brown/burnt sugar .  absolutely nothing special about this beer . no head , opaque brown body .  very good mouthfeel . the malts and hops dance around the edges of the tongue with the adequate carbonation .
nice sweet hoppy aroma with some citrus that even my gf liked .  pours a yellow color , with a greasy haze ( like pickle brine ) . head is pretty insubstantial .  m : light body , good carbonation .

aroma is of caramel malt and piny hops .  it pours reddish-brown , with next to no head , no lace and no collar .  m - the feel was nice and even when i swished and swallowed . probably the best part about this beer .

s- citrus and floral hop aroma with little to no malt charcterisitic t- light and lager-esk with a nice medium hop characteristic m- very light body with a spice at the front , malt covering about mid palate and hop finishing that is citrus and floral throughout d- very drinkable at around 5 % and very light for a nice summer session  a : darker than straw , poured a one-finger-thick head that , well , quickly is overused ... speedily ? dissipated , leaving no lacing . t : unobtrusive and unimpressive .  mouthfeel is ideal for the style .

no lacing s - smells citrusy , somewhat floral and a little sour . the smell kind of makes me excited t - not much of the nose makes its way into my mouth , which is a shame as i was kind of excited .  pours like ginger ale , which coincidentally is frequently sold in the same trade-green color containers . well ... okay , i had to stop laughing and give it a try . it did take me 2 years to stop laughing , however . it 's nothing exciting , and if it 's cheap and i 'm having a cheap party , i 'd buy a few 6-packs .  the best thing about this beer might be the mouthfeel - good carbonation , and an easy drink .

smell was big on berry like fruitiness which apparently is the pomegranate . a bit too mild flavored for me overall , but interesting .  no visible carbonation and no head , so obviously no retention and no lacing .  in texture , the ale is very weakly carbonated and quite smooth ; the overall impression is more like a pinot noir than a beer in this respect , and i probably enjoy it more than i should .

the smell was light and grassy with a bit of sour funkyness . overall not to bad , one of the better mass produced ab offerings .  poured into duvel tulip glass with zero head and retention .  mouthfeel is decent , not too thin or thick .

smell- not a whole lot going on in the aroma . a little caramel malt sweetness and that is about it . overall- unimpressed with this offering . the sales of this brand may support a good cause , but it is a very unmemorable beer .  pours a pale yellow with a 60 second , three finger head .  m - english style carbonation ( soft ) and lighter bodied . appropriate for the style .

resinous and citrus hops on the nose . a good amount of earthiness , as well .  red , cloudy , not much head , no retention or lacing .  m : the body is thick and creamy with a moderate level of carbonation .

poured out of the bottle dark with a little light showing through.smells good coffee like .  i picked this up at the local grocery trying to get some beer on the cheap . a - i was supprised when i poured this beer , at its very light ( for a honey brown ) color . it was light amber !  the liquid 's nicely velvety , smooth as it moves about . body between medium and medium-heavy . very light fizziness .

strong and sweet aroma of treacle / caramel , roasted malts , molasses , bakery and chocolate . nice !  the appearance is yellow . just nasty yellow fizzy beer look .  the mouthfeel is light to medium body with mild carbonation .

average head retention & lacing s : bready , grassy , lemony , white pepper & coriander . i wish this tasted it like it smelled t : lemons , orange peel & grassyness up front , then some coriander up front , along some nice wheat tartness . finishes crisp & slightly grassy mf : light bodied with slight carbonation drinks really easy , liked this much better than a previous time when i had this on draft years ago ( served too cold imo ) , nice if simple take on the style  the watery light lager cuts the spicy gochujang that i lather all over the meat ( galbi / bulgogi ) . first off , it 's one of the lighest color beers i 've ever seen . if you soaked a few grains of straw in glass of tonic water for an hour , the color would be unmistakeably hite-ish . the taste is n't terrible - it 's watery , there 's lil character but it is refreshing .  m : chewy o : ehh i 'm not so pleased with this whole concept .

it smells , ahhh , like something nice and rotten . i was pretty excited while smelling it .  341ml bottle poured into pint glass may26 2010 a pale straw yellow with a few bubbles and some suspended particles and no head or lace s the same fruity bread smell in qv only with some booze t what i smell but with a boozy chemical flavor that i ca n't place but it may be a good thing i ca n't place it m a little thin and not the smoothest finish d hard to swallow , not one i would drink again my 6 pack mixer is finished and i 'm not too upset it 's gone .  while i thought the mouthfeel of this beer was quite good , i was not a huge fan of its sour grape and champagne flavor .

the aroma was nice .  pours a hazy very pale yellow-orange color with a 1/2 inch white head that fades to a fizzy film on the top of the beer . no lacing whatsoever .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied , lightly carbonated , and smooth .

brown bottle , no freshness date appearence : cloudy bronze with a thin head , small lacing . smell : blossoms , pomegranate , grapefruit , pale grains . taste : citrus , pine , finishing with a nice drying herbal spiciness .  appearance is meh , straw yellow , no real head or lacing .  medium carbonation . a bit dry for my taste .

bold and delicious scented . t : ouch , fail . overall : i had hopes for this beer that was only a $ 1 , but it was n't worth it , smells great but poor appearance , carbonation , and enjoyability .  pours up a little murky straw color . not much head .  body is on the lighter side of medium , drinkability , along with quality , seem to be the missing ingredients in this concoction . & # 428 ; & # 943 ; c & # 409 ; .

the smell is very sweet , it smells like candy kind of . also smells faintly citrusy and a little scent of alcohol .  the scots most redeeming quality is its bright , sugary smell , which carries forward to the taste , though oddly , the taste stays sugary without touching upon real fruit . theres also no head , no lace , and no trace of peat .  mouthfeel is pretty soft but not to thin .

the aroma is actually fairly nice . i get some lemons and wheat , as well as a very inviting tartness .  weird rose colored purplish color , no head to speak of , looked like wine .  very creamy mouthfeel , but i must admit that this brew was far too heavy for my taste .
