nose is very roasty . i 've been trying to place this aroma for a while now , and i 'm convinced it is a type of wheat , torrified or roasted or something , but its not roasted barley .  poured a light straw color .  m : medium-bodied with light carbonation .

smell : really nice and light , very pleasing aroma . fragrant apricot , light toasted wheat and lemon make this really inviting .  a : pours a clear , pale gold color with a fizzy , one-finger white head . the head quickly recedes to a small ring around the glass , which does not lace very well . however , the lifeless appearance and disagreeable aroma of this brew pull the score down a bit .  the dry , champagne like finish along with the funky yeast was pleasant , however . mouththfeel was right on with the style , and was my favorite part of this beer .

being a small beer made from old foghorn i expected a little more going on in the malt department . it is a bit thin , not a lot happening on the malt side but it dones have a nice hop bitterness to it . if i remember right the brewer said he was shooting for an authentic english bitter .  looked like a sad pilsner moreso than a helles lager , not that there 's a ton of difference , but just looked that straw yellow .  i 've used pine to describe beers before but never has it been so true . smells like they really got the spruce tips going in here . lingering earthy bitterness and an aftertaste that kind of reminds of what it feels like when you eat something that is n't meant to be edible ( like for instance a pine cone ! ) somewhat crisp , drinkability only suffers because personally i am put off by the flavor .

the aroma is pretty nice . there 's definitely cocoa powder there .  i actually thought i received the wrong beer when it arrived at my table , seeing a slightly cloudy liquid , looking like a light pilsner in color ( it was dark bar , so they may have been some orange , but certainly nothing purple ) , and with hardly any head .  m - full bodied , nice carbonation level , and a pleasant warming effect .

the fine and inviting smell got notes of coffee and toffee and a peculiar touch of dry digestive biscuits .  served in a can from brick store pub , atlanta , ga a : pale orange with no head . seemed to look like a flat watermelon soda than a beer .  on the palate , medium-bodied , nicely carbonated , but not an easy drinker .

looks really nice . s- mmm ... beautiful nuttiness and roasted malts . very smoky .  this one 's a fairly clear gold on the lighter side . the white head fades quickly and there 's little to no lacing at all . the pumpkin does n't really come through so much in the aroma either .  mouthfeel is full and round .

aroma is a light sweet malt backed by a mild spicy hop type aroma .  there 's no head , lacing or any other staying of carbonation at the top of the beer , coupled with the colour of apple juice makes it receive a poor grade . anyone giving it a good rating is probably drunk .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel although sticky and overly sweet is not harsh at all in terms of alcohol bite .

give you three guesses as to what this brew smells like ( and the first two do n't count ! yes , lots of raspberry in the nose . the flavor is very mellowed out raspberry , along with ... well nothing .  some white head and pale golden beer with more floaties then my worst abbaye du rocs experience .  nice and heavy feel . too big and lacking flavors from the malts to balance off the alcohol and bourbon .
( s ) - lots of ripe orange , lemon , and piney citrus .  a good effort marred by a poor head .  m & # 8211 ; kolsch always has good mouthfeel , it is one of its hallmarks , to me .

very reminiscent to a sauvignon blanc i feel . mouthfeel is also somewhat jellyish.. quite odd . my girlfriend , a non beer drinker , though , loved it .  appearance : pours a light golden color with just a fraction of head .  a buttery mouthfeel which is unique and nice . medium body and medium carbonation .

pretty good smelling beer .  pours black with no head . i mean zero head . i 've never quite seen a beer pour this flat ever .  this shows a lot of warm nutty flavors , which is nice , but this is just too sweet , with a little odd , steely bitterness on the finish ... this , combined with the sweetness , just does n't really work mouthfeel : fairly full , which makes the sweetness seem more intense drinkability : medium at best conclusion : this has really nice aromas and appearance , but the flavor just falls a bit flat .

aromas were slightly wheaty and grainy . i ca n't remember the last time a brew let me down so much after such beautiful sights . the expected phenols were virtually nonexistant . drinkable only to be nice and not to seem like a snob when someone offered it to me in kind .  because it poured out pretty flat with no head .  mouthfeel : medium body , medium carbonation , smooth and sticky .

smell is of apples and pears , maybe a hint of grapefruit as well .  i picked this up on a thursday night looking to try something new its not a horrible beer or anything its just nothing special just another run of the mill ale .  m -- -medium bodied with good carbonation .

aroma is massive , just massive . where to start ... big sweet malt backbone with lots of candy sugar and dark fruits - figs , raisins , overripe plums . throw in a hint of lest her and some substantial oak and alcohol and you 've got a stunning nose . taste is similar but the sweetness is so thick that it really gets cloying . well , the nose on this one is fantastic but the taste and mouthfeel do n't quite stack up . over the top .  asahi is a pretty drinkable beer , but nothing significant . the pale golden colour and magically disappearing head are unimpressive .  m - very smooth with good carbonation , well rounded .

smell : some nice floral hops with some notes of pine .  on tap at the petrol station in houston tx a : pours an opaque , hazed orange . unattractive murky , and dirty . at first a two finger white head forms , but recedes to nothing in a second . i think it is a combination of the really unattractive look and the bitterness that continues to build with each sip .  the taste is bitter , more of the citrus but it just taste wrong or something , it 's not very pleasant and leaves this as a long , lingering after-effect , mouthfeel is medium and decently carbonated .

a - pours up cloudy pale yellow , almost white with a thick white head that dissipates slowly s - smells mostly of yeast , some citrus in the background and a hint of spice t - starts off with sharp carbonation tingle , replaced with slight sweetness at the edge of the tongue , and finishes with a hint of spice .  got this from the lcbo discovery pack pours pale and thin with a weak head that disappears immediately .  the willamette & tettnang hops gave it an interesting bittering character , although i 'm not sure i liked it that much . you do get some malt up from but the hop bitterness really overshadowed any malt character .

source/serving : 500ml bottle smell : has big malt intensity with a delicious biscuit character buttressed by lemon , caramel , and fresh grains and surrounded by yeasty earthiness . lightly grassy and metallic . finish has an unpleasant dry , metallic , slightly astringent character overpowering the delicate earthiness and punky grains .  very small head , zero lacing down the glass . apperance is not impressive s : smell is sweet and malty . also smells kindof musty like wet cardboard or something .  m - this has a nice smooth feel to it .

aromas of yeast , some fruit and spice .  chill hazed deep gold with a wisp of whitish foam that disappeared almost immediately , even with a constant stream of bubbles rising to the surface .  m - medium mody and moderate carbonation .

if you open this beer , let it settle , you 'll see a pleasant amber beer with a nice spicy smell . decent taste if you can get by the carbonation .  the amoeba floats around for about half the glass before dissipating -- i named it mortimer . cloudy brown color .  has a good body , definitely fuller than most ipas . some creaminess .

aroma is sweet malt , chocolate covered cherries , eisbock like taste is malty , chocolate , hop bitterness , the right amount of carbonation for the style i can see this beer turning very sherry like at the end of the aging period  pours a watery looking translucent burgundy-brown color . produces an inital loose , fluffy tan head which quickly dissapates to a spotty , wispy film . mouthfeel is very disappointing for a beer of this style .  the mouthfeel was smooth , creamy and fuller bodied with a fine , moderate effervescence .

wow , what a nice little ale ! very plesant biscuity malt flavor with a nice bitter hop presence . pours a beautiful pale orange with a large and persistant head . drinkability is sky high due to creaminess and overall refreshing quality of this beer . this is my third sampling from rogue and i have been very impressed with all three so far , ca n't wait to try more .  somehow i had zero head on this one . literally . no lace either . still in date and everything else seemed fine just no foam at all . nice brownish amber color for whatever that 's worth .  very good for the style .

a : orange hued , 1/4 '' head s : not a lot going on , primarily hoppy pine aromas . t : very pleasant .  a : almost no head . very pale gold .  mouthfeel : good body , unfortunately probably the high point of this beer .

this beer has a great aroma and then lets you down big time . nice golden color and pretty white , billowy head and nice lace .  a clear piss yellow color with no head whatsoever .  smell - malt smells dominate , chocolate msotly from what i can detect , not overpowering , in fact it 's very pleasant to the nose . the first thing i thought of was wine , sour and not pleasantly so . frankly i do n't like it . overall - a beer that 's exceptional in every area except the most important one : how it tastes .

smell : reminds me almost of one of my homebrews . the smell of spice hits the nose right off , followed by a mild hop and malt combination .  this beer pours a clear dehydrated urine yellow color .  it does have a great thick mouthfeel and if i could n't taste anything i would enjoy this well enough .

provides plenty of aroma ... fruits , oak with a hint of the high alcohol content .  i 'm not one to taste , chew and enjoy light beers , but i try them , and every now and then , i find one passable . this was not that beer . it was way light , amber touch , almost water . went down like a beer , this is coors . slight hops , hint that this is an amber , but water , water , coors again . while not totally tasteless , i even have enjoyed na 's more than this , with kaliber being a good amber na that tastes like an amber beer , not water .  mf : low carbonation , medium body , smooth d : interesting pairing- coffee with doppelbock.. ca n't say that it 's my favorite combo , but i 'm not sure if that is more due to the stale coffee character or if it is the pairing i 'm not the biggest fan of .

aroma : rich malt , layered mesquite smoked characteristics .  still this stuff was $ 5.99 a six pack for a dollar more you could at least move up to the much better busch light or stroh 's light . a- looks like light beer s- not bad almost smells like a beer t- sweetish malts that fade into an ok fimish m- normal for the style d- i wo n't buy this again  a little bit of hop dryness at the end m : full bodied , smooth , creamy mouthfeel d : this beer was not easy to finish , however i did .

hmm odd beer here . too much fruit on the finish just out of whack really . spicey and an almost rye flavor on the finish as well .  poured into a pint glass and it has a medium hue golden appearence with a one finger head that disappears fast .  appearance : dark chestnut brown with ruby highlights , good clarity , medium layer of tan froth aroma : light roast and malt ; bit of brown sugar flavor : medium malt sweetness with a weak coffee bitterness on the back end ; hints of brown sugar and vanilla pipe tobacco ; finishes semisweet mouthfeel : medium body , spritzy carbonation , soft texture other comments : meh ... fairly lacklustre .

not sure what i was expecting from this brew , but the nose was a big surprise . overhwelmingly bitter and floral , with caramel sweetness singing backup .  my friends constantly drink this , so it 's free and downing a few large cans gets you drunk pretty quick . head and color are your average american macro lager .  m : a soft and fluffy texture , no carbonation , medium body .

smell : deep roasted malts ; very oaty and raw ; nice coffee-esque scents .  obviously not as big as some macros . well , it poured like a lot of macros with a light straw color and almost no head .  mouthfeel : heavy bodied .

smell : just like coffee . mouthfeel : thick beer , as what you would expect from a stout .  very crisp , has a bite . wheat does not present itself ( thumbs down here ) , the honey barely comes through . there must be adjuncts here , i 'm confident there are some .  m : smooth and balanced . body is light-medium .

$ 7.99 at whole foods for a 750ml . was expecting a really good stout with the packaging and brewery location . poured gently into a pint glass , i received less than an inch of beer and the rest head , and it did not settle . i have seen other reviewers speak of nothing ut head in the cisco beers , but then rate it ok . update after contact with brewer . brewer admits to carbonation and suggests letting the beer settle , offered to send me a fresh one which he believes will not be as heavily carbonated as the one i sampled .  all i had was a large wine glass , resembles the look of apple juice . no head retention , but this could be from the glassware . my first few tastes of this beer , i was very unimpressed .  full mouthfeel .

nose is sweet fruit with raspberry and pear tones ; hint of sour ; hint of brett ; mouthfeel is thin but the flavors are unique and a bit overwhelming such that mouthfeel is not of great importance here , although one 's initial reaction is that the beer is out of balance .  clear fizzy yellow beer with a small white head , looks like thousands of other beers in the world that look like budweiser .  mouthfeel - i actually have no complaints in this department . it 's comparatively crisp and the carbonation is appropriate .

smell has no hops at all , lots of bready malt flavors with a strong honey presence , that of a honey wheat or something of that nature .  a - bright yellow , no head what-so-ever .  well-carbonated and oily on the tongue .

strong , spiced , bubble come aroma . man , you can smell that belgian yeast good . super smooth mouthfeel , kind of thick .  very pale , little head which dissipates immediately .  mouthfeel - a good mouthfeel . smooth and slightly oily , crisp carbonation , one of the better areas of the beer .

nose is saltwater taffy with some fresh bready malty aspects .  deep yellow color , some head , most of which disappears . no lacing . i thing it wo n't rate very highly due to the overall appearance , but it should be considered a good , refreshing beer for a summer afternoon .  m-really pretty rich and smooth in body with medium carbonation and a slightly slick mouthfeel .

pours a reddish orange color with white head . nose is dominated by raspberries with a little grassy bits as well . very raspberry flavours almost tastes like slushie syrup .  of the beers i have not had this was one i was looking forward to ; very disappointed . served in a chalice from tap there was little or no head or lacing . i spent the whole time drinking it looking at the other options and wishing i could return it .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

the aroma is intriguing , as it has a huge fresh wheat character initially , along with some cheerios like maltiness , some fruity esters , and a touch of the banana/clove yeastiness typical of the style .  serving : poured into a chilled beer mug color : not so great of a color looking back , but at the time i though it looked ok . pale yellow and rather thin .  mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with low carbonation .

smell- wow , that is exactly what chocolate covered cherries smell like when you have bit into that sugary center . taste- the nose does not transfer as well to the palate , bummer . mouth feel- definitely too thin for what smells like a very decadent beer . overall- this beer was enjoyable if only for the nose that did a wonderful job of portraying chocolate cherry .  it pours a pale yellow color with a hint of sweet malt in the smell .  mouth feel is light and smooth . this `` bock '' is very plain and offers little flavor .

smell ; a sweet and sappy spruce resin aroma .  this beer for the price is actually quite good . really transparent yellow tinted coloring .  mouthfeel : nice light mouthfeel with a decent amount of carbonation .

it smelle overwhelmingly of berries and the taste was even more intense . this was a very bubbly heffe and and a very sweet mouthfeel .  poured out of bottle into pint glass with very little head and much too clear for an `` unfiltered beer . on the second glass i added a small slice of orange which helped some but i believe in a good hef you shouldnt have to do that . i think i 'll stick with their boston lager in the future .  mouthfeel : light carbonation . good to form .

interesting aromas of strong malt , toffee , and cinnamon . the flavors dont quite live up to the aromatic billing , with some fairly bland yet sweet malty notes along with some minor bread and roasted malt tastes .  sure , i think of this beer as `` better '' than american macros but usually given the price difference involved and the kind of occaisions when asked to choose between a `` heiny '' and miller or coors ( or pabst ) , i end up choosing the latter . i find it amusing when americans drink this stuff because they feel it above or better than american beers ... that this is what real , `` german '' beers are supposed to be like . i 've had european friends tell me this is usually the cheapest beer you can find in pubs ... probably not a horrible choice when fresh .  the mouthfeel is a bit creamy as the name implies . overall i 'd say the mouthfeel is the best part about this beer but nothing to get excited about .

s - sweet malts and roasted nuts not too shabby .  definatley a good beer to drink to quench your thirst . but it does seem to get you drunk pretty fast 5.9 % abv . everytime i drunk more than four of these i got a headache . it just confuses me on how some business could make a beer that is this flavorless . it still looks and smells great . a nice brown/amber color with a two finger tan head .  it pours a yeasty apricot color with no head and no lacing with yeast chunks in the bottom .  i must divulge that i am somewhat ignorant on strong belgian ales . smell is super caramel and alcohol is present . it says brewed with rasins but the alcohol is so overpowering that it could be mangos for all i know . addmitatly this beer has a time and place to be consumed and at my house tonight is not it .

1/14/09 bell 's winter white ale : app : orangey yellow haze sits quietly under a slight white head which dissipated within the first 30 seconds ... a nice effervescence was seen throughout the life of the beer however somehow did not contribute to head aroma : classical wit character of sweet wheat , coriander and a slight citrus nose.. pleasant overall taste : slight spicey coriander with sweetness derived from a nice wheat backbone , and a mildly hoppy bitterness to round it out mouthfeel : medium light body that was broken up by the more than adequate carbonation .  pours a very clear , slightly insipid pale golden colour , with a filmy head of nothingness that forms nothing more than a bubbly ring around the edge . extremely light body , slightly scummy and rather unappealing .  mouthfeel is pretty good , though .

good , malty smell , with a hint of white grapes .  disappointed in the lack of head and lace .  the thick and coating mouthfeel means the tongue ca n't escape the fusal fumes .

smell - hmm this beers really weak point . slight roasted coffee smell is about all i detect .  poured much paler than i expected . it 's a very pale yellow : little color at all .  come to think of it , drinking peeber is like drinking water . very thin .

s- ca n't find much of anything on the nose . t- generic 'beer ' taste . better than some other macro lagers .  appearance : cloudy , light-copper color with an unusually large amount of suspended particulate matter . small , white head disappears quickly leaving average lacing .  thin mouth feel .

served in a wine glass , the color was almost see-thru yellow , fairly pale . odor had a slight skunk to it , but nothing off-putting or enough to raise an alarm and send it back .  from the firkin into a pint glass : no head , no carbonation , cloudy , brownish , watery . ugly , ugly beer .  mouthfeel was watery and dry with nothing to stick on the tongue .

smell is almost non existant . in fact the only thing i smell is a touch of skunk . flavor defies the smell thankfully .  pours a light straw color . floaties galore , rather poor looking beer .  m- thin and carbonated . probably the worst dimension to this so-so beer .

s : strong skunky odor , some malts , the skunk is dominate .  a : clear gold , with a thin and foamy head that dissipated quickly . once the head was gone , the beer was essentially golden water . left no lace . the beer 's glaring weak spot .  rather thin . left a grimey feeling in my mouth .

a wierd vegetable smell , a little like eggs . a good bitterness , though vegetable notes .  appearance - 2.0 pours a thumb 's thickness of white head that settled to a thin layer , then disappeared over a pale gold body with a lot of chill haze that later disappeared . smell - 3.0 there is something very macro european about the smell of this beer , reminding me of heineken in particular . drinkability - 3.5 unexciting , but actually a very easy drinking beer , though sweetness detracts somewhat .  however the body of the beer let it down , very watery , no head retention ; this very quickly started to remind me of lager .

pours clear yellow with a big white head . smell is truffles . this is one terrible beer -- or , rather , i ca n't tell what this beer is like , because of the damn truffle salt .  as i drink more beers this is still my favorite light beer . the importance of this beer is that it 's drinkable and cheap .  mouthfeel is seltzer water + a little .

this one starts with a skunky nose that passes after about 15 minutes of airing out .  pours a solid clear amber with no head , very little carbonation at all .  mouthfeel was very disappointing - none of the creamy smoothness that i love and was almost cola-like in its carbonation level .

smell initially has a euro lager skunk , but mellows out as it breaths .  a- a very clear gold to pale color with high carbonation . looked bland from the lack of color or depth . worth the money and a good choice for cheap beer .  mouthfeel was a bit thin and slippery .

smell is overpowering and almost skunky . skunky bitter hops smell that fills the room .  despite the rather bland appearance ( looked like the usual bmc kind of pale yellow clear-like-urine junk ) , this was a terrifically spicey beer .  could barely detect any spices , very thin body .

the aroma is almost non-existant and the color is a slightly cloudy golden . the mouth is at or below average for a pale ale and the finish is also a bit weak , with a bit of dry hoppiness .  near satanic looking label , doubt this would ever get approved for sale here ... pours a brown tinged ebony with a thumb of tan colored head . zero head retention & lacing ( this beer achilles heel ) s : coffee & not much else t : much coffee up front along with some dulce de leche & a touch of orchard fruit up front .  mouthfeel : high carbonation . mouthfeel hurts it 's `` sessionability '' despite the abv .

s- kinda smells like wet grass and a bit of citrus . not much depth to this at all . kind of boring .  i must have gotten a bad bottle of this because the pour gave no head like a date with a nun .  body is watery to excess .
smell was n't bad just barely discernable .  a - pours copper-gold with no head .  m : very high carbonation .

no aroma . more like an imperial hefeweizen than a weizenbock .  lots of carbonation . dominant grainy smell of corn mostly . after all , it 's made by anheuser-busch.. but if i take it at face value , it 's got ta be one of the best adjunct lagers i 've had ... and while that 's still not saying much , i believe it 's a decent example of the style .  mouthfeel - thin body , high carbonation do n't match ideally to the bigger taste .

i do n't really get a lot of smell to this at all . maybe a little barley smell ... but it 's really pretty bland .  pours red/brown , hazy , zero bubbles or head of any kind . the complete lack of carbonation makes this taste like a juice/vinegar combo .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with zero carbonation .

aroma of sour grain , cola/caramel , licorice and a faint smoke .  the beer pours that peculiar strain which can only be called corn yellow .  way too much carbonation..and the mouthfeel is too bubbly . even if the carbonation was done well , i do n't think this would be anything better than an `` above-average '' porter .

s - the smell is right there where you want it : boozy , older , spicy , with notes of grape and caramel . t - it tastes as it smells , plus wood , and a caramel-toffee flavor .  pale golden , didnt look like an ipa at all . its a very drinkable beer , but does not taste like a real ipa , maybe they should rename it halifax pale ale .  poor amount of carbonation .

very bland .  a : super dark brown colored beer . even with super aggressive pour , near no head ( mocha colored ) with really bad retention .  too carbonated for my taste and has a dry character on the tail as it warms that i do n't care for .

the colour is pale yellow ; the airy white head disappears quickly into a thin lid . the smell is relatively mild with notes of honey and a neutral bitterness . and it is still one of their best lagers , as it lacks the unpleasant sweetness that have become a sign of bro .  pours a pale straw yellow , average sized , bubbly white head that fades . it is what it is , cheap pale lager aimed at the masses .  the aroma makes you think this will be a rich and luscious beer , but i was disappointed with its watery body and complete lack of depth . this is a lightly flavored , light bodied beer that has a slightly fruity sweet finish .

not a pleasant nose . d : a decent enough beer but the nose was a mess .  pours a cloudy pale lemony-orange color with a white head that disappears almost immediately . lots of little floaties in this pour .  mouthfeel is pretty watery with not a good amount of carbonation .

nice khaki head , unfortunately there was no retention ... strange scent ... makes me think of a cleanser ... .comet ?  sadly this beer was not very good and barely resembles a saison in appearance , flavor or aroma . appearance is a clear light gold with a whitish head that disappears immediately and leaves no lacing .  the feel was too thin . what smoothness there was came more from thinness than anything else .

smells kind of malty with some skunk maybe , but i wo n't jump to conclusions . somewhat sweet with citrus hints , but skunky .  poured into a 12oz tumbler appearance - very pale straw yellow appearence , with a finger head that disappears fairly quickly smell - in terms of smell , the only scent i picked up was a mild bread/yeast smell .  however - carbonation is a real problem here , with sherbet-like tingling insistence on the tongue , which kills the remaining flavour .

had a bunch more since then since it 's now all over long island ( at bars and restaurants ) i 'm a big amber fan and this one is right up there with the best of them . very well balanced and just gives me that caramel malt flavor that i crave from time to time when i 'm all hopped out  bottle clearly states to swirl the leftover yeast and pour it into your glass which imo is a really big mistake . most of the time there is a inch or two of yeasty sediment in the bottle which yields a gross looking beer .  mouthfeel is awful due to the lack of carbonation . absolutely no carbonation whatsoever - none , nada . a very interesting beer but the lack of carbonation easily keeps this one from being world class .

smells pumpkiny , stringy vegetal fruits mixed with rotten silo-aged grains . something is very sour , very off here . aroma like wet cereal brings out the worst of locals like mcneills and rock art . microbrew at its aromatic peak of sloppiness .  pours a sweet ruby and medium brown color , but with no head ?  mouthfeel is not so good , since the beer is basically flat .

sweet coconut and nutty smells , very nice . the taste is another matter -- to me ... i , too , had a bottle not destined to expire for many months and still got a heavy mix of slight skunk and `` wet cardboard '' from the malts .  pours a clear yellow with a fizzy white head that quickly diminishes to a thin collar that leaves a little lacing .  had the banana and clove aroma and taste but the body is just way too think and the lack of carbonation makes it tough to drink .

s : nose is straight booze that covers almost everything else . some chocolate and molasses make its way out little by little but the alcohol covers everything else . not a fan . t : opens sweet soy sauce , chocolate , raisins , booze , mocha and molasses throughout .  other than that , there 's no head at all , no lacing , it 's hazy , and has bits of sediment in it .  m : light , fizzy , thin finish .

not much on the nose . right to edge of the tounge with welcome caramel flavor .  this one poured into the glass a lightly hazed copper orange color . the head was a finger of fizzy white foam that was entirely gone in less than two minutes . no trace of a cap or lacing .  carbonation is stupidly high .

almost smells like a sweaty sock .  but i was not impressed it had about the same color as miller altho a little darker and near the same smell and taste .  far too over-carbonated , and watery mouthfeel .

not too impressive aroma . definately more on the malty side . the taste is more enjoyable than the aroma , but still no really noticable rye effects .  looks like a thick pepsi .  mouthfeel was pretty weak .
not much of any hops in the aroma but i do smell some corn .  baltika # 9 is a weak pale yellow in color with an average-sized , bright white head .  ok mouthfeel is pretty bad . thin and watery .

aroma - kind of skunky and familiar corn adjunct appearance - pale , plae yellow no head and very little carbonation .  drinkable beacause it goes down easy , since it has no real taste . from a college standpoint , this is not good since you can get drunk quicker on the same priced key ice or natty ice , which tast better too . better tasteing cheap beer can be had quite easily .  mouthfeel : smooth but horribly dry , especially on the finish , which is reminiscent of a stale cracker .

s- the aroma is not that pleasant . sweet grain and a really off caramel aroma .  you wont believe me but this canned lager is full of floaties ! it definetly loses all points for . well not appearanceall points because it has a great lasting head . this must just be a fluke .  the taste is average with a slightly bitter aftertaste the mouthfeel is lacking . it feels a bit watered down .

however , the aroma put me off pretty quickly . something sort of like the smell of fresh asparagus .  this beer is average . slightly darker than a standard pils with an off-white thin head . really nothing spectacular .  felt very thin in the mouth for a stout , with a little bit of carbonation .

there 's a deep roasted malt background in there too , but the citrus is just too much for me and very distracting .  a : it is a very pale yellow color , lighter than the color of straw . the beer is opaque , and eventually leaves no head or lacing at all . it looks like fruit juice in the glass .  m - this beer was way too overcarbonated and it distracted from the taste .

clear straw yellow in color . simple bmc taste profile and although some other reviews i 'd read mentioned apple and other things i did n't get any of that .  medium brown color with a bit of creamy tan head the fades and leaves no lace . it is off on almost every detail -- too much yeast fruitiness , not enough malt , not enough body , too much carbonation , no head retention or lacing .  mouth is really thin , watery almost .

s - smelled very musty , just like a malty mustiness that was not pleasant at all to me . not very pleasing to me at all .  a-light gold , almost no head , lots of bubbles . looks like an adjunct s-smells like mango !  m - not much carbonation ; watery d - no reason to drink more than one .

the scent is a fairly pungent sweet corn , not too sharp .  this is a solid beer for the price . when they say extra pale on the front of the bottle , they mean extra pale . it has almost no head and it really does n't smell like much of anything . this beer seems to be the choice of many non-beer drinkers that normally drink liquor because it does n't have much of a beer taste .  the palate is thin .

smells great . many people have stressed the coffee part .  apper- clear golden with short lasting head smell- cheap lime flavoring taste- carbonated water with lime juice , and a hint of beer mouthfeel- dry feeling , nothing to pleasant .  m - medium body with a dry finish , yet an odd carbonation that again reminds me of soda .

oddly enough , there was no detectable smell . the taste was quite muted as well .  cloudy ( or very hazy ) amber . nice beer overall , but not impressive to look at .  m- one thing that can not be salvaged , of course , is the thin body and high carbonation .

smells of yeast and a little copper ?  from the mix pack along with the red and the witbier . appearance : clear blond color. , no head at all smell : nothing like an ipa should smell .  nearly flat and medium-bodied , the mouthfeel becomes slick towards the end and the drinkability suffers .

aromatics on this beer are well a little faint with a slight caramel malt tone but no real hop aroma to be found . taste is creamy buttered caramel malts with faint hop bitterness in the background to balance out the sweetness and touches of dark roasts add to the experience .  pours a very unattractive and light orange brown color with a thin bubbly `` head '' .  feel is flat , untextured , un-nuanced .

totally uninteresting and bland .  light coppery color . very minimal lacing . i dunno who is responsible for marketing at berghoff but baby blue and white does not say oktoberfest to me .  thin taste of belgian white beer . most other beers i 've tried from unibroue has been fairly strong , maybe that 's why i thought this one lacked body ? still , it 's not as good as hoegaarden if comparing to another belgian wit .

smells very wheaty , but at the same time quite chocolatey . not a very powerful nose but extremely pleasant . taste is actually quite spicy , and while there are hints of that sweet , chocolatey nose , they 're mostly absent here .  apple juice looking beer with a ton of carbonation but no head , no lacing , nothing .  mouthfeel is super thin and watery .

very comperable to an american pale ale or lager . s - there is not much of a smell . just not a lot going on . pleasing , malty flavor with not much in the way of hops . very clean finish with the slightest hint of bitterness .  superior is a pale yellow with almost no carbonation .  mouthfeel is light considering how malty this is . thin .

overly skunky smell .  pored from a bottle to a glass appearance - kind of light appearance , reminds me of a bud light appearance with just a little more foam smell - smells much better than bud light but has a sweet tint to the smell taste - its not the best hefeweizen i 've had but its decent .  mouthfeel - extremely watery overall - an uninteresting yet swilling pumpkin ale .

this is miller 's highest rated beer and it deserves to be . flavor of perhaps lemon , but little else . not as much character as the best industrial lagers of europe , and little hop or barley flavors , but a crisp clean taste with none of the off-flavors that creep into american macros - cooked veggies , stale or skunky hops , etc . one of the only us macros i plan to buy again , if only for the dubious reason that there 's nothing offensively bad about it .  i have to say , this is one of my prefered `` shit '' beer of choice . light and able to be consummed one right after the other , not to filling , yet a decent amount of flavor .  the middle is thin and sweetens some . when cold , the finish is slightly metallic with some obvious alcohol . this is n't bad compared to american macros and some other strong export lagers , but that 's about it .

hardly any aroma at all , faint smell of sweetness from the malts , but little more than that .  a : black as engine oil , little or no head .  fairly thin with a lot of carbonation , watery , with some hop flavor . i am really enjoying all the craft beer i 've been drinking lately , but a bunch of miller lites iced down in a cooler on a hot summer day will work for me anytime .

not much smell . tastes of floral hops which is not my preference .  appearance : cloudy hazy gold , tightly carbonated with nice white head that dissipates quickly . good for style .  the real indicator was the body too thin and the general overall weakness will not make this a serious porter contender .

a touch earthy hit with pine nuts in the aroma , but otherwise shelter is nothing more than a leafy pbr . it has no brightness on the nose and the taste is thin , accented by the fruitless wilamette ( oddly , it takes the earthiness of wilamette but none of the fruit ) . i love dfh , but i 'm stunned that they were able to get on their feet with this as their flagship . it 's inoffensive and great to wash down food with , however , and dfh was first a brewpub so it makes sense that this would sell .  poured into my duvel green tulip pours and a very murky golden yellow that is not see-through at all . from an average pour a giant 3 finger head of white foam erupted .  the body was very thin .
smell : old damp wood , barnyard , swine pen , rainy forest .  appearance : nice looking beer , golden in color .  mouthfeel is extremely thin for the style with no chewiness at all .

the smell is rather weak , there is a hint of rye grain .  a : black with a big beige head . scattered lacing .  t/m : the mouthfeel is thin and quite watery ; the taste is equally limp . mouthfeel and a general weakness of character ruins any chance at more than a passable brew .

skoal !  looks good , nice hazy soft peach colour , good head with some retention and lace .  m- horrid ! lacked any body whatsoever . i mind as well have been drinking seltzer water that had no carbonation . d- given the water-like mouthfeel , it went down pretty easy .

it did not have much flavor to srart out with other than grain and corn , but the taste was smoothe and not to intrusive . this is definantly a beer to get wasted on and not to seriously drink .  2007 vintage in a 12 oz bottle . poured black with a small brownish head .  it hinders the mouthfeel and makes it seem more syrupy and cloying that originally intended ( just guessing ) .

s mildly soapy aroma .  pours a light golden colour with a full bodied and firm head of creamy white . good lacing . looks cloudy in the frosted glass . otherwise , it looks pretty good for what it is .  mouthfeel was also very light and thin .

smells was pretty clean with underlying macro lager .  pours a nice copper color with a 1 finger off white head that quickly fades to a thin coating .  clearly a lawnmower/party beer , but its quite refreshing and a lot more tolerable and most of the other cheap beers , plus it 's the same price ... one of my favorite cheap beers .

aroma 2/5 nondescript aroma with some sweet malt character and an odd sharpness , like a pilsner . more malts and perhaps more hops will make this beer better , but the unoffensive character ( ? ) might get lost .  a - a deep red beer with a fairly large foamy head . the slightly pink head lingers for a few minutes and leaves thin sheats of lacing down the sides . looks good for a cherry lambic .  the mouthfeel is medium to light bodied and watery .

nothing too special about the smell , maybe even a bit skunky . pretty plain if anything .  blackish with dark brown edges , two fingers of cream colored head with rings of sticky lace left behind .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel does n't carry the taste evenly - it 's too smooth and yet too coarse at the same time .

old and musky coffee in the nose . this is really lacking in this department . t : some grainy malt and bread .  looks pretty , golden with a nice head .  palate is watery , but drinkable . as i commented to the purveyor , for a pale lager in a can from wisconsin , its not bad .

aroma almost non-existant slight grassy smell . good bit of hoppiness up front with a slightly malt finish .  purchased as part of `` build-your-own-six-pack '' at local grocer . poured small head on a dark amber body .  light to medium body with a watery texture .

poured into a 20 oz pint glass appearance - at first glance this was a wheat beer , cloudy to the point that one could not see through and relatively pale . smell - some faint malts without any hops that i could notice .  pours a cloudy dark amber with a small light biege head , good lacing .  a bit heavy despite the watery feel in the mouth .

s - there really is n't a lot of aroma to this beer . a hint of roasted barley , but not very impressive t - there is n't a ton of taste either .  a : black with a nice persistent dark tan head and lacing .  it drinks well but it does n't leave much of a feel in your mouth .

s : nothing is to strong here . i 'm picking up a mixture of sweet malts and some breadiness . faint cinnamon and molasses is all i can really smell here t : it follows the smell - i can not taste much . i do n't know what to say about it , i can not smell or taste much .  beautiful rust color but the soapy , flat taste is unbearable .  and the mouthfeel is oddly thin , does n't fit well with the boozy vibe .

maybe a very faint malt smell , but it 's surprisingly odorless . very odd . taste : for something with very little smell it makes up for it in flavor .  a foamy , frothy tan head builds aggressively on top of this beer . looks like a coffee milkshake sitting atop the black beer . lots of sticky lace . a much better looking beer vs. the flavor .  m - low marks again . thin and not up to snuff .

when it comes to american macro lagers , i like smoothness becuase i know i 'll get nothing else out of it .  everything about its appearance was fine- good head , good color , good cloudiness , but thats not what is most important- i found the taste was an overpowered brew .  the mouthfeel lets this drink down , as the carbonation is too intense and overpowers the flavour , so i found myself agitating my glass to draws some of it out .

nose is very tame and mild not too hoppy at all .  that being said , the head was immediate and gargantuan atop a hazy amber . retention was equally as impressive , leaving a lumpy cone on the way down .  mouf & gt ; overly carbonated and full . the mouthfeel sucks . '' drinkability & gt ; we finished the bottle because it still tasted good , but it was not as good as the 2008 .

speaking of the beer under it , it 's a slightly cloudy yellow with absolutely no smell . that really surprised me - i could n't smell a thing . despite that , however , it had a nice fruity , slightly bitter taste and a surprisingly thick mouthfeel .  point : thick white head , tan body . first sip , very watery . good head retention . i 'd have pbr all day long over this .  m - low carbonation , slick , flat finish .

the aroma is slightly sweet yet sour with a hint of hops .  medium straw colored , super size head that has decent staying power . collapses and then brings some nice lace , forget about everything you have been told about lace .  mouthfeel was light and thin , due to the low carbonation , so it was lacking the smooth velvety body that you would expect from a oatmeal stout .

s : malty ... corn ... not much recognizable hops , kinda metallic , and slightly skunky .  reddish sherry colored . creamy short topping . imagine mulled wine steeped in a thousand tea bags .  much too much carbonation .

it smells like 7-up , which is not unpleasant , and the bottle says it is a 50:50 blend of beer and lemon soda , so no surprises . i can picture it as something you might have on a long bike ride or as a summer lawnmower beer .  a : bright cloudy orange beer with a good finger head which dissipates on the quick side , large bubbles .  the flavor follows those same tastes with with an overall malt sweetness and thin feel to it . not thin in a good way , thin like flavor is missing .

s-very little aroma . slight scent of malt and a very faint citrus aroma .  pours up nice ... .excellent color ... i was real excited to drink this .  very rich , sweet and no carbonation to balance it . what i like least : the lack of carbonation .

honestly , it smells pretty awful .  has a great dark black color to it , was disappointed with the smell or rather lack there of .  thin bodied with a watery finish , this could still be a passable summer brew for when you have little else in the fridge .

white head and no lacing to talk about . smell , again , is grainy ( what sort of malts do these guys use ? formaldehide , maybe ? taste is crisp , naturally .  a : the cork comes out with out a pop and the beer is black , somewhat thick , and flat . black hole is already boozy as it is and the bourbon barrel seems to have just added to it unnecessarily . the bourbon and alcohol from the base beer just attack you , and the other flavors are not very good either : soy sauce , chemical solvent , and only a hint of chocolate . it 's rather sad to say , this was actually better than the scotch version .  m - the one flaw . too wet and smooth .

s. slightly metallic and not very attractive t. light with very subtle hops . d. see taste and smell comments .  it has a medium amber color and forms a decent head .  mouthfeel is where this brew suffers : it 's really just pretty thin .

the aroma ... well is not too impressive , somewhat hefe smell , no distinctions , very bland for a 'boston beer ' product .  this brew has a clear , amber body that is typical of this style . the nice creamy head is actually better than most of the german o-fests i 've seen . smells watery , and oxidated ( though when i drank it i knew it was not oxidated ) .  too thin and the carbonation is too high given the taste . overall : the taste and smell of this beer are amazing , but the mouthfeel really took away from the beer .

smell weak , grainy and of alcohol .  a : pours a dark brown body . i want to check out the edges and see if it 's translucent , but the head -- 3 fingers of huge , fluffy bubbles -- lasts forever . i was told this is infected , so i was n't surprised to see this .  mouthfeel is the most dissappointing part of this beer ; it 's far too watery .

there was not much nose on this beer so i really couldnt get too excited . the taste was a solid lager .  it poured well to a big head with tons of little bubbles , like champagne , and i eagerly was anticipating a big tasting lager .  the carbonation is way too strong with small sharp bubbles .

very faint smell , i have to try hard to get all of the aromas , but i smell basic cascade and amarillo hops , that give off a smell thats between orange and lemon .  pours a 1/4 '' light mocha head with barely frothy lacing , neither of which stick around long . pours a deep root beer color into a black cauldron body , no light penetrates this fucker .  the mouthfeel is very lively , very slippery/oily and buttery . too carbonated , which is strange for a stout . drinkability is ok given the high abv , but the bitterness , aftertaste and carbonation cancel that out somewhat .

even if this were considered an english style , however , the diacetyl levels in my glass were unacceptably high . the unmistakeable buttery aroma met me before i even put my nose to the glass , overwhelming most everything else . i did manage to ferret out the flowery hop aroma , but the butter was distracting .  a-cherry wood brown with an off-white colored head s-very faint scent of chocolate malts t-comes in with a smooth and slightly bold taste of dark roasted coffee with a slightly bitter taste that reminds me if i was actually sucking on a real coffee bean ... it is n't something you actually want to be doing .  mouthfeel : very thin , body like water .

the aroma is malty without much trace of hops . at first i thought this might be the temperature it was served at , but as it warmed up a bit , the scent did n't improve at all . if the aroma was improved i might have been inclined to try another to get a better opinion .  pours a dark orange/amber color with a large white head and nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is extraordinarily watery .

the smell is malt , grain , and grass - nothing special . it 's a pretty typical macro lager smell . no whiff of camels or any other skunky smells .  it looked pretty , the color was quite nice , and the smell , while a bit sugary , was n't bad .  just a touch of carbonation zing at the swallow . i just dont know what to think , and that slimey mouthfeel is really starting to irritate my gag reflex .

the smell and the appearance were below average , but i actually liked the taste .  beer looks very healthy and refreshing .  pouring out in a sweaty yellow with high carbonation and zippy flavor , lionshead light offers enough personality and taste to get you past its weaker qualities ( gritty mouthfeel , odd aftertaste , general banality ) and is definitely there for you when you need a night of drinking without the cost of high-quality suds .

smell : rootbeer and yeast with a slight chicory note .  a-pours a golden color , bright , slight haze to it with some sediment floating around . the head is fluffy and bubbly with an off white head .  m : very thin and dry a low carbonation and a bitterness at the end .

very corny nose - kind of a wet , spoiled corn .  a- pours a nice brown that sits pretty dark in glass . a nice rocky khaki head forms . decent lacing .  it 's a cheap american beer produced for the masses . i actually like this beer and if i 'm drinking bmc and am going the light route this is my preference .

aroma : smokey ? coriander rules ! all in all , enchanting . appearance : oddly , viewed from the side it showed significant hazy , but it was clear when viewed from the top .  this beer poured a bright golden straw color . it had a decent head which lasted halfway through the beer .  a - this beer poured a light golden color , crystal clear , that produced a foamy white head that disappeared quickly and left no lacing on the glass , not surprised s - the only notes on the nose where malts and lager yeasts t - this beer had a one dimensional taste to it , as one would expect from a regular lager , not a harshness i get from adjunct lagers , but still pretty lame m - this beer had a very thin watery body , and was loaded with carbonation d - this beer would be a very drinkable beer in the summertime to quench the thirst , if not for the high amounts of carbonation , which seems to accompany most abitas .

smell - mild starchy smell of , at best pale malt but probably corn or rice starch . the `` skunky '' linseed smell of pilsners .  poured from a 12 oz bottle the liquid is dark and inviting , with good carbonation . the head is ok smallish with a dark tan foam the fade fase to a pad leaving no lace .  the flavour is rather thin and feels watered down .

it reminded me a lot of your average over the counter macro brew . smell : the first smell was n't quite right and the taste confirmed the initial diagnosis . there 's not much there and the smell certainly does n't pull you in . taste : the taste is a bit lacking , nothing strong or overwhelming but nothing bad about it either .  pours a clear golden orange with decent head .  in the appearance , is a coppery color , with a poor head of foam , the bottle and the logo are retro ; lot of caramel and sugar in the smell ; some essences of caramel and roasted malts in the taste ; the drinkability is good ; the mouthfeel is watery and fizzy , with a low bitterness .

the aroma is a little off putting . so i guess i could say this does n't look like much at first and the aroma is a bit off in my opinion but this is some pretty good drinking .  the color was a pretty golden-yellow with ne-quality clarity .  the mouthfeel is actually kind of weak and bitter , surprisingly , given the pleasant look and smell of this beer .

the smell is sweet and lemony with noticeable nobel hop in the scent . grain and more so corn are major scent components . fairly strong cooked vegetable aroma .  i taste phenols like they tried belgian yeast in an imperial stout . i love avery beers but this one falls short for me .  flat and watery mouthfeel , very thin , no body .

the smell is pretty raunchy .  appearance this beer is a light , very pretty yellow with tremendous carbonation and a good , rising head that showed some retention and left a lot of lacing . im impressed .  there is no body to this wit . it drinks like a cheap lager leaving very little for the finish .

nose is uncommonly clean , save mabye a whiff of sulfur . corn and pale malt sweet upfront , with a curious blend of sulfur and ester , but nothing really offensive it and fades quickly .  ruby brown color .  smell-fairly clean , i do detect some malt but not much else , no hoppiness , alcohol , or otherwise . taste-fairly tasteless , some malt does come through again but for the most part this tastes like water . drinkability-somewhat malty and low abv , you could pound these that 's for sure . overall-yawn , sorry for the not so detailed review but this is another not so detailed light beer , even from an ok brewery like pocono .

nose is stale grains with some sulfur notes .  it started out ok , the beer appeared bright and clean , a golden amber body with a good solid foaming white head on top .  mouthfeel is bad . it burns there is so much carbonation .

the aroma is fantastic . it 's a boquet of floral hops .  ok - this one was part of a big haul of random canadian brews ... a : poured from the 500ml can into a weizen glass ; it 's a slightly cloudy , pale , straw gold ; snow white head is enormous and manages some really nice lacing .  mouthfeel - this is probably my biggest problem with this beer a very watery mouthfeel and it is very under-carbonated , almost flat .

' i do n't know if this is because of the high alchohol content , or because they , molson , put a bit more effort into brewing it than they do their other beers . it smells pretty bad , actually , a bit like a bud but a bit more acrid . but for it 's vaguely unpleasant appearance , and sour smell , it actually tastes pretty good .  right after the pour i picked up a sweet , yet sharp fruit and perfume aroma . i suppose it 's not bad for a sour beer , or if you 're into sour beer . it 's not a nasty infection that smells like vomit , but rather a lemon-lime juice sour tang that could use some sweetening .  the mouthfeel just might be below the level of previous commented on mab , with the watery feel and the slight body .

maybe my nose is off tonight but i do n't smell anything . it is however very flavorful . tangerine , spices , honey ... i like it , but there is nothing belgian about it , hence the low scores .  this beer pours a clear amber with a nice off-white head ... has a good head retention and leaves a fair amount of lace .  my biggest disappointment was the mouthfeel with no lasting carbonation or creaminess .

smell is the biggest problem to me , besides limestone and dust , i do n't smell mcuh , maybe some caramel .  poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 3/4 '' tan head above a deeply reddish brown brew .  i 'm not a huge brown ale fan but i 've had some dang good ones lately so i 'm hoping this will be another winner ... pours a warm brown with a very thick creamy head of off white ... very warm and fall-like and makes me wish it was october ... very faint malty earthy aromas that seem rather muted ... toffee and caramel notes for sure but just not pronounced enough for my tastes ... very thin and watery , this one falls short in several categories ... definite caramel malt presence but there 's not enough substance to really enjoy it . almost get a little yeastiness here that mingles with the malts that give this a weird almost oxidized flavor.. sort of sweet and toffee-like but this could really use a little more thickness ... very average brown to me ... might do in a pinch but not one i 'd reach for by choice

s : macroy with a bit of honey , corn and rice otherwise , meh ... smells like a plain old beer .  i 'm tempering my scores as it was made to sound like an american ipa , which it most clearly wasn't pouring a mildly hazy orange with a dense , off-white head with good retention and nice lacing , this is a pretty nice looking beer .  m - this is where the beer is odd ... when cold , a really carbonated mouthfeel that is unappealing .

s : not much of a nose . t : it advertised a `` toasty ... malt '' taste ... sorry , very underwhelmed .  received this one from twiggamortis420 in a recent bif a- pours a golden amber with a huge fizzy head and some good carbonation , nice lacing .  body is way too thin for the style and way too filtered imo .

smell- there is something a little off in the aroma . there are tones of citrus , floral hops and metal .  the appearance is good . it looks like an ipa , it 's a darker shade of orange with a finger of tawny head that hangs in there and leaves decent lacing .  m- thin , watery with crisp prickly carbonation throughout .

s-wet dog with a hint of coffee , pretty dissapointing t- weak flavor , i pick up the oatmeal and coffee m- thick and creamy with hints of carbonation d- pretty much could only have one of these  poured and looked good but then hit the brakes .  the beers got a big body , almost too big for its style . its not terrible , the body is really killing this one for me .

s- the aroma is very faint even for pale ale standards , let alone an ipa from california . there is some malt along with hints of citrusy hops . t- the taste has a little more flavor than i was expecting based on the weak aroma , but it still leaves a lot of flavor to be desired . '' overall , blue frog ipa is pretty decent brew , but there are many better ipas out there to buy this one again .  a - pours medium , straw golden with a 3/4 '' frothy , sudsy white head that holds its own and gradually reduces to a tiny ring and a pocket of small bubbles in the center .  m : this is where the beer loses me ... it feels thin and watery where i was expecting a richer , creamier texture . it 's just too bad it 's so thin ... if they boosted the maltiness a bit this would be a killer beer .

s : yikes , the only positive is the burnt bread , but the rest is metallic and bland . t : looks can be deceiving i guess .  this beer poured a medium amber with a small amount of lasting head .  mouthfeel : very light , watery body with not much to recommend it .

leaves a little spotty lacing the aroma is really , really faint .  typical color . easy on the pour as this is one pumped up porter . frothy , loose head , covers the glass all the way down .  mouthfeel : very thin with a little bit of bubble .

the aroma is like toasted bread but not toasted malts along with grain and rice .  appearance : pours up a clear , brown body with a frothed , ivory-hued head .  poured chilled in flared glass a : dark caramel , clear ; very thick head ; good carb beads ; great lacing s : a bit univiting ; thin , malty ( sweet ) aroma ; but i do n't smell a bock here t : one-dimensional bock ; little double about it m : watery , thin , dead it looks fantastic , but 'tai n't .

the smell was almost reminiscent of an american lager - not too appealing .  a : looked very promising . ruby-black , awesome plethora of fluffy , off-white head .  probably too carbonated , almost prickly on the palate . this is a thin bodied beer , and other from the carbonation it goes down easily enough .

the smell is heavy on candy banana . it smells like those cheap candy lolly bananas you can buy . it is not as bananary ( is that a word ) as the smell insinuates , but it is passable .  i finally got around to trying the moylan 's hopsickle imperial ale . i had heard good things and often love over the top hops but this one did n't work for me . lots of hops but lacking other elements to help show them off and you are left with a bitter finish that easily lasts 10 minutes .  m - light bodied , harsh carbonation level , odd , gritty texture .

it has the weakest nose of the four ; maybe i smell some pumpkin puree and cinnamon ? maybe this beer is suffering because it 's the last in my line up and my palate has become dulled , but then if the nose is weak , i should n't be surprised if the flavor profile is weak .  appearance - very dark brown . light brown , sudsy head .  flavor is rather thin , but consists of light chocolate and roast , and a dash of hops on top of a thin , very dry body that leaves a short finish .

the beer poors golden clear with good carbonation that give a white foamy head for a brief time . the smell and taste are enhanced with grain .  it poured a nice gold with a surprisingly thick head that left lotsa lacing.but ... tis true looks can be deceiving.the aroma was non existent , the flavor followed suit , very , very bland and totallly lacking any discernable character.my father-in-law drinks this , that 's where i got the bottle to review , thanks pop , but no thanks .  sticky & flabby .

nose was sour apples and rotting wood .  huge foamy slightly off-white head , average sized bubbles .  mouthfeel was loose and watery ( though the taste did not seem to reflect the watery nature of the beer 's feel ) .

the smell is very non-sescript , maybe a hint of malt , thats about it .  a : pours a clear ruby red/brown color . a two finger beige head forms . the wispy foam has good retention , and some lace is left behind .  the mouthfeel was too full bodied for the style and was a major negative point .

aroma is faint , almost nonexistent . pale malt ?  poured into a pub glass , a clear , ruby red color , looks nice . the head was off-white nice and creamy with good retention .  it 's body , unfortunately , is fatally flawed : this beer feels more watery than water . an interesting beer that starts off at a sprinter 's pace for excellence and quickly slides downhill .

smells amazing ! big on citrus and grapefruit , smells like sugar in your nose.. really great.. taste follows well and tickles the tongue in all the right ways without feeling boozy especially for a 10 % beer .  it looked like a real winter brew ( what i 'm use to ) , a rich looking dark amber with a nice head on it .  the mouthfeel is crappy . maybe not terrible , but too thin and too fizzy when it first hits the palate .

the intial scent is that of a sweet extra pale lager , but undernearth it lurks something that smells like my car after i left a hoagie in it on a hot day . but since this smell is not overpowering , its not that big of a deal .  pitch black with a froathy off white head . it really draws you in with its looks and then bam !  f - pretty limp , even more than i remember . like stout-flavored water .

smell is almost non existent .  appearance : super high score except for the head , the appearnace is of a great apple cider just made in front of you ( of course due to non filtered/non pastuerized ) , the lace isnt much to comment about , so no 5 here . verdict : got this is the dark brown bottle with the tissue wrap , the cork was very dry ( almost broke off into the beer when opening ) , very unimpressive , looks like a beautiful unfiltered gem , but doesnt back it up in the taste .  mouthfeel - watery and thin .

leaves behind a off white cap . s - wow ... . smells like finger polish with a slight raspberry sweet smell . really funky and alcoholic .  a loose tan head with loud exploding bubbles .  thin mouthfeel , just like drinking sparkling water with raspberry flavoring . sparkling water .

s : very thin and watery on the nose . i pick up a few hints of roasted malt and maybe some chocolate . d : this is really disappointing .  super fresh best before june 2011 , pours a slightly hazed copper golden hue with a bright white head billowing above the edge of my imperial pint , fine speckled lacing left behind .  slight caramel flavors present mouthfeel : thin and highly carbonated .

s - rice lager odor and then a caramel sweetness with a bit of dates in the mix .  clear amber body with a thick white head that stayed there for a while.nice lacing.this is where the beer goes downhill for me .  taste is very mild , with almost nil carbonation . no hops , only water , malt and honey as noted on the label .

the nose is mostly grainy rice with just a hint of spices .  how odd that guinness chooses not to produce an actual pint-sized can ( like murphy 's ) - it 's weird pouring the beer into its branded glassware and not filling it all the way to the top . the cascading 's not as pretty , the head is n't dense and incredibly creamy , the lacing 's not as impressive .  drinks : warm , the obnoxious funk flavor , paired with the unsettling mouthfeel , makes this beer nigh undrinkable .

the smell was metallic but the flavor was complex and good , with elements of grass , citrus , and an unusual lemony finish . it was perfect in that setting ; however it tasted and felt a little like a wit . it was darn good , but not a great ipa .  draft pint at the brewpub ; dark , dark brown with a big quality head that disapated slowly .  unfortunately thin but carbonation does what it can .
better than bud light in taste , but it does fall short of something great . cheap beer , 30 pack cans here are $ 10.99 .  pours a nice golden with a big rocky head .  m/d - it is unbelievably thin .

s - grainy . not much .  label is colored a reddish /auburn hue . there is a woman who is being held by the devil no doubt with orange flames comming from underneath . the lacing in nice to look at all over the glass .  the mouthfeel is very gaseous . i 've had 3 of their beers now and they have all felt shitty in the mouth .

smells like sweet dirt . smells like a lightly infected batch of underattenuated extract homebrew .  typical dark appearance with good head retention .  a very wimpy brew , foamy in the mouth , with a twinge of a soapy taste .

nose is sweet , but slightly organic , with a rotting character that really does n't bear repeating .  starts with an appearance that 's good , amber color and fine head .  the mouthfeel is hot as hell . let a mouthful of this rest on your palate for 10-15 seconds , and it feels like the insides of your mouth are being dissolved . it 's very astringent and has a monster bite.the aftertaste is just ... boozy .

medium pour gave an impressive 2 '' tan colored head w/equally impressive retention , after 5 minutes still had `` head , very good lacing , clear amber color . not much on the nose , a little grassy/malty that 's about it . for a mrzen ... not bad but just a little thin for the style , not very much on the malt and i swear there may be a little dms . not a good representation of a mrzen thus the lower stm # 's but an easy drinking and refreshing beer regardless .  pours nicely , thick head , laced well . dark color , very reminiscent of raspberries . the taste was just as unimpressive - a lot like drinking water , and if it was n't for the slight ( and i mean slight ) buzz i caught off of it , i 'd swear i was drinking a watered down raspberry smoothy .  mouthfeel : watery in comparison to a pint drawn in a good pub with a nitrogen system . the watered down mouthfeel really detracts .

smelled like wet tin cans .  a : opaque body topped off by 2 inches of billowing tan foam .  body is terribly watery , the pacman yeast ( which i usually like ) just does n't fit with this beer . the mouthfeel is as hearty as a hawiian death metal band .
smell is pretty unappealing .  a very soft pour yields a clear dark brown beer with a huge khaki head that takes a while to subside .  thin mouthfeel with a dry center and a rather silent finish .

appearance and smell are both pretty bad , typical for a common micro the taste has more going on than i would expect for this price .  looks good but i expected more of a head .  mouthfeel is very flat , yet not undrinkable .

very , very faint aroma of hop . flavor is primarily of hop , with just a tiny bit of malt dripping through .  22 oz bottle dark brown into a snifter with a short lived half inch tan head equal blend of milk and dark chocolates , coffee , and plastic .  very little aroma , mouthfeel 's watery .
s - the smell reminded me a bit of raw meat .  looks pretty good .  the mouthfeel is medium to light bodied and pretty watery which washes out the flavors .
no smell at all , maybe a hint of malt , but that 's it . disappointing .  nice enough looking brew .  mouthfeel is watery .

this is my first time that i test this beer and for me it taste a little like a high class budweiser at the end , the head last longer than an averege lager , love the color is dark amber , a bit of hob/malty flavor and a far sweetnes at the end.what i like about this beer is when it gets about 58 degrees the the aroma become a bit more intense bit the flavor still the same not like the some lagers that become undrinkable .  poured bronze , with a nice sized tan head .  body is thin and woefully under-carbonated , but in it 's defense , roswell alien amber does n't have any detectable off-notes .

this beer smells of coffee and sweet chocolate . overall another good beer from ccb .  poured from a bottle , this brown ale hits the glass with just enough head and a medium brown opaque color .  mouthfeel is disappointingly watery .

the smell is somewhat sour / doughy . a quite uninteresting pale lager .  appearance- this one looked pretty damn good . golden pour with a nice stream of bubbles coming from the bottom of my duvel glass . i guess that makes any beer look better than it actually is . good solid while creamy head and average lacing .  extremely thin mouthfeel . drinkable , but not recommended .

s-smells strongly of oak and smoked bacon with some very mild caramel .  the beer pours a very nice golden straw color with a small but lingering white head .  except for the very poor mouthfeel , a great beer , one that i would recommend from the bottle .

instead , i get the aroma of uncooked , canned , corn and a hint of euroskunk hops .  the appearance is right , it 's dark brown with a large tan head .  a bit slick on the tongue and a little watery for a barley wine . good carbonation level . not a strong malt profile to speak of and the mouthfeel was watery .

virtually no nose .  a : the pour is quite dark , essentially black with a nice big tan head on it .  taste/mouthfeel- watery feel to the beer , some grain and alcohol , hops and malt are present but do n't really make much of an impression . drinkability-refreshing on a hot summer day , other than that the thin feel dissapoints .

has a slightly skunky smell to it , but not terrible .  i purchased a pint bottle of this , since im a fan of spaten beers like their oktoberfest beer , pilser ect.. btu this bock beer was just way too syrupy to me taste wasnt that bad but overwhelming . this is good beer to try a few sips but after a while the strong syrupy taste does get to you  the feel is super watery .

lovely . a bit of grassiness as well . it 's like they have left a shadow but the hops totally overwhelm everything .  poured dark amber , with a light tan head .  2.0 m : water body . good moderate carbonation . too light and watery to appreciate .

the smell was not what i expected from a belgian white , as it was very raw and doughy .  a : at least this beer looks good , because that 's all it has going for it . a black pour with a nice fluffy mocha colored head on top .  mouthfeel : thin body , watery texture , moderate-lively carbonation drinkability : well , not bad for the style .

i only have one comment that may add value , aroma - there was virtually no aroma to my pour .  medium amber color with a medium sized head with decent looking lace .  m : mouthful was disappointing , bland and thin .

s : lightly skunked ( clear bottles , anyone ? ) and otherwise aromatically challenged . t : definitely a corn-based adjunct beer .  pours clear golden with a good sized head and good lace .  it is thin bodied despite the nitro , with a masked , watery aroma . the beer may perhaps be too traditional to appreciate as it shows more modesty than american craft beers usually do . shannon 's core values are a dry grain and chaff taste with some show of dark lace . but the lack of body and flavor are obstacles to appreciation .

smells a little dank , and leafy . not really appealing to me . i hope this is n't a bad omen for the whole beer .  pours a pitch black opaque body with an inch of khaki head .  a- typical clear pale yellow with fast fading head s- corn and just a pinch of hops t- corn and just a pinch of hops and some sweetness m- thin watery mouthfeel d- as far as the mexican/south american beers go its decent but its still a diluted session beer .

s : smells like grass and spent grains . definitely leaves something to be desired .  a : poured a jet black with ok carbonation leaving behind a small tannish cap and some bubbles s : light oats , not much vanilla , roasted notes , pretty tame t : oats , roasted malt , the flavors for this beer were very mute .  extremely light on body , even for an old ale .

soy sauce aroma some maltiness i guess but the soy sauce is pretty overpowering some coffee a little chocolate , i do n't know what was up with the smell but i tastes much better than it smells , coffee , chocolate and some roasted malt is pretty pleasant . a little hot for my tastes really light in body for an imperial , feels watery overall not bad but it all feels a little forced , maybe with some time it 'll turn into a damn fine beer but right now it 's not something i 'll have again  pours a dark , opaque black , as a stout should with about one finger of head that stays around .  mouthfeel is thin and watery , not helping to blend the flavors together , but rather separating .

a bit of citrus and sweet caramel mixed in only makes this better . top notch !  average size head . lots of lace left behind as the head rapidly diminishes .  since it is so thin compared to other stouts , i do have to rate it accordingly . sorry but it could be thicker .

when i opened the bottle it gave an over ripe smell of chocolate and something spoiled .  nice golden color in the glass ... nice head and lace ... in fact as i write this ( ten minutes after opening this guy ) there is still a thin head in my glass .  beer is lightly carbonated .

a - fairly clear with a decent foamy white head that settles into a well retained collar and leaves nice lacing s - diacetyl ( buttered popcorn ) initially and behind it some grainy malt t - brief sweet malt intially with a strong noble hop like flavor and a moderately strong bitter hop finish ; diacetyl is lighter in flavor but in aroma , but still present to a mild degree m - medium-light body with high carbonation d - this would be a decent version of a german pilsner if it were n't for the diacetyl .  the beer looked promising , had a cloudy tannish-yellow appearance with a nice 2 '' head . upon tasting the beer she made a grimacing face , which surprised me , expecting this homemade hefe would be pretty top notch .  the mouthfeel is too undercarbonated and watery .

very typical in appearance and nose for a macro .  pours a moderate copper color with a good white head and a nice amount of spotty lacing as the beer falls down into a nice cap and collar .  the first mouth , however , leaves a slight citrus hand over her mouth to deliver a body too thin , very watery and the obvious lack of spices .
s- lemony with a strong dirty sock aroma .  bottle ... a : deep copper brown with red hues with a 1 inch white head that fades quickly . good .  the mouthfeel is very thin .

4.0 smells like a crappy adjunct lager . not really a whole lot going on here .  pours a sturdy brown-black and is capped with a big umber head ; lace is deposited in small spots .  mf : very coarse and dry for the style .

it smelled of grain and adjuncts , rice , tasted the same , a little bread , some sweetness .  pours a nice dark color with a slight coffee aroma but the flavor was seriously lacking .  a weak attempt at a flemish sour . the beer has good light redish color and the lactic sourness is present but it is thin and watery . no hop aroma or other funky lambic type aromas , just a lactic beer .
pretty sad smelling .  as for appearance , it is extremely dark in color with a thin foam .  not what i want from an ipa . mouthfeel - watery . flat .

heavy nose of molasses & toffee .  a : very dark brown/black with 1-2 finger creamy , off-white head with decent retention and rings of lace .  the body is decidedly watery , or maybe that 's the too-high carbonation producing a spritzy , foamy finish .

looks like your average fizzy yellow mega brew . aroma is a little corn adjunct and just a hint of hops . clean lager fermentation so no real yeast character .  a : looks like a nice brown ale - dark brown , lighter highlights , tan head of a good size .  mouthfeel is thin and fizzy , not at all what i want in a chocolate bock .

smell like sweet water and corn .  pours a ridiculously nice looking mocha brown and then gets darker .  a text book pilsener-which is a positive note but the bready quality is not full . finish is clean but it has the after-taste of the gaterade power water . drinks ok , and i would enjoy this on a hot summer day-just a bit pricey for a miller lite clone in a nicer bottle .

the low carbonation in this beer makes it ideal for heavy food , which of course mexican typically is . i would n't recommend this beer without lime .  pours to a dark earthy amber color , quite clear with little to no carbonation , and a nice white head that recedes to a thin film in minutes .  m thin and really kind of boring .

scent is not great .  poured a cloudy golden yellow with a thick stark white head that subsided slowly .  tingly carbonation . thin and watery on the tongue ; not what i would expect from a wheat wine . the intense carbonation dances with the crisp flavor and light body similarly to a belgian saison .
