i wasnt impressed with this stout . pure black with a minimal head . the smell is what disappointed me the most . there was no discernible smell at all , so before i even taste it i am wondering if true test is going to be as flat as the smell .  painfully awful . this beer smells and looks great .  finishes a bit metallic , grainy & a bit of toasty malt mf : thin with low carbonation this alright , i remember it darker back in the day , but i could be mistaken .

unfortunately i guess i got a batch similar to mabz , as there was no aroma on this beer . first time i 've ever had any sort of ipa without any hops smell . weird . after many doubtful looks from the nose , i was willing to admit i got the right beer only after the first taste .  dark bronze color .  there 's no bite , no kick , to the mouthfeel , and it 's not creamy or dense either . that said , there 's nothing to prevent you from having many , because it goes down like water .
way too much hop aroma , and a definite blast of hop flavor .  january 2006 batch poured into a tulip glass . very , very black in color .  the palate is thin and poorly carbonated .

smells were very sweet , malty , maple syrup , caramel and a touch of floral . sadly , those did not translate over to taste , which was dominated by a distinct unappealing dusty and skunkiness . overpowers anything else in there .  nice lightbrown head and a dark beercollor . nose is lots of yeast autolysation giving it a kind of soapy nose next to the good caramel and banana aromes .  m - dry finish , kind of tough , alcohol harshness , medium bodied .

aroma and flavor are extremely light . grain and honey notes are barely perceptible . outstanding carbonation streams . very bland but completely non-repulsive .  advertised on the label as 'milk stout with caramel color added ' ; really ? a : dark and 'stout'-like , nearly impenetrable . nice creamy head , a yellow-tan sudsiness that builds to over one-finger and fades quickly to a bubbly film and tight curtain of lace .  mouthfeel is watery with a lackluster carbonation . would n't seek out again as the finish was too medicinaly and the feel was thin and watery .

the aroma is , well , hoppy . fresh squeezed lemon juice , handfuls of fresh pine needles , a bit of grapefruit and some lemon zest thrown in , to add a bit of bitterness . the flavor is n't as hoppy as the aroma . the mouthfeel is a bit thin but it really does n't affect the quality of the beer .  appearance - 4.0 poured two fingers of fluffy , bubbly white head that steadily reduced to a thin layer . the colour is a very clear gold that looks to be moderately carbonated . mouthfeel - 2.5 a little less carbonated than most macros , feels moderately weighted in the mouth .  mouthfeel : thin and watery .

it poured a very pale golden yellow with a thin white head that retained for a short amount of time . although it 's classified as a macro lager , it definitely had more taste than bud or anything like that .  a - poured from bottle , about a finger of head , perfect color and haziness for the style .  thin mouthfeel i could down a lot of these .

no smell that i can detect .  this spring-bok-beer looks good . orange-golden , clear , with an initial nice head , nice bubbles too .  i was really looking forward to my first sip of this years bbcs on draft until the chap next to me said it was thin . my first sip tasted fantastic but yes it did indeed feel thin . as it warmed it should have gotten tastier but the thinness was more obvious than it was cold .
nose smells cheap and grainy .  dark red with orange glowing around the edges .  nasty aftertaste which lingered , a kind of alcohol with no body to it .

very dim in the nose with a slightly sweet , grainy note and a metallic character . adjunct grain and little else . this style is generally not known for its complexity and depth of aroma so i suppose i ca n't be too critical . lots of slightly buttery grain and a hint of faint hops . not my first choice by any means but still nice .  apperance : long lasting whipped cream looking head , decent lacing , golden crystal clear .  mouthfeel is thin and watery , with little-to-no carbonation .
s - wine with some very faint fruit . i can hardly smell it , though .  nicey hazy golden color . lots of carbonation . fluffy , pillowy head with some rings of lace .  very thin and watery .

the great part about strohs is that along with being the best tasting american swill around here , is that it is also very cheap compared to budweiser , coors , and miller . the only downfall is that it is a little difficult to find so i am forced to buy it at room temperature at the local grocery store .  pours clear copper with off-white head . active carbonation and nice lacing developing .  mouthfeel : very thin for a stout not a chewy texture to note very much light to medium body when it should be medium to full in body .

very pleasant aromas on the nose . like the nose , the traditional pumpkin pie flavors come thru immediately . like the aroma , i get decent doses of graham cracker malts and hints of roasted nuts , and sweet baking spices , perhaps some light brown sugar .  dark brown with hints of red when held up against the light . about one finger of a creamy beige head that holds decently and sticky but fairly thin lacing .  it 's almost watery .

this tops a clear , dark golden fluid devoid of any but the mildest leafy aroma . chilled , this is very bland .  ingredients : malt , hops , starch , fragrance , ayamurasaki imo a - pinkish orange body with smallish white head .  the mouthfeel is thin , carbonated , and sickening .

smell : funny thing is , when i smell it i do n't find anything . no malt sweetness , no hop bitterness , nothing .  looks like a normal stout , but smells and tastes very tart and very sour .  next to no beer flavour of any sort , may as well be soda water with a lime wedge .

ah , the nose , lemons , fresh cut grass , yeast , sweet malted grains a plethora of olfactory delights . finish is almost ferine in its acidity , the pleasant and spicy , quite dry and a very drinkable beer , not a great wit , but quite drinkable nonetheless .  this bottled batch is about a month old and it seems well made but short on flavor and a little light on body for me.the fizz is good and the lacing is respectable , and it 's pretty to look at , but i keep waiting for more flavor .  chalky astringent mouthfeel .

500 ml bottle , a : pour a standard yellow lager with an impressive rocky white head , long-lasting , sporadic lace . s : very light , but some malt comes through . t : typical bready malt character , sourdough bread .  it pours an amber/orange with a foamy off-white head that billows up pretty nicely and easily and sticks for a bit before receding with some decent lacing .  the body is much more a brown ale similar to newcastle , thin and watery , without much aftertaste .

s : very little aroma , i 'm just not getting much there . a subtle hint of caramel is about all i 'm picking up . t : a bit of caramel . toasted malts .  a - golden with an amber tint and two fingers of frothy off white head that dissipates in about two minutes leaving a mostly filled ring of lace behind .  the mouthfeel is way too light and thin .

it smells hoppy . also , it smells sort of like grass . i smell no malty aroma at all . i dont think i like the aroma at all .  appearance : pours out a black body with an acceptably-sized , beige head .  mouthfeel : on thin side .

oddly , no aroma . odd because of the flavor , which is ... flavor is all cascade .  a - pours with a quick-dissolving white foam that settles to a thin ring and some filmy haze , leaving behind spots of lace .  m - overly carbonated .

it hits you hard with the cinnamon upfront , and some ginger , nutmeg , and malt ... it smells like a gingerbread cookie ... also boozy especially when it warms and then maybe some citrus peel and some brown sugar t- lots of flavor ... cinnamon , pretty boozy , and bready ... again like a cinnamon/gingerbread cookie ... a tiny bit of dark berries on the finish ... the cinnamon sticks with you throughout ( like their pumpkin ale ) m- more carbonated than i anticipated ( a good thing ) ... creamy but also crip enough to keep me sipping d- would n't be able to drink too many of these because of the richness but then again you can never complain about too much flavor right ?  a : the beer pours a lightly cloudy golden orange color with a dense white head .  m : 2.0 a very watery beer , while the flavors are constantly present there are no real stand out characteristics in the feel . d : 3.0 goes down easy thanks to its thin consistency .

in the aroma , small malt and a hint of earth .  pours with a light fine bubbled head that dissipates quickly leaving light lace . appealing . it is very unsatisfying - especially considering the price . i 've had cantillon , boon , mort subite , and lindeman 's that just blow the temptation out of the box with great complexity and depth .  m : awful dry , tannic bitterness d : not so average

seems very dark for a 'pale ale' s : nice american hops aroma .  pours a nice golden color with thick head the thins to a lace .  light-medium carbonation and light bodied . grapefruit hop nose and flavor is same - grapefruit hops with hints of caramel , watery . $ 1.85 for a 12oz bottle from colonial spirits acton , ma .

s : weak , some faint malt notes , but not much , on par with a typical macro lager .  poured a typical darkish golden amber with decent head , which left nce lacing as the beer was drunk . the appearance was the high point with this beer , unfortunately .  the taste can only be described as `` extremely watery '' . as far as mouthfeel goes , once again the key words are `` extremely watery '' . flat and dull .
aroma is grainy , fruity and sweet . light hops .  nice head . corn flavor .  mouthfeel - watery , no bubbles , flat . drinkability - obviously not very drinkable for the fact this is 98 % flat .

colour is a very light copper and the only smell was a faint dry hop off of the initial pour which disappeared quickly but returns at the bottom of the glass . i would recommend this to somebody who is just breaking into trying new things and are used to the typical american lager , namely my father in law .  here goes ... pours a medium brown , clear color with two fingers of light beige head .  mouth-feel is light and watery .

rum soaked sweet cherries , vinegar . excellent very sour - prevalent sharp acidic vinegar flavor + tart berries .  beer is a stunning clear ruby .  m : pretty dry and heavily carbonated with an unpleasant metallic aftertaste . body is pretty thin and in line with other macro lagers .

aroma is very unappealing to me , very earthy and musty , beets obviously , i do n't know ... dirt ?  pours a golden orange with a soapy white head that retains well and leaves some lacing .  thin body , but still somehow manages to stay around on the palate as if i drank lme .

bready smell at first , and then it became more fruity as the head waned . i was hoping for more of a malty aroma , and i was disappointed not to get it .  a - bright yellow opaque color . fair lacing .  m - thin and watery with a weakly carbonation and a flimsy neutral finish .

very faint and sporadick bubbling . smell is a light yet somewhat sweet malt offering .  nice dark color , small head recedes quickly , no lacing to speak of .  flavor is malty with a thinnish mouthfeel . high carbonation , too much alcohol , not very drinkable , however it does n't have a bunch of absurd off-flavors like most organic beers .

aroma : first whiff is largely corn and dms , but deeper in there are some nice hops and malt notes . american hop flavors , but not really citric , too mild for me to place and all in the bittering end , none at the aroma end . mouthfeel : fairly creamy , good carbonation . im getting a strong dms flavor and smell , and maybe a touch of diacetyl to butter that corn .  mostly clear , straw colour with a big , fluffy white head . decent head retention .  really takes away from the mouthfeel leaving too thin for the style .

the smell however is n't anything to call home about .  pours a pretty red amber color with a healthy head on it , about one finger tall .  body is very thin and rather watery , and the finish is akin to a watered-down lemon-lime soda .

very nice . whoa ! it 's tastes ok but so far off from the fantastic nose . the sweet grains you smell taste like wet toast wrapped in paper towel . the flavor has a slight mustiness to it that i find to be very boring .  good color , mouthfeel , and hop taste overwhelmed by bad fruit flavors .  the mouthfeel is where this beer really falls short .

s : smells faintly of grains ... that 's about all however . clean and crisp .  jack d'or - bottled oct 2009 - batch nine c : nice golden yellow/orange color . pours with a very large head .  mouthfeel is painfully thin .

the aroma fills the room with floral , piney hops as soon as the cap is popped on this gem . the aroma really opens up as the beer is being poured and starts to showcase some citrusy notes as well . really quite good , and i can see what much of the hype is about .  color : light to medium brown head : slight to low head , very bubbly , great tight bubbles .  a hint of sweet dark malts , but no body to speak of to give these flavours any context . it is a very , very thin amber ale , hardly an alt .

smell is mildly unpleasant ; reminds me of a lager more than an ale -- smells more like budweiser than anything else .  pours a good two-finger , frothy head that leaves decent lacing . if all you drink is bud light and you 're looking for something a little more daring , you really ca n't go wrong with american ale as a stepping stone .  also , way too much carbonation for what i would have wanted in a beer like this .

i was unable to detect much of anything aroma wise , so i guess it 's up to the taste buds .  picked this one up at gordon 's in waltham on 11/12/09 a : this beer pours a jet black with a two/three finger head of light brown sudsy , rocky head .  very thin in the mouth .

s - i really could n't smell much of anything .  it poured a deep mahogany brown color with a thin , frothy tan head barely covering the top of the beer .  taste : i thought it had a burnt tar like flavor with some coffee and chocolate tones mouthfeel : it was very thin and watery for a stout .
s - quite disappointing scent . very bland .  great light golden color .  m/d : sticky , syrupy , and way under carbonated .

a : pours a very light straw yellow . s : not much going on here . faint bready aromoas .  appearance was the best part of this beer . the nice effect from the nitro cap made it fun to watch while i poured . the head magically settled on top of the slightly cloudy bronze ale . it did ti pretty quickly too . the head was thick and cramy with generous tracing .  m - there simply is n't enough texture here for a great dunkel . at first it seems almost medium but the brew quickly becomes far too thin for the style .

aroma is a very faint malt scent .  this is a good looking beer that does n't follow with good taste ( to me ) . dark amber on the pour with a very slight reddish cast . good head with nice lacing .  it has an ok flavor , but it 's very thin .
the smell is very faint . sweet and metallic .  medium yellow body , crystal clear with surprisingly decent head retention and lacing .  m : mouthfeel ruined it . way too fizzy , drinks like a coke .

very mild and buttery in the aroma . a slight metallic character is present along with a bit of malty grain . i 'm not terribly familiar with the style , but i would consider the smell lacking regardless . i 'm usually a bit fan of flying dog brews but i ca n't help but be a little disappointed with this one .  lots of fine bubbles . head looks pretty creamy , white color . lacing looks nice on the glass .  the feel is pretty terrible ; flat , lifeless , sweet with some metallic bitterness . it is sweet from the dark fruit which is nice but no carbonation just kills this beer .

a- light in color , yellowish with little to no head s - corn adjunct , enough said t- a lot of carbonation in this beer which some people desire .  from 22oz bomber to jackie 's o 's tulip on 7/14/11 *from notes a : lovely presentation . unfiltered pinkish-red radish in color , with a touch of warm amber at the edges . solid 2.75 finger head on a good pour . the head dies quite quickly , leaving just a bit of lacing . t : the taste is a touch better then the nose , but it sure is n't gon na win rogue any awards .  lightly hopped and sparkling on the tongue , this brew is quite flavorful , and has a mouthfeel of carbonated water .

s : smell is dominated by grassy hops , not very strong and not the greatest hop aroma , some unpleasant stale malt with a hint of alcohol . smells more like a hop forward pale ale than an ipa . t : tastes a bit better than it smells but not the hop dominant taste you expect from an ipa .  a : pours and orangeish red , touch lighter than a marzen . head is very nice ... fluffy and barely off white .  m - very watery , light bodied and even undercarbonated .

smells like tar , burnt plastic , slight coffee , maybe even charcoal . thankfully , the flavor is better than the aroma . the aroma really gets in the way for me .  the colour is dark amber , almost brown . the finger thick head is pale beige with a tint of red . lots of fine lacing .  mouthfeel : very thin and watery .

nothing really on the nose . the taste is very average . many better kolsch beers are to be found .  brown ale/old ale nutty , brown appearance . no hops , high alcohol on the palate ( way higher than the abv would suggest ) , nutty , not thick viscosity wise . brown mead without the sweetness . same w/ port 's anniversary beer .  m- thin with pretty high carbonation .

overall : quite possibly the worst smelling beer i 've ever smelt , yet one of the best tasting .  the beer appears transparent and light in orange in color . the head is approximately a half inch thick and leaves some decent lacing in its wake .  mouthfeel is unremarkable , almost like water .

smell : very , very faint . bit of a musty grainy presence with a dusty hop scent , and that 's it .  a : average light brown , creamy head . lasts long and very sticky . very good lacing . the color was dark , dark brown and not quite black .  m - pretty light bodied . surprising lack of carbonation given the beautiful head on this .

s : not much to note . some hops and corn . average for a mexican lager . i will grab one of these any time over corona or some of the other generic mexican lagers .  bottle pours a clear , rich , pretty copper color with a small white had that thins .  however , i was very distracted from the taste of this beer with a watery and flat-feeling mouthfeel . this is a good tasting beer , but the mouthfeel issue led me to be slightly disappointed with it .

s : a little skunky , as is expected from this style . actually smells a bit gross compared to other pale ales .  the appearence of this beer was good , a very nice golden color with a great head that lasted well .  pours dark dark brown almost black with a 1/2 finger tan head that faded to nothing and left no lacing smell is almost identical to dfh palo santo - very intoxicating taste - again palo santo clone with out the wood - vanilla booze chocolate mouthfeel is not good - the body is too light and the carbonation mixed with the booze stings my mouth drinkability takes a hit due to the mouthfeel but the flavor on this beer is great and maybe some age will mellow the carbonation ?

it poured a nice clear amber and had a big foamy off white head with fairly thick and generous lacings gracing the inside of my glass . aroma/taste/mouthfeel/drinkability nothing wrong with the malts in this one , in fact they were quite nice with a clear , dry biscuit character with a hint of caramel . what was wrong was the hops , smelled skunked with a hint of citrus and pine . still managed to drink this one ( must be my cheap scottish roots ) , and once my palate was numb to the skunkiness a mild citrus peel bitterness with a piney edge revealed itself to compliment the nice malts , but still finished with a lingering skunkiness . nicely balanced light to medium bodied english style ipa with nice malts and slightly skunked hops .  pours a a dark brown with a khaki head leaving some lacing along the glass .  the mouthfeel is medium and watery with almost no carbonation ( seems to be common of ep beers ) .

smells more like a pilsner . t : taste is much more like a whitbier .  i dont know if it was that i bought an xmas seasonal in april from blue max liquor in burnsville , mn and thats why it was only $ 3.99 for 750ml , or if the batch itself of december 2010 was just horrid . a : nice amber to reddish color . head retention is good , carbonation is good , lacing is good .  no carbonation whatsoever , so it pours like an extremely dark port .

s : light grassy hops and a bit of indistinguishable sweet malts . not a big fan of this smell ; it 's weak , but more importantly , it 's not particularly enjoyable . t : taste packs a large punch both for the style and considering the weak smell ; a dominant flavor of freshly cut grass , which is far more intense than i expected . '' sweet malts also show up once again ; they 're so light and sweet that they taste almost like corn , although i know this is n't the case .  looks like a blonde ale to me , yellow with a wisp of orange and lightly cloudy with a nice white head that laces lightly .  mouthfeel : watery .

excellent . the beer is the color of honey , and since this is a honey ale , it succeeds in this area as well . the taste and mouthfeel are light , pleasant , and ultimately forgettable .  having just finished viewing a concert at the keswick theatre of king crimson i crossed the street and walked into the g.g . however as i looked at the five beers they had my expectations dropped ... two light beers and two fruit beers i tried the brown eyed girl and one other beer worth trying the aroma definitely had some brown ale character but one would have to search for it .  mouthfeel - thin and watery .

this is your typical lawnmower , i want something cheap and light beer.as far as light beers go this is my # 1 choice , the app , smell , and taste are not that impressive , but if taken in context of the brew , they 're not bad .  little to no head on this beer even with a moderately vigorous pour . the color is spot on amber to almost a garnet hue . deep and rich colored .  thin feel .

although when i play that foul , foul game known as beer pong , a tecate beer looks like a pretty little lady down at the bottom of my solo cup . the smell is usually reminiscent of a fart a little bit .  appearance : pours a clear dark red/amber color with a layer of off white head .  do n't like the mouthfeel in this - fizz seems a bit harsh and the body a bit watery .

s - not much here . pretty faint malt smell .  nice foamy head that stays around and leaves a sticky lacing on the glass . not straw colored as the bottle says , but a very light orange-brown . nice .  the finish is extremely light , almost watery .

s : nothing really special to report . smells like a cerveza ! t : it 's light , crisp , and has that lager taste to it and it 's a good blend for a summer beer .  the pour is nice , black and viscous with a tan head that fades to a thin ring . very thick and almost slick in the mouth .  m - again thin and watery .

this beer smells like lake wilhelm . faint nutty smells . no hoppy aroma to speak of . the wilhelm smell is just creeping me out .  pours a translucent almost an iced tea color with a pinkish tint , topped with a helping of medium bodied half inch bleachy head .  mouthful is thin and reminds me of rice .

s - smells slightly sweet and grainy . no hops to speak of in the aroma .  nice head , good lace .  very light body , coupled with carbonation and sweetness , this was closer to soda pop than banana bread . m=very loose ; no body whatsoever .

the scent is slightly skunky which was weird for anderson valley and kind of overpowered the smells of hops and malt .  while drinking imperial while on vacation may suffice for a week ( at most ) , having to consume the flagship beer of costa rica 's monopolistic beer industry on a regular basis makes me wish i liked hard booze more . it looks good , it 's certainly clear , and when it 's 98 degrees out and it 's chilled bottle is in your hand everything seems right ... but that 's as good as it gets .  but the bottle i had was too carbonated which gave it a bad mouthfeel , blocking the tastes .

nothing good coming from a deep smell off this beer . smells like 'beer ' , and not in a good way . thankfully , tastes much better than it smells . t- good .  appearance : dark orange . nice , off-white head .  thin and filmy .

s : smells really strange . there 's sort of a funky cheese aroma ( sort of like the powdered cheddar cheese from popcorn ) up front , but it 's quickly cut through by a sharp alcohol aroma . t : the flavor is a little better than the nose , but not really all that great .  appearance : the ale pours with a healthy two finger head . it has a nice dark black color with hints of red throughout . i ca n't tell if there is any sediment in here .  i had a really weird reaction to this beer - it caused me my mouth to water . the mouthfeel clings , even as my mouth is fighting back with spit . did i mention it makes my mouth water ?

the smell is faint , not good at all , musty almost , very grainy ... it may be a blessing that it is a faint smell .  not much carbonation , average head , nice amber color which happens to be the high point of this beer .  fizzy carbonation ruined the mouthfeel for me here , this one seemed a bit over carbonated .

smell is pungent with a powerful alcohol smell . almost reminds me of the smell of name tag beer which is n't the greatest smell in the world . taste had some coffee and mocha flavors as the bottle suggested . i have had other bottles from there that had stuff in it as well and just were n't very fresh .  a very brown to brown-black . tan head 1/2-1/4 inch which gradual disappeared .  * mouthfeel is thin and watery , with a plethora of fine carbonation .

the nose is off . it smells like a wild field .  dark brown with a ruby bottom and a very nice head .  i really love the taste but the complete lack of carbonation is disappointing . i like this but even with some mild carbonation i would love this !

s - soapy and grainy aroma .  this beer pours a solid brown with some decent off white head that fades very fast .  flavor is one dimensional : black coffee . just tastes bitter and thin , like someone aged seltzer water in a used-coffee-filter-lined barrel .

coors light 's twin . the color is yellow and clear with good carbonation that results in a white foam head that dissapates quickly . smell and taste are primarily grain with attempted balnace of hops , etc .  pours a slight hazed golden colour with a big fluffy white head ... simple smell ... taste is quite simple too , does n't seem offensive but lacks any real character ... .  the mouth feel is watery and chalky .

s- smell is of bread , and a slight bit of hops , but also very metallic . the metallic smell is the most predominant and almost ruins the nose in my opinion . the metallic smell is not nearly as noticeable in the taste ( thankfully ) .  i enjoyed the flavors of this pa , lots of grapefruity and piney hops .  the taste is pretty much the same , grains . there is a sharp bite of carbonation , and the coldness is getting to me . this is the beer that defines drinkability , they go down like water .

smell : hint of beer , tomatoes and a strange fishy smell .  pours a mud brown with hues of mahogany and dirty white foam that forms about a half-inch head on the first pour and lasts for quite a while .  the body is unexpectedly quite thin and as a consequence seems to have too much carbonation .

pretty damn good tart raspberry smell and taste , though after that , there 's not much going on .  a- appealing looking bottle , cool lettering . light yellow color , poured into a pint glass .  peppery tongue from the over carbonation ... weak aqueous body , light on malts , raspberry flavor over powers ( flavor additive ? ) tart , dry fast finish ... no after taste . not much here ... too fizzy ... too soda-like in the smell and taste and weak ... .a good girly drink .

the first characteristic i notice in the nose is wet cardboard and some sort of mineral smell . earthy , musty .  pours with a nice fluffy head over bold golden liquid .  kinda on the watery side , not much for carbonation .

a - color is rustic brownish without any head to speak of s - the nose is of sweet bourbony aromas of vanilla and some caramel ; there are also dark fruits present on the nose t - sweet dark fruits open this one up nicely . next up are some raisins and sticky malts mixed with a little cola .  well , it looked good ... then it went downhill ... it poured a dark brown with a nice staying head and lacing .  the beer is failed by its thin and bubbly mouthfeel , though .

s - fantastic sweet , brown sugar , syrup and malt . it 's still worth it just to smell the nice flavors it has to offer .  i love the reddish amber color though and the nice foamy head did stick around for a while but thats about the only good thing i can say about it im afraid .  overly attenuated , skimpy and lean in overall body , with a mouthfeel that lacks any firm viscosity .
no smell initially . first taste is medicinal but it gets better .  appearance : clear copper color , huge head that volcanoes out of the glass .  the palate is thin .

the aroma is very weak .  a- pours a nice amber colour with an extremely well retaining slim , creamy head on top . looks quite good .  m : very thin on the palate , incredibly light bodied with high carbonation .

s : floral and grassy hop smell which is beautiful which combats a stinky yeast smell that i got when i first opened the beer .  appearance : best part of the beer . nice amber pour .  m : the mouthfeel was very slippery .

s = cough syrup , wet hay which is starting to rot , quite unpleasant .  deep brown color ... .i really like the nose ... .definite cocoa and a slight hit of cherries ... the nose is top notch but it goes down the tubes from there ... a tart/sour flavor overwhelmes this..perhaps it 's the cherries ... a soft chocloate flavor is a slightly noticable underlying flavor ... .  the mouthfeel is thin and watery with little carbonation .

immediate skunky smell .  appearance-dark brown , some shades of maroon coming through when held up to the light . a pretty nice 2 finger tan head .  the consistency of this beer was watery , and the mouth feel was rather weak .

smell is very bland . faint musty hops and a bit of sulfur with a backdrop of sweet caramel malt .  anyway . the carbonation is nice and the golden hue is lovely .  m - thin with too much carbonation .

a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher  i started with an open mind ; appearance was nice , but there is n't much more here than that .  m - very little carbonation and does not engender any real tongue sensation .

smell was a bit skunky with a light hoppy background .  a : dark brown , thick and appears chocoately , decent head , lots of lacing . looks good . looks like more money went into the presentation ( ceramic bottle ) than the beer .  huge carbonation ( for a cask ale ) in a hazy golden orange body , with a low pure white head . mild flavor , thin body , mild bitterness .

s- malt , light hops , and a stinky , grassy , musky smell that is a real turnoff . i 'm really hoping the taste is quite a bit better than this . t- ok ... much better than the nose . the stinky smell does n't show up in the taste at all .  a - it pours a straw-yellow hue , hazy , and is capped with a good sized white frothy head .  no carbonation , flat . but it 's flat .

lovely aroma of smooth tootsie roll chocolate laced with some burnt edgyness of char and roastyness of burnt coffee .  the beer poured nicely with a decent head and good retention .  mouthfeel is cloying and thick . too thick and cloying , long sour finish is too much for me .

the scent is delicious with a mildly sweet and flavorful burst of hazelnut .  a : not as syrupy looking as i 'd expected . middle of the road stout looking .  light roast lingers in the finish , not much bitterness , but again a very thin body detracts majorly from this beer and keeps it from being recommendable .
smells like adjunct corn lager .  it looks and pours great .  thin , watery mouth , very little body .

smell reminds me of bud light , and nothing more memorable than that .  this poured a clear amber color with a good rocky cratery head that sticks around for a little white . decent lacing .  extremely watery .

the smell and taste was powered by grain and some malt/hop .  the beer poured a brilliant gold color . nice 1 finger white head that lasted awhile and left some decent lacing on the glass .  carbonation is annoyingly high , yet still manages to fail at drying out the sweetness .

330ml bottle 6.5 % abv i tried this beer on december 14 , 2008 after purchasing a 4 pack of 'historic scottish ales ' from one of my local lcbo outets . the aroma was very weak , but there were hints of sweet malt .  pours a deep brown with reddish highlights , i 'm guessing from the port ?  m - medium bodied with poor carbonation levels . the carbonation is just wrong for this style of beer .

the smell was awful , unwashed feet and hidden mould . getting through the aroma there was good drinkability but it was wierd and boozy , as if this monster developed into a 10 % plus overnight.above average mouthfeel .  pours a gorgeous super deep black , with a quickly diminishing small tan head that leaves no lacing .  it is watery and just doesnt taste as strong as i think a porter should . you taste what you smell , but the mouthfeel always leaves me thinking , `` why did i buy this again '' ? if you like the taste of porters but do not like the thickness and wish it felt more like a light beer , this is for you !

s - very neutral smell . picked up a little hop aroma but very weak by pale ale standards .  appearance : opaque reddish brown with an inch tall white head .  m : too much carbonation ; even more than spa red .

carbonation seems average s- quite malty with a bit of hops . the smell is not strong and its hard to coax . theres also a standard grain stink to it .  a- this one pours a dark amber colored body with a large fluffy white head . the head lasts a long time and leaves spotty lacing on the sides of my glass . s- those cheap grainy/metallic adjunct lager scents are the first things i notice . i hope that people starting to get into craft beers dont try this and get turned off to esbs , its a horrendous representation of the style .  body is medium , but there 's almost zero carbonation - leaves the mouthfeel lacking . other than the weak mouthfeel , it 's quite solid .

smell is burnt and offensive and a little bit like burnt popcorn .  nice colour , nice head ( not much lacing ) , but taste that lasts as long as it takes to swallow .  the body is really watery for the style and unsatisfying despite the flavor being pretty good .

on first pour into a standard schooner glass very little head formed and unlike some reviewers i got little aroma except a very faint toffee .  i had a bottle with a someone a couple nights ago , hands down the worst tasting beer i have ever had . it looked fine , but it smelled and tasted like someone poured a glass of rum and a punch of rotten , fermented pumpkin in my ale .  m - thin . very thin .

s - extremely mild malts with maybe just a touch of chocolate . the scent is so mild that it us hard to tell .  appearance : clear dark copper color , moderate white head , fast fade .  yikes ... this is supposed to be an ipa ? this tastes like a half assed version of an apa . thin , watery , no head , no lacing , very little taste . where the hell are the hops ? this is a pale ale right ? wow , not a good beer .

not much aroma - light hints of malt , adjunct , and a little bit of astringency . at its premium price , though , i 'd rather drink pabst and save the money .  to reiterate - i dont get this beer or the brewery. & lt ; br & gt ; & lt ; br & gt ; dark chocolate brown with very small creamy heads that fades quickly .  thin . thinner than their lager . kind of sad , really , as the thin body nearly ruins this otherwise nice stout .

the aroma is sugar , lemon , and skunk . skunk is there , but not as bad as i thought from the aroma .  pours a opaque brown with a thick creamy tan head .  it 's cheap , surprisingly light-tasting ( for a 40 ) and packs a mighty whallop in terms of buzz . as a long fan of steel reserve 211 and st. ides , i admit that they do n't stand up to double malt in terms of taste and mouthfeel .

s : hardly any aroma .  pours into a giant white 3 finger foamy head . settles forming little craters , foamy spiderweb lacing clings to the sides of the glass as it does .  mouthfeel is on the watery side .

s - heavy malts and booze ca n't really pick up anything else .  appearance : pours out a brilliant , yellow body with a tall , white head .  smelled a little like fermented corn and seltzer water with a hint stale beer tastes exactly like it smells yet it is smooth on the palate felt like carbonated water in my mouth ... nothing more nothing less even with the above statements ... this beer is easy to drink ... i remember the days of throwing these thing back without sense of direction ... .they did the job and still do if i bring myself to drink them .

flavors are really faint .  the tap handle has an old boxer 's body from the waist up , which is really cool , and it looks good like all the nitro stouts . ab managed to isolate everything that sucks about nitro guinness and use it to make this stout .  t-again kinda thin ... .bready notes very slight coffee flavors coming through .

s : lagery yeasts , some resident spiciness . somewhat unimpressive as it reminds me of most macro-lager smells .  the pour was nice with a good frothy white head and a nice cloudy golden color .  feels flat for how much fizzing is going on .

its downhill from there , with really odd smells , not the glass but it is bleach and soap . chocolate most of all .  poured from a 12oz can into a tulip glass . but the second can was about the same ... a : pours an orange-straw colored with a 1/2 inch head that hangs around nicely .  too thin and not very exciting .

it had a nice dark chocolate smell , with a touch of bread .  appearance : solid black with thick lingering head . one of the better looking beers from a pint glass .  watery porter with good bittersweet chocolate malt . finish is dry and watery , with overwhelming carbonation .

the smell wasnt very eloquant , it reminded me of some sweet beverage , i cant even target a specific smell . the taste wasnt that bad , nothing great , but very refreshing . a shy soft hoppish taste was present but nothing to throw myself on the wall .  well , this is a pretty beer , kind of a cloudy red-amber with a nice head .  mouthfeel is too thin .

smell : pleasantly bold and fruity , with lots of orange peel , soapy lemon , and spicy coriander plus sweet grapes , strawberries , limes , caramel , and white wine in the background . there is also a hefeweizen-esque banana tone , plus plenty of alcohol with a suggestion of malibu . taste : very boozy and quite sweet , and frankly there is little to distinguish it as a `` white '' beer of any kind as opposed to just an ordinary belgian strong ale . this tastes like a not-so-good version of chimay red .  bottle : poured a clear golden color ale with a large foamy head with good retention and minimal lacing .  sweet , lacking much body . basically a soda pop with a very low abv .
the smell malty , and nothing too spectacular . the flavor is amazing .  dark brown in appearance .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with no carbonation .

tons of sweet , caramel malts in the aroma , but the hops are there as well with a touch of pine and citrus rind .  has a little viscosity to it and a gold-amber hue topped with a sticky off-white froth .  first of all the palate was very thin , with hints of chocolate and a slightly smoke flavour .

nose is great , offering bold notes of bitter chocolate , coffee , and roasted malt with secondary characteristics of anise and molasses . still a damn good beer , but this there 's so much fierce competition in the style that , for me , you really have to earn your as .  pours a nice thick white foamy head that dies into a ring of lace .  relatively poor mouthfeel .
definitely too fragrant , there are too many pleasant odors smashed together , not much is decernable .  appearance : hazy brick red pour with a fluffy off-white head .  the palate is thin .

this beer poured a nice dark brown with very little head , and had very little in the way of aroma . very faint smell of roast malt .  poured from 12oz bottle a - dark rich amber with soft bubbly head and loose lacing .  it does leave a really nice lingering coffee flavor on your palate m : very thin . lacks carbonation .

the aroma was of apple juice , which is not a good thing because i hate apple juice .  appearance : pours a brown colour . vigousous pour leads to a thick off white head , lots of retention .  mouthfeel is thin and flat .

aroma is surprisingly faint .  appearance : pours a clear amber color with a finger of off white head . good retention .  m : dry , i think the mouthfeel takes something away from the beer . overall , i like the complexity and smell but the mouthfeel totally ruins this beer for me .

smells excessively cold . i let it warm up and it still is very faint . caramely with spice . decent , but very , very faint .  i have to say that this beer does make for a good presentation in my lager glass . it 's straw in color , but not as pale as i had feared it would be . the head is impressive , billowing out to a good 2.5 inches and rising above the glass rim . it 's slightly off-white and has the look of marshmallow ... not right from the package but from when you scorch the crap out of it over a campfire and then pull off the burnt part . at least it was nice enough to leave behind a bit of lacing .  m : mouthfeel is oily , almost cloying .

s - extremely catty and earthy hops , with a bit of pine and soap mixed in there as well . not pleasant in my book .  pouring dark brown with a dense tan head that recedes to a disk , this beer leaves some patchy lace on the side of the glass . quite attractive .  mouthfeel is flat and has little carbonation which surprises me .

the scent was very faint , i caught a vague wiff of hops . the taste was , thankfully , a bit more fulfilling than the scent . a decent lagre , hops and barley and a little earthy taste .  2011 from the dentist a : black with three fingers of persistent toasted foam .  m - probably the biggest flaw with this beer . a bit thin on the body and a decent amount over carbonated . my only complaint is the mouthfeel , too much carbonation and not enough body .

the aroma is dusty , metallic , ( hoppy ) floral , and malty in an adjunct kind of way .  appearance may be best part of brew , this is a nice mahoghany copper color .  finally , the finish of this thin bodied beer was short and watery .

not much of a nose to this one . taste is light to medium bodied ... awkward mouthfeel . drinkable and not terribly bad , but off-putting for sure and certainly not a good , well balanced beer .  pours a medium black with a quickly dissipating tan head .  this beer is able to skate by because it 's not cloying and the sourness distracts for the most part , but i can only imagine how good this would be if it were properly carbonated .

fragrant hop aroma . average mouthfeel .  the beer pours an attractive gold color with very nice head retention and lacing .  woody creek white , flying dog 's 'new ' summer seasonal , pours as near white as one might imagine possible for a beer , which makes for an impressive look that is countered ( and unfortunately not enhanced ) by a fizzy , quick-to-dissipate head . across the tongue , this really just disappears , and the initial spice and malt flavors turn watery . this is not my favorite colorado wit nor my favorite flying dog brew .

not much to be noticed in the nose ... some sweet malts , a little bready .  i was really looking forward to the release of this seasonal oktoberfest beer . i do not like this beer . i search and search for a good marzen and have issues getting anything good except in deutschland . i love the other offerings of ayinger , but this is not what i want . the bottle and the cap is beautiful ... try again with the brew .  felt very flat and rather unpleasant on the palate .
